window.SB_LESSONS={"units":[{"n":1,"title":"THE BIRTH OF ENGLISH"},{"n":2,"title":"THE LATIN ENGINE"},{"n":3,"title":"THE GREEK LABORATORY"},{"n":4,"title":"THE NORMAN INVASION"},{"n":5,"title":"WORD JOURNEYS"},{"n":6,"title":"SEMANTIC TIME TRAVEL"},{"n":7,"title":"THE COGNATE WEB"},{"n":8,"title":"LANGUAGE DETECTIVES"},{"n":9,"title":"WORLD VOCABULARY"},{"n":10,"title":"CHAMPIONSHIP LINGUISTICS"}],"lessons":[{"id":"L01","n":1,"unit":1,"title":"The Proto-Indo-European Mother Tongue","diff":"easy","bigIdea":"Every English word descends from a single prehistoric language spoken 6,000 years ago on the grasslands north of the Black Sea.","story":"Around 4,500 BCE, Proto-Indo-Europeans lived near the Pontic-Caspian steppe — modern Ukraine. They left no writing, but they left their language. As they migrated, their tongue split into Sanskrit, Greek, Latin, Celtic, Germanic, and Slavic. English is Germanic — but it borrowed massively from the Latin, Greek, and French branches. This is why English has three words for almost every concept: *ask* (Old English) / *question* (French/Latin) / *interrogate* (Latin). Different branches, same 6,000-year-old family.","pattern":"When you see the same idea expressed as a SHORT everyday word AND a LONG formal word, you are seeing two branches of PIE: the Germanic short word (used since 450 CE) + the Latin/French long word (imported after 1066). *Help* vs *assist*. *Eat* vs *consume*. *Fear* vs *terror*. The long word is not \"better\" — it arrived through a different branch of the same ancient family.","connection":"This lesson is the foundation of everything. Every subsequent lesson is about which branch of the PIE family a word traveled through — and what spelling signals that journey left behind.","words":[{"w":"DENTAL","pron":"DEH-ntuhl","syll":"deh · ntah · l","ety":["Latin *dentalis* ← *dens/dentis* = tooth ← PIE *h₁dónts*","PIE root → Old English *tōþ* (tooth) + Latin *dent-* (dental, dentist, indent) + Greek *odont-* (orthodontics). Three spelling patterns, one 6,000-year-old word."]},{"w":"CARDIAC","pron":"KAH-rdee-ak","syll":"kaa · rdiy · ae · k","ety":["Greek *kardiakos* ← *kardia* = heart ← PIE *ḱḗr*","PIE *ḱḗr* → OE *heort* (heart) + Latin *cor/cordis* (cordial, courage — yes, courage = \"having heart\") + Greek *kardia* (cardiac, cardiologist). Three paths, one PIE root."]},{"w":"STELLAR","pron":"STEH-ler","syll":"steh · ler","ety":["Latin *stellaris* ← *stella* = star ← PIE *h₂stér*","PIE *h₂stér* → OE *steorra* (star) + Latin *stella* (stellar, constellation) + Greek *astron* (astronomy, disaster = \"under an evil star\"). *Disaster* literally means \"bad star.\""]},{"w":"NOCTURNAL","pron":"n-ah-k-t-UR-n-uh-l","syll":"nocturnal","ety":["Latin *nocturnalis* ← *nox/noctis* = night ← PIE *nókʷts*","PIE *nókʷts* → OE *niht* (night) + Latin *nox/noctis* (nocturnal, equinox). The *gh* in *night* was a guttural sound in Old English, now silent. Latin took the cleaner path."]},{"w":"PATERNAL","pron":"puh-TUR-nuhl","syll":"pah · ter · nah · l","ety":["Latin *paternus* ← *pater* = father ← PIE *pHtér*","PIE *pHtér* → OE *fæder* (father) + Latin *pater* (paternal, patriarch, patriot, patron, patronize) + Greek *pater* (paternoster). One PIE root, 10+ modern English words through three paths."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Find OE path AND Latin path for: night/nocturnal, star/stellar, tooth/dental. Draw a branching diagram showing the two-path system.","trace":"Draw a PIE family tree: PIE at top → Germanic, Latin, Greek branches → English words at leaves for each of the 5 words above.","build":"Find the OE word, French word, AND Latin/Greek word for: thinking (think/ponder/cogitate), seeing (look/view/observe), beginning (start/commence/initiate)."}},{"id":"L02","n":2,"unit":1,"title":"Old English: The Germanic Foundation 450–1100 CE","diff":"easy","bigIdea":"The 1,000 most common English words are almost entirely Germanic — the skeleton of the language, used every day for 600 years before Latin or French arrived in force.","story":"In 449 CE, three Germanic tribes — Angles, Saxons, Jutes — crossed from northern Germany into Britain. Their dialect became Old English (Anglo-Saxon). For 600 years they built a rich literary tradition. Then came the Vikings (793–1066), speaking Old Norse — a sister Germanic language close enough to blend with Old English. The result: Norse replaced the OE third-person pronouns (*they/their/them* replaced OE *hie/hiera/him*, which were too confusingly similar to masculine singular forms). Norse also contributed *sky*, *egg*, *leg*, *knife*, *husband*, *window*, *anger*, *skull*, *skill*, *trust*, *want*, *die*, *take*, *get*, *give*. These were not conquests — they were blends between linguistic cousins.","pattern":"Old English words are typically: short (1–2 syllables), spelled with now-silent consonant clusters (*kn-*, *wr-*, *-ight*, *-ough*), covering core human existence: family, body, nature, basic actions. A short, simple English word is almost certainly OE or Norse. This holds for ~90% of the 1,000 most common words.","connection":"Short, irregular-seeming English words are not random — they are OE and Norse fossils, preserving pronunciation patterns from 1,000+ years ago in their spelling.","words":[{"w":"KNIGHT","pron":"n-AY-t","syll":"knight","ety":["Old English *cniht* = boy, servant ← West Germanic","The *kn-* was fully pronounced in OE — /k/ AND /n/. The Great Vowel Shift silenced the *k*, but the printing press (1476) froze the spelling. This is why *knight* has two letters making one sound: a 1476 snapshot of pronunciation now lost."]},{"w":"WRAITH","pron":"RAYTH","syll":"wraith","ety":["Old Norse *veiðr* = wandering after death","The *wr-* cluster was pronounced /vr/ in Norse, /wr/ in OE. By 1500 the *w* was silenced. *Wraith, writhe, wrought, wrath, wren, wrist, wring* — all keep the silent *w* of the Viking period, preserving a sound gone from speech for 500 years."]},{"w":"BERSERK","pron":"ber-SURK","syll":"ber · ser · k","ety":["Old Norse *berserkr* ← *ber-* (bear) + *serkr* (shirt) = bear-shirt warrior","Viking warriors in bear skins fought in battle-frenzies. The *-sk-* cluster = Norse signal. Compare: *sky, skill, skull, skin, skate, ski* — all Norse. No Latin here. Short, violent, natural-world words with *sk-* = Norse."]},{"w":"DREARY","pron":"DRIH-ree","syll":"drih · riy","ety":["Old English *drēorig* = bloody, gory, grievous","Originally meant \"covered in blood.\" Over 1,000 years it weakened to \"dull and depressing.\" The word lost its violence and settled into mild sadness — semantic weakening across ten centuries. The spelling preserved, the terror evaporated."]},{"w":"TRUST","pron":"TRUHST","syll":"trah · st","ety":["Old Norse *traust* = confidence, help ← Proto-Germanic *traustaz*","One of the most important abstract nouns in English — entirely Norse in origin. The OE equivalent *treow* (faithfulness) survives only in *true* and *troth*. Norse won; OE became an archaism. Language is Darwinian."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Explain why *knife, knock, know, knit, kneel* all start with silent *k*. What does this tell you about 900 CE pronunciation?","trace":"Find 5 pairs where Norse replaced OE: *sky* replaced OE *heofon*, *egg* replaced OE *ǣg*, *they* replaced OE *hie*. Find 3 more pairs.","build":"List 15 one-syllable words covering core human existence. Confirm they are OE or Norse. What do they have in common about spelling complexity?"}},{"id":"L03","n":3,"unit":1,"title":"Latin Wave One — The Church Brings Latin 600–1066 CE","diff":"easy","bigIdea":"Christianity brought the first wave of Latin into English — not through conquest, but through monasteries, books, and the vocabulary of spiritual life.","story":"In 597 CE, Pope Gregory sent Augustine of Canterbury to convert the Anglo-Saxons. Within 50 years most of England was Christian. With Christianity came Latin — the language of the Church and Scripture. Anglo-Saxon monks borrowed Latin words for concepts their language lacked: *altar, monk, bishop, candle, school, verse, chest*. These words were Anglicized — given English pronunciations and patterns. This First Latin Wave is small in number (a few hundred words) but enormous in cultural importance. They look like English because they were adapted so early.","pattern":"First-Wave Latin (pre-1066) looks English: *school, candle, verse*. Second-Wave Latin via French (1066–1400) looks French: *justice, noble, court*. Third-Wave Latin via Renaissance (1450–1700) looks purely Latin: *auditorium, curriculum, spectrum*. Earlier entry = more Anglicized. Wave of entry predicts how Latin-looking the word is.","connection":"The First Latin Wave shows Latin entered English in three distinct waves, each leaving different spelling fingerprints. Wave of entry = degree of Anglicization.","words":[{"w":"CANDLE","pron":"KA-nduhl","syll":"kae · ndah · l","ety":["Latin *candela* = torch ← *candere* = to shine white","*Cand-* (shine white) → *candid* (shining with truth = frank), *incandescent* (glowing white-hot), *candidate* (Roman candidates wore white togas = *candidatus*). A church candle and a political candidate share the same Latin root."]},{"w":"SCHOOL","pron":"SKOOL","syll":"skuw · l","ety":["Latin *schola* ← Greek *skholē* = leisure, rest, discussion","Originally: free time — leisure was when Greek citizens discussed ideas. *School* = a place of leisured learning. *Scholar* = one who has the luxury of learning. Education was originally a leisure-class activity; the word carries that origin."]},{"w":"MONK","pron":"MUHNGK","syll":"mah · ngk","ety":["Latin *monachus* ← Greek *monakhos* = solitary ← *monos* = alone, single","*Monos* = alone → *monologue, monopoly, monotone, monotheism, monogamy, monarchy, monocle*. A monk was \"one who lives alone\" — and the Greek root for his lifestyle unlocks an entire word family."]},{"w":"VERSE","pron":"VURS","syll":"ver · s","ety":["Latin *versus* = a line, furrow ← *vertere* = to turn","A furrow = one row plowed across a field; at the end you *turn* back. Poets borrowed the metaphor: a verse = one line, then you turn to the next. Same root: *version, revert, convert, universe* (turned into one = everything). Farming gave us poetry's architecture."]},{"w":"ALTAR","pron":"AW-lter","syll":"ao · lter","ety":["Latin *altare* = high place ← *altus* = high","*Altus* = high → *altitude, exalt, alto* (the higher voice). An altar was literally \"the high place\" for offerings. Every time a singer performs *alto* and a priest stands at an *altar*, both use the same Latin word for high."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Separate these into First Wave (Anglicized), Second Wave (French-style), Third Wave (purely Latin): *candle, beauty, curriculum, monk, noble, specimen, school, justice, vacuum, verse*.","trace":"The root *altus* = high. Build the family: *altitude, exalt, alto, altar, exaltation, exhalt*. Find 3 more English words from *altus*.","build":"List 10 pre-1066 Latin loanwords. Then list 10 Renaissance Latin loanwords. Compare how they look spelled and how they sound."}},{"id":"L04","n":4,"unit":1,"title":"The Viking Age — Norse Reshapes English Grammar 793–1100 CE","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"The Vikings gave English its pronouns, simplified its grammar, and contributed hundreds of everyday words — because Old Norse and Old English were close enough to blend at the deepest level.","story":"In 793 CE, Viking raiders attacked Lindisfarne. By 878 CE the Danelaw covered half of England. Because Old English and Old Norse were sister languages (both descended from Proto-Germanic), speakers could largely understand each other. The languages blended uniquely: OE lost its complex case endings (simplifying grammar dramatically), and third-person plural pronouns were completely replaced by Norse forms (*they/their/them*). The Norse *sk-* cluster survived where OE *sc-* was shifting to *sh-* — creating a diagnostic: words with *sk-* = usually Norse. This explains the doublet pair *shirt* (OE *scyrte*) / *skirt* (ON *skyrta*): the same Proto-Germanic garment, named twice through two paths.","pattern":"Norse words carry the *sk-* cluster (*sky, skill, skull, skin, skirt*) where OE had *sc-* (shifting to *sh-*). This diagnostic works: hear a short, punchy English word with *sk-*? Think Norse. Hear the same meaning in a *sh-* word? Think OE. *Ship* (OE) vs *skipper* (Norse). *Share* (OE) vs *score* (Norse, originally a notch cut to keep count).","connection":"Norse and OE were close enough to blend at the grammar level — the rarest and deepest kind of linguistic influence. This created hundreds of doublets and explains why English pronouns are Scandinavian.","words":[{"w":"WINDOW","pron":"WIH-ndoh","syll":"wih · ndow","ety":["Old Norse *vindauga* = wind-eye ← *vindr* (wind) + *auga* (eye)","A window is the \"eye through which wind enters.\" OE called the same thing *ēagþyrel* = \"eye-hole.\" Norse won. Every time you look out a *window* you use a Viking compound noun that defeated its Old English rival."]},{"w":"ANGER","pron":"A-ngger","syll":"ae · ngger","ety":["Old Norse *angr* = distress, grief ← PIE *angh-* = to choke, constrict","PIE *angh-* also gave Latin *angustus* = narrow → English *anguish, anxious, anxiety*. Physical tightness in the chest = emotional distress. Norse path → *anger*; Latin path → *anxiety*. Same PIE body-feeling, two languages, two words."]},{"w":"UGLY","pron":"UH-glee","syll":"ah · gliy","ety":["Old Norse *uggligr* = dreadful, to be feared ← *ugga* = to fear","Originally meant \"frightening\" — something causing terror. Weakened over 600 years to mean merely visually unpleasant. The word lost its terror and settled into aesthetic judgment. Semantic weakening documented from Old Norse through to modern English."]},{"w":"HUSBAND","pron":"HUH-zbuhnd","syll":"hhah · zbah · nd","ety":["Old Norse *húsbóndi* = house dweller/master ← *hús* (house) + *bóndi* (freeholder)","A *husband* was first \"the master of the house,\" not primarily a marital term. The marital sense developed because the householder was naturally his spouse. Journey: household management → domestic role → marital relationship over 300 years."]},{"w":"SKILL","pron":"SKIHL","syll":"skih · l","ety":["Old Norse *skil* = distinction, discernment ← *skilja* = to separate, discern","Originally: ability to *distinguish* — separate good from bad. Evolved to mean practical ability. The *sk-* = Norse signal. OE for the same concept used *cræft* (= *craft*), which narrowed to mean manual or artistic skill specifically."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Find the OE and Norse doublet for each: *shirt/skirt, rear/raise, whole/hale, no/nay, from/fro*. Which survived more strongly in each case?","trace":"Confirm these are Norse by etymology: *husband, knife, egg, die, call, take, want, cast, get, give*.","build":"OE *scyrte* and ON *skyrta* both meant a garment. English kept both as *shirt* and *skirt* with different meanings. Find 3 more OE/Norse doublets where English kept both words with slightly different meanings."}},{"id":"L05","n":5,"unit":1,"title":"1066 — The Day English Vocabulary Changed Forever","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"When William the Conqueror defeated Harold at Hastings in 1066, French became the language of the English court — and English absorbed 10,000+ French words that still define \"educated\" speech today.","story":"October 14, 1066. William, Duke of Normandy, becomes King of England. He speaks no English — only Norman French. His court speaks French. His laws are in French. His Church speaks Latin. For roughly 200 years England was trilingual: French for elites, Latin for clergy, OE for commoners. By 1250 the Norman nobility's descendants were speaking English as their first language — but they brought along a flood of French vocabulary covering law, government, art, fashion, food, warfare. These 10,000+ French loanwords became the formal, elevated register of English that still marks educated speech. The famous result: English farmers raised *cows* (OE) but Norman nobles ate *beef* (French *bœuf*). The conquered named the living animals; the conquerors named the cuisine.","pattern":"The social hierarchy of 1066 is still audible in the register hierarchy of modern English. Old English word = informal/everyday. French word = formal/elevated. Latin word = technical/scholarly. *Ask / question / interrogate. Help / assist / aid. Kingly / royal / sovereign. Cow-pig-sheep / beef-pork-mutton.* The syllable count rises with formality — because it rises with the social ladder of 1066.","connection":"Every \"fancy\" word in English is almost certainly French or Latin. Every \"plain\" word is almost certainly OE or Norse. The Norman Conquest created the register hierarchy that still governs English formality 960 years later.","words":[{"w":"BEEF","pron":"BEEF","syll":"biy · f","ety":["Old French *boef* ← Latin *bos/bovis* = ox","The animal has an OE name (*cow*); the meat has a French name. The farmer spoke English; the lord spoke French. The split: *cow/beef, pig/pork, sheep/mutton, calf/veal* — all reflect who raised the animals and who ate them at the Norman table."]},{"w":"SOVEREIGN","pron":"s-AH-v-r-uh-n","syll":"sovereign","ety":["Old French *souverain* ← Latin *superanus* = supreme ← *super* = above","Same Latin root as *supreme, surpass, superior*. The French path gave the *-eign* ending (like *foreign, reign, feign*) where *-gn* is silent. A *sovereign* = \"the one above all.\" Both French silent-letter pattern AND Latin ancestry visible in one word."]},{"w":"JUSTICE","pron":"JUH-stuhs","syll":"jhah · stah · s","ety":["Old French *justice* ← Latin *justitia* ← *justus* = righteous ← *jus* = law","*Jus* (law) → *just, justify, jurisdiction, jury, judge, judicial, injustice*. The Normans brought the entire French legal vocabulary. English courts conducted proceedings in French until 1362. The vocabulary of law is still 85% French/Latin because of 1066."]},{"w":"PEDIGREE","pron":"PEH-duh-gree","syll":"ped · i · gree","ety":["Old French *pé de grue* = foot of a crane — a folk etymology word","A genealogical chart's branching lines looked like a crane's footprint. The French phrase became the English word for a family tree. The visual origin is completely forgotten. Classic folk-etymology: origin = visual observation, not linguistic analysis."]},{"w":"TOURNAMENT","pron":"TUU-rnuh-muhnt","syll":"tuh · rnah · mah · nt","ety":["Old French *torneiement* ← *torneier* = to joust ← *torner* = to turn","*Torner/tourner* = to turn → *turn, tour, tourist, return, detour, contour*. A tournament = a contest where knights turned to face each other repeatedly. The *-ment* suffix (French noun-forming = result/means of action) entered English wholesale through this wave."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Find the OE word AND French word for each: *hide/conceal, begin/commence, end/finish, buy/purchase, smell/aroma, help/assist*.","trace":"Verify that *dinner, supper, feast, banquet, appetite, sauce, roast, boil* are French. What does this tell you about who controlled cuisine and language simultaneously after 1066?","build":"Research 10 legal terms: *court, verdict, jury, plaintiff, defendant, evidence, attorney, bail, felony, pardon*. Confirm they are French/Latin. Write one sentence explaining why."}},{"id":"L06","n":6,"unit":1,"title":"Middle English — The Glorious Mess 1100–1500 CE","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"Middle English was a language in productive chaos: OE grammar crumbling, French flooding in, spelling unstandardized. Out of this chaos came Chaucer — and eventually Shakespeare.","story":"Between 1100 and 1500, OE's complex case system dissolved (word order became grammatically important for the first time). French poured in at every register. Latin stayed the scholarly language. Spelling was personal: a scribe might spell the same word four ways on the same page. Shakespeare spelled his own name at least six different ways in his own signatures. Geoffrey Chaucer (1343–1400), writing in the London dialect, helped establish a written standard. But spelling wasn't truly fixed until William Caxton introduced the printing press in 1476 — and then it froze mid-Great Vowel Shift. Pronunciation kept evolving for 200 more years. Every \"irregular\" English spelling is a snapshot from 1476.","pattern":"\"Silent letters\" fall into three categories: (1) *Pronunciation-preserved*: *knight, kneel, wraith* — letters that were pronounced in 1476, now silent. (2) *Scholar-inserted*: *debt, doubt, scissors, island* — letters added in the 16th century to show Latin roots that were never pronounced. (3) *Dialect-transferred*: *ghost* — Flemish typesetter conventions imposed on English words. Knowing which category a silent letter belongs to reveals its linguistic origin.","connection":"Middle English is when Latin, French, and OE merged into the beautiful, \"illogical\" spelling system we have today. Every silent letter is a fossil — either of a real old sound, a scholar's decision, or a foreign typesetter's habit.","words":[{"w":"DEBT","pron":"DEHT","syll":"deh · t","ety":["Old French *dette* ← Latin *debitum* = thing owed ← *debere* = to owe","French had *dette* — no *b*. Renaissance scholars reinserted the *b* to show the Latin root *debitum*. The *b* was never pronounced in English; it exists purely as an etymological marker. *Debt, doubt* (*dubium*), *subtle* (*subtilis*) — all scholar-inserted silent letters."]},{"w":"ISLAND","pron":"EYE-luhnd","syll":"ay · lah · nd","ety":["Old English *iegland* = water-land ← *ieg* = island + *land*","Purely OE — no *s*. Renaissance scholars mistakenly connected it to French *isle* (Latin *insula*) and inserted a silent *s*: *i-s-land*. The *s* was never pronounced and was added by false etymology. A scholar's mistake 500 years ago is permanent in modern spelling."]},{"w":"SCISSORS","pron":"SIH-zerz","syll":"sih · zer · z","ety":["Old French *cisoires* ← Latin *caedere* = to cut","French *cisoires* had no *sc-*. Renaissance scholars added *sc* to show Latin *caedere*. The *c* in *scissors* has never been pronounced in English but has been spelled for 400+ years. It shows the Latin root while the French pronunciation ignores it."]},{"w":"GHOST","pron":"GOHST","syll":"gow · st","ety":["Old English *gāst* = spirit, breath ← Proto-Germanic *gaistaz*","OE had no *h* in *gāst*. Caxton's Flemish typesetters — whose Dutch word for spirit was *gheest* — inserted the *gh*. The *gh* in *ghost* is a Dutch typesetter's home language permanently embedded in the English word for spirit."]},{"w":"RECEIPT","pron":"r-ih-s-EE-t","syll":"receipt","ety":["Old French *recette* ← Latin *recipere* = to receive ← *re-* + *capere* = take back","French *recette* had no *p*. The *p* was reinserted in the 16th century to show Latin *recipere*. The *p* in *receipt* has never been pronounced in English but has been written for 500 years. It is an etymological decoration, not a phonological one."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Categorize these silent letters: *b* in *comb*, *w* in *sword*, *l* in *calm*, *p* in *psychology*, *k* in *knight*, *s* in *island*. Which of the three categories does each belong to?","trace":"Find a page from Chaucer's Canterbury Tales. Identify 10 words: which are OE, which are French, which are Latin borrowings already present by 1400?","build":"If Caxton had frozen spelling in 1976 instead of 1476, what would English spelling look like? Pick 5 words with major spelling/pronunciation gaps and write how they might be spelled."}},{"id":"L07","n":7,"unit":1,"title":"The Great Vowel Shift — Why Bite Once Sounded Like Beet","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"Between 1400 and 1700, all English long vowels shifted upward simultaneously — the most dramatic change in English pronunciation history, and the primary reason English spelling looks different from how it sounds.","story":"The Great Vowel Shift (GVS) was a chain reaction. The long vowel /aː/ raised to /eː/, which raised the vowel above it, which raised the next, until the highest vowels became diphthongs. Before the GVS: *bite* = /biːt/ (rhymed with \"beet\"), *meet* = /meːt/ (rhymed with \"mate\"), *name* = /naːmə/ (roughly \"nah-muh\"). After: modern pronunciations. The printing press froze spelling in 1476 — right mid-shift. Pronunciation kept moving for 200 more years. The gap between English spelling and English sound was born in this gap between the press (1476) and the end of the shift (~1700). The GVS explains ~60% of vowel exceptions in English spelling rules.","pattern":"The GVS raised every long vowel one step: *a* sounds like /eɪ/ (was /aː/), *e* sounds like /iː/ (was /eː/), *i* sounds like /aɪ/ (was /iː/). Every English long vowel is \"one step higher than expected\" because of the GVS. Scottish English and some Canadian dialects preserved pre-GVS vowels in words like *house* (\"hoose\"), which is why those dialects sound different from standard American or British English.","connection":"The GVS explains why English phonics rules have so many exceptions — the \"exceptions\" are words whose spelling was frozen before the shift completed. This lesson connects directly to every spelling bee where a vowel \"breaks the rules.\"","words":[{"w":"BITE","pron":"BEYET","syll":"bay · t","ety":["Old English *bītan* = to bite ← Proto-Germanic *bītanan*","Pre-GVS: /biːt/ (= \"beet\"). The shift diphthongized /iː/ to /aɪ/. Spelling stayed *bite*. If the GVS had not happened, *bite* would rhyme with *beet* — exactly as the spelling suggests it should. The spelling is honest; the pronunciation moved."]},{"w":"MEET","pron":"MEET","syll":"miy · t","ety":["Old English *mētan* = to meet ← Proto-Germanic *mōtijanan*","Pre-GVS: /meːt/ (rhymed with modern \"mate\"). Raised to /iː/. Now rhymes with \"feet.\" The word *mate* (from the same Germanic root via different path) preserves roughly what *meet* once sounded like — two words, same origin, frozen at different moments of the shift."]},{"w":"NAME","pron":"NAYM","syll":"ney · m","ety":["Old English *nama* = name ← Proto-Germanic *namô*","Pre-GVS: /naːmə/ (roughly \"nah-muh\"). The unstressed final *-a* was dropped. The *a* was raised from /aː/ to /eɪ/. Modern \"name\" sounds nothing like OE *nama* — but both use the letter *a*, because the spelling froze before the vowel finished moving."]},{"w":"HOUSE","pron":"HOWS","syll":"hhaw · s","ety":["Old English *hūs* = house ← Proto-Germanic *hūsą*","Pre-GVS: /huːs/ (= \"hoose\"). The *ū* diphthongized to /aʊ/. Scottish English still preserves /huːs/ in some dialects — a vowel frozen before the GVS reached the north. The GVS was a southern English phenomenon that didn't reach all dialects equally."]},{"w":"TIME","pron":"TEYEM","syll":"tay · m","ety":["Old English *tīma* ← Proto-Germanic *tīmô*","Pre-GVS: /tiːmə/ (roughly \"teem-uh\"). The final *-a* dropped; the *ī* diphthongized to /aɪ/. Modern \"time\" sounds nothing like OE *tīma* — but the spelling preserves the *i* that was raised. The letter *i* in time = honest 1476 spelling of the pre-shift vowel."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Find 5 words where the vowel does NOT match what the letter \"should\" sound like by basic phonics. Explain each using the GVS (the vowel was raised from what the spelling shows).","trace":"Compare how *house, out, about, mouth* sound in modern British vs American vs Scottish English. Which dialect preserves the pre-GVS vowel closest?","build":"The GVS raised long vowels. Short vowels were mostly unaffected. Find 5 long-vowel/short-vowel minimal pairs (*bite/bit, meet/met, name/nap, time/Tim, house/hussy*) that show the contrast."}},{"id":"L08","n":8,"unit":1,"title":"Renaissance Latin — When Scholars Made English Sound Learned","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"In the 1500s–1600s, English scholars imported thousands of Latin and Greek words to elevate the language — creating \"inkhorn terms\" mocked as pretentious, but most of which survived to become standard English.","story":"The Renaissance revived classical learning. English scholars felt English lacked the vocabulary for serious thought. So they imported Latin and Greek wholesale, barely changing the words. Critics called these \"inkhorn terms\" — existing only in ink, never in real speech. Words like *impede, dismiss, celebrate, exist, expectation* were mocked as pretentious in the 1500s. But most survived and are now standard English. The Renaissance also introduced Latin plurals — *datum/data, criterion/criteria, phenomenon/phenomena, alumnus/alumni* — creating grammatical confusion that still generates arguments about whether \"data is\" or \"data are\" is correct. The answer depends on whether you honor the Latin plural or treat the word as fully English.","pattern":"Renaissance Latin loanwords look like their Latin sources: *specimen* (← *specimen*), *genius* (← *genius*), *vacuum* (← *vacuum*), *curriculum* (← *curriculum*). This wave also introduced the Latin/Greek irregular plural forms. Knowing the Latin noun class predicts the plural: *-us/-i* (2nd declension masculine: *alumnus/alumni*), *-um/-a* (2nd declension neuter: *datum/data*), *-is/-es* (Greek 3rd declension: *crisis/crises, thesis/theses*).","connection":"The Renaissance Latin wave created the three-tier synonym system unique to English: OE word (informal) + French word (formal) + Latin/Greek word (technical). No other language has this triple-layer system.","words":[{"w":"SPECIMEN","pron":"SPEH-suh-muhn","syll":"spec · i · men","ety":["Latin *specimen* = a sample, sign ← *specere* = to look","*Specere* = to look → *spectacle, inspect, perspective, suspicious, specious, species, spectrum, conspicuous, perspicacious*. A *specimen* = \"something to be looked at.\" One of the most productive Latin roots in the database: 36 attested English words."]},{"w":"CURRICULUM","pron":"ker-IH-kyuh-luhm","syll":"ker · ih · kyah · lah · m","ety":["Latin *curriculum* = a running course, race ← *currere* = to run","*Currere* = to run → *current* (running water), *cursive* (running handwriting), *cursor* (a runner), *concurrent, excursion, incur, recur*. Corpus data: *currere* generated 59 English words. A school *curriculum* = \"the race-course you run\" to earn an education."]},{"w":"GENIUS","pron":"JEE-nyuhs","syll":"jhiy · nyah · s","ety":["Latin *genius* = an attendant spirit ← *gignere* = to beget","Originally: the divine spirit one is born with. Romans believed each person had a *genius* — a guardian spirit. Evolved to mean the exceptional quality itself. *Gignere* → *generous, genuine, genial, congenital, indigenous, gender, genre, generate, genesis*."]},{"w":"ANONYMOUS","pron":"uh-NAH-nuh-muhs","syll":"ah · naa · nah · mah · s","ety":["Greek *anōnymos* ← *an-* (without) + *onoma* (name)","*Onoma* = name → *synonym* (same name), *antonym* (opposite name), *pseudonym* (false name), *homonym* (same name for different things), *acronym* (beginning-letter name), *eponym* (named after a person). Pattern: words ending in *-onym* are all about names."]},{"w":"VOCABULARY","pron":"voh-KA-byuh-leh-ree","syll":"vo · cab · u · lar · y","ety":["Medieval Latin *vocabularium* ← *vocabulum* = name, word ← *vocare* = to call","*Vocare* = to call → *vocal, vocation, invoke, advocate, provoke, evoke, revoke, convoke, equivocate*. Corpus: *vocare* generated 63 English words. Irony: the word for a list of words (*vocabulary*) was itself an imported Renaissance Latin term."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Find the OE word, French word, AND Latin/Greek word for: thinking (think/ponder/cogitate), seeing (look/view/observe), beginning (start/commence/initiate), ending (end/finish/terminate), asking (ask/question/interrogate).","trace":"These were mocked as \"inkhorn terms\" in the 1500s but survived: *absurd, exist, dismiss, celebrate, emulate, meditate*. Find their Latin originals. Why do you think they survived the mockery?","build":"Latin plural patterns: *datum/data, medium/media, criterion/criteria, phenomenon/phenomena, alumnus/alumni, bacterium/bacteria*. Identify the Latin noun class of each and explain the plural rule."}},{"id":"L09","n":9,"unit":1,"title":"The Printing Press — When Spelling Froze in 1476","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"William Caxton brought the printing press to England in 1476, and the spelling he chose — London dialect, mid-Great Vowel Shift — became the permanent standard forever.","story":"Before printing, spelling was personal. Caxton set up his press at Westminster in 1476 and needed consistent spelling to set type efficiently. He chose the London dialect — the prestige form of English. He employed Flemish typesetters who used Dutch spelling conventions (the *gh* in *ghost* is Dutch). The press standardized spelling based on one dialect, one moment, right in the middle of the Great Vowel Shift. After 1476, spelling was fixed. Pronunciation kept evolving for 200 more years. The gap between English spelling and English sound was born that year and has never closed. Without the printing press, English spelling might have evolved continuously to match pronunciation — as it does in Spanish and Finnish, where spelling and sound correspond closely today.","pattern":"The three categories of \"strange\" English spelling: (1) Mid-GVS snapshots: vowels frozen mid-shift (*bite, night, through*). (2) Scholar interventions: silent letters inserted to show Latin roots (*debt, doubt, subtle, scissors*). (3) Typesetter habits: *ghost* with Dutch *gh*. Every \"irregular\" spelling has one of these three explanations. There are no truly arbitrary spellings — only spellings whose history needs to be understood.","connection":"The printing press is the reason English spelling seems arbitrary — it isn't arbitrary, but it reflects 1476, not 2026. Every lesson in this program is about bridging that 550-year gap.","words":[{"w":"PARLIAMENT","pron":"PAH-rluh-muhnt","syll":"paa · rlah · mah · nt","ety":["Old French *parlement* ← *parler* = to speak ← Vulgar Latin *parabolare*","*Parler* → *parley* (a negotiation), *parole* (spoken word of honor), *parable* (spoken beside the point = allegory). A Parliament = \"a speaking place.\" The *-ment* suffix (French noun-forming) entered English wholesale after 1066 and was thoroughly established by 1476."]},{"w":"THROUGH","pron":"THROO","syll":"thruw","ety":["Old English *þurh* = through ← Proto-Germanic *þurh*","Pre-1476 this word had 20+ spellings: *thurh, thorh, thrugh, thurȝ*. Caxton chose one — it became permanent. The *-ough* spelling = one of its six pronunciation values: /θruː/. The press crystallized one spelling out of the Middle English chaos; the sound has moved while the letters stayed."]},{"w":"LANGUAGE","pron":"LA-nggwuhj","syll":"lae · nggwah · jh","ety":["Old French *langage* ← *langue* = tongue ← Latin *lingua*","*Lingua* → *linguistic, bilingual, multilingual*. The spelling *language* came through French; the pronunciation evolved after 1476. The *-uage* ending is French. A purely Latin word would be *lingua*. This word shows both its French journey (the spelling) and its post-1476 pronunciation shift."]},{"w":"SUBTLE","pron":"s-UH-t-uh-l","syll":"subtle","ety":["Old French *soutil* ← Latin *subtilis* = fine ← *sub-* + *tela* = woven below","French had *soutil* — no *b*. Renaissance scholars added *b* to show Latin *subtilis*. The *b* was never pronounced. Without the printing press to freeze it, the *b* might have been dropped. The press preserved the scholar's choice for all time."]},{"w":"STOMACH","pron":"STUH-muhk","syll":"stah · mah · k","ety":["Old French *estomac* ← Latin *stomachus* ← Greek *stomakhos* = throat, gullet ← *stoma* = mouth","*Stoma* = mouth → *stomatology* (study of the mouth), *stomatitis* (mouth inflammation). Greek *stomakhos* originally meant the throat/gullet, not the organ we call the stomach. The meaning narrowed from \"throat\" to \"digestive organ\" over centuries — semantic narrowing documented in the word's journey from Greek to English."]}],"practice":{"decode":"If Caxton had been from Yorkshire instead of London, English might have standardized around Yorkshire dialect. Find 3 dialect words from northern England that might have become \"standard\" instead.","trace":"Languages with consistent spelling: Spanish, Finnish, Italian. Languages with inconsistent spelling: English, French. What historical factors (printing press timing, GVS timing, borrowing history) explain this difference?","build":"Research how English spelling reformers (Noah Webster in America, George Bernard Shaw, the Simplified Spelling Board) tried to regularize English spelling. Why did they largely fail?"}},{"id":"L10","n":10,"unit":1,"title":"Modern English — A World Language That Never Stopped Borrowing","diff":"hard","bigIdea":"From 1600 to now, English absorbed vocabulary from every empire it built, every technology it invented, every culture it traded with — making it the language with the largest documented vocabulary of any language in history.","story":"The British Empire (1600–1950) made English global, and a global language absorbs from everywhere. From India: *shampoo, bungalow, loot, jungle, thug, pyjamas, bandana, dinghy, cheetah*. From the Americas: *chocolate, tomato, potato, hurricane, canoe, tobacco, barbecue*. From Africa via Swahili/Arabic: *safari, zombie, voodoo, jumbo*. From Australia: *kangaroo, boomerang*. Meanwhile English invented words: *blurb* (1907, Gelett Burgess), *nerd* (first printed 1950 in Dr. Seuss; slang meaning emerged ~1951), *selfie* (2002, Australian internet forums), *googol* (1938, named by a nine-year-old child). The 129K database shows: 0.4% Japanese, 0.7% Arabic, 0.3% Sanskrit, 0.3% Hindi — small percentages representing hundreds of words each, absorbed through specific historical contact.","pattern":"English word formation uses eight simultaneous processes: (1) Borrowing (*sushi, angst, karaoke*), (2) Compounding (*bookworm, brainstorm*), (3) Derivation (*unhappiness, postmodern*), (4) Clipping (*phone, blog, gym*), (5) Blending/Portmanteau (*brunch, smog, podcast*), (6) Acronyms (*laser, radar, scuba*), (7) Eponyms (*sandwich, boycott, algorithm*), (8) Backformation (*edit* from *editor*, *donate* from *donation*). No other world language uses all eight simultaneously at scale.","connection":"Unit 1 gave you the complete timeline: PIE → OE → Norse → Church Latin → Norman French → Renaissance Latin/Greek → Colonial borrowing → Modern coinage. Every lesson in Units 2–10 goes deep into one of these layers.","words":[{"w":"KANGAROO","pron":"ka-ngger-OO","syll":"kan · ga · roo","ety":["Guugu Yimithirr (Australian Aboriginal) *gangurru* = a large grey kangaroo, recorded 1770","Joseph Banks (naturalist on Cook's 1770 expedition) first recorded the local name on 12 July 1770 — Cook himself noted it on 4 August. The popular myth that it means \"I don't understand\" is false — it is a real Guugu Yimithirr word for a specific kangaroo. 250 years in English, still retaining the phonology of an Australian Aboriginal language."]},{"w":"RADAR","pron":"RAY-dahr","syll":"rey · daa · r","ety":["English acronym: Radio Detection And Ranging, coined 1941 US Navy","Created as a technical acronym, immediately used as a common noun. Within a generation, speakers forgot it was an acronym. Plural *radars*, verb *to radar* followed. When an acronym becomes a common word it has completed the full lexical lifecycle. Compare: *laser, scuba, sonar, NATO, AWOL*."]},{"w":"JUGGERNAUT","pron":"JUH-ger-nawt","syll":"jhah · ger · nao · t","ety":["Sanskrit *Jagannātha* = Lord of the Universe ← *jagat* (world) + *nātha* (lord)","A Hindu deity's enormous temple cart was exaggerated by missionaries. By the 1800s *juggernaut* in English = any unstoppable force. A Sanskrit divine name → English secular metaphor. *Jagannātha* → *juggernaut*: five syllables become three through Anglicization. Etymology records colonial-era exaggeration embedded permanently in vocabulary."]},{"w":"SERENDIPITY","pron":"s-eh-r-uh-n-d-IH-p-ih-t-ee","syll":"serendipity","ety":["Coined 1754 by Horace Walpole ← *Serendip* = Arabic/Persian name for Sri Lanka","Walpole coined this from a Persian fairy tale. *Serendip* = Arabic *Sarandīb* = Sanskrit *Siṃhaladvīpa* = \"Island of Lions\" = Sri Lanka. A coined English word from a Persian tale, named for Sri Lanka, meaning happy accident. One word contains the linguistic traces of four civilizations crossing 25 centuries."]},{"w":"BUNGALOW","pron":"BUH-ngguh-loh","syll":"bah · nggah · low","ety":["Hindi *bāṃglā* = of Bengal, Bengali-style ← Sanskrit *Vaṅga* = Bengal","A Bengali-style house with a veranda. Entered English through British colonial India (1800s). The house style spread globally; the Indian word traveled with it. Now used worldwide for a single-story house, the Bengali origin completely invisible in everyday use."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Identify which of the 8 word-formation processes created: *blog, podcast, laser, smog, brunch, motel, edit, donate, selfie, radar, saxophone, nerd*.","trace":"Find 5 English words from British colonial contact with India, 5 from the Americas, 5 from Africa. Write one sentence about what each word's origin reveals about history.","build":"Create 3 portmanteau words for modern concepts that don't yet have a dedicated word. Define them and show the blending strategy."}},{"id":"L11","n":11,"unit":2,"title":"Latin — The Language That Refused to Die","diff":"easy","bigIdea":"Latin was declared a dead language over 1,500 years ago. But it is the single largest source of English vocabulary — because it never really died. It transformed into French, Spanish, Italian, Portuguese, and Romanian, and English borrowed from all of them.","story":"Latin peaked as a spoken language during the Roman Empire (roughly 100 BCE – 400 CE). When the empire fell, Latin split into regional dialects: France got French, Spain got Spanish, Italy got Italian. Meanwhile, Classical Latin survived as the written language of the Church and scholarship. English absorbed Latin through five distinct channels: (1) directly from Church Latin before 1066, (2) through Old French after 1066, (3) directly from Classical Latin during the Renaissance, (4) through scientific Latin in the 1600s–1800s, (5) through Spanish and Italian as England traded globally. The corpus confirms this layered absorption: 45,519 Latin-origin words in the 129K database — 35.4% of all words.","pattern":"Latin verbs leave different spelling patterns depending on conjugation: 1st conjugation (-are): *amare* → *amateur, amorous*; 2nd conjugation (-ēre): *tenēre* → *tenant, retain*; 3rd conjugation (-ere): *legere* → *legible, lecture*; 4th conjugation (-īre): *audīre* → *audible, audience*. Knowing the conjugation predicts which English relatives a word has.","connection":"Latin's five channels of entry into English created a layered vocabulary. Knowing which channel a word entered through tells you its spelling pattern and how Anglicized it appears.","words":[{"w":"AMATEUR","pron":"A-muh-tur","syll":"ae · mah · ter","ety":["French ← Latin *amator* = a lover ← *amare* = to love (1st conjugation)","An *amateur* does something out of love rather than pay. *Amare* → *amorous* (full of love), *enamored* (in love), *amiable* (loveable), *amity* (friendship), *inimical* (not friendly = hostile). Note: *amateur* ends in *-eur* not *-er* — it came through French before English."]},{"w":"TENANT","pron":"TEH-nuhnt","syll":"teh · nah · nt","ety":["Old French *tenant* ← Latin *tenēre* = to hold (2nd conjugation)","A *tenant* = \"one who holds\" a lease. *Tenēre* → *tenacious* (holding on), *detention* (held away), *contain* (hold together), *abstain* (hold away from), *lieutenant* (holds the place of the commander), *tenure* (the holding of a position). Corpus: *tenere* generates 32 English words."]},{"w":"LEGIBLE","pron":"l-EH-j-uh-b-uh-l","syll":"legible","ety":["Latin *legibilis* ← *legere* = to read/gather (3rd conjugation)","*Legere* → *lecture* (a reading), *select* (gather out), *elect* (gather out), *collect* (gather together), *neglect* (not-gather = ignore), *legend* (a thing to be read), *intelligent* (gathering-between = understanding). Corpus: *legere* generates 40 English words."]},{"w":"AUDIENCE","pron":"AH-dee-uhns","syll":"aa · diy · ah · ns","ety":["Latin *audientia* ← *audīre* = to hear (4th conjugation)","*Audīre* → *audible, audit, auditorium, audition*. ⚠️ BEE TRAP: *audacious* comes from *audere* (to dare) — different Latin root, same *aud-* beginning. An *audience* = \"a hearing\" — the people who come to hear. Corpus: *audire* generates 29 English words."]},{"w":"FINISH","pron":"FIH-nihsh","syll":"fih · nih · sh","ety":["Old French *finiss-* ← Latin *fīnīre* = to end, limit (4th conjugation)","*Finis* = end → *final, finite, infinite, define* (set the limits of), *refine* (re-limit = purify), *confine* (limit together), *finale, fine* (a payment that ends a dispute). Note how *fine* meaning \"penalty\" and *finish* meaning \"to end\" share the same Latin root for \"limit.\""]}],"practice":{"decode":"Group these by their Latin conjugation class: *portable, tenant, lecture, audible, amorous, vision, script, final, vocal, current*.","trace":"Build the full word family for *tenēre* = hold: list 10 English derivatives (*tenant, tenacious, tenure, detention, contain, abstain, lieutenant, retention, pertinent, impertinent*).","build":"The root *amare* = to love. List all English words you can find from this root. Then find the French-path words (entered through French, ending in *-eur* or French forms) vs direct Latin words."}},{"id":"L12","n":12,"unit":2,"title":"Facere — The Most Productive Latin Root in English","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"Latin *facere* = to make/do appears in 449 English words through four spelling forms: *fac-*, *fect-*, *fic-*, *feat*. Recognizing these four forms unlocks an entire vocabulary universe.","story":"*Facere* = to make, to do (Latin 3rd conjugation, irregular). Like all Latin verbs, it has two main stems: the present stem (*fac-/fic-*) and the perfect passive participle (*fact-/fect-*). English borrowed from both at different times through different languages. *Fact* (thing done), *factory* (place of making), *perfect* (thoroughly done), *affect* (done toward), *infect* (done into), *defect* (done away from), *effect* (done out of), *office* (place for doing), *efficient* (doing outward = working well), *sufficient* (doing enough), *artificial* (made by art), *manufacture* (made by hand), *benefit* (good doing), *malefactor* (evil doer)... The corpus shows 449 words — more than any other single Latin verb.","pattern":"*Facere* appears in four forms: (1) *fac-/fact-* at word start: *fact, factory, factor, faculty, facilitate*. (2) *-fect-* with prefix: *perfect, affect, defect, infect, effect, reflect, confect*. (3) *-fic-* compressed with prefix: *office, efficient, sufficient, artificial, magnificent, scientific, prolific*. (4) *feat/feit* through French: *feat, feature, defeat, forfeit, counterfeit*. Seeing any of these four forms = *facere* is present.","connection":"*Facere* shows how one Latin root, borrowed at different times through different languages, produces wildly different-looking English words. Recognizing the four forms (*fac/fect/fic/feat*) is a championship-level decoding skill.","words":[{"w":"MAGNIFICENT","pron":"m-a-g-n-IH-f-uh-s-uh-n-t","syll":"magnificent","ety":["Latin *magnificus* ← *magnus* (great) + *facere* (to make)","Literally \"making great.\" The *-fic-* = compressed *facere*. *Magnus* = great → *magnitude, magnify, magnanimous* (great-souled), *magnate* (a great person), *major* (greater = comparative of *magnus*), *maximum* (the greatest). Compound: \"great-making\" = magnificent."]},{"w":"ARTIFICIAL","pron":"ah-rtuh-FIH-shuhl","syll":"aa · rtah · fih · shah · l","ety":["Latin *artificialis* ← *ars/artis* (skill/art) + *facere* (to make)","Made by skill/art. *Ars/artis* → *art, artist, artisan* (a skilled maker), *artifact* (thing made by skill), *artful, inert* (without skill = not moving), *inertia*. The *-ific-* = the *fic-* compressed form. Art + making = artificial."]},{"w":"DEFECT","pron":"DEE-fehkt","syll":"diy · feh · kt","ety":["Latin *defectus* ← *de-* (away) + *facere* (to make/do)","Literally \"done away from.\" A defect = where something is undone/missing. The *-fect* suffix = perfect passive participle of *facere*. Compare: *perfect* (*per-* = thoroughly + *fect* = done = completely done), *infect* (*in-* = into = contaminated), *effect* (*ex-* = out = result/outcome)."]},{"w":"FORFEIT","pron":"FAW-rfiht","syll":"for · feit","ety":["Old French *forfait* ← *fors* (outside) + *fait* (done) ← Latin *facere*","Done outside the rules = a violation, then a penalty. *Fait* = French form of *facere*'s participle (*factus* → *fait*). Same root: *fact* (thing done), *feature* (thing made), *feat* (an achievement = a thing done), *defeat* (*de-* = un-done = overcome). French path vs Latin path, same root."]},{"w":"SATISFACTION","pron":"sa-tuh-SFA-kshuhn","syll":"sae · tah · sfae · kshah · n","ety":["Latin *satisfactio* ← *satis* (enough) + *facere* (to make) + *-ion*","Making enough. *Satis* = enough → *satisfy, saturate* (fill to enough = drench), *sate* (fill completely). The compound: when you have made enough, you are satisfied. *Dissatisfaction* = *dis-* + *satis* + *facere* + *-ion* = not-enough-making. Four morphemes, one word."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Identify the *facere* form hidden in: *office, sufficient, scientific, rectify, purify, horrify, mischief, chief, achieve, perfect, infect, magnificent*.","trace":"Draw a word family tree for *facere*: list all 4 forms, then 5 words from each form. Count your total — how close do you get to the database's 449?","build":"Find 5 English words where *facere* combined with each Latin prefix: *ab-* (abiect?), *con-* (confect), *de-* (defect), *in-* (infect), *per-* (perfect), *re-* (refect?). What does each prefix+*facere* compound mean literally?"}},{"id":"L13","n":13,"unit":2,"title":"Latin Prefixes as Directional Maps","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"Latin prepositions became English prefixes, and they are literal spatial metaphors — 12 prefixes that unlock 5,000+ English words once you see them as directions in space.","story":"Latin prepositions described physical space before they described conceptual relationships. *Ab* meant \"away from\" physically before it meant \"conceptually away from.\" When Latin speakers combined *ab-* + *cedere* (to go), they meant \"going away from a position physically.\" Over centuries, the physical meanings became conceptual: *inter-* (between places) → (between ideas). This is why knowing the prefix = knowing the spatial/conceptual relationship inside the word. The 12 core prefixes: *ab-* (away), *ad-* (toward), *con-* (together), *de-* (down/away), *ex-* (out), *in-* (into or not), *per-* (through), *pre-* (before), *pro-* (forward), *re-* (back), *sub-* (under), *trans-* (across).","pattern":"Latin prefixes ASSIMILATE — they change shape to match the first letter of the root they attach to, always resulting in a doubled consonant: *ad-* before *g* → *ag-* (aggrandize), *al-* (alleviate), *ap-* (appease), *as-* (assiduous), *at-* (attenuate). *con-* before *l* → *col-* (collaborate), before *r* → *cor-* (corroborate). *in-* before *l* → *il-* (illicit), before *m* → *im-* (impossible), before *r* → *ir-* (irrefutable). The DOUBLED LETTER in a word = assimilation = always the spelling signal.","connection":"Latin prefixes are directional spatial metaphors. Once you know the 12 core prefixes and their assimilation rules, you can identify the prefix in any Latin-derived word and predict its directional meaning.","words":[{"w":"SURREPTITIOUS","pron":"sur-uh-PTIH-shuhs","syll":"sur · rep · ti · tious","ety":["Latin *surrepticius* ← *sub-* (under) + *rapere* (to seize)","*Sub-* before *r* → *sur-* (assimilation = double *r*). \"Seized from under\" = done secretively. *Rapere* = seize → *rapacious* (seizing greedily), *rapture* (seized by joy), *rapid* (moving as if seized). The double *r* in *surreptitious* = assimilation signal for hidden *sub-* prefix."]},{"w":"COLLATERAL","pron":"kuh-LA-ter-uhl","syll":"kah · lae · ter · ah · l","ety":["Latin *collateralis* ← *con-* (together) + *latus/lateris* (side)","*Con-* before *l* → *col-*. \"At the side together\" = side by side. *Latus/lateris* = side → *lateral, bilateral, unilateral, multilateral, equilateral*. Every *-lateral* word contains Latin for \"side.\" The double *l* = assimilation of *con-* + *l-*root."]},{"w":"AGGREGATE","pron":"A-gruh-guht","syll":"ae · grah · gah · t","ety":["Latin *aggregatus* ← *ad-* (toward) + *gregare* (to gather in a flock)","*Ad-* before *g* → *ag-*. \"Gathered toward.\" *Grex/gregis* = flock → *gregarious* (loves flocks = sociable), *congregation* (gathered together), *segregation* (separated from the flock), *egregious* (out of the flock = outstandingly bad). One shepherd's metaphor generates a vocabulary cluster."]},{"w":"IMMORAL","pron":"ih-MAW-ruhl","syll":"ih · mao · rah · l","ety":["Latin *immoralis* ← *in-* (not) + *moralis* ← *mos/moris* = custom, habit","*In-* before *m* → *im-*. \"Not of good custom/habit.\" *Mos/moris* = custom → *moral, morality, morals, mores* (the customs of a society). ⚠️ *in-* also means \"into\" — *immortal* = \"not mortal\" (negation), but *immerse* = \"put into the sea\" (direction). Context and definition distinguish which *in-* is present."]},{"w":"TRANSGRESS","pron":"tra-NZGREHS","syll":"trae · nzgreh · s","ety":["Latin *transgressus* ← *trans-* (across) + *gradi* (to step)","Stepping across a boundary. *Gradi* = step → *grade* (a step in a scale), *gradual* (step by step), *graduate* (one who steps up), *degrade* (step down), *retrograde* (step backward), *ingredient* (stepping into = a component), *aggression* (stepping toward aggressively). Corpus: *gradi* generates 40 English words."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Identify the assimilated prefix and its original form in: *collect* (con-+l), *aggressive* (ad-+g), *annotation* (ad-+n), *appreciate* (ad-+p), *corrode* (con-+r), *suppress* (sub-+p), *suffuse* (sub-+f), *illuminate* (in-+l).","trace":"Take *cedere* = to go. Build all English words using different Latin prefixes: *ac-cede, con-cede, ex-ceed, pro-ceed, re-cede, se-cede, pre-cede, in-ter-cede*. What does each mean literally?","build":"The prefix *in-* has two meanings: \"not\" and \"into.\" Find 5 examples of each. How do you tell which meaning applies? (Hint: definition + root meaning together reveal it.)"}},{"id":"L14","n":14,"unit":2,"title":"Latin Noun Families — Declensions and Their English Descendants","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"Latin had five noun declension patterns — five types of endings — and each one left different fingerprints in English plurals, adjectives, and derivatives.","story":"Latin nouns changed their endings based on grammatical role (case), number (singular/plural), and gender (masculine/feminine/neuter). When these nouns entered English through French or directly from Latin, they carried their ending patterns with them. The 2nd declension masculine (*-us/-i*) gives *alumnus/alumni, radius/radii, cactus/cacti*. The 2nd declension neuter (*-um/-a*) gives *datum/data, medium/media, curriculum/curricula, bacterium/bacteria*. The 3rd declension irregular gives *corpus/corpora, genus/genera, opus/opera*. The Greek 3rd declension (*-is/-es*) gives *crisis/crises, thesis/theses, analysis/analyses, phenomenon*... wait, *phenomenon* is Greek neuter *-on/-a* → *phenomena*. Each pattern has a rule.","pattern":"Latin/Greek irregular plurals are formed from the Latin/Greek source word's own plural, not from English rules. Three key patterns: (1) 2nd masc. *-us → -i*: *alumnus/alumni, radius/radii, syllabus/syllabi, cactus/cacti, nucleus/nuclei*. (2) 2nd neut. *-um → -a*: *datum/data, medium/media, curriculum/curricula, bacterium/bacteria*. (3) Greek *-is → -es*: *crisis/crises, thesis/theses, analysis/analyses, basis/bases, axis/axes, parenthesis/parentheses*. Knowing the Latin/Greek source class = knowing the correct English plural.","connection":"Latin/Greek irregular plurals are not exceptions — they are the Latin/Greek plural rules imported directly into English. Knowing the source language class predicts the plural form.","words":[{"w":"RADIUS","pron":"RAY-dee-uhs","syll":"rey · diy · ah · s","ety":["Latin *radius* = spoke of a wheel, ray of light — 2nd declension masculine","Plural: *radii*. Same root → *radiate, radiation, radio, radar, radiant*. The *-us* → *-i* plural rule: 2nd declension masculine nouns. Knowing Latin tells you the plural before you need to memorize it."]},{"w":"MEDIUM","pron":"MEE-dee-uhm","syll":"miy · diy · ah · m","ety":["Latin *medium* = middle — 2nd declension neuter ← *medius* = middle","Plural: *media*. *Medius* = middle → *median, mediate, medieval, Mediterranean* (middle of the earth = the sea in the middle). ⚠️ Modern usage debate: \"the media is\" vs \"the media are\" — the argument is between treating *media* as fully English (singular allowed) vs honoring the Latin neuter plural."]},{"w":"PHENOMENON","pron":"f-uh-n-AH-m-uh-n-ah-n","syll":"phenomenon","ety":["Greek *phainomenon* = thing that appears ← *phainein* = to show — Greek neuter","Plural: *phenomena* (neuter -on → -a, Greek). The same *phainein* = to appear → *fantasy* (appearing in the mind), *phase* (an appearance), *phantom* (an appearance), *diaphanous* (shining through), *epiphany* (appearing upon you = sudden realization). One Greek root, six English words through different paths."]},{"w":"CRISIS","pron":"KREYE-suhs","syll":"kray · sah · s","ety":["Greek *krisis* = a decisive moment ← *krinein* = to judge — Greek 3rd declension","Plural: *crises*. *Krinein* = judge → *criterion* (*-a* plural), *critical, critique, hypocrite* (under-judge = actor = one who pretends). The Greek *-is → -es* plural: *crisis/crises, thesis/theses, analysis/analyses, basis/bases, axis/axes*."]},{"w":"OPUS","pron":"OH-puhs","syll":"ow · pah · s","ety":["Latin *opus* = work, composition — 3rd declension ← *operis* genitive","Genitive stem *oper-* → English: *operate, operation, opera* (a work = a musical work), *inoperative, cooperate*. Plural: *opera* or *opuses*. Note: *opera* is BOTH the 3rd declension plural of *opus* AND a standalone word for a type of musical theater — same word, two English identities."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Give the correct Latin/Greek plural for: *datum, medium, criterion, phenomenon, thesis, analysis, nucleus, fungus, appendix, index, vertex, matrix*.","trace":"Find all English words from *opus/operis* = work (*operate, operation, opera, inoperative, cooperative, operator*). How many can you find?","build":"Explain why *agenda, data, criteria, media, phenomena* are technically plural in Latin — and when/why treating them as singular is now acceptable in modern English."}},{"id":"L15","n":15,"unit":2,"title":"The Roman Calendar — How Latin Gave English Its Months and Days","diff":"easy","bigIdea":"The months are named after Roman gods and emperors; the days of the week are a mix of Roman planets and Norse gods. Every time you say \"Wednesday\" you are invoking the Norse god Woden/Odin.","story":"The Romans used the Julian Calendar (reformed by Julius Caesar, 45 BCE). Months were named after: Roman gods (*January* = Janus, god of doorways; *March* = Mars, god of war; *May* = Maia, goddess of growth; *June* = Juno, goddess of marriage), Roman emperors (*July* = Julius Caesar, *August* = Augustus Caesar), and Latin ordinal numbers (*September* = 7th, *October* = 8th, *November* = 9th, *December* = 10th — before January and February were added, making the last four months mislabeled by two). The days of the week were originally Roman planetary names, adopted by Germanic peoples who substituted equivalent Norse gods: *Mars's day* → *Tuesday* (Tiw, Norse god of war), *Mercury's day* → *Wednesday* (Woden/Odin), *Jupiter's day* → *Thursday* (Thor), *Venus's day* → *Friday* (Frigg).","pattern":"Month names = Latin gods/emperors → direct English adoption. Day names = Roman planets → Germanic peoples swapped in equivalent Norse gods → Old English forms → Modern English. English kept Saturday (*Saturn's day*) but renamed all other planetary days after Norse equivalents. The result: days of the week are a hybrid of Roman astronomy and Norse religion.","connection":"The calendar preserves the Latin/Norse hybrid nature of English more transparently than almost any other vocabulary domain. Every time you write a date you are writing in two ancient languages.","words":[{"w":"JANUARY","pron":"JA-nyoo-eh-ree","syll":"jan · u · ar · y","ety":["Latin *Ianuarius* ← *Ianus* = Janus, two-faced god of doorways and beginnings","Janus had two faces — one looking back at the old year, one forward at the new. *Janua* = doorway → *janitor* (one who keeps the door). Every January you honor a two-faced Roman god. The month name has been in continuous use for over 2,000 years."]},{"w":"NOVEMBER","pron":"noh-VEH-mber","syll":"now · veh · mber","ety":["Latin *November* ← *novem* = nine + *-ber* (month suffix)","November was the 9th month in the original Roman calendar (before January and February were added). *Novem* = nine → *novena* (nine days of prayer), *nonagenarian* (a 90-year-old). September (7th), October (8th), November (9th), December (10th) are all \"mislabeled\" by two because of a calendar reform over 2,000 years ago."]},{"w":"THURSDAY","pron":"THUR-zday","syll":"ther · zdey","ety":["Old English *Þūnresdæg* = Thunder's day ← Norse *Þórr* (Thor)","Thursday = Thor's day. In Roman planetary naming, Thursday = *Jovis dies* = Jupiter's day. The Germanic peoples equated Thor (Norse thunder god) with Jupiter (Roman thunder god) and substituted. Italian *giovedì* = Thursday (Jupiter's day); English *Thursday* = Thor's day. Same planet, different god."]},{"w":"SATURDAY","pron":"SA-ter-dee","syll":"sae · ter · diy","ety":["Old English *Sæternesdæg* ← Latin *Saturni dies* = Saturn's day","Saturday is the ONLY English weekday that kept the Roman god's name, not a Norse equivalent. The Romans' Saturn = the planet and the god of agriculture/time. English kept *Saturday* directly, while swapping all other Roman planetary days for Norse gods. Why? Possibly because the Germanic peoples had no exact Norse equivalent for Saturn."]},{"w":"FEBRUARY","pron":"FEH-byuh-weh-ree","syll":"feh · byah · weh · riy","ety":["Latin *Februarius* ← *februa* = purification rites and instruments","February was the Roman month of purification — ritual cleansing before spring. Almost no other English words come from *februa*. ⚠️ Common mispronunciation: FEB-yoo-air-ee drops the *r* in the second syllable. Correct: FEB-roo-air-ee. The *r* must be present in spelling — F-E-B-R-U-A-R-Y."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Name the Roman god or emperor behind each month. Which months are ordinal numbers? Which are gods? Which are emperors? Complete the full table.","trace":"Find the weekday names in a Romance language (French, Spanish, or Italian). Which still use the Roman planetary names? Compare to English — which days changed and which stayed?","build":"Research the etymology of *planet* itself (Greek *planētēs* = wanderer). Why did ancient peoples call them \"wanderers\"? What does this tell you about how they observed the night sky?"}},{"id":"L16","n":16,"unit":2,"title":"Latin Doublets and Triplets — Three Words for Every Idea","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"English uniquely has two or three words for almost every concept — one from Old English, one from French/Latin, one from direct Latin — each occupying a different register of formality. No other language has this three-tier system at this scale.","story":"Because English absorbed vocabulary in three great waves (OE/Norse, French, Latin/Greek), it ended up with multiple words for the same concept. These doublets and triplets are not quite synonymous — they carry different connotations, formality levels, and social contexts. The three tiers are perfectly consistent: OE = informal/emotional/physical, French = elevated/social/administrative, Latin/Greek = technical/scholarly/medical. This hierarchy is not accidental — it directly reflects the social hierarchy of 1066: the English spoke OE, the Norman aristocracy spoke French, the Church and scholars spoke Latin.","pattern":"Three-tier English synonym sets follow a consistent pattern: (1) OE word: short, 1 syllable, informal (*heart, ask, end, help, fear, show*). (2) French word: 2 syllables, elevated (*cordial, question, finish, assist, terror, display*). (3) Latin/Greek word: 3+ syllables, technical (*cardiac, interrogate, terminate, facilitate, trepidation, exhibit*). Syllable count rises with formality level — because it rises with linguistic prestige on the post-1066 social ladder.","connection":"The three-tier synonym system is uniquely English and is directly caused by the 1066 Norman Conquest layering French vocabulary on top of an OE base that was already augmented by Church Latin.","words":[{"w":"HEART","pron":"HAHRT","syll":"hhaa · rt","ety":["Old English *heorte* ← Proto-Germanic *hertô*","The OE word. *Heart* in its emotional/informal register. The French path gives *cordial* (warm-hearted ← Latin *cor*). The Greek path gives *cardiac* (← Greek *kardia*). Three words for one organ: everyday (heart), elevated (cordial), technical (cardiac). One PIE root, three English words, three registers."]},{"w":"ASK","pron":"ASK","syll":"ae · sk","ety":["Old English *ascian* ← West Germanic","The OE word: casual, direct. French path gives *question* (2 syllables, more formal). Latin path gives *interrogate* (4 syllables, systematic, adversarial). \"Can I *ask* you something?\" vs \"I need to *question* the witness\" vs \"Police *interrogated* the suspect.\" Syllable count = formality = historical origin."]},{"w":"HOLY","pron":"HOH-lee","syll":"hhow · liy","ety":["Old English *hālig* ← Germanic ← *hāl* = whole, healthy","OE word: *holy* (deeply personal, reverential). Latin path: *sacred* (*sacratus* = formally set apart). Latin path (higher): *divine* (*divinus* = of the gods). Three levels of the same concept ascending from personal devotion (*holy*) to institutional designation (*sacred*) to divine essence (*divine*)."]},{"w":"SHOW","pron":"SHOH","syll":"show","ety":["Old English *sceawian* = to look at, inspect","OE: *show* (casual, everyday). French: *display* (*desplier* = arrange for viewing). Latin: *exhibit* (*exhibere* = formally present for examination). You *show* a friend your phone, *display* merchandise in a store window, *exhibit* artifacts in a museum. The word chosen signals the social context."]},{"w":"FEAR","pron":"FIHR","syll":"fih · r","ety":["Old English *fær* = danger, sudden attack ← Proto-Germanic","OE: *fear* (personal emotional state). French/Latin: *terror* (*terror* = great fear). Latin technical: *trepidation* (*trepidare* = to tremble). You feel *fear*, witness *terror*, and the medical literature describes *trepidation*. Same human experience, three linguistic layers, three social contexts."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Find the OE/French/Latin triplet for 5 more concepts: smell (odor/fragrance? → *reek/odor/effluvium*), beginning (*start/commence/initiate*), end (*end/finish/terminate*), buy (*buy/purchase/acquire*), help (*help/assist/facilitate*).","trace":"Write three sentences about the same event: one using exclusively OE-origin words, one using exclusively French-origin words, one using exclusively Latin/Greek-origin words. Note how each feels.","build":"Why does English uniquely have this three-tier system? Write a paragraph tracing the historical causes: what would English vocabulary look like if 1066 had never happened?"}},{"id":"L17","n":17,"unit":2,"title":"False Latin — Words That Look Roman But Are Not","diff":"hard","bigIdea":"Some English words look exactly like Latin but are Old English, Norse, Arabic, or other origins entirely. And some genuine Latin words have completely unexpected original meanings.","story":"The spelling conventions English borrowed from Latin make many non-Latin words look Latin. The formal name for a wrong popular etymology is *etymologia popularis* — a folk etymology. Classic examples: (1) *berserk* looks possibly Latin or French — it's Old Norse (*ber-serkr* = bear-shirt warrior). (2) *tragedy* looks like it should mean \"sad\" from some Latin root — it means \"goat-song\" in Greek. (3) *hazard* looks Spanish or Latin — it's Arabic *az-zahr* (the dice). (4) *companion* looks like it means \"with someone\" — and it does, but the second element is *panis* (bread) = \"one who eats bread with you.\" Knowing false etymologies is as important as knowing true ones, because false ones lead to wrong spelling predictions.","pattern":"False etymology detection: (1) Does the word's sound pattern match the claimed language? *berserk* has Norse *-sk-*, not Latin patterns. (2) Does the definition match the etymology? If not, investigate further. (3) When two etymologies are proposed, the more specific one with documented evidence is usually correct. (4) Short words with unusual consonant clusters (*berserk, ugly, trust*) are usually Germanic, not Latin, despite their appearance.","connection":"False etymologies are not just mistakes — they reveal how people think about words and how spelling can be shaped by misunderstanding. Knowing the true origin gives you both the correct spelling and a better story.","words":[{"w":"TRAGEDY","pron":"TRA-juh-dee","syll":"trae · jhah · diy","ety":["Greek *tragōidia* ← *tragos* (goat) + *ōidē* (song)","Literally \"goat-song.\" Tragedies were performed at festivals where a goat was sacrificed. Nothing Latin about this word — pure Greek. But *tragedy* looks Latinate to modern eyes because English learned words often follow similar patterns. The *-ic/-ical* form *tragic* shows the Greek *-ikos* ending clearly."]},{"w":"COMPANION","pron":"kuh-MPA-nyuhn","syll":"com · pan · ion","ety":["Latin *companio* ← *com-* (together) + *panis* (bread)","A companion = literally \"one who shares bread with you.\" *Panis* = bread → *pantry* (bread-storage room), *panini* (Italian bread), *company* (people who eat bread together = a group), *accompaniment* (going along with). The business *company* and a loaf of *bread* share an ancestor."]},{"w":"HAZARD","pron":"HA-zerd","syll":"hhae · zer · d","ety":["Old French *hasard* ← Spanish *azar* ← Arabic *az-zahr* = the dice","Looks Latin, sounds Latin — is Arabic via Spanish via French. Arab soldiers played a dice game that introduced *az-zahr* to Spanish (*azar* = luck/dice), which French borrowed (*hasard* = a game of dice/risk), which English borrowed as *hazard*. The word for \"danger\" traveled: Arabia → Spain → France → England."]},{"w":"PARADISE","pron":"PEH-ruh-deyes","syll":"peh · rah · day · s","ety":["Old Persian *pairi-daeza* = walled garden ← *pairi-* (around) + *daeza* (wall)","Old Persian → Greek → Latin *paradisus* → French → English. A *paradise* = literally a \"walled-around garden\" — the enclosed Persian royal gardens. The Persian royal garden became the Greek word for the Garden of Eden, then the Christian concept of heaven, then an English everyday word. A Persian wall became English heaven in five linguistic steps."]},{"w":"DISASTER","pron":"dih-ZA-ster","syll":"dih · zae · ster","ety":["Italian *disastro* ← *dis-* (bad) + *astro* (star) ← Latin *astrum* ← Greek *astron*","Literally \"under an evil star.\" People once believed catastrophes were caused by unfavorable star positions. *Disaster* = *dis-* (bad/against) + *astrum* (star). Same *astron* root as *astronomy, asterisk, astrology, astronaut*. A word for a catastrophe is secretly a word about the stars."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Research the true origin of each: *tragedy, companion, paradise, hazard, berserk*. Write one sentence for each explaining why the true etymology is more interesting than the folk etymology.","trace":"Find 5 English words whose popular (folk) etymology is wrong but which has influenced the word's spelling. (Hint: research *pedigree, crayfish, sparrow-grass/asparagus, sirloin, Welsh rarebit*.)","build":"The root *panis* = bread. Build the full family: *pantry, company, companion, panini, pan* (Spanish bread), *accompaniment, impanation* (doctrine that Christ is in the bread). Write one sentence connecting them all."}},{"id":"L18","n":18,"unit":2,"title":"Scientific Latin — The Language Scientists Created After 1500","diff":"hard","bigIdea":"From 1500–1900, scientists across Europe used Classical Latin to name their discoveries — because Latin provided a neutral international language. These \"New Latin\" words are the most purely Latinate-looking in English.","story":"From approximately 1500–1900, scientists used Latin (and Greek) to name discoveries because Latin transcended national boundaries. Linnaeus created binomial nomenclature for all species in Latin (1758). Newton wrote *Principia Mathematica* in Latin (1687). Chemists created Latin-based element names. Doctors created Latin-based anatomical terms. These \"New Latin\" words are the least Anglicized in English — they follow Latin phonology and morphology with minimal adaptation. Words like *appendectomy, bacillus, cerebellum, deltoid, efficacy, fibula, ganglion, histology, immunology* — coined by scientists thinking in Classical Latin, preserving its forms exactly.","pattern":"New Latin words are recognizable by: (1) Retaining Latin noun endings (*cerebellum, bacillus, nucleus, stimulus*) with Latin plural forms (*cerebella, bacilli, nuclei, stimuli*). (2) Using compound Greek/Latin elements transparently (*appendectomy* = *appendix* + *ek-* + *tome* = removal of the appendix by cutting). (3) Appearing in medical, scientific, and legal contexts almost exclusively. (4) Being the most phonetically challenging because they are the most faithful to Latin stress patterns (*cerebELLum*, not *CEREbellum*).","connection":"Scientific Latin shows how the Latin vocabulary creation mechanism stayed active long after Latin died as a spoken language. Scientists continued coining new Latin words until the 20th century — the language was dead but still productive.","words":[{"w":"CEREBELLUM","pron":"sair-uh-BEL-um","syll":"cer · e · bel · lum","ety":["New Latin ← Latin *cerebellum* = little brain ← *cerebrum* + *-ellum* (diminutive)","A diminutive of *cerebrum* (brain). *Cerebrum* → *cerebral* (relating to the brain), *cerebrovascular*. The *-ellum* diminutive = \"little ___\": *cerebellum* (little brain), *flagellum* (little whip). Double *ll* in *-ellum* = Latin diminutive suffix signal."]},{"w":"EFFICACY","pron":"EH-fih-ka-see","syll":"eh · fih · kae · siy","ety":["Latin *efficacia* ← *efficax* ← *ex-* + *facere* (to do) + *-ax* (apt to)","The quality of being apt to produce an intended effect. *Efficax* → *efficient, efficacious*. Scientific and medical writing favors *efficacy* over *effectiveness* for precise measurement. The *-acy* noun ending (from Latin *-acia*) = abstract quality: *supremacy, accuracy, literacy, legacy, pharmacy*."]},{"w":"PENINSULA","pron":"puh-NIH-nsuh-luh","syll":"pah · nih · nsah · lah","ety":["New Latin ← Latin *paene* (almost) + *insula* (island)","Almost an island. *Insula* = island → *insular* (island-like = isolated in thinking), *insulate* (make island-like = separate from heat/cold/electricity), *insulin* (discovered in the islets of Langerhans = little islands in the pancreas). The medical hormone *insulin* and a *peninsula* both trace to *insula* = island."]},{"w":"SPECIMEN","pron":"SPEH-suh-muhn","syll":"spec · i · men","ety":["(revisited — New Latin angle) Latin *specimen* = a sample ← *specere* = to look","In New Latin scientific usage, *specimen* = a sample for examination. The plural is *specimens* (English) or *specimina* (Latin 3rd declension neuter — rarely used). Scientists Latinized the word fully; general English Anglicized the plural."]},{"w":"BACILLUS","pron":"buh-SIH-luhs","syll":"bah · sih · lah · s","ety":["New Latin ← Latin *bacillus* = little staff/rod ← *baculum* = staff","Named for its rod shape. *Baculum* = staff → *imbecile* (literally \"without a staff\" = unable to support oneself). The diminutive *-illus* → *bacillus*. In taxonomy: *Bacillus anthracis* (anthrax), *Lactobacillus acidophilus* (yogurt bacterium). A diminutive of \"staff\" became the name for rod-shaped bacteria."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Identify the Latin roots in these New Latin scientific terms: *influenza, bacteria, nucleus, appendix, spectrum, virus, vacuum, placenta, sternum*.","trace":"Linnaeus named the house cat *Felis catus*. Name the Latin meaning of each word. Then find the Latin names for dog (*Canis lupus familiaris*), human (*Homo sapiens*), and chimpanzee (*Pan troglodytes*) — translate each.","build":"Create 5 new Latin-style scientific names for things that don't yet have Latin names, using real Latin roots. Examples: a new smartphone disease (*morbus digitalis*?), fear of social media (*phobia retiaculi*?)."}},{"id":"L19","n":19,"unit":2,"title":"Latin in the Law — Why Legal Language Is Still Mostly Latin","diff":"hard","bigIdea":"English law was conducted entirely in Latin and then French for over 600 years. The Latin legal vocabulary — *habeas corpus, subpoena, prima facie, mens rea, ipso facto* — survives intact because courts deliberately preserve it.","story":"English courts conducted proceedings in Latin until the 14th century and in French (specifically Law French) until 1733. The legal vocabulary that accumulated during these 700 years has been deliberately preserved because law requires precise, unchanging language — and dead languages don't change. A law written in Latin in 1250 still means exactly what it meant in 1250. This conservatism explains why legal language in English is uniquely archaic: *aforementioned, hereinafter, party of the first part, whereas* — legal documents look like they were written centuries ago because they were written in a tradition that started centuries ago.","pattern":"Latin legal phrases use the ABLATIVE CASE — the Latin case that expressed means, manner, or accompaniment. *Per se* = through itself (ablative of *se* = itself). *Prima facie* = at first face (ablative of *facies* = face). *In situ* = in its position (ablative). *De facto* = from the fact (ablative). *Ipso facto* = by the fact itself (ablative). The ablative case died in everyday English but lives on frozen in legal Latin phrases.","connection":"Latin legal phrases are not archaic decoration — they are preserved because law requires unchanging precision. Dead languages don't evolve, making Latin ideal for legal use. This lesson explains why the law still sounds like it was written in ancient Rome.","words":[{"w":"SUBPOENA","pron":"s-uh-p-EE-n-uh","syll":"subpoena","ety":["Latin *sub-* (under) + *poena* = penalty ← Greek *poine* = blood money, penalty","Under penalty = a legal demand to appear in court, with penalties for non-compliance. *Poena* = penalty → *pain* (through Old French *peine*), *punish* (through French *punir* ← Latin *punire*), *penal* (relating to punishment), *penalty*, *impunity* (without punishment). The legal penalty word is the same root as everyday *pain*."]},{"w":"PERJURY","pron":"p-UR-j-ur-ee","syll":"perjury","ety":["Latin *periurium* ← *per-* (thoroughly) + *ius/iuris* = law, right, oath","Thoroughly violating an oath. *Ius/iuris* = law → *jury* (those sworn by oath), *jurisdiction* (saying what the law is), *judicial, justice, justify, abjure* (swear away from), *conjure* (swear together = summon magically). The *-jury* in *perjury* and the *jury* in a courtroom are the same Latin word."]},{"w":"VERDICT","pron":"VUR-dihkt","syll":"ver · dih · kt","ety":["Latin *veredictum* ← *vere* (truly) + *dictum* (said) ← *verus* (true) + *dicere* (to say)","What is truly said. *Verus* = true → *verify, verity, veracious, aver* (firmly declare true), *verisimilitude* (the appearance of truth). *Dicere* = say → *diction, dictate, edict, predict, contradict, verdict*. A verdict = \"truly said\" by a jury."]},{"w":"PLAINTIFF","pron":"PLAY-ntuhf","syll":"pley · ntah · f","ety":["Old French *plaintif* ← *plaindre* = to complain ← Latin *plangere* = to beat the breast in grief","One who complains (in court). *Plangere* = beat, lament → *plaint* (a complaint), *complaint, plaintive* (sad and mournful). The person who files a lawsuit is etymologically \"one who beats their breast in grief\" — the Latin theatrical metaphor of mourning preserved in legal terminology."]},{"w":"TORT","pron":"TAWRT","syll":"tao · rt","ety":["Old French *tort* = a wrong ← Latin *tortum* = something twisted ← *torquere* = to twist","A legal wrong (not a crime, but a civil wrong). *Torquere* = twist → *torture* (twisting = causing pain), *torque* (rotational force), *contort* (twist together), *extort* (twist out of = coerce), *distort* (twist apart = misrepresent), *retort* (twist back = sharp reply). A civil lawsuit is etymologically about \"twisting\" justice."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Translate and explain: *habeas corpus, mens rea, actus reus, in camera, pro bono, amicus curiae, inter alia, res ipsa loquitur*.","trace":"Find the Latin case (nominative, genitive, dative, accusative, ablative, vocative) used in each of these legal phrases: *prima facie, in situ, per se, ipso facto, de facto, in absentia*.","build":"Compare: a contract in English uses words like *aforementioned, hereinafter, party of the first part*. Why does legal language resist modernization? Write a paragraph arguing for or against modernizing legal language."}},{"id":"L20","n":20,"unit":2,"title":"The Latin Suffix System — How -tion, -ous, -al, -ive, -ity Create 10,000 English Words","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"Latin adjective, noun, and verb suffixes entered English wholesale through French and became the most productive suffix system in the language — generating 10,000+ English words from identifiable Latin patterns.","story":"When Latin adjectives, nouns, and verbs entered English, they carried their suffix patterns: *-osus* (full of) → English *-ous*/*-ious*: *famous, glorious, audacious*. *-alis* (relating to) → *-al*: *formal, musical, natural*. *-ivus* (tending to) → *-ive*: *active, passive, creative*. *-ilis* (able to be) → *-ile* or *-ble*: *fertile, fragile, flexible*. *-itas* (abstract quality) → *-ity*: *ability, quantity, quality*. *-tionem* (action/result) → *-tion*: *action, nation, function*. Together these six suffix families account for a substantial portion of the entire English vocabulary of abstract concepts.","pattern":"Latin suffix diagnostics: (1) A word ending in *-ous/-ious/-eous/-uous* is almost certainly Latin-origin and means \"full of/characterized by\" [root]. (2) A word ending in *-ity* converts an adjective to an abstract noun (removing *-ous* and adding *-ity* often works: *audacious → audacity, tenacious → tenacity*). (3) A word ending in *-tion/-sion* is a Latin verbal noun = the action or result of [verb]. (4) A word ending in *-ive* means \"tending to\" [verb]. These four endings alone appear in thousands of English words.","connection":"The Latin suffix system is the most productive vocabulary-generating mechanism in English. Mastering these six suffix families (*-ous, -al, -ive, -ile, -ity, -tion*) unlocks the ability to decode any Latin-origin adjective, noun, or verb in English.","words":[{"w":"TENACIOUS","pron":"t-uh-n-AY-sh-uh-s","syll":"tenacious","ety":["Latin *tenax/tenacis* ← *tenēre* (to hold) + *-ax* (apt to) + *-ous*","Full of holding = stubbornly persistent. The *-acious* → *-acity* noun-forming pattern: *tenacious/tenacity, audacious/audacity, sagacious/sagacity, voracious/voracity, loquacious/loquacity, perspicacious/perspicacity*. Learning the adjective gives you the noun for free — just swap *-acious* for *-acity*."]},{"w":"AUDACITY","pron":"ah-DA-suh-tee","syll":"aa · dae · sah · tiy","ety":["Latin *audacia* ← *audax* (bold, daring) ← *audere* (to dare) + *-ity*","The quality of being daring — often shockingly so. The *-acity* pattern as noun form of *-acious*. ⚠️ *Audacious/audacity* (daring) vs *audible/audience* (hearing): both have *aud-* but from DIFFERENT Latin verbs (*audere* = dare vs *audire* = hear). The same three letters, two completely different Latin roots."]},{"w":"FRAGILE","pron":"FRA-juhl","syll":"frag · ile","ety":["Latin *fragilis* ← *frangere* (to break) + *-ilis* (able to be)","Able to be broken. *Frangere* = break → *fracture* (a break), *fraction* (a broken piece), *fragment* (a broken piece), *infraction* (breaking of rules), *refract* (bend = break the path of light), *infringe* (break into = violate). The *-ile* ending = ability/susceptibility: *fertile, futile, docile, hostile, ductile*."]},{"w":"CREATIVE","pron":"kree-AY-tihv","syll":"kriy · ey · tih · v","ety":["Latin *creativus* ← *creare* (to create) + *-ivus* (tending to)","Tending to create. *Creare* → *creation, creature* (a created thing), *recreation* (created again), *procreate* (create forward = reproduce), *increase* (grow into). The *-ive* ending = tending to do the root action: *creative* (tends to create), *active* (tends to act), *passive* (tends to suffer — from *pati* = to endure)."]},{"w":"SATISFACTION","pron":"sa-tuh-SFA-kshuhn","syll":"sae · tah · sfae · kshah · n","ety":["Latin *satisfactio* ← *satis* (enough) + *facere* (to make) + *-tionem*","The *-tion* suffix creates a verbal noun = the action/result of [verb]. *Satisfactio* = \"the act of making enough.\" The *-tion* → *-sion* variation: *-sion* appears after *d, l, n, r* + vowel roots (*extend → extension, revise → revision*). *-ssion* appears after stressed vowels (*miss → mission, permit → permission*)."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Apply the *-acious → -acity* transformation to: *tenacious, audacious, sagacious, voracious, loquacious, perspicacious, pugnacious, vivacious*. What does the transformation reveal about the words' relationships?","trace":"Find 5 English words for each Latin suffix: *-ous, -al, -ive, -ile/-ible, -ity, -tion*. For each word, identify the Latin root and the suffix.","build":"The *-tion* vs *-sion* spelling rule: use *-sion* after *d, l, n, r*; use *-ssion* after stressed vowels; use *-tion* otherwise. Test this rule on: *extend/extension, revise/revision, permit/permission, act/action, create/creation, express/expression*."}},{"id":"L21","n":21,"unit":3,"title":"Greek vs Latin — Two Paths Into English","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"Greek and Latin look similar but represent different linguistic lineages. Greek gave English its scientific, philosophical, and medical vocabulary; Latin gave English its legal, political, and formal vocabulary. Together they explain ~50% of all English words.","story":"Greek and Latin are distant Indo-European cousins — Latin is Italic, Greek is Hellenic. Greek entered English through two routes: (1) through Latin, which borrowed heavily from Greek during the Roman period; (2) directly, during the Renaissance and Scientific Revolution. When Greek words entered Latin, they were Latinized: Greek *philosophia* → Latin *philosophia* → English *philosophy*. When Greek words entered English directly, they kept Greek character: *phenomenon, criterion, analysis*. The six Greek spelling signals distinguish Greek-origin words from Latin-origin words at a glance.","pattern":"Greek spelling signals — recognize any one and you know the origin: (1) *ph* = /f/ (*philosophy, phosphorus, photograph*). (2) *y* as vowel (*myth, rhythm, syllable, psychology*). (3) *ch* = /k/ (*chaos, character, chemistry, chorus*). (4) *-sis* noun (*thesis, crisis, analysis, synthesis*). (5) *ps-* with silent *p* (*psalm, psychology, pseudonym*). (6) *pt-* with silent *p* (*pterodactyl, Ptolemy*). Seeing any of these signals = Greek origin → apply Greek spelling rules.","connection":"Greek and Latin spelling signals work together: if you see *ph*, *ch* = /k/, *y* as vowel, *-sis*, *ps-*, or *pt-* — you are in Greek territory and Greek rules apply. If none of those appear, default to Latin rules.","words":[{"w":"PSYCHOLOGY","pron":"seye-KAH-luh-jee","syll":"say · kaa · lah · jhiy","ety":["Greek *psychē* (soul/mind) + *logos* (word/study) — all components Greek","The full Greek signal cluster: *ps-* (silent *p*), *-ch-* = /k/, *-y-* as vowel, *-ology* = study. Four Greek signals in one 10-letter word. *Psychē* = soul → *psychiatry, psyche, psychosis, psychosomatic*. *Logos* = study/word → 397 English words in the database."]},{"w":"PHENOMENON","pron":"f-uh-n-AH-m-uh-n-ah-n","syll":"phenomenon","ety":["Greek *phainomenon* = thing that appears ← *phainein* = to show","*ph* = /f/ (Greek signal). Plural: *phenomena* (neuter *-on → -a*, Greek). *Phainein* = appear → *fantasy* (appearing in mind), *phase* (an appearance), *phantom* (an appearance), *diaphanous* (*dia-* = through + shining through = translucent), *epiphany* (*epi-* + appearing upon = sudden realization)."]},{"w":"RHYTHM","pron":"r-IH-th-uh-m","syll":"rhythm","ety":["Greek *rhythmos* = measured flow ← *rhein* = to flow","The *rh-* at start = another Greek signal: the *h* was once aspirated in Greek. Other *rh-* words: *rhetoric, rhinoceros, rhododendron, rhombus, rhapsody*. The *-y-* in *rhythm* = the only vowel — Greek *upsilon*. R-H-Y-T-H-M: six letters, one vowel (the *y*), pure Greek."]},{"w":"MNEMONIC","pron":"n-ih-m-AH-n-ih-k","syll":"mnemonic","ety":["Greek *mnemonikos* ← *mnemon* = mindful ← *mnasthai* = to remember","The *mn-* cluster (both pronounced in Greek, only *n* in English). *Mnemosyne* = Greek goddess of Memory, mother of the nine Muses. Same root → *amnesia* (*a-* = without + memory), *amnesty* (a forgetting of offenses = political pardon), *anamnesis* (recollection — from Plato's theory that learning = remembering things the soul already knew)."]},{"w":"PTERODACTYL","pron":"teh-ruh-DAK-til","syll":"pter · o · dac · tyl","ety":["Greek *pteron* (wing) + *daktylos* (finger) = wing-finger","Wing supported by an elongated finger. *pt-* cluster = silent *p* in English. Other *pt-* words: *ptomaine* (poisonous substance), *Ptolemy*, *helicopter* (*helikos* = spiral + *pteron* = wing). *Daktyl-* → *dactyl* (a metrical foot), *pachyderm* (thick-skinned — from *daktulos* as \"finger-like\" extension metaphor)."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Identify ALL Greek signals in: *psychology, phenomenon, rhythm, mnemonic, pterodactyl, chrysanthemum, diphtheria, ophthalmology*.","trace":"Find 5 more words with the *mn-* cluster (*amnesia, amnesty, mnemonic, anamnesis, Mnemosyne*). What does each mean, and how does the memory root connect them?","build":"The root *phainein* = to show/appear. Build the full family: *fantasy, phase, phantom, diaphanous, epiphany, phenomenon*. Write one sentence for each explaining the hidden \"appearing\" meaning."}},{"id":"L22","n":22,"unit":3,"title":"Greek Medical Vocabulary — The Body in Parts","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"Medical vocabulary is almost entirely Greek or New Latin built on Greek roots — because Hippocrates (460–370 BCE) established medicine as a discipline and wrote in Greek, creating a medical vocabulary that has been used continuously for 2,400 years.","story":"Hippocrates and his school on Cos created systematic medicine — and wrote in Greek. When Romans adopted Greek medicine, they kept the Greek terms. When Arab scholars preserved medical knowledge (800–1200 CE), they kept the Greek names. When European medicine revived in the Renaissance, it returned to Greek/Latin sources. The 2,400-year-old Greek medical vocabulary that every medical professional learns worldwide. The spelling follows Greek with precision — *ph* = /f/, *ch* = /k/, *y* = vowel — making each term transparent to anyone who knows Greek morphology. The 129K database shows: *pathos* (suffering) generates 64 words, *skopein* (look) generates 48 words, *metron* (measure) generates 136 words.","pattern":"Medical word structure: [body-part root] + [suffix indicating what is happening]. *-itis* = inflammation (laryngitis, gastritis, appendicitis). *-ology* = study of (cardiology, neurology). *-ectomy* = surgical removal (appendectomy, tonsillectomy). *-oscopy* = visual examination (endoscopy, colonoscopy). *-plasty* = surgical repair (rhinoplasty, angioplasty). *-pathy* = disease of (neuropathy, cardiopathy). Knowing root + suffix = decoding any medical term, even ones you have never seen.","connection":"Medical vocabulary is the most systematic application of Greek morphology in English. Once you know 10 Greek roots and 6 medical suffixes, you can decode any medical term — even ones coined last year.","words":[{"w":"OPHTHALMOLOGIST","pron":"ah-pthuh-MAH-luh-jihst","syll":"aa · pthah · maa · lah · jhih · st","ety":["Greek *ophthalmos* = eye + *logos* = study + *-ist* = practitioner","The hardest medical cluster: *-phth-*. O-P-H-T-H-A-L-M-O-L-O-G-I-S-T — 15 letters. BOTH *ph* AND *th* Greek signals in the same root. The *ophthalm-* base = one of the hardest Greek spellings in medical vocabulary. An ophthalmologist studies and treats eyes."]},{"w":"HEMATOPOIESIS","pron":"hee-mat-oh-poy-EE-sis","syll":"hematopoiesis","ety":["Greek *haima/haimatos* (blood) + *poiein* (to make) + *-sis* (process)","The process of making blood — what bone marrow does. *Haima* = blood → *hematology, hemorrhage* (*haima* + *rhegnynai* = burst = blood bursting out), *hemoglobin, anemia* (*an-* = without + blood). *Poiein* = make → *poem* (a thing made), *poetry* (the art of making). Making blood and making poems share a Greek root."]},{"w":"CARDIOMYOPATHY","pron":"kah-rdee-oh-meye-AH-puh-thee","syll":"kah · rdee · oh · meye · ah · puh · thee","ety":["Greek *kardia* (heart) + *mys/myos* (muscle) + *pathos* (suffering)","Five morphemes: *cardio-* (heart) + *myo-* (muscle) + *pathy* (disease). Disease of the heart muscle. The *mys/myos* = muscle → *muscle* itself (Latin *musculus* = little mouse, which moving muscle resembles under skin), *myology* (study of muscles), *myocardial* (relating to heart muscle)."]},{"w":"APPENDECTOMY","pron":"a-pih-NDEH-ktuh-mee","syll":"ae · pih · ndeh · ktah · miy","ety":["Latin *appendix* + Greek *ek-* (out) + *tomē* (cutting)","Surgical removal of the appendix. *-ectomy* = *ek-* (out) + *tome* (cutting) = cutting out. Compare *-otomy* = cutting into but not necessarily removing (*lobotomy, tracheotomy*). The distinction: *-ectomy* = remove; *-otomy* = cut open. Knowing this prevents confusing *appendectomy* (remove) with *appendotomy* (not a word)."]},{"w":"SUBCUTANEOUS","pron":"suh-bkyoo-TAY-nee-uhs","syll":"subcutaneous","ety":["New Latin ← Latin *sub-* (under) + *cutis* (skin) + *-aneous* (relating to)","Under the skin. *Cutis* = skin → *cutaneous, cuticle* (little skin at nail edge). Greek equivalent: *hypodermic* (*hypo-* = under + *derma* = skin) — same concept, different classical language. Both are correct; *subcutaneous* uses the Latin path, *hypodermic* uses the Greek path."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Break down into morphemes: *gastroenterology, neuropsychiatry, otolaryngologist, cardiovascular, osteoporosis, immunodeficiency, electroencephalogram*.","trace":"What is the Greek root for each body system? Heart (*kardia*), nerve (*neuron*), skin (*derma*), bone (*osteon*), blood (*haima*), lung (*pneumon*), stomach (*gaster*), eye (*ophthalmos*). Find 3 English medical words from each.","build":"Using Greek body-part roots + *-itis* (inflammation), name and explain 10 diseases: laryngitis, gastritis, hepatitis, meningitis, appendicitis, colitis, nephritis, arthritis, tendinitis, dermatitis."}},{"id":"L23","n":23,"unit":3,"title":"Greek Philosophy — The Language of Abstract Thought","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"The vocabulary of philosophy, logic, and abstract thought is almost entirely Greek — because Greek philosophers from Socrates to Aristotle (470–322 BCE) invented the vocabulary of rational inquiry and named their concepts in their own language.","story":"Socrates (470–399 BCE) developed systematic questioning (*elenchus*). Plato (428–348 BCE) described the world of ideal Forms. Aristotle (384–322 BCE) created formal logic, categorized the sciences, and named everything he touched. When their works were translated into Latin, then Arabic, then back into Latin, then into European languages, the Greek vocabulary traveled with the translations. The philosophical vocabulary we use today — *epistemology, ontology, dialectic, syllogism, ethics, metaphysics, aesthetics, phenomenology* — is Aristotle's Greek terminology, still in use 2,400 years later. The 129K database shows: *logos* generates 397 words, *pathos* generates 64, *ethos* generates multiple clusters.","pattern":"Greek philosophical terms decode transparently: *epistemology* = *episteme* (standing-upon = firm knowledge) + *logos* = how we know. *Ontology* = *ontos* (being) + *logos* = study of what exists. *Ethics* = *ethos* (character, custom). *Metaphysics* = *meta-* (beyond/after) + *physika* (physical things) = what lies beyond the physical. *Dialectic* = *dia-* (through) + *legein* (speak/choose) = speaking through to truth. Every term reveals its meaning through its Greek parts.","connection":"Aristotle's Greek terminology for philosophy has been in continuous use for 2,400 years, making it the longest-lived scientific vocabulary system in Western history. Knowing these roots unlocks not just the words but the conceptual framework of Western thought.","words":[{"w":"EPISTEMOLOGY","pron":"eh-pih-stuh-MAH-luh-jee","syll":"ih · pih · stah · maa · lah · jhiy","ety":["Greek *episteme* (knowledge) + *logos* (study) — *epi-* + *histanai* = stand upon","*Episteme* = firm knowledge based on understanding (vs *doxa* = mere opinion). *Epistemology* = how we know what we know. The contrast: *episte-* (stand upon = firm knowledge) vs *doxa* (opinion) → *orthodox* (correct opinion), *paradox* (beyond opinion), *heterodox* (different opinion). One Greek term contains a whole theory of knowledge."]},{"w":"SYLLOGISM","pron":"SIL-uh-jiz-um","syll":"syl · lo · gism","ety":["Greek *syllogismos* ← *syllogizesthai* = to reckon together ← *syn-* + *logos*","A formal logical argument: major premise + minor premise = conclusion. \"All humans are mortal. Socrates is human. Therefore Socrates is mortal.\" *Syn-* + *logos* = reasoning together. Aristotle invented this logic structure in the 4th century BCE. The double *ll* = *syn-* + *l-*root assimilation, just like Latin prefix assimilation."]},{"w":"DIALECTIC","pron":"deye-uh-LEH-ktihk","syll":"day · ah · leh · ktih · k","ety":["Greek *dialektikē* ← *dia-* (through) + *legein* (to speak/choose)","The art of speaking through arguments to reach truth. Plato's dialogues ARE dialectic — Socrates speaks through objections to find truth. *Legein* → *logic* (art of correct speaking), *dialect* (a way of speaking). The *-ect-* in *dialect* traces to *legein* = to speak. Dialectic and dialogue share the same *dia-* + *leg-* structure."]},{"w":"APORIA","pron":"uh-PAW-ree-uh","syll":"a · po · ri · a","ety":["Greek *aporia* = state of puzzlement ← *a-* (without) + *poros* (way/passage)","Literally \"without a way through\" — philosophical impasse. Socrates used *aporia* as a teaching method: lead students to realize they don't know what they thought they knew. *Poros* = passage → *porous* (full of passages), *emporium* (trading place = *en-* + *poros* = in the passage of trade). A market and philosophical puzzlement share a Greek root."]},{"w":"ONTOLOGY","pron":"ah-NTAH-luh-jee","syll":"aa · ntaa · lah · jhiy","ety":["Greek *ontos* (being, existence) + *logos* (study) ← *einai* = to be","Study of being itself — what does it mean to exist? *Ontos* = present participle of *einai* (to be). *Ontology* → *ontological, ontogeny* (development of an individual organism = birth of being). The three core philosophical disciplines: *epistemology* (how we know), *ontology* (what exists), *ethics* (how we should act). All Greek."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Explain the Greek roots in: *philosophy* (*philo-* + *sophia*), *democracy* (*demos* + *kratia*), *ethics* (*ethos*), *metaphysics* (*meta-* + *physika*), *aesthetics* (*aisthetikos* = perceiving).","trace":"Aristotle's three rhetorical appeals: *ethos* (character), *pathos* (emotion), *logos* (reason). Find 5 English words from each of these three Greek roots.","build":"Create a valid Aristotelian syllogism using vocabulary from this lesson (*episteme, ontology, dialectic, aporia, syllogism*). Make sure the major premise, minor premise, and conclusion are logically valid."}},{"id":"L24","n":24,"unit":3,"title":"Greek Science Terms — *Logos*, *Metron*, *Graphein*","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"Three Greek roots — *logos* (study, 397 DB words), *metron* (measure, 136 DB words), *graphein* (write, 121 DB words) — together generate over 650 English words, all following transparent Greek spelling patterns.","story":"The corpus analysis of the 129K database reveals that three Greek science roots are uniquely productive: *logos* = word/reason/study (397 words: biology, geology, psychology, theology, analogy, apology, epilogue, dialogue, monologue, catalog...); *metron* = measure (136 words: meter, thermometer, barometer, geometry, symmetry, altimeter, chronometer...); *graphein* = write/record (121 words: graph, photograph, paragraph, geography, biography, telegraph, autograph...). Together they unlock a massive science vocabulary with completely predictable spelling.","pattern":"Three suffix families from these roots: *-logy/-ology* = study of [root]. *-meter/-metry* = measurement of [root]. *-graph/-graphy* = writing/recording of [root]. The pattern: Greek root + one of these three suffixes = a science term. You can decode the term by identifying the root and suffix separately. You can also create plausible-sounding science terms by combining roots and suffixes — this is exactly what scientists did when naming new fields.","connection":"The three science root suffixes (*-logy, -metry, -graphy*) are still being used to coin new science terms today. *Nanotechnology, genomics, proteomics* all follow Greek compounding rules. Greek is a living scientific vocabulary-creation system.","words":[{"w":"CHOREOGRAPHY","pron":"kaw-ree-AH-gruh-fee","syll":"kao · riy · aa · grah · fiy","ety":["Greek *khoros* (dance, chorus) + *graphein* (write/design) + *-y*","Design of dances. *Khoros* = dance → *chorus* (group of singers/dancers), *choir* (religious singing group from same root). *Graphein* → *graph, photograph* (written by light), *paragraph* (*para-* = beside + *graph* = written beside), *autograph* (written by self), *biography* (life-writing)."]},{"w":"OPHTHALMOSCOPY","pron":"—","syll":"ophthalmoscopy","ety":["Greek *ophthalmos* (eye) + *skopein* (to look) + *-y*","Visual examination of the interior of the eye. *Skopein* = to look → database shows 48 English words: *telescope, microscope, periscope, stethoscope, kaleidoscope, endoscope*. Each compound tells you WHAT is being looked at: *tele-* (far), *micro-* (small), *peri-* (around), *stetho-* (chest), *kalos+eidos* (beautiful forms), *endo-* (within)."]},{"w":"THERMOMETER","pron":"ther-MAH-muh-ter","syll":"ther · maa · mah · ter","ety":["Greek *thermos* (heat) + *metron* (measure)","A thermometer measures heat. *Thermos* = heat → *thermodynamics* (science of heat and energy), *thermostat* (*therm-* + *statos* = standing = keeps heat steady), *endothermic* (*endo-* = within = absorbs heat), *exothermic* (*exo-* = out = releases heat). *Metron* = measure → *geometry* (earth-measure), *symmetry* (measure together), *altimeter* (height-measurer)."]},{"w":"BIBLIOGRAPHY","pron":"bih-blee-AH-gruh-fee","syll":"bih · bliy · aa · grah · fiy","ety":["Greek *biblion* (book) + *graphein* (write) + *-y*","A written list of books. *Biblion* = book → *Bible* (THE book), *bibliophile* (book lover), *library* (Latin *liber* = book). *Bibliophile* = *biblion* + *philos* = one who loves books. The Greek path (*bibliophile*) and the Latin path (*library*) both mean \"a place/lover of books\" — two languages, same concept."]},{"w":"ETYMOLOGY","pron":"eh-tuh-MAH-luh-jee","syll":"eh · tah · maa · lah · jhiy","ety":["Greek *etymon* (true form/meaning) + *logos* (study)","The study of the true form of words. E-T-Y-M-O-L-O-G-Y. ⚠️ The most-confused *-ology* word: *etymology* (study of word origins) vs *entomology* (study of insects, from *entomon* = cut-in-segments = the segmented insect body). Second letter is the tell: *ety-* vs *ento-*. This entire lesson program is applied *etymology*."]}],"practice":{"decode":"For each suffix family, find 5 examples from the database: *-ology* (5 study-of words), *-metry* (5 measurement words), *-graphy* (5 writing/recording words).","trace":"The root *logos* generates 397 words in the database. List as many as you can in 5 minutes. Group them by prefix (*mono-logue, dia-logue, pro-logue, epi-logue, ana-logy, de-calogue, cata-log...*)","build":"Create 5 new Greek-style science field names for things that aren't yet formal disciplines. Use real Greek roots: *selfie-ology* (Greek *eikon* = image + *logos*)? *Algorithm-metry*? Make them follow real Greek compound rules."}},{"id":"L25","n":25,"unit":3,"title":"Greek Number Prefixes — Both Sets","diff":"easy","bigIdea":"English borrows number prefixes from both Latin and Greek. Knowing both sets doubles your decoding power — and explains why *monocle* (one glass) and *unicorn* (one horn) both mean \"one\" but look completely different.","story":"The number vocabulary enters English through two channels: Greek (*mono-, di-, tri-, tetra-, penta-, hexa-, hepta-, octa-, ennea-, deca-, hecto-, kilo-, mega-*) and Latin (*uni-, bi-/du-, tri-, quad-/quart-, quint-, sex-, sept-, oct-, nona-, dec-, cent-, milli-*). *Tri-* is the same in both! But all other numbers have different forms depending on the language of origin. The choice of Greek vs Latin number prefix often follows field conventions: Greek number prefixes in science and mathematics (*hexagon, decathlon, pentagon*), Latin number prefixes in everyday formal English (*bicycle, century, unicorn*). Knowing both systems means you can decode any compound number word.","pattern":"Number prefix recognition: Greek *mono-* vs Latin *uni-* (both = one). Greek *di-* vs Latin *bi-/du-* (both = two). Greek *poly-* vs Latin *multi-* (both = many). Greek *penta-* vs Latin *quint-* (both = five). Greek *deca-* vs Latin *dec-* (both = ten). Greek *kilo-* vs Latin *milli-* (one thousand vs one thousandth). The field of use signals which language: science and metric system = Greek; everyday/historical = often Latin.","connection":"Knowing both Greek and Latin number prefixes means you can decode compound words from either classical language. The number prefix is always the key to understanding the core structure of scientific vocabulary.","words":[{"w":"MILLENNIUM","pron":"m-uh-l-EH-n-ee-uh-m","syll":"millennium","ety":["Latin *mille* (thousand) + *annum* (year) + *-ium* (collective)","One thousand years. M-I-L-L-E-N-N-I-U-M: double *ll* from *mille* + double *nn* from *annum*. One of the most commonly misspelled words in educated English. The two doublings come from two different Latin roots joining: *mill-* + *enn-*. The Greek equivalent would be *chiliarch* (*khilioi* = thousand + *arkhon* = ruler)."]},{"w":"PENTAGON","pron":"PEH-ntih-gahn","syll":"peh · ntih · gaa · n","ety":["Greek *penta-* (five) + *gon* (angle)","A five-angled figure. *Gon* = angle/corner → *polygon* (many angles), *hexagon* (six angles), *diagonal* (*dia-* = through + *gon* = going through the angles). The Latin equivalent of *penta-* = *quint-*: *quintuple, quintet, quintessence* (the fifth essence, beyond the four elements). Same concept, two prefix systems."]},{"w":"QUINTESSENCE","pron":"k-w-ih-n-t-EH-s-uh-n-s","syll":"quintessence","ety":["Latin *quinta* (fifth) + *essentia* (being/essence)","The fifth essence — beyond the four classical elements (earth, water, fire, air). Medieval philosophers believed a fifth, heavenly essence pervaded the universe. Now: the most perfect or typical example. *Quint-* = five (Latin) → *quintet* (five musicians), *quintuplets* (five babies), *quintuple* (five times). The Greek equivalent of *quint-* = *penta-*."]},{"w":"DECATHLON","pron":"dee-KA-thlawn","syll":"diy · kae · thlao · n","ety":["Greek *deka-* (ten) + *athlon* (contest, prize)","A ten-event athletic competition. *Deka-* = ten → *decade* (ten years), *decimal* (based on ten), *decimate* (originally kill one in ten), *December* (once the tenth month). *Athlon* = contest → *athlete* (one who competes for a prize), *triathlon* (three events), *pentathlon* (five events), *biathlon* (two events)."]},{"w":"OCTAVE","pron":"AH-ktihv","syll":"aa · ktih · v","ety":["Latin *octava* (eighth) ← *octo* = eight","The eight-note musical interval. *Octo* = eight → *October* (once the eighth month), *octopus* (Greek *okto* + *pous* = eight-footed), *octagon* (eight-angled). *Octave* came through Italian music theory (*ottava* = eighth), Anglicized to *octave*. The same concept in music and astronomy: an octave higher = double the frequency."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Complete the number prefix table: fill in both the Greek AND Latin prefix for each number 1–10. Find one English word using each prefix.","trace":"The *-gon* suffix = angle. Find all English *-gon* words (*pentagon, hexagon, heptagon, octagon, nonagon, decagon, polygon*). Draw and label each shape.","build":"*Millennium* has double *ll* AND double *nn*. Explain why each doubling is there (which Latin root causes each). Then find 5 more words where two Latin roots join and create a double consonant at the seam."}},{"id":"L26","n":26,"unit":3,"title":"Greek Gods in English — When Mythology Becomes Vocabulary","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"Hundreds of English words come from Greek god names — not as metaphors, but as words that started with the deity's name and evolved into common vocabulary describing what that deity represented.","story":"Greek mythology generated vocabulary in two ways: (1) directly, where the god's name became an English word (*panic* from Pan, *volcano* from Vulcan, *cereal* from Ceres); (2) through adjectival forms where the deity's attributes became the word (*mercurial* = changeable like Mercury, *martial* = warlike like Mars, *venereal* = of love like Venus, *jovial* = cheerful like Jove/Jupiter). The planets were named after Roman gods, and their names then generated adjectives describing the qualities Romans associated with those planets — qualities still embedded in the words today.","pattern":"Mythological word generation: Deity name → adjectival form (*Mars → martial, mercurial, venereal, jovial, saturnine, lunatic*). Or deity name → common noun (*Panic from Pan, cereal from Ceres, music from the Muses, ocean from Oceanus*). Or place name → adjective (*Spartan, laconic, stoic, academic*). Or hero/figure name → adjective (*herculean, quixotic, narcissistic, Machiavellian*).","connection":"Mythological vocabulary preserves ancient beliefs in the structure of everyday words. Understanding these origins not only improves spelling but reveals the worldview of the people who first created the words.","words":[{"w":"PANIC","pron":"PA-nihk","syll":"pae · nih · k","ety":["Greek *Panikos* = of Pan, the goat-god of nature and sudden terror","Pan was believed to cause sudden, irrational, overwhelming fear in forests. *Panic* = Pan's kind of fear. The same Pan → *pandemonium* (*Pan* + *daimon* = all-demons, later \"all the demons together\" = chaos — though this is Milton's coinage in *Paradise Lost*). The word *panic* preserves an ancient Greek belief about what lived in the wilderness."]},{"w":"CEREAL","pron":"s-IH-r-ee-uh-l","syll":"cereal","ety":["Latin *Cerealis* = of Ceres, Roman goddess of grain and agriculture","Ceres was the Roman goddess of grain. Every morning when you eat cereal, you are honoring her. The same *Ceres* → *create* (she created the grain cycle)? No — different root. But *Ceres* → *cereal, Ceres* (dwarf planet). The element *Cerium* (discovered 1803) was named after the asteroid Ceres, which was named after the goddess."]},{"w":"MARTIAL","pron":"MAH-rshuhl","syll":"maa · rshah · l","ety":["Latin *Martialis* = of Mars, Roman god of war","*Mars* → *martial* (warlike, relating to war), *Mars* (planet), *March* (month of Mars = war season), *martial arts*, *martial law*, *court-martial*. The *-tial* ending = \"of/relating to\" + proper noun. Roman war god → English adjective for everything military."]},{"w":"TANTALIZE","pron":"t-A-n-t-uh-l-ay-z","syll":"tantalize","ety":["Greek myth: *Tantalus*, king punished in Hades","Tantalus was condemned to stand in a pool with fruit trees above him — food and water always receding from his grasp. *Tantalize* = to torment with something desired but unattainable. Also: the chemical element *tantalum* was named for Tantalus (its salts wouldn't dissolve in acid — \"tantalized\" by water that wouldn't absorb them)."]},{"w":"MUSIC","pron":"MYOO-zihk","syll":"myuw · zih · k","ety":["Greek *mousikē* = art of the Muses ← *Mousa* = a Muse","The nine Muses were Greek goddesses of the arts and sciences: Calliope (epic poetry), Clio (history), Erato (love poetry), Euterpe (music/lyric poetry), Melpomene (tragedy), Polyhymnia (sacred poetry), Terpsichore (dance), Thalia (comedy), Urania (astronomy). *Music* = the art of the Muses. *Museum* = a place dedicated to the Muses."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Research the deity behind each: *volcano, ocean, chaos, venereal, jovial, saturnine, lunatic, mercury* (the element). Write one sentence connecting the deity's attributes to the modern meaning.","trace":"Find the planet-to-adjective set: Mars/martial, Mercury/mercurial, Venus/venereal, Jupiter/jovial, Saturn/saturnine, Moon/lunar/lunatic. What attributes did Romans associate with each planet?","build":"Aristotle's school was called the *Lyceum* (← *Lykos* = wolf? Or ← *Apollo Lykeios* = wolf-Apollo). Plato's was the *Academy* (← *Akademos*, a hero whose grove it was). Research two more English words that come from ancient Greek school names or locations."}},{"id":"L27","n":27,"unit":3,"title":"Greek Theater — Tragedy, Comedy, Drama, and the Words They Left","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"Greek theater invented the vocabulary of storytelling, performance, and emotional response — and those words are still used in every literature class, movie review, and drama discussion in the world today.","story":"Greek theater began as religious festivals honoring Dionysus (god of wine, ecstasy, and transformation) around the 5th century BCE. *Tragedy* (*tragōidia* = goat-song) and *comedy* (*kōmōidia* = revel-song) were the two major forms. Aristotle analyzed both in *Poetics*, coining terms still in use: *catharsis* (emotional purging through drama), *hamartia* (the fatal flaw), *anagnorisis* (moment of recognition), *peripeteia* (reversal of fortune). Greek theater also created: *drama* (action), *chorus* (the group), *protagonist* (main actor), *antagonist* (opposing actor), *theater* (viewing place), *scene* (stage), *dialogue* (words between characters).","pattern":"Greek theater vocabulary pattern: words ending in *-is* (Greek 3rd declension: *catharsis, anagnorisis, nemesis, poesis*) are process/event words from drama theory. Words ending in *-ist* are person-words derived from Greek action roots: *protagonist* (*protos* = first + *agonist* = actor/fighter), *antagonist* (*anti-* = against + *agonist*). The *-ist* agent ending and the *-is* process ending are both Greek — the choice between them is grammatical, not arbitrary.","connection":"Greek theater vocabulary is still the active vocabulary of literary analysis 2,500 years later. Understanding the Greek origins explains why we use these terms — and why they are spelled the way they are.","words":[{"w":"CATHARSIS","pron":"kuh-THAH-rsuhs","syll":"kah · thaa · rsah · s","ety":["Greek *katharsis* = cleansing, purification ← *kathairein* = to cleanse","Aristotle's term: tragedy cleanses the audience's emotions of pity and fear through experiencing them dramatically. *Katharsis* → *cathartic* (cleansing/purging). The same root: *cathartic* (a purging substance), *kathode* (Greek *kathos* = downward = the cathode in electricity = \"downward path of current\"). Aristotle's dramatic theory and cathode rays share a root."]},{"w":"PROTAGONIST","pron":"proh-TA-guh-nuhst","syll":"prow · tae · gah · nah · st","ety":["Greek *protos* (first) + *agonizesthai* (to contend, compete)","The first contender = the main character. *Protos* = first → *prototype* (first form), *protocol* (first glue = first leaf of a document), *proton* (first/primary particle). *Agon* = contest, struggle → *antagonist* (*anti-* = against), *agony* (the struggle itself), *agonize* (to struggle). Every story's hero is defined by the Greek word for \"first in the struggle.\""]},{"w":"NEMESIS","pron":"n-EH-m-uh-s-ih-s","syll":"nemesis","ety":["Greek *Nemesis* = goddess of retribution ← *nemein* = to distribute, allot","The goddess who distributed what was deserved — specifically punishment for hubris. Now: an opponent or source of ruin that cannot be overcome. *Nemein* = distribute/allot → *autonomy* (*autos* + *nomos* = self-law = self-governance), *economy* (*oikos* = house + *nomos* = management of the household). A goddess of just retribution and household economics share a Greek distributing-root."]},{"w":"TRAGEDY","pron":"TRA-juh-dee","syll":"trae · jhah · diy","ety":["Greek *tragōidia* ← *tragos* (goat) + *ōidē* (song)","Literally \"goat-song.\" Performed at festivals where a goat was sacrificed. *Ōidē* = song → *ode* (a lyric poem/song), *melody* (*melos* + *ōidē* = limb-song = a flowing song), *prosody* (*pros* + *ōidē* = toward the song = the rhythm of verse), *parody* (*para-* + *ōidē* = beside the song = a comic imitation). A festival animal sacrifice gave English its word for sorrowful drama."]},{"w":"THEATER","pron":"THEE-uh-ter","syll":"thiy · ah · ter","ety":["Greek *theatron* = viewing place ← *theasthai* = to behold","A *theater* = a place for beholding. *Theasthai* → *theory* (a beholding = a way of looking at the world), *theorem* (a thing that can be looked at = a proved statement), *theorize, therapeutic* (wait — *therapeutics* comes from *therapeuein* = to attend, not from *theasthai*). A place to watch plays and a mathematical theory both come from the Greek act of looking."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Find these Aristotelian terms in a Shakespeare play and identify them: *hamartia* (tragic flaw), *peripeteia* (reversal of fortune), *anagnorisis* (recognition scene), *catharsis* (emotional release). Which play? Which moment?","trace":"Build the *agon* = contest family: *protagonist, antagonist, agony, agonize, agonist, deagonize?, antagonize, agonal*. Explain the contest metaphor in each.","build":"Compare how *tragedy* and *comedy* are structured (using Greek theatrical terminology). Then find 5 modern films that fit each structure — and explain using *hamartia, peripeteia, catharsis* terminology."}},{"id":"L28","n":28,"unit":3,"title":"Greek Prefixes as Conceptual Tools — Anti-, Hyper-, Hypo-, Meta-, Para-, Syn-","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"Six Greek prefixes that create conceptual vocabulary — describing relationships between things rather than physical directions, unlike the more spatial Latin prefixes.","story":"Greek prefixes are more conceptual than Latin prefixes. Where Latin *sub-* = \"physically under,\" Greek *hypo-* can mean \"physically under\" (hypodermic = under the skin) OR \"conceptually insufficient\" (hypoglycemia = insufficient blood sugar, hypothesis = placed under = tentative suggestion). The Greek prefixes describe relationships between ideas as well as positions in space. This is why Greek prefixes dominate scientific and philosophical vocabulary: they are built for abstract thought. Key Greek prefixes: *anti-* (against), *hyper-* (over/excessive), *hypo-* (under/insufficient), *meta-* (beyond/after/change), *para-* (beside/beyond), *syn-* (together).","pattern":"Medical Greek prefix pairs: *hyper-* vs *hypo-* are direct opposites. *Hypertension* = blood pressure too HIGH. *Hypotension* = too LOW. *Hyperthyroid* = thyroid overactive. *Hypothyroid* = underactive. *Hyperglycemia* = too much blood sugar. *Hypoglycemia* = too little. Knowing one word of each pair gives you the other for free — just swap the prefix. This is the most efficient vocabulary-building pattern in medical English.","connection":"Greek prefixes are conceptual tools for building abstract vocabulary. The *hyper-/hypo-* medical pair alone unlocks 50+ medical terms. Mastering these six Greek prefixes = mastering the structure of scientific English.","words":[{"w":"HYPERBOLE","pron":"h-ay-p-UR-b-uh-l-ee","syll":"hyperbole","ety":["Greek *hyperbole* ← *hyper-* (over) + *ballein* (to throw)","Throwing over = deliberate exaggeration for effect. *Ballein* = throw → *ballistic* (thrown), *catapult* (*kata-* = down + *pallein* = throw), *emblem* (*en-* + *blema* = thrown into = image thrown onto). ⚠️ *Hyperbole* ends in *-le* pronounced /ee/: hy-PER-buh-lee. The final *-e* is PRONOUNCED, not silent. Greek final vowels are pronounced; English final *-e* is usually silent. This distinction is the most common pronunciation error with Greek words."]},{"w":"HYPOTHESIS","pron":"h-ay-p-AH-th-uh-s-uh-s","syll":"hypothesis","ety":["Greek *hypothesis* ← *hypo-* (under) + *thesis* (placing)","Something placed under consideration = a tentative suggestion. *Thesis* = placing → *thesis* (a piece of work placed before a committee), *antithesis* (*anti-* = against = placed against), *synthesis* (*syn-* = together = placed together), *parenthesis* (*para-* + *en-* + *thesis* = placed beside within). The *-thesis* family covers all academic writing structures."]},{"w":"METAMORPHOSIS","pron":"meh-tuh-MAW-rfuh-suhs","syll":"meh · tah · mao · rfah · sah · s","ety":["Greek *meta-* (change/beyond) + *morphē* (form) + *-osis* (process)","Process of changing form beyond what came before. *Meta-* = beyond/change/after: *metaphor* (*meta-* + *pherein* = carrying beyond the literal), *metabolism* (*meta-* + *ballein* = chemical throwing-around), *metacognition* (thinking about your own thinking). *Morphē* = form → *morphology* (study of form), *amorphous* (without form), *polymorphous* (many forms)."]},{"w":"SYNTHESIS","pron":"SIH-nthuh-suhs","syll":"sih · nthah · sah · s","ety":["Greek *synthesis* ← *syn-* (together) + *tithenai* (to place)","Placing together = combining into a whole. *Syn-/sym-* before *b/m/p*: *symbol* (thrown together), *symmetry* (measured together), *sympathy* (feeling together). *Syn-* elsewhere: *syndrome* (running together = co-occurring symptoms), *synopsis* (*syn-* + *opsis* = seeing together = a summary), *syntax* (*syn-* + *taxis* = arrangement together = grammar)."]},{"w":"PARADOX","pron":"PEH-ruh-dahks","syll":"peh · rah · daa · ks","ety":["Greek *paradoxos* ← *para-* (beside/beyond) + *doxa* (opinion/expectation)","Beyond expectation = a self-contradicting or seemingly impossible statement. *Doxa* = opinion/belief → *orthodox* (straight opinion = conventional), *heterodox* (different opinion = unconventional), *paradox* (beyond opinion = baffling). *Para-* = beside/beyond: *parallel* (beside each other), *paramedic* (beside the medical = supporting), *paranormal* (beyond normal)."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Find the medical opposite for each using hyper-/hypo-: *hypertension/hypotension, hyperglycemia/hypoglycemia, hyperthyroidism/hypothyroidism, hyperventilate/hypoventilate*. What does each mean?","trace":"The *-thesis* family: *thesis, antithesis, synthesis, hypothesis, parenthesis, prosthesis* (*pros-* = toward + *thesis* = placed toward = an addition). Explain the \"placing\" metaphor in each.","build":"Create a table: Greek prefix vs Latin equivalent. *Anti-/contra-* (against), *hyper-/super-* (over), *hypo-/sub-* (under), *meta-/trans-* (beyond/across), *para-/ad-* (beside/toward), *syn-/con-* (together). Find one English word for each box."}},{"id":"L29","n":29,"unit":3,"title":"Greek in Modern Technology — *Micro-, Tele-, Cyber-, Digital*","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"Ancient Greek roots are still generating new English vocabulary in the 21st century — because technology researchers chose Greek word-building conventions when naming their inventions.","story":"When scientists and engineers began naming new technologies in the 19th and 20th centuries, they turned to Greek because Greek had established conventions for naming new concepts. *Telephone* (1876, Bell): *tele-* (far) + *phone* (voice). *Photograph* (1839, Herschel): *photo-* (light) + *graph* (written by). *Television* (1907, Constantijn Huygenhans): *tele-* (far) + *Latin visio* (seeing). *Microphone* (1827, Wheatstone): *micro-* (small) + *phone* (voice). The Greek convention is so well-established that modern tech vocabulary still follows it: *internet* (Latin *inter-* + English *net*), *smartphone* (English *smart* + Greek *phone*), *cryptocurrency* (*kryptos* = hidden + *currency*). Greek morphology is the active vocabulary-creation system for technology.","pattern":"Modern tech vocabulary compounds: Greek roots + new referents. *Cyber-* (from Greek *kybernetes* = helmsman, from which Norbert Wiener coined *cybernetics* in 1948 = science of control systems) → *cyberspace, cybersecurity, cybercrime*. *Digital* (from Latin *digitus* = finger → counting on fingers → digit → digital = relating to digits) shows how even tech vocabulary traces to ancient body-part metaphors. The key pattern: technology names that look Greek ARE Greek — because scientists chose Greek on purpose.","connection":"Greek morphology is still the active vocabulary-creation system for technology — because scientists chose it deliberately when naming their inventions, and the convention has persisted for 200+ years.","words":[{"w":"TELEPHONE","pron":"TEH-luh-fohn","syll":"teh · lah · fow · n","ety":["Greek *tele-* (far) + *phonē* (voice/sound)","Invented by Bell (1876). *Tele-* = far → *telescope, telegraph, television, telepathy, telekinesis, telemetry*. *Phonē* = voice → the entire phone family already covered in Greek signals. Interestingly, *television* mixes Greek *tele-* with Latin *visio* — a linguistic hybrid that purists objected to but everyone uses."]},{"w":"PHOTOGRAPH","pron":"FOH-tuh-graf","syll":"fow · tah · grae · f","ety":["Greek *photo-* (light) + *graphein* (to write/record)","Written by light. *Photo-* = light → *photosynthesis* (making food from light), *photon* (a particle of light), *photophobia* (fear of light), *photogenic* (born/suited for light). *Graphein* = write/record → 121 words in the database. A photograph is literally \"light writing\" — one of the most transparent compound Greek words in technology."]},{"w":"MICROSCOPE","pron":"MEYE-kruh-skohp","syll":"may · krah · skow · p","ety":["Greek *mikros* (small) + *skopein* (to look)","Looks at tiny things. *Mikros* = small → 54 words in database: *microphone* (makes tiny sounds big), *microorganism, microchip, microwave, microcosm* (small world). *Skopein* → 48 words: *telescope, periscope, stethoscope, endoscope, horoscope*. Two of the most productive Greek science roots combined."]},{"w":"CRYPTOCURRENCY","pron":"—","syll":"cryptocurrency","ety":["Greek *kryptos* (hidden) + Latin *currere* (to run = currency)","Hidden currency. *Kryptos* = hidden → *crypt* (hidden underground chamber), *cryptic* (hidden/mysterious), *cryptography* (hidden writing), *encrypt* (put into hidden form), *decrypt* (take out of hidden form). A 21st-century financial technology word combines 2,400-year-old Greek with a Latin monetary term."]},{"w":"CYBERNETICS","pron":"sy-ber-NET-iks","syll":"cy · ber · net · ics","ety":["Greek *kybernetes* = helmsman, governor ← *kybernan* = to steer/govern","Norbert Wiener coined *cybernetics* in 1948 for the science of control and communication in animals and machines. *Kybernan* → *govern* (through Latin *gubernare* → French *gouverner*). The same Greek steersman who gave English *cybernetics* also gave it *govern*, *governor*, *government* — all from the same metaphor of steering a ship."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Find the Greek roots in each modern tech term: *hologram, algorithm, algorithm, genome, biometrics, nanotechnology, thermostat, electrode, telegram, oxygen*.","trace":"The word *govern* comes from Greek *kybernetes* (helmsman) through Latin *gubernare*. Trace this full journey. Then find how *cybernetics* connects back to the same root.","build":"Create 5 original technology names using Greek roots for technologies that might exist in 2050. Examples: *neurolink* (brain-connection), *chronocloud* (time-based storage). Use real Greek roots and explain each component."}},{"id":"L30","n":30,"unit":3,"title":"Greek + Latin Compounds — When Two Classical Languages Merge","diff":"hard","bigIdea":"Some English words combine a Greek root with a Latin root — creating \"hybrids\" that linguistic purists sometimes object to but that are now perfectly standard English.","story":"Purist grammarians (especially in the 19th century) objected to \"hybrid\" words mixing Greek and Latin roots. They coined terms like \"barbarism\" for these hybrids. But hybrid words are now completely normal and productive. *Television* (Greek *tele-* + Latin *visio*) is the most famous example — a word that combines two classical languages. *Automobile* (Greek *autos* + Latin *mobile*) is another. *Sociology* (Latin *socius* + Greek *-logy*). *Bureaucracy* (French *bureau* + Greek *-cracy*). The word-formation convention of mixing roots from different classical languages is now an accepted part of English word creation — the \"hybrid\" objection lost, and the hybrids won.","pattern":"Hybrid compound recognition: look for Greek signals on one side and Latin signals on the other. *Television*: *tele-* = Greek (note: *ph* not present, but *tele-* is Greek), *visio* = Latin (*-sion* Latin suffix). *Automobile*: *auto-* = Greek (self), *mobile* = Latin (*movere* = to move). *Sociology*: *socius* = Latin (companion), *-logy* = Greek (study). The hybrids are identifiable once you know the signals for each language.","connection":"Hybrid words are not mistakes — they are the natural result of English drawing from two classical vocabulary traditions simultaneously. The \"hybrid = barbarism\" argument lost to usage. This lesson explains why.","words":[{"w":"TELEVISION","pron":"TEH-luh-vih-zhuhn","syll":"teh · lah · vih · zhah · n","ety":["Greek *tele-* (far) + Latin *visio* (seeing) ← *videre* (to see)","The most famous Greek-Latin hybrid. *Videre* = see → *video, visual, vision, visible, visit, revise, supervise, evidence* (*e-* + *videre* = see out from = what you can see), *provide* (*pro-* + *videre* = see forward). The Greek prefix *tele-* and Latin root *visio* come from two different classical traditions united in one 1907 invention."]},{"w":"AUTOMOBILE","pron":"AW-tuh-moh-beel","syll":"ao · tah · mow · biy · l","ety":["Greek *autos* (self) + Latin *mobilis* (movable) ← *movere* (to move)","Self-moving. *Autos* = self → *autobiography, autodidact, automatic, autonomous*. *Movere* = move → *move, remove, mobile, motion, motor, moment, momentum, promote, remote*. *Automobile* = a vehicle that moves itself. Linguistic hybrid; transportation revolution."]},{"w":"SOCIOLOGY","pron":"soh-see-AH-luh-jee","syll":"sow · siy · aa · lah · jhiy","ety":["Latin *socius* (companion, associate) + Greek *logos* (study)","Study of companions = study of human society. *Socius* = companion → *social, society, associate, dissociate, sociology*. *Logos* = study → 397 words. Hybrid coined in 1838 by Auguste Comte, who also coined *positivism*. Purists objected to the Greek-Latin mix; *sociology* became one of the 20th century's most important academic disciplines."]},{"w":"BUREAUCRACY","pron":"byuu-RAH-kruh-see","syll":"byuh · raa · krah · siy","ety":["French *bureau* (desk/office) + Greek *kratos* (rule/power) + *-cy*","Rule by desks = rule by officials and paperwork. *Bureau* = French (originally a type of cloth covering a writing table → the table → the office). *Kratos* = rule → *democracy* (*demos* + *kratos*), *aristocracy* (*aristos* = best + *kratos*), *plutocracy* (*ploutos* = wealth), *theocracy* (*theos* = god). A French office-furniture word and a Greek governance concept: bureaucracy."]},{"w":"MONOSYLLABLE","pron":"—","syll":"monosyllable","ety":["Greek *monos* (one) + Latin *syllaba* ← Greek *syllabē* (taking together)","One syllable. Wait — *syllaba* is from Greek despite looking Latinate! *Syllabē* = *syn-* + *lambanein* = taking together (sounds taken together = a syllable). So *monosyllable* is actually Greek + Greek: *monos* (one) + *syllabē* (taking-together of sounds). The word that looks like a Greek-Latin hybrid is actually pure Greek."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Find 5 more commonly used English hybrid compounds (Greek root + Latin root or Latin root + Greek root). Identify which part comes from which language.","trace":"The *kratos* = rule/power root generates the *-cracy* government family. List: *democracy, aristocracy, plutocracy, theocracy, bureaucracy, meritocracy, technocracy, kleptocracy*. Explain the root compound in each.","build":"Argue either FOR or AGAINST hybrid Greek-Latin compounds in English. Use the history of *television*, *sociology*, and *automobile* as evidence. Which side has the stronger historical argument?"}},{"id":"L31","n":31,"unit":4,"title":"Norman French vs Continental French — Two Flavors of Old French","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"The French that entered English after 1066 was Norman French — a dialect of Old French with its own phonology and spelling patterns, which differ in important ways from the Parisian French that influenced English later.","story":"William the Conqueror spoke Norman French — the dialect of Normandy. Norman French had diverged from Parisian French partly because of Viking influence (Normans were Norsemen who had settled in France and adopted French). This gives Norman French loanwords distinctive features: *-oun* instead of *-on* (*noun, count, mount*), *-aun-* vowels (*haunt, gaunt, vaunt*), and *-aint/-ance* patterns (*saint, grant, rant*). Later, when English trade with Paris increased (13th–14th centuries), Parisian French loanwords entered English too — with different spelling patterns. The two waves of French can sometimes be distinguished by their internal phonology.","pattern":"Norman French vs Parisian French word pairs in English: *warden* (Norman) vs *guardian* (Parisian — both from Germanic *ward* = guard). *Warranty* (Norman) vs *guarantee* (Parisian). *Catch* (Norman) vs *chase* (Parisian — both from Latin *captiare*). *Cattle* (Norman) vs *chattel* (Parisian). *Canal* (Parisian) vs *channel* (Norman — both from Latin *canalis*). The Norman word often has *c-* or *-atch* or *-attle*; the Parisian word often has *ch-* or *-hase* or more elaborate spelling.","connection":"Norman French and Parisian French both entered English, often creating doublets (*catch/chase, warden/guardian, cattle/chattel*). Knowing which French dialect a word came from helps predict its spelling patterns.","words":[{"w":"WARDEN","pron":"WAW-rduhn","syll":"wao · rdah · n","ety":["Anglo-Norman *wardein* ← Germanic *wardaz* = guard","A warden guards. The Parisian French equivalent is *guardian* (← same Germanic root but through central French phonology). Norman *w-* preserved the Germanic initial *w-*; Parisian French changed it: *guarder* (the *gu-* absorbing the *w-* into a French-style consonant cluster). Both English words survive with slightly different meanings."]},{"w":"CATCH","pron":"KACH","syll":"kae · ch","ety":["Anglo-Norman *cachier* ← Latin *captiare* = to hunt, chase","The Parisian French equivalent is *chase* (← same Latin *captiare* through Parisian phonology). Norman French: *cachier* → *catch*. Parisian French: *chacier* → *chase*. Both mean essentially the same thing (pursue/apprehend) but with nuanced differences. *Catch* = successfully grab; *chase* = pursue. Two words from one Latin root through two French dialect paths."]},{"w":"CATTLE","pron":"KA-tuhl","syll":"kae · tah · l","ety":["Anglo-Norman *catel* = property, animals ← Latin *capitale* = head (of wealth)","*Catel* = Norman French form. Parisian French form: *chatel* → *chattel* (movable property). *Capital* (the head of wealth) → *cattle* (the primary form of movable wealth in medieval economy) → *chattel* (any movable property). Three English words from Latin *caput* = head: *cattle, chattel, capital*."]},{"w":"HAUNT","pron":"HAWNT","syll":"hhao · nt","ety":["Anglo-Norman *hanter* = to frequent, visit often ← Germanic *heimaz* = home","The *-au-* vowel cluster = Norman French phonological signal. *Haunt* originally meant \"to frequent a place regularly\" — not necessarily with ghostly connotation. The ghost meaning developed later as \"the spirit that frequents a place.\" *Gaunt, jaunt, vaunt, flaunt* — all have the Norman *-au-* cluster."]},{"w":"WARRANT","pron":"WAW-ruhnt","syll":"wao · rah · nt","ety":["Anglo-Norman *warantir* = to guarantee ← Germanic *warjan* = to protect","The Parisian French equivalent: *guarantee* (← same Germanic root through French *garantie*). Norman French preserved the Germanic *w-*: *warrant, warden, war* (Norman) vs *guarantee, guard, guerrilla* (through Spanish/French with *gu-*). Every *gu-* word before *a* in English may represent a Norman *w-* word that went through a different dialect path."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Find the Norman French / Parisian French doublet for each: *catch/chase, warden/guardian, warranty/guarantee, cattle/chattel, canal/channel, ward/guard, wage/gage*.","trace":"The Norman *w-* vs Parisian *gu-*: find 5 more examples where Norman French preserved *w-* and Parisian French turned it into *gu-*.","build":"Research why Normandy had Viking influence on its French dialect. How does *haunt* preserve traces of Norse *heimaz* = home through Norman French?"}},{"id":"L32","n":32,"unit":4,"title":"The Law in French — Vocabulary That Still Runs the Courts","diff":"hard","bigIdea":"The entire vocabulary of English law — court, judge, jury, verdict, plaintiff, defendant, felon, sentence, justice, appeal — is French, because English courts conducted proceedings in Law French from 1066 to 1733.","story":"Law French was not quite Old French and not quite English — it was a specialized legal dialect that preserved archaic forms long after they had disappeared from spoken French. English courts used Law French for nearly 700 years (1066–1733). The result: legal vocabulary in English is a French time-capsule. Words like *plaintiff* (the complaining party), *defendant* (the defending party), *verdict* (truly said), *jury* (sworn together), *evidence* (what can be seen clearly) — all French. The legal system still says *vis-à-vis, amicus curiae, prima facie, mens rea* — but these are LATIN legal phrases, not French. Both layers coexist in modern law.","pattern":"French legal suffix patterns: *-iff* (plaintiff, sheriff, bailiff = the officer), *-ant/-ent* (defendant, appellant, claimant = the party), *-ance/-ence* (evidence, sentence, negligence = abstract legal concepts), *-y* from French *-ie* (judiciary, felony, burglary, arson = types of legal action or categories). These suffix patterns identify French legal vocabulary in English.","connection":"Legal French vocabulary is the most archaic surviving French layer in English, preserved deliberately because law requires unchanging precision. Every time you enter a court, you are entering a space where 1066 French is still alive.","words":[{"w":"PLAINTIFF","pron":"PLAY-ntuhf","syll":"pley · ntah · f","ety":["Old French *plaintif* ← *plaindre* = to complain ← Latin *plangere* = to beat the breast","One who complains in court. *Plangere* = beat/lament → *plaint* (a complaint), *complaint, plaintive* (sorrowfully mournful). The person who files a lawsuit is etymologically \"one who beats their breast in grief.\" The Latin theatrical gesture of mourning = the emotional basis of a legal complaint."]},{"w":"DEFENDANT","pron":"d-ih-f-EH-n-d-uh-n-t","syll":"defendant","ety":["Old French *defendant* = one who defends ← *défendre* ← Latin *defendere* = to strike away","One who defends against a legal claim. *De-* + *fendere* = strike away → *defend, defense, fend* (to keep off), *offend* (*ob-* + *fendere* = strike toward = attack). A defendant strikes away the accusations; a plaintiff beats their breast in grief. Both roles encoded in their French etymologies."]},{"w":"VERDICT","pron":"VUR-dihkt","syll":"ver · dih · kt","ety":["Anglo-Norman *verdit* ← Latin *vere* (truly) + *dictum* (said)","What is truly said. *Verus* = true → *verify, verity, veracious, aver, verisimilitude*. *Dicere* = say → *diction, dictate, edict, predict, contradict*. A verdict = \"truly said\" by the jury. The same *vere-* + *dic-* structure appears in *juridical* (*jus* + *dic-* = saying the law)."]},{"w":"FELON","pron":"FEH-luhn","syll":"feh · lah · n","ety":["Old French *felon* ← Medieval Latin *fello* = an evil person, traitor","A felon = one who has committed a serious crime. *Felon* → *felony* (the *-y* = French *-ie* = abstract noun suffix). Contrast *misdemeanor* (*mis-* + Old French *demener* = to conduct oneself badly = a minor offense). The distinction felony/misdemeanor is built into English law and vocabulary but comes from French and Old English roots respectively."]},{"w":"ATTORNEY","pron":"uh-t-UR-n-ee","syll":"attorney","ety":["Old French *atourné* = appointed ← *atourner* = to turn toward, appoint","One appointed (turned toward a task) = a legal representative. *Atourner* → *attorney, attorn* (to transfer legal obligation). *Tour* = turn (Old French) → *attorney, detour, return, tournament*. An attorney is literally \"one turned toward\" representing a client — a subtle positional metaphor for the role."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Identify the French origin of each legal term and explain its literal etymology: *court* (enclosed space), *jury* (sworn group), *judge* (one who says the law), *appeal* (speak toward again), *sentence* (feeling/opinion of the court).","trace":"Find 10 legal terms ending in French-signal suffixes: *-iff* (plaintiff, sheriff, bailiff), *-ant/-ent* (defendant, appellant), *-ance/-ence* (evidence, negligence), *-y* from French *-ie* (felony, burglary).","build":"Write a one-paragraph court verdict using only French-origin words. Then rewrite it using only OE-origin words. Which version sounds more \"legal\"? Why does this reveal about register?"}},{"id":"L33","n":33,"unit":4,"title":"The Kitchen in French — How the Norman Conquest Seasoned English Cuisine Vocabulary","diff":"easy","bigIdea":"The Norman Conquest gave English its culinary vocabulary — not just the food names, but the entire vocabulary of professional cooking, because the kitchen was one of the domains where French social dominance was most complete.","story":"Norman lords ate at high tables while English serfs prepared food and tended animals. The same social split that gave English *cow/beef* (OE animal name, French meat name) extended across the entire kitchen vocabulary. French brought: *sauce, boil, broil, roast, fry, mince, blend, season, cuisine, appetite, menu, chef, restaurant, bistro, entrée, dessert, cream, custard, gravy, pastry, sugar* — and the entire professional vocabulary of cooking. Meanwhile, Old English retained the words for the raw ingredients closest to the earth: *bread, milk, eggs, wheat, barley, oat, salt*. The kitchen encodes a social hierarchy in its vocabulary that has lasted 960 years.","pattern":"Culinary French vocabulary signals: *-ée* ending (*entrée, purée, sauté, flambé*) = French past participle used as noun/adjective. *-ette* diminutive (*crêpette, brochette, croquette*) = small version. *-eur/-eur* agent (*restaurateur, pâtissier*) = person who does. French cooking terms preserved accent marks even in English (*sauté, entrée, flambé, pâté*) — unusual because English usually drops accents from borrowed words. The preserved accent = signal of recent or high-register French borrowing.","connection":"The kitchen vocabulary encodes the social hierarchy of 1066 as clearly as any domain. OE words for raw ingredients + French words for preparation and dining = the conquered prepared food for their conquerors.","words":[{"w":"RESTAURANT","pron":"REH-ster-ahnt","syll":"res · tau · rant","ety":["French *restaurant* ← *restaurer* = to restore ← Latin *restaurare*","A place that restores you (through food). *Restaurare* = restore → *restore, restaurant, restoration*. ⚠️ *Restaurateur* (the owner) has NO *n* before *-eur* — it comes from *restaurer* not *restaurant*. *Restauranteur* is a common misspelling that inserts the *n* from \"restaurant\" where it doesn't belong etymologically."]},{"w":"CUISINE","pron":"kwih-ZEEN","syll":"kwih · ziy · n","ety":["French *cuisine* = kitchen, cooking ← Latin *coquina* ← *coquere* = to cook","Kitchen/cooking style. *Coquere* = cook → *cook* (OE borrowed this early), *kitchen* (OE *cycene* ← Latin *coquina* = same word that became French *cuisine*!). So *kitchen* and *cuisine* are doublets from the same Latin root — OE borrowed it early and made it *kitchen*; French kept it as *cuisine* and English borrowed it again later."]},{"w":"SAUCE","pron":"SAWS","syll":"sao · s","ety":["Old French *sauce* ← Medieval Latin *salsa* = salted thing ← *sal* = salt","A sauce was originally a salted, seasoned liquid. *Sal* = salt → *salt* (OE), *sauce, sausage* (seasoned with salt), *salsa* (Spanish salted thing), *salary* (Roman soldiers were paid in salt = *salarium*). *Sauce* and *salary* share a root: both are \"salt things.\" Food seasoning and pay both come from Latin *sal*."]},{"w":"DESSERT","pron":"d-ih-z-UR-t","syll":"dessert","ety":["French *dessert* ← *desservir* = to clear the table ← *de-* + *servir* = to serve away","Literally \"the un-serving\" — the final course after the main dishes are cleared (*served away*). *Servir* = serve → *servant, service, deserve* (*de-* + *serve* = serve away from = earn), *disservice* (serving away badly). *Desert* (abandon) and *dessert* (sweet final course) differ by one *s* — and the single *s* word = \"to abandon\" (*deserter* = one who abandons duty)."]},{"w":"FLAVOR","pron":"FLAY-ver","syll":"fley · ver","ety":["Old French *flaour* ← Latin *flatorius* ← *flare* = to blow","The thing that blows from food = the scent/taste that reaches you. *Flare* = blow → *flatulent* (*flatus* = a blowing = a gas), *inflate* (*in-* + *flare* = blow into), *deflate* (*de-* + *flare* = blow down from). The word for the taste of food literally means \"what blows toward you\" — a sensory metaphor preserved from Latin."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Sort into OE or French: *bread, sauce, milk, roast, wheat, boil, egg, fry, oat, season, salt, cuisine, barley, dessert, cream*. What pattern do you see?","trace":"Build the *sal* = salt family: *salt, sauce, sausage, salsa, salary, saline, brine* (OE). Then explain why Roman soldiers were paid in salt (*salarium* → salary).","build":"Research the *kitchen/cuisine* doublet: both come from Latin *coquina*. How did OE borrow it to get *kitchen* and French borrow it to get *cuisine*? Draw a diagram showing the two paths from one Latin source."}},{"id":"L34","n":34,"unit":4,"title":"French Fashion and Abstract Vocabulary — The Social Layer","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"French didn't just bring food and legal terms — it brought the entire vocabulary of social life, abstract thought, fashion, emotion, and courtesy that defines \"polite society\" in English to this day.","story":"The Norman elite controlled not just law and kitchen but art, fashion, architecture, religion, and social discourse. French brought: the vocabulary of emotion (*joy, pain, grief, pity, mercy, grace, desire, pleasure*), of courtesy (*courtesy, polite, gentle, noble, honor, loyal*), of fashion (*gown, robe, veil, lace, ribbon, jewel, fashion*), of governance (*government, council, mayor, noble, prince, parliament, sovereign*), and of the arts (*music, art, poetry, prose, verse, color, beauty, image*). Most \"abstract\" English vocabulary is French — because abstraction was the domain of the educated class that spoke French.","pattern":"French abstract vocabulary patterns: *-ment* suffix (*government, movement, moment, torment, sentiment*) = state or result of action. *-tion* through French (*nation, action, condition, potion, passion*) = same Latin *-tionem* but entering through French phonology. *-ity* through French (*city, pity, beauty, quality*) = Latin *-itatem* through French. When a word has an abstract meaning and ends in one of these suffixes, it almost certainly came through French after 1066.","connection":"The French abstract vocabulary layer defines \"educated\" and \"polite\" English. Virtually all English words about social status, emotion, courtesy, and abstract concepts entered through French after 1066 — and they still carry that social elevation today.","words":[{"w":"GRACE","pron":"GRAYS","syll":"grey · s","ety":["Old French *grace* ← Latin *gratia* = favor, goodwill ← *gratus* = pleasing","*Gratus* = pleasing → *grace, gracious, grateful* (full of grace/thankfulness), *gratitude, gratify, gratis* (freely, as a favor), *gratuity* (a tip = a favor). The Italian cognate: *grazie* (thank you = grace). *Dis-grace* = removal of grace = shame. In theology, *grace* = undeserved divine favor. The language of divine favor and table manners comes from the same Latin root."]},{"w":"BEAUTY","pron":"BYOO-tee","syll":"byuw · tiy","ety":["Old French *beauté* ← Latin *bellitas* ← *bellus* = beautiful, fine","*Bellus* = beautiful → *beauty, beautiful, belle* (beautiful woman, French loanword), *embellish* (*em-* + *bellish* = make beautiful). Latin *bellum* (war) is different from *bellus* (beautiful) — despite looking similar. *Belladonna* (*bella* + *donna* = beautiful woman) = deadly nightshade (which women used to dilate pupils, making eyes appear more beautiful)."]},{"w":"MERCY","pron":"MUR-see","syll":"mer · siy","ety":["Old French *merci* ← Latin *merces* = pay, reward, wages ← *merx* = goods","Originally: pay/reward given to a captive's life. Evolved to: clemency, compassion. *Merx* = goods → *merchant* (one who deals in goods), *merchandise* (goods for trade), *market* (place for goods), *commerce* (*com-* + *merx* = goods together = trade). Mercy and merchandise share a root: both originally involved an exchange of value."]},{"w":"GENTLE","pron":"JEH-ntuhl","syll":"jheh · ntah · l","ety":["Old French *gentil* ← Latin *gentilis* = of the same clan ← *gens/gentis* = family, clan","*Gens* = family/clan → *gentle, genteel, gentry, gentleman, gentile* (of another clan/nation = non-Jewish in Christian usage), *gendarme* (French: armed clan member = police), *genetics, gender, genus, generate*. A \"gentleman\" = originally \"a man of good family.\" Gentleness was a class attribute before it became a behavior attribute."]},{"w":"FASHION","pron":"FA-shuhn","syll":"fae · shah · n","ety":["Old French *façon* ← Latin *factio* ← *facere* = to make","Fashion = a making = a style of making/doing things. *Facere* (our L12 root!) → *fashion* (through French *façon*), *satisfaction, fact, artifact, manufacture*. The word for trendy clothing comes from the same Latin root that gives *fact, factor, perfect*. Fashion = a way of making things look a certain way."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Identify the French origin and original concrete meaning behind these abstract words: *grace* (favor), *mercy* (payment), *gentle* (family/clan), *beauty* (fine/beautiful), *fashion* (making). How did each become abstract?","trace":"Find 10 French abstract vocabulary words in each category: (1) emotions, (2) courtesy words, (3) governance words, (4) art/aesthetic words. Confirm each is French by etymology.","build":"Write a paragraph about a medieval court using only French-origin words. Then write the same scene using only OE-origin words. Which sounds \"courtly\"? Why?"}},{"id":"L35","n":35,"unit":4,"title":"French Doublets — When English Kept Both Words","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"English often borrowed a word from French while retaining the Old English word for the same concept — creating \"doublets\" where both survive with slightly different meanings, registers, or nuances.","story":"A doublet pair consists of two English words that descend from the same ultimate source but entered English through different paths, at different times, with different phonological development. Some come from the same Latin root through both OE (early) and French (late): *inn* (OE *inn*) / *hotel* (French *hôtel* ← Latin *hospitale*). Others come from the same French word borrowed twice at different times: *guarantee* (14th century) / *warranty* (13th century) — both from same Germanic root through French. The corpus of 129K words contains hundreds of such doublet pairs — and knowing them reveals both the OE and the French layer simultaneously.","pattern":"Doublet identification: if two words mean nearly the same thing but differ in register (one formal, one informal), they are likely doublets. The OE word = informal, concrete, physical. The French word = formal, abstract, elevated. Compare: *ask/question*, *begin/commence*, *end/finish*, *help/assist*, *holy/sacred*, *body/corpse*, *house/mansion*, *fear/terror*, *buy/purchase*. The pattern is consistent: short word = OE, longer word = French.","connection":"Doublets are the most visible evidence of English's layered vocabulary history. Every doublet pair is a record of two different historical moments: the OE/Norse layer and the French layer arriving at the same semantic destination through different paths.","words":[{"w":"FRAGILE","pron":"FRA-juhl","syll":"frag · ile","ety":["French *fragile* ← Latin *fragilis* ← *frangere* = to break","The doublet: *frail* (from the same Latin *fragilis* through different Old French path = *fraile* → English *frail*). *Fragile* = French scholarly borrowing, more technical. *Frail* = Old French common word, more everyday. Same Latin root, two French paths, two English words with slightly different registers."]},{"w":"GUARANTEE","pron":"geh-ruh-NTEE","syll":"geh · rah · ntiy","ety":["French *garantie* ← Germanic *warjan* = to protect","The doublet: *warranty* (from Anglo-Norman *warantie*, same Germanic root through Norman French path). *Guarantee* = more formal legal/commercial term. *Warranty* = specific commercial promise. Both from the same Germanic root through two different French dialects (Parisian *garantie* vs Norman *warantie*)."]},{"w":"ROYAL","pron":"ROY-uhl","syll":"roy · ah · l","ety":["Old French *roial* ← Latin *regalis* = of the king ← *rex/regis* = king","The doublet: *regal* (from same Latin *regalis* through different path — direct Latin borrowing). *Royal* = French path, more everyday in modern English. *Regal* = more purely Latin path, more formal/poetic. Same root, two paths, two English words. Same *rex/regis* = king → *reign, regent, regulate, correct* (*cor-* + *rect* = straight = rule correctly)."]},{"w":"GUARANTEE","pron":"geh-ruh-NTEE","syll":"geh · rah · ntiy","ety":["already used — swap to: *hostel*","Old French *hostel* ← Latin *hospitale* = guest house ← *hospes/hospitis* = host/guest. The doublet: *hotel* (later French *hôtel* = same Latin origin, more elevated). *Hospital* = same root again (a place for guests, then for patients). Three English words from one Latin root: *hostel, hotel, hospital* — three different paths from *hospitale*, entering English at different times with different social registers."]},{"w":"PITY","pron":"PIH-tee","syll":"pih · tiy","ety":["Old French *pité* ← Latin *pietas* = duty, piety, compassion","The doublet: *piety* (from same Latin *pietas* through more direct Latin path). *Pity* = French path, emotional compassion. *Piety* = more direct Latin path, religious devotion. Both from *pietas* = the quality of fulfilling one's duties (to gods, family, state). *Pius* = dutiful → *pious, impious, expiate* (fulfill a duty to remove guilt)."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Find the doublet partners: *fragile/frail, hostel/hotel, guarantee/warranty, royal/regal, pity/piety*. For each pair, explain the difference in register, timing, and path of entry.","trace":"The *rex/regis* = king root: find all English words from this root (*royal, regal, reign, regent, regnant, regulate, correct, rectangle, erect, surge*). Group them by which language they entered through.","build":"Create a \"doublet finder\" exercise: take 10 formal English words and find their informal OE equivalents. Confirm each pair is a true doublet (same ultimate source, different paths)."}},{"id":"L36","n":36,"unit":4,"title":"French Silent Letters — The Frozen Pronunciation of Medieval Paris","diff":"hard","bigIdea":"French loanwords preserved in English carry French silent letters — final consonants that were once pronounced in Old French but fell silent as French phonology evolved, while English spelling preserved the archaic forms.","story":"Old French (as spoken 1066–1400) pronounced many final consonants that Modern French (and Modern English borrowings) do not. When English borrowed French words, it sometimes preserved the old pronunciation (making the final consonant part of English pronunciation) and sometimes preserved only the spelling (keeping the consonant silent as French had made it). The result: words like *ballet* (ba-LAY, final *-t* silent), *bouquet* (boo-KAY, final *-t* silent), *rendezvous* (RON-day-voo, final *-s* silent), *corps* (KOR, both *p* AND *s* silent). These represent the frozen spelling of medieval French pronunciation preserved in modern English.","pattern":"French silent consonant patterns in English: Final *-t* silent after vowel: *ballet, bouquet, crochet, ricochet, parquet, valet, buffet, debut*. Final *-s* silent: *rendezvous, corps, chassis, debris*. Final *-x* silent in plurals: *tableaux, châteaux, beaux* (compare singular *tableau, château, beau*). Silent *-p* in *corps* — both *p* and *s* are silent! At a spelling bee: ask \"What language?\" + \"Is there a final silent consonant?\" for any French word.","connection":"French silent letters are not errors — they preserve the pronunciation of 14th-century Parisian French in the spelling of 21st-century English. Every silent final consonant in a French loanword is a phonological fossil.","words":[{"w":"RENDEZVOUS","pron":"RAH-ndih-voo","syll":"raa · ndih · vuw","ety":["French *rendez-vous* = present yourselves ← *rendre* = to present + *vous* = you (formal)","Final *-s* completely silent: RON-day-voo. Both the *z* in *rendez-* AND the *s* in *-vous* are silent. Spelling frozen from Old French where this was a verb phrase (*rendez-vous* = \"present yourselves [at this place]\") that became a noun. One of the most challenging French spellings: R-E-N-D-E-Z-V-O-U-S."]},{"w":"CORPS","pron":"KAWR","syll":"kao · r","ety":["French *corps* = body ← Latin *corpus* = body","Both the *p* AND the *s* are silent: /KOR/. Plural *corps* = /KORZ/ (the *s* becomes /z/ in the plural — finally pronounced!). *Corps* is the most dramatically silent English word: 4 letters, only 3 sounds, and the *p* has been silent since French stopped pronouncing it. Military *corps* and human *corpse* are the same Latin *corpus*."]},{"w":"BALLET","pron":"ba-LAY","syll":"bae · ley","ety":["French *ballet* ← Italian *balletto* ← *ballare* = to dance ← Medieval Latin *ballare*","Final *-t* silent: ba-LAY. The word traveled from Latin through Italian (*balletto* = little dance) to French (*ballet*) to English. Each language borrowed the spelling of the previous; English borrowed the French spelling AND the French pronunciation (silent *t*). Italian diminutive *-etto* → French *-et* → English *-et* (usually silent)."]},{"w":"SILHOUETTE","pron":"s-ih-l-uh-w-EH-t","syll":"silhouette","ety":["French *silhouette* ← Étienne de Silhouette (French finance minister, 1709–1767)","An eponym — named after the finance minister who imposed austerity measures; his name became slang for cheap, outline-only portraiture (done in his honor mockingly). The final *-ette* = French diminutive suffix (double-t). S-I-L-H-O-U-E-T-T-E: the *-h-* is silent, the *-ou-* = /oo/, the *-ette* = /et/. French spelling patterns throughout."]},{"w":"DEBUT","pron":"day-BYOO","syll":"dey · byuw","ety":["French *début* ← *débuter* = to lead off ← *de-* + *but* = target/goal","A debut = one's first appearance (leading off toward the goal). Final *-t* silent: day-BYOO. *But* in French = goal/target (still used in soccer: *but* = a goal). English *butt* (a target) comes from the same source. The soccer goal and a performer's debut share a French word for \"target.\""]}],"practice":{"decode":"For each French loanword, identify: which consonant is silent, AND what the pronunciation is: *ballet, bouquet, crochet, ricochet, parquet, valet, buffet, debut, rendezvous, corps*.","trace":"The *-eau/-eaux* pattern: singular *tableau/château/bureau* → plural *tableaux/châteaux/bureaux* (the *x* is silent in both). Find 5 more *-eau* words and confirm their silent *x* plurals.","build":"Research how to identify French words at a spelling bee microphone: what 3 questions should you ask, and what rules does each answer activate? Write your personal \"French word protocol.\""}},{"id":"L37","n":37,"unit":4,"title":"French Verb Patterns — How -ize, -ify, -ment Entered English","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"French brought verb-forming and noun-forming suffixes that are now among the most productive in English — *-ize*, *-ify*, *-ment*, *-ance/-ence* are all ultimately French imports that English has made its own.","story":"When French verbs entered English, they carried their verb-forming suffixes: *-iser* (French) → *-ize* in English (*organize, realize, recognize, criticize*). *-ifier* (French) → *-ify* in English (*modify, terrify, satisfy, justify*). *-ment* (French noun suffix) → English *-ment* (*movement, government, judgment, torment, sentiment*). *-ance/-ence* (French abstract noun suffixes) → English (*distance, balance, patience, science*). These suffixes are now \"English\" — we use them to form new words from non-French roots: *Americanize, computerize, monetize, publicize*. The French suffixes outlasted their French roots.","pattern":"Suffix productivity in modern English: *-ize* is now the most productive verb-forming suffix in English — used to coin new verbs from any noun or adjective: *hospitalize, prioritize, finalize, maximize, customize, digitize, computerize, monetize*. It entered through French but is now attached to roots from any language. *-ify* = make into (*terrify = make terrible, purify = make pure, magnify = make great*). *-ment* creates abstract nouns from verbs (*move → movement, govern → government, judge → judgment, achieve → achievement*).","connection":"French verb and noun suffixes (*-ize, -ify, -ment, -ance/-ence*) are now the most productive suffixes in English — used to coin new words from any language's roots. French provided the machinery; English has been using it for 900 years.","words":[{"w":"ORGANIZE","pron":"AW-rguh-neyez","syll":"ao · rgah · nay · z","ety":["French *organiser* ← Medieval Latin *organizare* ← Greek *organon* = tool/instrument","To organize = make into a functioning instrument/tool. *Organon* = instrument → *organ* (musical instrument, then body organ), *organic* (instrument-like = living), *organism* (a living instrument). *-ize* = French suffix → English productive verb-forming suffix. Every new *-ize* verb (*digitize, monetize*) follows the French pattern."]},{"w":"TERRIFY","pron":"t-EH-r-uh-f-ay","syll":"terrify","ety":["French *terrifier* ← Latin *terrere* (to frighten) + *-fy* ← *facere* (to make)","To make terror. *-ify* = French *-ifier* = Latin *-ficare* = *facere* (make) + connecting vowel. *Terrere* = frighten → *terrible, terror, terrific* (originally \"causing terror\"), *deter* (*de-* + *terrere* = frighten away from). *Terrific* once meant \"causing great terror\" — now means \"extremely good.\" Semantic amelioration over 400 years."]},{"w":"MOVEMENT","pron":"MOO-vmuhnt","syll":"muw · vmah · nt","ety":["Old French *movement* ← *mouvoir* = to move ← Latin *movere*","The *-ment* suffix creates an abstract noun from a verb: *move → movement*. Also: *government* (act of governing), *judgment* (act of judging), *achievement* (act of achieving), *settlement* (act of settling), *astonishment* (act of being astonished). The *-ment* suffix = French *-ment* = Latin *-mentum* = means/result of the action."]},{"w":"PATIENCE","pron":"p-AY-sh-uh-n-s","syll":"patience","ety":["Old French *pacience* ← Latin *patientia* ← *pati* = to suffer, endure","The ability to endure. *Pati* = suffer/endure → *patience, patient* (one who endures = a medical patient), *passion* (enduring great suffering = Christ's passion), *compassion* (*com-* + *pati* = suffering together), *impassive* (not moved by suffering), *passive* (enduring without action). Medical and emotional vocabulary connected through *pati*."]},{"w":"BALANCE","pron":"BA-luhns","syll":"bae · lah · ns","ety":["Old French *balance* ← Latin *bilanx* = two-pan scale ← *bi-* (two) + *lanx* (pan)","A balance has two pans. *Lanx* = plate/pan (rare in English; more common in Italian *bilancia*). *Bi-* + *lanx* → *balance*. The same *bi-* = two appears throughout English (bicycle, bilingual). The two-pan scale metaphor → weighing equally → equilibrium → the modern meaning of balance in all its senses (financial balance, work-life balance, balance of power)."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Find 10 recently coined *-ize* verbs (*monetize, digitize, customize, maximize, prioritize...*). For each, identify the root language of the base word (OE, Latin, French, Greek, or other).","trace":"The *pati* = suffer root: find *patience, patient, passion, compassion, passive, impassive, compatible* (*com-* + *pati* = being able to suffer together). Explain how each word uses the \"suffering/enduring\" metaphor.","build":"The *-ment* suffix creates abstract nouns: *move/movement, govern/government, judge/judgment, achieve/achievement*. Create 10 more pairs. Then find 5 cases where the *-ment* noun has changed meaning significantly from its verb (e.g., *moment* from *move* — hardly obvious now)."}},{"id":"L38","n":38,"unit":4,"title":"French -eur Words — The Agent Suffix That Never Anglicized","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"French *-eur* = one who does (masculine agent suffix). These words never Anglicized their ending to *-er* — they kept the French *-eur* permanently. The most common misspelling: *restauranteur* (should be *restaurateur* — no *n*!).","story":"When French masculine agent nouns entered English, they kept their *-eur* ending instead of adopting the English *-er*: *connoisseur, chauffeur, raconteur, saboteur, entrepreneur, provocateur, restaurateur*. This is unusual — English usually forces French words into English patterns. The *-eur* words resisted because they arrived in English fully formed, carrying prestige, in formal/educated contexts where the French form was the \"correct\" form. Additionally, *-eur* words are still being borrowed from French: *auteur* (film director as author, 1950s film theory), *flaneur* (one who strolls observing the city = a wanderer).","pattern":"The *-eur* spelling rule: if a word means \"a person who does [sophisticated/formal activity]\" and ends in /ur/ sound, write *-eur* not *-er*: *connoisseur, chauffeur, raconteur, saboteur, entrepreneur, restaurateur, provocateur, grandeur, auteur*. ⚠️ *Restaurateur* = NO *n* before *-eur*. It comes from *restaurer* (to restore) — not from *restaurant*. The *-n-* in *restaurant* is NOT part of the *restaurer* verb stem that generates the agent noun. *Restauranteur* inserts a *n* that doesn't belong.","connection":"The French *-eur* agent suffix refused to Anglicize — it is one of the clearest examples of English preserving a borrowed suffix intact when the social prestige of the source language demanded it.","words":[{"w":"ENTREPRENEUR","pron":"ah-n-t-r-uh-p-r-uh-n-UR","syll":"entrepreneur","ety":["French *entreprendre* = to undertake ← *entre-* (between) + *prendre* (to take)","One who undertakes (takes on a project between supplier and customer). E-N-T-R-E-P-R-E-N-E-U-R — 12 letters, four syllables, NO double letters anywhere despite the complexity. Spell by syllables: *en·tre·pre·neur*. The *-eur* = French agent suffix. *Prendre* = take → *comprehend* (*com-* + *prehend* = take together), *apprehend* (*ad-* + *prehend* = take toward)."]},{"w":"CONNOISSEUR","pron":"k-ah-n-uh-s-UR","syll":"connoisseur","ety":["French *connaisseur* ← *connaître* = to know ← Latin *cognoscere*","One who knows (deeply, expertly). C-O-N-N-O-I-S-S-E-U-R: double-*n* (from *con-* prefix meeting *n-*root) AND double-*s* (French *-aiss-* → *-oiss-*) AND *-eur* suffix. Three spelling challenges in one word. The *cognoscere* root → *recognize, cognitive, incognito* (unknown), *cognizant*."]},{"w":"CHAUFFEUR","pron":"sh-oh-f-UR","syll":"chauffeur","ety":["French *chauffeur* = one who heats ← *chauffer* = to heat ← Latin *calefacere*","Etymologically: one who heats. Early steam-powered cars needed a *chauffeur* to heat/stoke the boiler. The word stuck even after steam engines were replaced by internal combustion. C-H-A-U-F-F-E-U-R: double-*f* from French *chauffer* + *-eur* suffix. *Calefacere* = heat → *chafe* (warm by rubbing), *chafing dish* (a heated serving vessel)."]},{"w":"RACONTEUR","pron":"ra-kah-NTOOR","syll":"rae · kaa · ntuw · r","ety":["French *raconteur* ← *raconter* = to tell stories ← *re-* + *aconter* = to count up again","One who tells stories (skillfully). *Compter/conter* = to count, to recount (a story) → *recount* (tell again), *account* (a telling = a financial telling). The connection between counting (numbers) and recounting (stories) is preserved in the shared *conter/compter* root. A raconteur and an accountant share a Latin root."]},{"w":"RESTAURATEUR","pron":"reh-ster-uh-TUR","syll":"reh · ster · ah · ter","ety":["French *restaurateur* ← *restaurer* = to restore ← Latin *restaurare*","One who restores (through food). NO *n* before *-eur*: R-E-S-T-A-U-R-A-T-E-U-R. *Restaurare* = restore → *restore, restoration, restaurant* (a place that restores you). The agent noun comes from the VERB *restaurer*, not from the NOUN *restaurant*. The *n* in *restaurant* comes from the French present participle *-ant* ending — it does NOT transfer to the agent noun."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Find 5 more English words with the French *-eur* agent ending (*auteur, flaneur, voyageur, masseur, coiffeur, grandeur*). For each, identify the French verb it comes from.","trace":"The *restaurateur* trap: explain in your own words why *restauranteur* is wrong and *restaurateur* is correct. Then find 3 other commonly misspelled *-eur* words.","build":"The French *-eur* suffix and the English *-er* suffix both mean \"one who does.\" List 5 English *-er* words and their French *-eur* equivalents for the same profession: *worker/laborer (→ travailleur), teacher/instructor, cook/chef, driver/chauffeur, storyteller/raconteur*."}},{"id":"L39","n":39,"unit":4,"title":"French Spelling Patterns — A Complete Reference","diff":"hard","bigIdea":"French loanwords follow identifiable spelling patterns that differ systematically from Latin and Greek patterns. This lesson is a reference for French spelling recognition at the championship level.","story":"The complete French spelling signal system: (1) *-eau/-eaux* = /oh/, plural adds *x*: *tableau/tableaux, château/châteaux, bureau/bureaux*. (2) *-oir/-oire* = /wahr/: *boudoir, reservoir, memoir, repertoire*. (3) *-ette* = French diminutive (double-t): *pirouette, marionette, silhouette, vignette*. (4) *-esque* = in the style of: *picturesque, grotesque, arabesque*. (5) *-ique* = French adjective signal /eek/: *unique, oblique, technique, boutique*. (6) *-eur* = French agent: see L38. (7) Silent final consonants: *-t, -s, -x* after vowels (see L36). (8) *-tion* = /shon/ not /shun/ in words directly from French: *nation, passion* (same suffix, different path). These 8 patterns cover ~80% of French loanword spelling challenges.","pattern":"French word diagnostic at the spelling bee microphone: Is it French? Key questions: Does it end in a silent consonant? Does it have *-eau/-oir/-ette/-esque/-ique*? Does it have an *-eur* agent? Is it a culinary/legal/fashion/art term? If yes to any of these → apply French spelling rules: accent-aware, silent-final, *qu* = /k/, no *-er* agent endings.","connection":"The 8 French spelling patterns cover ~80% of French spelling challenges. At the spelling bee microphone: identify French → run through the 8-pattern checklist → commit to the spelling.","words":[{"w":"BOUTIQUE","pron":"b-oo-t-EE-k","syll":"boutique","ety":["French *boutique* = small shop ← Greek *apothēkē* = storehouse ← *apo-* + *tithēnai* = to place away","Small specialty shop. The *-ique* ending = /eek/ — French signal. Note the journey: Greek *apothēkē* → Latin *apotheca* → Old French *boitigue/botique* → French *boutique* → English. Also: *bodega* (Spanish from same Greek root = a wine cellar/small store), *apothecary* (Medieval Latin form = a pharmacist). Three different English words from one Greek \"placing-away\" storehouse."]},{"w":"RESERVOIR","pron":"r-EH-z-uh-v-w-ah-r","syll":"reservoir","ety":["French *réservoir* ← *réserver* = to reserve ← Latin *reservare*","A place that stores/reserves water. R-E-S-E-R-V-O-I-R: the *-oir* = /wahr/ ending (French signal). The *-oir* ending always signals French. *Reserve* came through French too but Anglicized (dropping *-oir*). *Reservoir* kept the French form. Same Latin *reservare* root: *reserve, reservation, reserved, unreserved*."]},{"w":"VIGNETTE","pron":"vih-NYEHT","syll":"vi · gnette","ety":["French *vignette* ← *vigne* = vine (diminutive = little vine)","Originally: a decorative vine-border on a book page. Then: a small illustration. Then: a brief literary sketch. The *-ette* diminutive = double-t always: V-I-G-N-E-T-T-E. *Vigne* = vine → *wine* (through Germanic path: *wein*), *vine* (through French), *vintage* (*vendange* = grape harvest = *vendre* + *vandange*), *vineyard*. Vines gave English *vignette* and *wine*."]},{"w":"ARABESQUE","pron":"ar-ah-BESK","syll":"ar · a · besque","ety":["French *arabesque* ← Italian *arabesco* = in the Arabic style","An ornate geometric design (from Arabic architectural patterns). *-esque* = in the style of: *picturesque* (in the style of a picture = visually charming), *grotesque* (*grotto* style = bizarre), *burlesque* (comic theatrical style), *statuesque* (statue-like = impressively tall). The *-esque* suffix entered English through French and Italian and is still productive: *Kafkaesque, Orwellian* (different suffix)."]},{"w":"PIROUETTE","pron":"p-ih-r-oo-EH","syll":"pirouette","ety":["French *pirouette* ← *pirer* = to spin","A spinning turn in ballet. P-I-R-O-U-E-T-T-E: the *-ette* ending (double-t), the *-ou-* = /oo/ vowel combination. Four French spelling patterns visible: *-ou-*, *-ette*, final *-e* (silent), stress on the final syllable (French stress pattern vs English first-syllable stress). This single word is a French spelling exam."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Apply the 8-pattern French spelling system to: *reservoir* (-oir), *tableau* (-eau), *pirouette* (-ette), *boutique* (-ique), *arabesque* (-esque), *restaurateur* (-eur), *ballet* (silent-t), *corps* (silent-ps). Identify which pattern each uses.","trace":"The *-ique* pattern: *unique, oblique, technique, boutique, mystique, antique, clique, opaque* (note: *opaque* uses *-que* not *-ique*). Sort by sub-pattern: *-ique* (with *-i-* before *que*) vs *-que* (just *que*). Which pronunciation does each have?","build":"Build a complete \"French Spelling Cheat Sheet\" with all 8 patterns, 3 examples each, and the pronunciation rule for each. This is your personal championship reference card."}},{"id":"L40","n":40,"unit":4,"title":"Anglo-Norman Oddities — When French Got Weird in England","diff":"hard","bigIdea":"Anglo-Norman was a dialect of French spoken in England after 1066, isolated from Parisian French for 300 years. This isolation created unique spelling and pronunciation developments that appear in specific English legal and formal vocabulary.","story":"Anglo-Norman French (the French of England, 1066–1400) diverged from continental French because English speakers were using it alongside Old English. The result: Anglo-Norman preserved archaic French forms that continental French discarded, created unique spellings influenced by English scribal habits, and developed pronunciations that differed from Parisian French. Words like *attorney, affidavit, estoppel, tortfeasor, chattel, vavasour* are recognizably Anglo-Norman because of their archaic spelling patterns. Even more interesting: some words entered English from Anglo-Norman with spellings that differ from the modern French equivalent — because the Anglo-Norman spelling was fixed before Parisian French reformed its own spelling.","pattern":"Anglo-Norman distinctive patterns: *-oun* for *-on*: *noun, count, mount, fount* (vs French *-on*). *-aun-* cluster: *haunt, gaunt, vaunt, daunt, jaunt, gauntlet*. *-aint-*: *saint, faint, plaint, taint, quaint*. *-aign-*: *reign, feign, deign, arraign*. *-eur-* (not *-our-*) in some words. These patterns are fossil forms of 12th-century Norman French preserved in English while continental French moved on.","connection":"Anglo-Norman is a linguistic time-capsule — 12th-century French frozen in English while continental French kept evolving. The distinctive *-eign/-aign/-aint/-aun-* patterns are its fingerprints in the English vocabulary.","words":[{"w":"SOVEREIGN","pron":"s-AH-v-r-uh-n","syll":"sovereign","ety":["Anglo-Norman *soverain* ← Vulgar Latin *superanus* = supreme","The *-eign* ending = Anglo-Norman preservation of an old form (continental French would give *souverain* → *sovereign* with slightly different development). S-O-V-E-R-E-I-G-N: the silent *-gn* at the end is the Anglo-Norman spelling signal. Compare *foreign* (*forain* in Old French → *foreign* in English), *reign* (*reigner* → *reign*), *feign* (*feindre* → *feign*). All have silent *-gn* from Anglo-Norman."]},{"w":"ATTORNEY","pron":"uh-t-UR-n-ee","syll":"attorney","ety":["Anglo-Norman *atourné* = appointed ← *atourner* = to turn toward","The Anglo-Norman spelling preserved the *at-* prefix form (continental French would develop differently). *Atourner* = *a-* + *tourner* = turn toward = appoint. The *-ney* ending = Anglo-Norman evolution of French *-né* (past participle). Compare *journey* (*journée* = a day's travel → Anglo-Norman *jornee* → *journey*)."]},{"w":"QUAINT","pron":"KWAYNT","syll":"kwey · nt","ety":["Anglo-Norman *cointe* = clever, knowledgeable ← Latin *cognitus* = known","Originally meant \"clever, ingenious, skillfully made.\" The Anglo-Norman form *cointe* → English *quaint* with vowel shift. By the 19th century: attractively old-fashioned. Semantic shift from \"cleverly made\" to \"charmingly old.\" *Cognitus* = known → *cognizant, recognize, incognito* (unknown). A word meaning \"clever/known\" evolved to mean \"charmingly antique.\""]},{"w":"GAUGE","pron":"g-AY-j","syll":"gauge","ety":["Anglo-Norman *gauge* = a measuring instrument ← Germanic *galgo* = a pole, measuring rod","G-A-U-G-E: the *-au-* cluster = Anglo-Norman vowel signal. *Galgo* = pole/rod (for measurement) → *gauge*. The related word *engage* (*en-* + *gage* = put in a pledge = commit) and *disengage* share the same root. A measuring rod, a pledge, and military disengagement all trace to a Germanic measuring-pole."]},{"w":"HAUNT","pron":"HAWNT","syll":"hhao · nt","ety":["Anglo-Norman *hanter* = to frequent ← Germanic *heimaz* = home","The *-au-* cluster = Anglo-Norman signal. Originally: to visit a place regularly (as if it were your home). The ghost meaning developed because spirits were believed to \"haunt\" = frequent the places of their former lives. The OE *home* concept traveled through Germanic → Norse → Anglo-Norman, acquiring the supernatural connotation in English."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Identify the Anglo-Norman pattern in each: *sovereign* (-eign), *reign* (-eign), *foreign* (-eign), *feign* (-eign), *arraign* (-aign), *campaign* (-aign), *saint* (-aint), *faint* (-aint), *haunt* (-au-), *gaunt* (-au-). What do all these patterns have in common?","trace":"Compare modern French spelling with Anglo-Norman spelling for the same words: *French souverain / English sovereign*, *French feindre / English feign*, *French campagne / English campaign*. What systematic differences do you see?","build":"The *-gn* silent cluster in Anglo-Norman English: *sign, design, align, assign, benign, malign, reign, foreign, sovereign*. Research why the *g* is silent in these words. What was the original pronunciation, and when did it fall silent?"}},{"id":"L41","n":41,"unit":5,"title":"The Journey of Alcohol — From Arabic Eye Makeup to English Spirits","diff":"hard","bigIdea":"A single word can travel through 5 languages over 1,000 years, changing meaning at every stop, yet arrive in English with a recognizable shape. *Alcohol* is the most dramatic example.","story":"Arabic *al-kuḥl* (with the definite article *al-* = \"the\") originally referred to a fine powder of antimony sulfide used as eye makeup — what we now call *kohl* (the eyeliner). Medieval Arabic alchemists extended *al-kuḥl* to describe any fine powder obtained through sublimation. Medieval European alchemists borrowed the Arabic term and applied it to spirits distilled by sublimation — first *alcohol of wine*. Eventually \"of wine\" was dropped and *alcohol* came to mean the distilled substance itself. Journey: Arabic (eye makeup powder) → Latin alchemical term (any sublimated powder) → European chemistry (distilled spirits) → English everyday (intoxicating drink). Five stops, five meaning shifts, one word.","pattern":"Arabic word journeys always involve the definite article *al-* = \"the.\" The *al-* prefix was absorbed WITH the word into English: *alcohol* (*al-kuḥl*), *algebra* (*al-jabr*), *algorithm* (from *al-Khwarizmi*), *alchemy* (*al-kimiya*), *almanac* (*al-manakh*), *alcove* (*al-qubba*), *aldehyde* (*al-kuḥl* + *de-hydrogen-ated*), *alkali* (*al-qily* = wood ash). The *al-* in these words = fossilized Arabic \"the.\" It is the most recognizable Arabic loan signal in English.","connection":"Word journeys reveal the history of trade, conquest, science, and cultural exchange embedded in vocabulary. Every word with multiple language stops tells a story of human contact across civilizations.","words":[{"w":"ALCOHOL","pron":"A-lkuh-hahl","syll":"ae · lkah · hhaa · l","ety":["Arabic *al-kuḥl* (eye powder) → Latin *alcohol* (sublimated powder) → English (distilled spirit)","Full journey: Arabic eye makeup → medieval alchemy technical term → European chemical vocabulary → modern English everyday word. A-L-C-O-H-O-L: the *al-* = Arabic \"the.\" The word *kohl* (eyeliner) is the same Arabic root without the article. The eyeliner and the drink share an Arabic word for \"fine powder.\""]},{"w":"ALGEBRA","pron":"A-ljuh-bruh","syll":"ae · ljhah · brah","ety":["Arabic *al-jabr* = the reunion of broken parts ← *jabara* = to reunite broken bones","Al-Khwarizmi's 830 CE treatise: *Kitāb al-mukhtaṣar fī ḥisāb al-jabr wal-muqābalah*. *Al-jabr* = completing broken equations by moving terms — a bone-setting metaphor. A medical procedure for broken bones became the name of a branch of mathematics. Journey: Arabic surgery metaphor → mathematical operation → English academic subject."]},{"w":"ASSASSIN","pron":"uh-s-A-s-uh-n","syll":"assassin","ety":["Arabic *Ḥashshāshīn* (hashish users) → Old French *assassin* → English","A medieval Islamic sect (the Nizari Ismailis) was labeled *Ḥashshāshīn* by their enemies — supposedly hashish users. Crusaders encountered them and brought the word to France as *assassin*. English borrowed it from French. The original drug-user slur became the English word for a political killer. Journey: Arabic slur → French military term → English crime vocabulary."]},{"w":"MAGAZINE","pron":"MA-guh-zeen","syll":"mae · gah · ziy · n","ety":["Arabic *makhāzin* (pl. of *makhzan* = storehouse) → Italian *magazzino* → French *magasin* → English","Arabic storehouse → Italian warehouse → French military storehouse (for ammunition) → English storage of information → English periodical publication. A storehouse became a publication because both \"store\" goods/information. Journey: Arabic storage → Italian warehouse → French armory → English periodical."]},{"w":"SUGAR","pron":"SHUU-ger","syll":"shuh · ger","ety":["Sanskrit *śarkarā* (gravel, gritty sugar) → Arabic *sukkar* → Medieval Latin *succarum* → Old French *sucre* → English","Journey through 5 languages: Sanskrit (gritty crystals resembling gravel) → Arabic trade vocabulary → Medieval Latin scholarly term → Old French (vowel change) → English (reduction). A Sanskrit word for grainy texture became English's sweetest word through five linguistic transfers over 1,000 years."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Trace the full journey of *alcohol* through its 5 stops. What was the meaning at each stop? What changed? What stayed the same?","trace":"Research the word *coffee* (Arabic *qahwa* → Turkish *kahve* → Italian *caffè* → French *café* → English). Map its journey: what happened to the word at each linguistic border?","build":"Write a \"word passport\" for *sugar*: country of origin, date of entry to each language (approximate), meaning change at each border. What does this journey reveal about the history of the sugar trade?"}},{"id":"L42","n":42,"unit":5,"title":"The Greek→Latin→French→English Pipeline","diff":"hard","bigIdea":"The single most common word journey in the 129K database: Greek word → borrowed into Latin → traveled to France as Latin → became French → entered English after 1066. 1,156 words follow this precise route.","story":"Greek philosophical and scientific vocabulary entered Latin during the Roman period (roughly 300 BCE – 400 CE). When Rome conquered the Mediterranean world, it encountered Greek civilization and absorbed it — including the vocabulary. Latin kept the Greek word but Latinized it: Greek *philosophia* → Latin *philosophia*. When the Roman Empire fell, Latin became the scholarly language preserved in monasteries. Medieval scholars working in France used Latin — including all the Latinized Greek words. When French developed as a written language, it absorbed this scholarly Latin — including the Greek-origin words. When English absorbed French after 1066, it got this entire chain. Example: Greek *philosophia* → Latin *philosophia* → Old French *philosophie* → English *philosophy*. The Greek word traveled 1,500 years and 4 languages to reach English.","pattern":"The Greek→Latin→French→English pipeline leaves a specific spelling signature: the word retains the Greek *ph* = /f/ spelling (because the *ph* was preserved throughout the chain), but loses other Greek signals (the *ch* = /k/ may become /sh/ in French, the *y* as vowel may change). So *philosophy* keeps *ph* but sounds nothing like Greek. *Phenomenon* (directly from Greek) keeps more Greek signals than *fancy* (from Latin *phantasia* ← Greek *phantazein*).","connection":"The Greek→Latin→French→English pipeline is the dominant word journey in formal English vocabulary. Recognizing it explains why formal English looks Latin while containing Greek ideas — the Greek traveled inside Latin like a seed inside a fruit.","words":[{"w":"PHILOSOPHY","pron":"fuh-LAH-suh-fee","syll":"fah · laa · sah · fiy","ety":["Greek *philosophia* → Latin *philosophia* → Old French *philosophie* → English","The clearest pipeline example. *Philo-* (love) + *sophia* (wisdom). The Greek *ph* = /f/ survives. The Greek *-ia* ending → French *-ie* → English *-y*. At each stage, something is preserved (*ph*, the meaning) and something changes (pronunciation, vowel endings). 1,500 years of travel, the word is still recognizably Greek."]},{"w":"FANTASY","pron":"FA-ntuh-see","syll":"fae · ntah · siy","ety":["Greek *phantazein* → Latin *phantasia* → Old French *fantasie* → English","Greek *phantazein* = to make visible (from *phainein* = to show). Latin *phantasia* = imagination. French *fantasie* = mental image. English *fantasy* = imaginative fiction. The *ph* changed to *f* in English (though British English keeps *ph*: *phantasy*). The Greek concept of \"making visible in the mind\" became the English word for imaginative fiction."]},{"w":"TRAGEDY","pron":"TRA-juh-dee","syll":"trae · jhah · diy","ety":["Greek *tragōidia* → Latin *tragoedia* → Old French *tragedie* → English","From L27: goat-song. Each language transliterated the Greek: Latin kept *tragoedia* (the *oe* = Latin rendering of Greek *oi*), French simplified to *tragedie*, English dropped the final *-e*. The word has been in continuous use since Greek theater, 2,500 years without losing its core meaning."]},{"w":"SYMMETRY","pron":"SIH-muh-tree","syll":"sih · mah · triy","ety":["Greek *symmetria* → Latin *symmetria* → French *symétrie* → English","*Syn-* (together) + *metron* (measure) = measured together = equal proportions. The pipeline: Greek mathematical term → Latin architecture/art term → French aesthetic term → English general term. At each stage the word expanded slightly in application while maintaining its core meaning."]},{"w":"PARADISE","pron":"PEH-ruh-deyes","syll":"peh · rah · day · s","ety":["Greek *paradeisos* ← Old Persian *pairi-daeza* → Latin *paradisus* → Old French *paradis* → English","This pipeline starts with OLD PERSIAN, not Greek! Persian *pairi-daeza* (walled garden) → Greek *paradeisos* → Latin *paradisus* (used for Garden of Eden in the Septuagint/Bible) → French *paradis* → English. A Persian royal garden became Hebrew/Christian heaven through Greek Bible translation, then traveled the standard pipeline to English."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Trace the complete pipeline for: *philosophy, fantasy, tragedy, symmetry, paradise*. At each stop, note what changed (spelling, pronunciation, meaning) and what was preserved.","trace":"Find 5 more words that followed the Greek→Latin→French→English pipeline. Confirm each step by checking etymology sources.","build":"Compare *phenomenon* (entered English directly from Greek) with *fancy* (Greek *phantazein* → Latin → French → English). How do their spelling and pronunciation differ, and why? What does this tell you about how much the pipeline changes a word?"}},{"id":"L43","n":43,"unit":5,"title":"The Silk Road in English — Words That Crossed Continents","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"The ancient trade routes connecting China, India, Persia, Arabia, and Europe carried not just silk and spices but words — and many of those words are now ordinary English.","story":"The Silk Road (roughly 130 BCE – 1450 CE) was a network of trade routes connecting China to the Mediterranean. As goods traveled, their names traveled with them. Words followed the routes of trade: Chinese → Persian → Arabic → Greek/Latin → European languages → English. Or: Sanskrit (India) → Arabic (trade middlemen) → European languages → English. Words like *silk* (Greek *sēr* = silkworm → Latin *sericum* → Old English *seoloc*), *cinnamon* (Hebrew *qinnāmôn* → Greek *kinnamōmon* → Latin → English), *ginger* (Sanskrit *śṛṅgavera* → Greek → Latin → French → English), *musk* (Sanskrit *muska* = scrotum → Pahlavi *mušk* → Arabic → Latin → French → English). Each word is a record of an ancient trade contact.","pattern":"Silk Road word journey pattern: the word originates in the producing culture (China for silk, India for spices), gets absorbed into the trade language (Persian, then Arabic), enters the scholarly/commercial language (Latin or Greek), then reaches Western European vernaculars (French, Italian), and finally enters English. The number of syllables often decreases at each step as the word becomes more familiar and colloquial.","connection":"Every spice in your kitchen has a word journey story. These journeys reveal which cultures were in contact, who controlled trade, and how commodities and their names spread simultaneously across the ancient world.","words":[{"w":"SILK","pron":"SIHLK","syll":"sih · lk","ety":["Greek *sēr* (silkworm) → Latin *sericum* → Old English *seoloc* → Middle English *silk*","The Silk Road gave English its most famous traded commodity's name. Greek *sēr* = the worm → *sericin* (the protein in silk), *sericulture* (silk farming). The journey compressed: Greek *sēr-ikon* (silken) → Latin *sericum* → OE *seoloc* → ME *silk* (5 syllables compressed to 1). The most-traveled commodity became the most-compressed word."]},{"w":"CINNAMON","pron":"SIH-nuh-muhn","syll":"cin · na · mon","ety":["Hebrew *qinnāmôn* → Greek *kinnamōmon* → Latin *cinnamomum* → Old French *cynamome* → English","Hebrew *qinnāmôn* probably from Malay/Phoenician trade vocabulary (the spice came from Ceylon/Sri Lanka). Journey: Southeast Asia → Phoenicia → Hebrew → Greek → Latin → French → English. Cinnamon traveled further to reach English than it did to reach Rome."]},{"w":"GINGER","pron":"JIH-njer","syll":"jhih · njher","ety":["Sanskrit *śṛṅgavera* → Greek *zingiberis* → Latin *zingiber* → Old French *gingibre* → English","Sanskrit *śṛṅgavera* = \"horn-body\" (from the shape of the root). Greek compressed this to *zingiberis*. Latin to *zingiber*. French to *gingibre*. English simplified to *ginger*. Each language step compressed the Sanskrit compound. The \"horn\" metaphor in the original Sanskrit is completely invisible in the modern English word."]},{"w":"JASMINE","pron":"JA-zmuhn","syll":"jhae · zmah · n","ety":["Arabic *yāsamīn* ← Persian *yāsamān* ← Sanskrit *yūthikā*","Persian flower name → Arabic trade word → entering European languages in multiple ways: French *jasmin*, Spanish *jazmín*, English *jasmine*. The final *-e* in English *jasmine* came from the French form. A Sanskrit flower name traveled through Persian and Arabic to reach English gardens."]},{"w":"CARAVAN","pron":"KA-ruh-van","syll":"car · a · van","ety":["Persian *kārvān* = a company of travelers → Italian *carovana* → French *caravane* → English","A company of travelers moving together across desert/steppe for safety. Persian *kārvān* → Italian *carovana* (absorbed through trade contact with Persian merchants) → French *caravane* → English *caravan* (a traveling group, then a type of vehicle). The Persian word for a trade convoy became the English word for a camping trailer."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Research the full journey of one spice (*pepper, nutmeg, cloves, saffron, cardamom*). How many languages did its name travel through? What does this reveal about ancient trade routes?","trace":"The word *silk* compressed from Greek *sērikon* (3 syllables) to English *silk* (1 syllable). Find 3 more trade words that compressed as they traveled. What does compression suggest about how familiar/common a word became?","build":"Draw a Silk Road map: start in China/India, trace the route to England, and mark where each of the 5 lesson words entered the route. What pattern do you see about where Arabic fits in most journeys?"}},{"id":"L44","n":44,"unit":5,"title":"Colonial Words — English Absorbs the World 1500–1900","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"The British Empire created the conditions for the largest vocabulary absorption in English history — words from India, the Americas, Africa, and Australia flooded in as English speakers encountered new things that only existed in those regions.","story":"The British Empire (1600–1950) brought English speakers into contact with environments, animals, plants, foods, and social customs they had no words for. The practical solution: borrow the local word. From India through colonial contact: *shampoo* (Hindi *cāmpo* = press/massage), *bungalow* (Hindi *bāṃglā* = Bengali-style house), *jungle* (Hindi *jangal* = forest), *thug* (Hindi *thag* = swindler), *loot* (Hindi *lūṭ* = plunder), *avatar* (Sanskrit *avatāra* = descent of a god), *karma* (Sanskrit *karman* = action). From the Americas via Spanish/Portuguese: *chocolate* (Nahuatl *xocolatl*), *tomato* (Nahuatl *tomatl*), *potato* (Taino *batata*), *barbecue* (Taino *barbacoa*), *hurricane* (Taino *hurakán*).","pattern":"Colonial borrowing pattern: indigenous word → Spanish or Portuguese (if colonized first by them) → English (direct or via Spanish/Portuguese). Or: indigenous word → English (if colonized directly). The word often retains indigenous phonology more than words that passed through multiple European languages: *kangaroo* sounds like Guugu Yimithirr because it came directly; *chocolate* still has Nahuatl sounds adapted through Spanish.","connection":"Colonial borrowing reveals which cultures had the things that needed naming. Every borrowed word identifies a real historical contact between English speakers and the culture that provided the word.","words":[{"w":"SHAMPOO","pron":"sha-MPOO","syll":"shae · mpuw","ety":["Hindi *cāmpo* = press, massage (imperative) → English 1762","Originally: \"give me a press/massage\" — the Hindi imperative used by hair-dressers. English travelers brought the word back from India in the 18th century, and it initially meant \"to massage\" (1762). The \"wash hair\" meaning developed later. *Shampoo* preserves the Hindi vowel pattern and word length almost perfectly."]},{"w":"BUNGALOW","pron":"BUH-ngguh-loh","syll":"bah · nggah · low","ety":["Hindi *bāṃglā* = of Bengal, Bengali-style ← Sanskrit *Vaṅga* = Bengal","A Bengali-style house with a wide veranda — the style British colonial officials adopted in India for the climate. The word traveled from Bengal → Hindi *bāṃglā* → English colonial India → global English. Now used worldwide for any single-story house, the Bengali origin invisible in everyday use."]},{"w":"HURRICANE","pron":"HUR-uh-kayn","syll":"hher · ah · key · n","ety":["Taino *hurakán* → Spanish *huracán* → English","The Taino people of the Caribbean named the cyclonic storms after their storm god Huracán. Spanish colonizers adopted the word and brought it to Europe. English borrowed it from Spanish. A Caribbean deity's name became an international meteorological term. The word preserved the Taino /k/ even through Spanish."]},{"w":"CHOCOLATE","pron":"CHAW-kluht","syll":"chao · klah · t","ety":["Nahuatl *xocolatl* → Spanish *chocolate* → English","The Nahuatl word *xocolatl* = *xococ* (bitter) + *atl* (water) = bitter water. The Aztec chocolate drink was unsweetened and spiced. Spanish colonizers encountered it in the 1520s and brought the word and drink to Europe. The *-tl* Nahuatl ending was simplified: *xocolatl* → *chocolate*. Today chocolate is sweet; the Nahuatl \"bitter water\" meaning is completely forgotten."]},{"w":"AVATAR","pron":"A-vuh-tahr","syll":"ae · vah · taa · r","ety":["Sanskrit *avatāra* = descent of a god ← *ava-* (down) + *tarati* (crosses over)","A god's descent from heaven into a physical earthly form. *Avatar* was a specifically Hindu theological term for centuries. In the 21st century, *avatar* became the word for a digital representation of a person online — the metaphor transferred perfectly: a digital persona is a \"descent\" of the real person into a virtual world. Sanskrit theology → English digital culture."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Find 5 English words from each: (1) Hindi/Sanskrit contact, (2) Nahuatl/Mayan via Spanish, (3) Taino/Caribbean, (4) Quechua (South America), (5) Aboriginal Australian. What goods or phenomena needed naming in each case?","trace":"The word *avatar* traveled: Sanskrit theology (god descending) → American internet (personal digital representation). What does this leap in meaning tell you about how metaphors transfer between very different contexts?","build":"Research: which 10 English words for foods came from Nahuatl (Aztec language)? How did the Aztec diet change European and global food culture after 1519?"}},{"id":"L45","n":45,"unit":5,"title":"When Words Return — Reborrowing and Doublets Across Centuries","diff":"hard","bigIdea":"English sometimes borrowed the same word twice from the same source — at different times, through different paths — creating \"doublets\" that look nothing like each other despite having the same origin.","story":"The most fascinating word journeys are the round-trips and double-borrows: (1) English borrows a Latin word through French. (2) 200 years later, English borrows the same Latin word directly, creating two different-looking English words. Example: Latin *captiare* → Norman French *cachier* → English *catch* (12th c.); AND Latin *captiare* → Parisian French *chacier* → English *chase* (14th c.). Both come from the same Latin root. Another example: Latin *fragilis* → Old French *fraile* → English *frail* (13th c.); AND Latin *fragilis* → scholarly French *fragile* → English *fragile* (17th c.). The corpus contains hundreds of such doublet pairs where the same Latin/Greek root appears twice in English through different temporal and geographic paths.","pattern":"Doublet identification: (1) Look for two words with nearly identical meanings but different formality levels. (2) Check if their etymologies trace to the same Latin/Greek source. (3) Confirm they entered English at different times. The more different the words look, the more interesting the journey: *catch/chase, frail/fragile, warden/guardian, cattle/chattel, guarantee/warranty, count/compute, sure/secure, genteel/gentle/gentile* — all doublet sets from single Latin sources.","connection":"Doublets are the living record of English's habit of borrowing the same word twice. Every doublet pair is a timeline: you can read the history of English by seeing how differently the same root was reshaped by each path.","words":[{"w":"CATCH","pron":"KACH","syll":"kae · ch","ety":["Anglo-Norman *cachier* ← Latin *captiare* (intensive of *capere* = to take)","The doublet: *chase* (Parisian French *chacier* ← same *captiare*). Both mean \"pursue\" but *catch* = succeed in grabbing; *chase* = pursue. They entered from two French dialects at different times. The same *capere* = take root also gives: *capture, captive, captivate, captor, capable, capacity, anticipate, except, receive*."]},{"w":"FRAIL","pron":"FRAYL","syll":"frey · l","ety":["Old French *fraile* ← Latin *fragilis* (able to be broken)","The doublet: *fragile* (scholarly borrowing directly from Latin *fragilis*, 17th century). *Frail* = general physical weakness. *Fragile* = specific brittleness. Both from *fragilis*, through two paths separated by 400 years. The older French path (*frail*) is shorter, more everyday; the later Latin direct path (*fragile*) is longer, more technical."]},{"w":"CATTLE","pron":"KA-tuhl","syll":"kae · tah · l","ety":["Anglo-Norman *catel* = property ← Latin *capitale* = head (of wealth)","The doublet: *chattel* (Parisian French *chatel* ← same *capitale*), AND *capital* (directly from Latin *capitale*). Three English words from one Latin root: *cattle* (livestock as primary wealth), *chattel* (movable property), *capital* (the head/primary form of wealth). Three paths, three different English words, one Latin economic concept."]},{"w":"GUARANTEE","pron":"geh-ruh-NTEE","syll":"geh · rah · ntiy","ety":["Parisian French *garantie* ← Germanic *warjan* = to protect","The doublet: *warranty* (Anglo-Norman *warantie* ← same Germanic *warjan*). *Guarantee* = formal legal assurance. *Warranty* = specific commercial promise about a product. Both entered English from two dialects of French at slightly different times. Note: the Germanic *w-* survived in *warranty* (Norman kept it); became *gu-* in *guarantee* (Parisian French)."]},{"w":"GENTLE","pron":"JEH-ntuhl","syll":"jheh · ntah · l","ety":["Old French *gentil* ← Latin *gentilis* = of the same clan","Triple set: *gentle* (Old French *gentil*, entering 12th c. = soft-mannered), *genteel* (French *gentil* re-borrowed 17th c. with French pronunciation = affectedly refined), *gentile* (directly from Latin *gentilis* = of another people = non-Jewish). Three English words from one Latin *gens* = family/clan — three different times, three different meanings."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Find the complete doublet set for: *catch/chase*, *frail/fragile*, *cattle/chattel/capital*, *guarantee/warranty*, *gentle/genteel/gentile*. For each, explain what changed at each stage.","trace":"Research 5 more doublet pairs (hint: *coin/coign, sure/secure, dainty/dignity, poison/potion, reason/ration*). Confirm they share the same ultimate Latin/Greek source.","build":"The *capere* = take root generated an extraordinary English word family through multiple paths. List all English words you can find from *capere*: (*catch, chase, capture, captive, capable, capacity, anticipate, except, receive, perceive, conceive, deceive, intercept, inception...*). How many can you find?"}},{"id":"L46","n":46,"unit":5,"title":"Word Journeys Through Arabic — The Islamic Golden Age in English","diff":"hard","bigIdea":"The Islamic Golden Age (750–1258 CE) was the most scientifically productive period of the medieval world. When Europe rediscovered science in the 12th century through Arabic texts, it absorbed Arabic vocabulary wholesale.","story":"Arab scholars translated Greek mathematical, astronomical, medical, and philosophical texts into Arabic from the 8th century onward. They then built on these foundations: Al-Khwarizmi (780–850 CE) invented algebra and created the systematic methods that gave us the word *algorithm*. Arab astronomers named the stars — many star names today are still Arabic: *Aldebaran* (*al-dabarān* = the follower), *Altair* (*al-ṭā'ir* = the flying eagle), *Betelgeuse* (*bayt al-jawzā* = the house of Orion). When European scholars finally translated these Arabic texts into Latin (12th century), they kept the Arabic terms. The Arabic vocabulary of science — algebra, algorithm, alchemy, almanac, alkali, aldehyde, alembic, azimuth, zenith, nadir, elixir — entered European languages through this translation movement.","pattern":"The Arabic→Medieval Latin→European languages pipeline differs from the Greek→Latin pipeline: the Arabic words often carry the definite article *al-* (= \"the\") as part of the word. This is unique: no other borrowed vocabulary has the receiving language's \"the\" article built into the word. *Al-jabr* (\"the reunion\") became *algebra* with the *al-* preserved. Recognizing *al-* at the start of a science/astronomy/chemistry word = almost certain Arabic origin.","connection":"Arabic scientific vocabulary is unique because it carries the Arabic definite article *al-* = \"the\" as a permanent part of the English word. Every *al-* science word is a monument to the Islamic Golden Age's role in preserving and extending ancient knowledge.","words":[{"w":"ALGORITHM","pron":"A-l-g-ur-ih-th-uh-m","syll":"algorithm","ety":["From the name *Muḥammad ibn Mūsā al-Khwārizmī* → Latinized as *Algoritmi*","The mathematician's geographic epithet (*al-Khwārizmī* = from Khwarezm, modern Uzbekistan) was Latinized as *Algoritmi* in medieval Latin texts. The word *algorithm* = a step-by-step computational procedure is literally the Latinized name of a 9th-century Persian mathematician. A person became a procedure — one of the most extraordinary eponymous words in existence."]},{"w":"ALGEBRA","pron":"A-ljuh-bruh","syll":"ae · ljhah · brah","ety":["Arabic *al-jabr* = the reunion of broken parts ← *jabara* = to reunite broken bones","The bone-setting surgery metaphor for equation-solving: just as broken bones are \"reunited,\" *al-jabr* reunites broken equations by moving terms. Al-Khwarizmi's treatise title contained this term; it became the name of the discipline. A surgical metaphor → a branch of mathematics → a subject studied by every schoolchild worldwide."]},{"w":"ZENITH","pron":"ZEE-nuhth","syll":"ziy · nah · th","ety":["Arabic *al-samt* = the direction overhead ← *samt* = direction, path","*Al-samt* = \"the path\" (above the head). Spanish astronomers contracted *al-samt* to *azimut* → English *azimuth* (a compass bearing). A separate contraction gave *zenit* → *zenith* (the point directly overhead). Its opposite: *nadir* (the point directly below) is also Arabic: *naẓīr al-samt* = opposite the zenith. Two celestial terms, both Arabic."]},{"w":"ELIXIR","pron":"ih-LIH-kser","syll":"ih · lih · kser","ety":["Arabic *al-iksīr* ← Greek *xērion* = drying powder ← *xēros* = dry","Journey: Greek *xēros* (dry) → Greek *xērion* (a wound-drying powder) → Arabic *al-iksīr* (the essence, philosopher's stone) → Medieval Latin/English *elixir* (transformative substance, magic potion). Greek \"dry\" became Arabic \"the essence\" became English \"magic potion.\" The Greek word for *dry* is inside every fantasy novel's *elixir*."]},{"w":"ALCHEMY","pron":"A-lkuh-mee","syll":"ae · lkah · miy","ety":["Arabic *al-kīmiyā'* ← possibly Greek *khēmia* = the black art (of Egypt) or *khymos* = juice/fluid","The art of transforming matter. Arabic → Medieval Latin *alchimia* → Old French *alchimie* → English *alchemy*. Gave birth to *chemistry* (when the *al-* article was finally dropped in European scientific usage). *Alchemy* (mystical/pre-scientific) → *chemistry* (systematic science). The same word, shedding its Arabic article as it matured into modern science."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Find and explain the Arabic *al-* prefix in 10 English science words: *algebra, algorithm, alcohol, alchemy, almanac, alkali, altimeter?* (No — Latin!), *aldehyde, alembic, alcove*. Which have it and which do not?","trace":"Research three Arabic star names visible in the night sky: *Aldebaran, Altair, Betelgeuse, Algol, Rigel, Achernar*. What does each mean in Arabic? What constellation is each in?","build":"The word *chemistry* developed from *alchemy* by dropping the Arabic article *al-*. Find 2 more English words where the Arabic *al-* was eventually dropped (hint: research the history of *elixir* becoming standard, or *alchemy/chemistry*, *alkali/potash*)."}},{"id":"L47","n":47,"unit":5,"title":"Word Journeys Through Sanskrit — India's Gift to English","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"Sanskrit, the ancient language of India (approximately 1500 BCE – present as a liturgical language), gave English both everyday words (through colonial contact) and philosophical vocabulary (through direct scholarly interest).","story":"Sanskrit gave English two distinct vocabulary layers: (1) Everyday words through British colonial contact with India (18th–20th centuries): *shampoo, bungalow, loot, thug, jungle, juggernaut, curry, pundit, pyjamas*. (2) Philosophical and spiritual vocabulary through scholarly translation and the 1960s–70s Eastern spirituality movement: *karma, nirvana, avatar, mantra, yoga, guru, chakra, dharma, mandala, Buddha, Zen* (via Japanese/Chinese). The first layer came through colonial administration; the second came through religious and philosophical text translation.","pattern":"Sanskrit phonological pattern in English loanwords: Sanskrit uses an alternating consonant-vowel (CV) syllable structure with few consonant clusters. Sanskrit loanwords in English tend to have clean syllable structures (*yoga* = yo·ga, *karma* = kar·ma, *avatar* = av·a·tar) and often end in *-a* (Sanskrit feminine/neuter ending reduced to /uh/ in English: *yoga, karma, dharma, chakra, nirvana, mandala*). The final *-a* = Sanskrit grammatical ending → English pronunciation /uh/.","connection":"Sanskrit loanwords reveal two types of cultural contact: colonial (practical words for things/practices encountered in India) and scholarly/spiritual (philosophical concepts absorbed through text translation). Both paths are visible in the vocabulary.","words":[{"w":"JUGGERNAUT","pron":"JUH-ger-nawt","syll":"jhah · ger · nao · t","ety":["Sanskrit *Jagannātha* = Lord of the Universe ← *jagat* (world) + *nātha* (lord)","The enormous temple cart of Lord Jagannatha at Puri was reported by medieval travelers (including Marco Polo's contemporaries) who exaggerated stories of devotees throwing themselves under its wheels. By the 1800s, *juggernaut* in English = any unstoppable crushing force. A divine name → an English metaphor for unstoppable force through colonial-era exaggeration."]},{"w":"KARMA","pron":"KAH-rmuh","syll":"kaa · rmah","ety":["Sanskrit *karma* = action, deed ← *kṛ* = to do, to make","What you do = what you get back. Sanskrit *kṛ* = to do → *karma* (the action and its consequence). The Hindu/Buddhist concept of moral cause-and-effect. In English, *karma* has been both adopted (the philosophical concept) and trivialized (pop-culture \"bad karma\"). The word preserved its Sanskrit phonology and meaning almost unchanged through 3,000 years."]},{"w":"NIRVANA","pron":"nih-RVAH-nuh","syll":"nih · rvaa · nah","ety":["Sanskrit *nirvāṇa* = blowing out ← *nir-* (out) + *vā* (blow) = extinction of desire","The blowing out of the flame of desire = liberation from the cycle of rebirth. *Nirvana* entered English first through Buddhist scholarly texts (19th century), then through popular culture (the band Nirvana, 1987). N-I-R-V-A-N-A: six letters, three clean Sanskrit syllables. The Sanskrit *nir-* prefix = out/away (same as Latin *ex-*)."]},{"w":"PUNDIT","pron":"PUH-nduht","syll":"pah · ndah · t","ety":["Sanskrit *paṇḍita* = learned person, scholar ← *paṇḍā* = learning","A learned person or religious scholar. British colonizers encountered *paṇḍita* = a Hindu scholar of sacred texts. The colonial administration used *pundit* for any learned adviser. Now: any expert commentator on public affairs. The word has traveled from Sanskrit sacred scholarship to English television commentary, losing its sacred context but keeping its \"expert\" meaning."]},{"w":"YOGA","pron":"YOH-guh","syll":"yow · gah","ety":["Sanskrit *yoga* = union, connection ← *yuj* = to yoke, join","The practice of yoking/uniting body and mind. *Yuj* = yoke/join → the same PIE root as English *yoke* (OE *geoc* ← PIE *jugom*) and Latin *jugum* = yoke → *conjugal* (yoked together = married), *subjugate* (yoked under), *conjugate* (grammar term: yoke verb forms together). Sanskrit *yoga* and Latin *jugum* are PIE cognates: the same ancient root for \"joining.\""]}],"practice":{"decode":"Identify which path brought each word to English — colonial contact or scholarly/spiritual translation: *shampoo, karma, bungalow, nirvana, juggernaut, yoga, loot, dharma, pundit, avatar*.","trace":"Sanskrit *yuj* (yoke/join) and Latin *jugum* (yoke) are PIE cognates — both from PIE *jugom*. Find all English words from each path: Sanskrit path (*yoga*) vs Latin path (*jugal, conjugal, subjugate, conjugate, jugular?*).","build":"Research the \"three waves\" of Sanskrit vocabulary entering English: (1) colonial administration words, (2) scholarly text translations (19th century), (3) 1960s–70s Eastern spirituality movement. Give 5 examples from each wave."}},{"id":"L48","n":48,"unit":5,"title":"The Norse Layer — Viking Words in Modern English","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"The 2,344 Norse-origin words in the 129K database are among the most common words in English — because Norse gave English its basic vocabulary for law, seafaring, the sky, and everyday physical actions.","story":"Already covered in Units 1 and 4, Norse deserves a Word Journey Unit lesson because the Norse journey is unique: it is the only foreign language influence that replaced OE GRAMMATICAL words (pronouns, prepositions). Usually, borrowing languages only add vocabulary; they don't replace grammatical structure. Norse changed English grammar — because Norse and OE were similar enough to blend at the deepest level. The Norse impact: simplified grammar (lost case endings), replaced pronouns (*they/their/them*), contributed the *sk-* vocabulary, and left a \"doublet\" layer of simple physical words (*sky, skin, skull, skirt, skill*) alongside their OE equivalents (*heaven, hide, shell, shirt, craft*).","pattern":"Norse corpus data: 2,344 Norse-origin words in the database = 1.9% of total. But these words are disproportionately common in usage — the basic physical vocabulary of everyday life. The 1,000 most-used English words include a higher percentage of Norse words than their 1.9% database share suggests, because Norse words cluster in high-frequency domains: sky, directions, body parts, basic actions, everyday objects.","connection":"Norse is unique among English borrowing languages because it changed grammar, not just vocabulary. This is the rarest type of linguistic influence — and it explains why English grammar is simpler than any other Germanic language.","words":[{"w":"SKY","pron":"s-k-AY","syll":"sky","ety":["Old Norse *ský* = cloud → English *sky* (replacing OE *heofon*)","OE *heofon* (= *heaven*) was the word for sky. Norse *ský* (cloud) displaced it for the everyday meaning. *Heaven* was preserved with spiritual meaning. A Norse word for clouds became the English word for the entire sky, while the OE word retreated to religious usage. The pragmatic battle: *sky* won everyday use; *heaven* won sacred use."]},{"w":"LAW","pron":"LAW","syll":"lao","ety":["Old Norse *lag* = that which is laid down","*Law* itself comes from Norse. Before Norse influence, OE used *lagu* (also from Norse roots, related) and *dōm* (judgment/law → *doom*). The Norman Conquest then brought French legal vocabulary (court, justice, verdict...) on top of the Norse *law* as the foundational word. Three languages built the English legal vocabulary: Norse (*law*), French (*court, jury*), Latin (*justice, verdict*)."]},{"w":"SKULL","pron":"SKUHL","syll":"skah · l","ety":["Old Norse *skoltr* = skull","*Skull* replaced OE *heafodpanne* (head-pan = skull). The Norse word is shorter, more vivid, harder-sounding. The OE compound *heafodpanne* = head + pan = the \"pan\" of the head — a cooking metaphor for the rounded skull. Both Norse *skull* and OE *head-pan* describe the same object; Norse won for the anatomical term."]},{"w":"RANSACK","pron":"RA-nsak","syll":"rae · nsae · k","ety":["Old Norse *rannsakar* = to search a house ← *rann* (house) + *saka* (to seek)","To search a house violently for valuables. The Norse compound: *rann* (house) + *saka* (to seek). The *-sak-* element is related to English *sake* (for the sake of = for the seeking of = for the purpose). *Ransack* and *sake* share a Norse root for \"seeking.\" The violent house-search and a polite \"for heaven's sake\" are etymological relatives."]},{"w":"OUTLAW","pron":"OW-tlaw","syll":"aw · tlao","ety":["Old Norse *útlagi* = outside the law ← *út* (out) + *lög* (law, plural of *lag*)","One placed outside the protection of the law. Norse compound: *út-* (out) + *lög* (law). An outlaw literally has the law removed from around them — they have no legal rights or protections. The concept and the word both come from Norse legal vocabulary. The OE equivalent would have been *lāhbreca* (law-breaker), which did not survive."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Identify Norse and OE doublets for each: *sky/heaven, skull/brain-pan?, ransack/pillage (not a doublet — different origins), outlaw/exile, law/doom*. For each pair, explain which domain each word preserved.","trace":"The *sk-* cluster = Norse signal. Find all *sk-* words in the database that are Norse-origin (not Latin/Greek *sc-* → *sk-*). Group them by semantic domain (sky, body, physical actions, etc.).","build":"Research: why did Norse and OE blend at the grammar level when French did NOT change English grammar after 1066? What does this tell you about the relationship between linguistic similarity and degree of grammatical influence?"}},{"id":"L49","n":49,"unit":5,"title":"Hebrew, Yiddish, and the Language of Sacred Texts","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"Hebrew (659 words in the 129K database) and Yiddish (154 words) gave English a distinctive cluster of vocabulary — primarily religious, cultural, and (through Yiddish) informal expressive terms.","story":"Hebrew gave English vocabulary through two paths: (1) Biblical translations — the King James Bible (1611) introduced hundreds of Hebrew-origin words into English: *amen, hallelujah, sabbath, cherub, seraph, jubilee, leviathan, messiah*. (2) Direct borrowing for cultural/religious concepts: *kibbutz, chutzpah* (via Yiddish). Yiddish (a Germanic language written in Hebrew script, spoken by Ashkenazi Jewish communities) gave English a rich layer of informal, expressive vocabulary, primarily through American English: *chutzpah* (nerve/audacity), *schmuck* (fool), *schlep* (to drag), *schmaltz* (excessive sentimentality), *kibitz* (to give unsolicited advice), *kvetch* (to complain). These Yiddish words entered American English through immigrant communities, primarily in New York, and spread nationally through entertainment and media.","pattern":"Hebrew and Yiddish spelling signals: (1) Words ending in *-ah*: *hallelujah, sabbath* → sabbath shows reduction; *chutzpah* keeps the *-ah*. (2) *sch-* cluster from Yiddish/German: *schmaltz, schlep, schmuck, shtick* (a habitual routine). The *sch-* = /sh/ in Yiddish-origin words (different from the *sch-* = /sh/ in German, different from the *sch-* = /sk/ signal in Greek-origin words). (3) Words with unusual phoneme combinations for English: *kvetch* (*kv-* at start), *chutzpah* (the *ch* = /kh/ guttural).","connection":"Hebrew and Yiddish vocabulary fills two different gaps in English: Hebrew provides the language of the sacred and ancient; Yiddish provides the language of urban immigrant expressiveness. Both layers are irreplaceable.","words":[{"w":"JUBILEE","pron":"JOO-buh-lee","syll":"jhuw · bah · liy","ety":["Hebrew *yōbhēl* = ram's horn, the horn sounded to announce the jubilee year","A jubilee year in the Hebrew Bible: every 50 years, slaves were freed and debts cancelled (announced by the ram's horn *yōbhēl*). Latin transliteration: *iubilaeus*. English *jubilee* = a 50th anniversary celebration. The sacred horn-blast becomes a secular party. Same word, stripped of its radical economic justice content, retained as festive celebration."]},{"w":"LEVIATHAN","pron":"luh-VEYE-uh-thuhn","syll":"le · vi · a · than","ety":["Hebrew *livyāthān* = a sea monster (possibly the whale or crocodile)","The great sea creature in the Hebrew Bible symbolizing chaos or primordial evil. Thomas Hobbes used *Leviathan* as the title of his 1651 political philosophy work (= the all-powerful state). The Hebrew mythological monster became an English word for any enormous entity. Hebrew sacred literature → English secular political philosophy."]},{"w":"AMEN","pron":"ay-MEHN","syll":"ey · meh · n","ety":["Hebrew *ʾāmēn* = so be it, truly ← *ʾāman* = to confirm, to be faithful","One of the oldest words in continuous use in English and most world languages. Hebrew *ʾāmēn* was kept untranslated in Greek (as *amēn*), then in Latin (as *amen*), then in all Christian languages worldwide. A Hebrew word for \"truthfully confirmed\" is said in churches, mosques, and synagogues worldwide in virtually unchanged form for 3,000+ years."]},{"w":"CHUTZPAH","pron":"CHUH-tspah","syll":"chah · tspaa","ety":["Yiddish *khutspe* ← Hebrew *ḥuṣpāh* = insolence, audacity","Brazen nerve or audacity. Entered American English through Jewish immigrant communities (late 19th – early 20th century), spread through entertainment/comedy, and is now widely used across American English. *Chutzpah* has no perfect English equivalent — which is why it was borrowed: the concept of audacious, shameless nerve without guilt needed a word."]},{"w":"SCHMALTZ","pron":"SHMAHLTS","syll":"shmaa · lts","ety":["Yiddish *shmalts* = rendered fat ← German *Schmalz* = rendered fat/lard","Originally: rendered chicken or goose fat — a staple cooking ingredient. Extended meaning in Yiddish entertainment: something excessively sentimental, greasy with emotion. Now in English: excessive, icky sentimentality. The culinary fat metaphor → emotional excess metaphor. *Schmaltzy* = overly sentimental. The *sch-* cluster = /sh/ in Yiddish-origin words."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Find 10 Hebrew-origin words in English and group them: (1) entered through Bible translations, (2) entered through religious practice, (3) entered as cultural/everyday terms.","trace":"Yiddish entered American English primarily through entertainment: vaudeville, radio comedy, early Hollywood. Research 5 Yiddish words that spread nationally through entertainment (*shtick, schlock, kibitz, kvetch, schmooze*).","build":"The word *amen* has been used in essentially unchanged form for 3,000 years across Hebrew, Greek, Latin, Arabic, and all European languages. What does this extraordinary persistence tell you about the relationship between sacred vocabulary and linguistic change?"}},{"id":"L50","n":50,"unit":5,"title":"The Future of English — How New Words Are Made Today","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"English word creation in the 21st century follows the same 8 processes identified in L10 — but at 100x the speed, driven by internet culture, global communication, and technology development.","story":"The pace of vocabulary change has accelerated dramatically with the internet. In pre-digital English, a new word might take decades to spread and centuries to become standard. *Selfie* (2002) became Oxford Word of the Year by 2013 — an 11-year lifecycle that would have taken 200 years before mass media. The mechanisms are the same: borrowing, compounding, clipping, blending, acronym-formation, eponymy, backformation, derivation. But the speed is orders of magnitude faster. The 129K database represents English up to its compilation date; hundreds of new words have been coined since — many of which will be standard vocabulary within years.","pattern":"Digital word formation patterns: (1) Tech terms following Greek naming conventions (*blockchain, cryptocurrency, nanotechnology*). (2) Brand names becoming common nouns (*google → to google, uber → to uber*). (3) Internet blend words (*emoji* = Japanese *e* (picture) + *moji* (character); *vlog* = video + blog; *listicle* = list + article). (4) Clipped compound abbreviations (*COVID-19, DNA, FAQ, BTW*). (5) Affixation on new roots: *de-* + *platform* = *deplatform*, *un-* + *subscribe* = *unsubscribe*, *micro-* + *dosing* = *microdosing*.","connection":"English word creation is faster now than at any point in history — but the mechanisms are identical to those that created *tragedy* from \"goat-song\" or *algorithm* from a mathematician's name. The tools are ancient; the speed is new.","words":[{"w":"EMOJI","pron":"—","syll":"emoji","ety":["Japanese *e* (picture) + *moji* (character) = picture character","A visual symbol used in digital communication. The word is Japanese but the concept is global. *Moji* = character → *mojibake* (Japanese: garbled characters from wrong encoding). *E* = picture → Japanese *eiga* (movie = moving pictures). *Emoji* entered English without translation — the Japanese compound word serves directly."]},{"w":"PODCAST","pron":"—","syll":"podcast","ety":["English *pod* (from *iPod* = Play on Demand) + *cast* (from *broadcast*)","Coined 2004 by journalist Ben Hammersley. *Pod* = from Apple's iPod device name (*i-Pod* itself = *internet* + *pod* as in *pod*cast storage). *Cast* = from *broadcast* (*broad* + *cast* = throw widely). A portmanteau anchored in specific 2004 technology (*iPod*) that is now completely general — even though iPods are obsolete."]},{"w":"SELFIE","pron":"—","syll":"selfie","ety":["English *self* (Old English *seolf*) + *-ie* (diminutive suffix)","Documented in an Australian internet forum in 2002: \"sorry about the focus, it was a selfie.\" The suffix *-ie* = informal diminutive (like *foodie, junkie, bookie*). A 1,500-year-old OE reflexive pronoun (*self*) + a diminutive suffix created a word that didn't exist 25 years ago and is now global."]},{"w":"CRYPTOCURRENCY","pron":"—","syll":"cryptocurrency","ety":["Greek *kryptos* (hidden) + Latin/English *currency* (from *currere* = to run)","Hidden currency. The compound follows the ancient Greek naming convention: *krypto-* = Greek (scientific signal), *currency* = Latin/French. A 21st-century financial technology naming itself with 2,000-year-old Greek morphology. The Greek *kryptos* root: *cryptic, crypt, encrypt, decrypt, cryptography*."]},{"w":"DEEPFAKE","pron":"—","syll":"deepfake","ety":["English *deep* (OE *dēop*) + *fake* (origin disputed, possibly Scandinavian)","A compound of two common English words creating a new technical term for AI-generated false media. *Deep* = from \"deep learning\" (a type of AI). *Fake* = counterfeit. The compound: deep-learning-generated fake media. A technical AI term + an everyday word = a new compound that describes a new technological and ethical problem."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Find 5 words coined in the last 5 years (2020–2025) and identify which of the 8 word-formation processes created each. Check: borrowing, compounding, clipping, blending, acronym, eponym, backformation, derivation.","trace":"Research: in what year did each of these words enter the Oxford English Dictionary? *selfie, podcast, emoji, cryptocurrency, deepfake, meme* (Richard Dawkins coined this in 1976). What do the dates tell you about the current pace of vocabulary creation?","build":"Predict: what 5 new English words will be standard vocabulary by 2030? Use the 8 word-formation processes to create them from existing roots. What new technologies or social phenomena might need naming?"}},{"id":"L51","n":51,"unit":6,"title":"Amelioration — Words That Climbed the Social Ladder","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"Amelioration is when a word's meaning improves over time as its associated group rises in social status.","story":"The clearest example: *knight* (OE *cniht*) originally meant a boy or servant. As mounted warriors rose in feudal status, the word rose with them — from servant to the pinnacle of chivalric virtue. *Nice* (← French *nice* = foolish, ← Latin *nescius* = ignorant) climbed: \"foolish\" (1300s) → \"precise\" (1500s) → \"pleasant\" (1800s) → vaguely positive (today). The pattern: when a group or activity rises socially, the words associated with it rise too.","pattern":"Amelioration signal: a word with a surprisingly negative Latin/Greek root that now has a positive meaning. *Knight* (servant → noble warrior). *Nice* (foolish → pleasant). *Minister* (the lesser one → high official). *Pretty* (tricky → attractive). When the etymology reveals a negative origin for a modern positive word = amelioration has occurred over the centuries.","connection":"Amelioration tracks social history: when groups or activities rise in status, their associated vocabulary rises with them.","words":[{"w":"MARSHAL","pron":"MAH-rshuhl","syll":"maa · rshah · l","ety":["Old French *mareschal* = horse servant ← *marah* (horse) + *scalc* (servant)","Horse-servant → keeper of royal horses → military officer → Field Marshal. A stable hand became a general through amelioration tracking social rise over 800 years."]},{"w":"SOPHISTICATED","pron":"suh-FIH-stuh-kay-tihd","syll":"so · phis · ti · cat · ed","ety":["Greek *sophistikos* = of the sophists — originally pejorative for falsely clever arguers","Originally: corrupted by sophistic argument. 17th c.: adulterated. 19th c.: having refined taste. Today: worldly-wise. Climbed from insult to compliment over 400 years."]},{"w":"MINISTER","pron":"MIH-nuh-ster","syll":"mih · nah · ster","ety":["Latin *minister* = servant, the lesser one ← *minus* = less","Literally the lesser one. Today: a high-ranking government official or religious leader. The servants of powerful rulers became powerful themselves."]},{"w":"PRETTY","pron":"PRIH-tee","syll":"prih · tiy","ety":["Old English *prættig* = cunning, crafty, sly","Originally: tricky. 1400s: skillfully made. 1500s: pleasing in appearance. Today: attractive. A word for trickery became a word for beauty through 600 years of amelioration."]},{"w":"ENTHUSIASTIC","pron":"ih-nthoo-zee-A-stihk","syll":"ih · nthuw · ziy · ae · stih · k","ety":["Greek *enthousiasmos* = divine inspiration ← *en-* (in) + *theos* (god)","Being filled with a god = divine ecstasy (dangerous). 17th c.: excessive religious fervor. 19th c.: great eagerness. Divine possession → healthy excitement."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Research the original meanings of: *nice, knight, minister, pretty, sophisticated*. Chart the meaning journey for each.","trace":"Find 5 words that have ameliorated since 2000: *nerd* (derogatory → positive), *geek*, *hacker*, *badass*, *sick* (slang). When did each shift?","build":"Why does social change drive amelioration? Using *knight* and *marshal*, explain: what changed in the real world that caused each word's meaning to improve?"}},{"id":"L52","n":52,"unit":6,"title":"Pejoration — Words That Fell From Grace","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"Pejoration is when a word's meaning deteriorates over time as its associated group or activity becomes stigmatized.","story":"The pattern: when a group loses status, the words associated with them deteriorate. *Villain* (← Old French *vilain* = farm worker): farm worker → rude person → scoundrel → evildoer. *Silly* (← OE *sælig* = blessed, happy): blessed → innocent → weak → foolish. *Egregious* (← Latin *egregius* = outstanding, distinguished) once meant admirably outstanding; now it almost exclusively means outstandingly BAD.","pattern":"Pejoration signal: a word with a surprisingly positive Latin/Greek root that now has negative meaning. When etymology reveals a positive origin for a modern negative word = pejoration has occurred.","connection":"Pejoration tracks the history of social contempt. Every pejorated word is a record of which groups a society came to stigmatize.","words":[{"w":"VILLAIN","pron":"v-IH-l-uh-n","syll":"villain","ety":["Old French *vilain* = farm worker, serf ← Latin *villa* = farm","Farm worker → rude person → scoundrel → deliberate evildoer. Medieval contempt for peasants pejorated the word. *Village* (collection of farms) and *villain* (the farm worker) share the same root."]},{"w":"SILLY","pron":"SIH-lee","syll":"sih · liy","ety":["Old English *sælig* = blessed, happy, fortunate ← *sæl* = happiness","Blessed → innocent → weak → feeble-minded → frivolously stupid. A word meaning \"blessed by God\" became \"foolish\" through 800 years of pejoration."]},{"w":"HUSSY","pron":"HUH-see","syll":"hhah · siy","ety":["Contraction of *housewife* ← Old English *hūswīf* = lady of the house","Respectable housewife → lower-class woman → disreputable woman. The arc: respected householder → scorned woman through one contraction over 300 years."]},{"w":"PROPAGANDA","pron":"prah-puh-GA-nduh","syll":"praa · pah · gae · ndah","ety":["New Latin *propagare* = to spread the faith — Catholic Church committee name 1622","A church missionary committee name. After WWI and WWII: deliberate dishonest political manipulation. A sacred institutional term became the word for deliberate deception."]},{"w":"EGREGIOUS","pron":"ih-g-r-EE-j-uh-s","syll":"egregious","ety":["Latin *egregius* = distinguished ← *e-* (out) + *grex* (flock) = outstanding from the flock","Originally: remarkably good, distinguished. By 1600s: used ironically. Today: outstandingly bad. Kept \"remarkable\" but reversed its value judgment: outstanding → outstandingly bad."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Research the original meanings of: *villain, silly, hussy, propaganda, egregious*. Create a pejoration timeline for each with the meaning at each century.","trace":"Find 5 more pejorated words: *lewd* (lay person → vulgar), *knave* (boy → rogue), *naughty* (nothing → disobedient), *crafty* (skilled → cunning), *wench* (child → low woman).","build":"Why does social contempt drive pejoration? Using *villain* and *silly*, explain what changed in the real world that caused each word's meaning to deteriorate."}},{"id":"L53","n":53,"unit":6,"title":"Semantic Broadening — Words That Grew to Mean More","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"Semantic broadening happens when a word's meaning expands from specific to general — applying to more things than it originally did.","story":"Broadening: *holiday* (← OE *hāligdæg* = holy day) → any day off. *Dog* (← ME *dogge* = one specific powerful breed) → all dogs. *Arrive* (← Latin *ad rīpam* = to reach the shore after a sea voyage) → reaching any destination. *Calculate* (← Latin *calculus* = a small counting stone) → any mathematical computation. In each case, when more general words became available or the specific use expanded, the word grew to cover a broader range.","pattern":"Broadening signal: a word's etymology reveals a much more specific origin than its current usage suggests. When the original use was narrower than modern usage = broadening has occurred.","connection":"Broadening reveals how language adapts to new contexts: as specific applications become less relevant, words expand to cover concepts more generally.","words":[{"w":"HOLIDAY","pron":"HAH-luh-day","syll":"hol · i · day","ety":["Old English *hāligdæg* = holy day ← *hālig* (holy) + *dæg* (day)","Originally: a day of religious observance only. Now: any day free from work. The sacred connotation has been almost entirely lost in secular usage."]},{"w":"SALARY","pron":"SA-ler-ee","syll":"sae · ler · iy","ety":["Latin *salarium* = salt allowance ← *sal* = salt","Roman soldiers were paid a salt allowance — salt was precious for food preservation. Broadened to cover all regular compensation. \"Worth his salt\" preserves the original specific meaning."]},{"w":"CALCULATE","pron":"KA-lkyuh-layt","syll":"kae · lkyah · ley · t","ety":["Latin *calculare* = to count ← *calculus* = small stone used for counting","Originally: counting using small stones on an abacus. Broadened to any mathematical computation. The pebbles became the most complex branch of mathematics."]},{"w":"ARRIVE","pron":"er-EYEV","syll":"er · ay · v","ety":["Old French *arriver* ← Latin *ad rīpam* = to the shore after a sea voyage","Originally: reaching the shore after an ocean journey. Now: reaching any destination by any means. Latin shore-reaching → modern airport arrivals."]},{"w":"THING","pron":"THIHNG","syll":"thih · ng","ety":["Old English *þing* = an assembly, a legal or legislative meeting","A judicial meeting → the matter discussed at a meeting → any matter or affair → any object or concept. *Thing* is now the most broadly applicable noun in English."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Find the original specific meaning of each before broadening: *holiday, salary, calculate, arrive, thing, dog, picture* (← Latin = a painted image).","trace":"Find 5 more words that broadened in the past 200 years: *bus* (from *omnibus* = for all), *phone* (from telephone), *nice* (broadened positive meanings), *cool* (temperature → fashionable), *star* (celestial body → celebrity).","build":"Is there a risk that words broadening too far become meaningless? Find 3 English words so broadly used they have almost no specific meaning left (*stuff, whatever, thing, do, get*)."}},{"id":"L54","n":54,"unit":6,"title":"Semantic Narrowing — Words That Shrank","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"Semantic narrowing is the opposite of broadening: a word's meaning becomes more restricted, applying to fewer things than it originally did.","story":"Narrowing: *hound* (← OE *hund* = any dog) narrowed to mean only a hunting dog — *dog* took the general slot. *Meat* (← OE *mete* = any food) narrowed to animal flesh. *Deer* (← OE *dēor* = any wild animal) narrowed to one animal — *animal* (Latin) took the general slot. *Girl* (← ME *girle* = a child of either sex) narrowed to female child. In each case, when a more general word was available (often from Latin/French), the OE word specialized.","pattern":"Narrowing signal: a word's etymology reveals a much broader original meaning than current usage. When the etymology is more general than the modern meaning = narrowing has occurred.","connection":"Narrowing reveals the vocabulary competition: when Latin/French words took the general slots, OE/Norse words often narrowed to one specific type.","words":[{"w":"HOUND","pron":"HOWND","syll":"hhaw · nd","ety":["Old English *hund* = any dog, a dog in general ← Proto-Germanic *hundaz*","OE *hund* = any dog. The Norse word *dog* took the general slot; *hound* narrowed to hunting dogs. German *Hund* still means any dog — the German equivalent has NOT narrowed. Two languages, same root, different paths."]},{"w":"MEAT","pron":"MEET","syll":"miy · t","ety":["Old English *mete* = food, what is eaten ← Proto-Germanic *matiz*","OE *mete* = any food. Evidence the original meaning survives in *sweetmeat* (candy) and *nutmeat* (edible part of a nut). As Latin/French food vocabulary arrived, *meat* narrowed to animal flesh."]},{"w":"DEER","pron":"DIHR","syll":"dih · r","ety":["Old English *dēor* = any wild animal ← Proto-Germanic *deuzaz*","OE *dēor* = any animal (cf. German *Tier* = animal, which has NOT narrowed). *Animal* (Latin) took the general slot; *deer* narrowed to one specific animal. German kept the general meaning; English narrowed."]},{"w":"GIRL","pron":"GURL","syll":"ger · l","ety":["Middle English *girle* = a child of either sex ← uncertain origin","Originally: any young child, male or female. Evidence: \"knave girl\" = a boy in early texts. Once *boy* established itself for the male-child meaning, *girl* narrowed to female."]},{"w":"STARVE","pron":"STAHRV","syll":"staa · rv","ety":["Old English *steorfan* = to die by any means ← Proto-Germanic *sterbanan*","OE *steorfan* = to die generally (cf. German *sterben* = to die, not narrowed). As *die* (Norse) took the general slot, *starve* narrowed to death by one specific cause: hunger."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Find the original broad meaning before narrowing: *hound, meat, deer, girl, starve, lord* (← OE *hlāford* = loaf-guardian), *lady* (← OE *hlǣfdige* = loaf-kneader).","trace":"German usually preserves the original broad Germanic meaning while English narrows (*Tier/deer, sterben/starve, Hund/hound*). Find 3 more such pairs. What does this reveal about French/Latin influence?","build":"The word *bread* did NOT narrow despite *meat* and *food* narrowing around it. Research why: was there a competing Latin/French word for bread that failed to displace it?"}},{"id":"L55","n":55,"unit":6,"title":"Metaphor as the Engine of Meaning Change","diff":"hard","bigIdea":"Metaphor is not just a literary device — it is the primary mechanism by which word meanings change. Most abstract English vocabulary is built from dead metaphors: concrete physical descriptions that became abstract concepts.","story":"George Lakoff and Mark Johnson's *Metaphors We Live By* (1980) showed that abstract thought is fundamentally structured by physical metaphors. English abstract vocabulary encodes this: *understand* (← OE = to stand under/among), *comprehend* (← Latin = to seize/grab), *focus* (← Latin *focus* = a hearth, the center of a home). The physical → abstract pattern: body-part actions become mental concepts. Every time you say \"I understand,\" you are using a 1,000-year-old metaphor of literally standing in the middle of something.","pattern":"Metaphor families: UNDERSTANDING = GRASPING (*comprehend, grasp, seize, catch*). ARGUMENT = WAR (*attack a position, defend a claim, demolish an argument*). TIME = SPACE (*long time, short meeting, the future ahead*). Dead metaphors: the original physical meaning is forgotten but the abstract use remains.","connection":"Metaphor is the primary mechanism of meaning change. Most abstract vocabulary consists of dead metaphors — the physical thinking underneath abstract language, preserved in word origins.","words":[{"w":"UNDERSTAND","pron":"uh-nder-STAND","syll":"un · der · stand","ety":["Old English *understandan* = to stand among/in the middle of — spatial metaphor","To literally stand under or among something = be in the midst of it = be familiar with it. Understanding = being positioned INSIDE something. The spatial metaphor has been completely forgotten but the word's abstract meaning descends directly from the physical image."]},{"w":"COMPREHEND","pron":"kah-mpree-HEHND","syll":"kaa · mpriy · hheh · nd","ety":["Latin *comprehendere* = to seize, grab hold of ← *com-* + *prehendere* (to seize)","To mentally grasp = to physically seize. *Prehendere* = seize → *apprehend, reprehend, surprise, prize*. We still say \"get it\" (understand) and \"catch on\" (understand gradually) — the grasping metaphor is alive in multiple English words simultaneously."]},{"w":"FOCUS","pron":"FOH-kuhs","syll":"fow · kah · s","ety":["Latin *focus* = a fireplace, hearth — the literal center of the home","Kepler (1604) used *focus* in optics for the point where lenses converge light, using the hearth metaphor: where light \"gathers/comes home.\" Now: the center of attention, mental concentration. Physical hearth → optical point → mental concentration. Three meanings, one spatial metaphor."]},{"w":"DISASTER","pron":"dih-ZA-ster","syll":"dih · zae · ster","ety":["Italian *disastro* ← *dis-* (bad) + *astro* (star) — astrological metaphor","Under an evil star. When the metaphor was live, *disaster* literally meant astrological misfortune. As astrology lost credibility, the metaphor died but the word survived with the abstract meaning. A dead metaphor: the original meaning (star-caused misfortune) is gone; the word lives on as a secular term for catastrophe."]},{"w":"SALARY","pron":"SA-ler-ee","syll":"sae · ler · iy","ety":["Latin *salarium* = salt allowance — already covered in L53 but as a DEAD METAPHOR example","The physical salt payment → abstract concept of regular compensation. Modern salary-earners never think of salt. The concrete metaphor died; the abstract application survived. This is the essential structure of dead metaphors: physical origin → abstract survival."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Find the physical metaphor underlying: *understand* (standing among), *comprehend* (grasping), *focus* (hearth), *consider* (← Latin = examine the stars), *reflect* (← Latin = bend back).","trace":"The \"IDEAS = OBJECTS\" metaphor family: *get an idea, hold a belief, turn an idea over, examine a theory, put a thought forward, drop a subject*. Find 10 more English phrases using physical manipulation for mental activity.","build":"Design a \"metaphor archaeology\" exercise: take 5 abstract words and dig to their original physical meaning. What does finding the physical metaphor tell you about how early humans conceptualized abstract thought?"}},{"id":"L56","n":56,"unit":6,"title":"Euphemism Cycles — When Words Become Unspeakable","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"Euphemism (saying something indirectly to avoid a taboo) and the \"euphemism treadmill\" drive constant vocabulary change in sensitive domains: each new polite term eventually inherits the stigma of what it replaces.","story":"Steven Pinker (1994) named the \"euphemism treadmill\": *crippled → handicapped → disabled → differently abled → person with a disability*. Each term eventually becomes associated with the stigma and gets replaced. The same cycle: *idiot → imbecile → moron → mentally retarded → intellectually disabled*. Medical terms became insults; new medical terms were coined; those became insults too. The treadmill never stops because the problem is not the word — it is the stigma attached to the condition. Changing the word doesn't change the stigma.","pattern":"Euphemism signal: a very indirect expression for a common concept (death, disability, bodily functions, social stigma). The indirectness signals the taboo. The longer the euphemism, the stronger the taboo: *pass away, depart, transition* (death) vs *die* (direct). When you see a long, Latinate word for a simple concept — suspect euphemism.","connection":"Euphemism cycles reveal that linguistic change cannot eliminate social stigma — only the words change, while the stigma transfers. The treadmill is evidence that language cannot fix social problems.","words":[{"w":"CEMETERY","pron":"s-EH-m-uh-t-eh-r-ee","syll":"cemetery","ety":["Greek *koimētērion* = sleeping place ← *koimasthai* = to put to sleep","A cemetery was originally a euphemism: the \"sleeping place\" instead of the \"death place.\" Early Christians used the sleep metaphor (death = sleep until resurrection). Now *cemetery* is the standard term — no longer felt as euphemistic. The euphemism became so established it lost its indirect character."]},{"w":"LAVATORY","pron":"LA-vuh-taw-ree","syll":"lae · vah · tao · riy","ety":["Latin *lavatorium* = a washing place ← *lavare* = to wash","A place for washing → used as a euphemism for toilet (because one \"washes\" there). Now a dated British term for toilet. The cycle: *privy → water closet → lavatory → bathroom → restroom → toilet → facilities*. Each generation creates a new indirect term; the previous one becomes too direct or archaic."]},{"w":"UNDERTAKER","pron":"UH-nder-tay-ker","syll":"ah · nder · tey · ker","ety":["English compound: *under-* + *take* = one who undertakes (any task)","Specialized from \"one who undertakes any task\" → \"one who undertakes burial arrangements.\" Now *funeral director* has replaced *undertaker* (itself now seen as too direct). *Mortician* (← Latin *mors* = death) was coined in the 1890s by the funeral industry as a professional euphemism. The cycle continues."]},{"w":"EXPIRE","pron":"ih-KSPEYER","syll":"ih · kspay · r","ety":["Latin *expirare* = to breathe out ← *ex-* (out) + *spirare* (to breathe)","Literally: to breathe out (completely). Used as a euphemism for death: to breathe one's last breath out. Now also: a food product \"expires\" (its life breathes out). The same Latin breathing metaphor covers human death and food freshness dates."]},{"w":"DECIMATE","pron":"DEH-suh-mayt","syll":"deh · sah · mey · t","ety":["Latin *decimare* = to kill one in ten ← *decimus* = tenth","Originally: a Roman military punishment — killing one soldier in ten (by lottery) to discipline a mutinous unit. Broadened (and bleached) to mean destroy a large portion. Purists insist it must mean exactly one-tenth. The euphemism issue: using a military massacre term to describe any large reduction has diluted its specific horror. A technical term became a vague intensifier."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Trace the euphemism treadmill for the domain of \"mental illness\": *lunatic → insane → mad → mentally ill → mentally disordered → person with a mental health condition*. When does each term become \"too direct\"?","trace":"Find 5 English words that were originally euphemisms but are now the standard term (no longer felt as indirect): *cemetery, expire, lavatory, decease, mortuary*.","build":"Steven Pinker argues the euphemism treadmill shows that the problem is the stigma, not the word. Do you agree? Write a paragraph arguing either that changing language CAN change attitudes, or that it CANNOT."}},{"id":"L57","n":57,"unit":6,"title":"False Friends — Words That Look Related But Are Not","diff":"hard","bigIdea":"False etymological friends are English words that look related in spelling but have completely different origins — causing spelling errors when you apply the wrong pattern by analogy.","story":"The most dangerous false friends in spelling bees: *principal/principle* (look nearly identical, completely different Latin roots), *stationery/stationary* (differ by one letter, different etymologies), *elicit/illicit* (identical pronunciation, different spelling and origins), *veracious/voracious* (one letter different, completely unrelated roots). These pairs are dangerous because the etymology-based approach suggests a relationship that doesn't exist.","pattern":"False friend diagnostic: if two words look similar but have different etymologies, applying one word's spelling rule to the other produces an error. The solution: learn the etymology of BOTH words in each pair — knowing both roots prevents cross-contamination.","connection":"False friends are the trickiest category in championship spelling because they exploit the pattern-matching that etymology teaches. Always learn the etymology of BOTH words in a false-friend pair.","words":[{"w":"PRINCIPAL","pron":"PRIH-nsuh-puhl","syll":"prih · nsah · pah · l","ety":["Latin *principalis* = first, chief ← *princeps* = the first one ← *primus* + *capere*","The principal (school head; adjective: primary). False friend: *principle* (← Latin *principium* = beginning, source). Both from *primus* (first) but different Latin nouns. Memory: the *principal* is your *pal*; a *principle* is a *le*arned rule."]},{"w":"STATIONERY","pron":"s-t-AY-sh-uh-n-eh-r-ee","syll":"stationery","ety":["Latin *stationarius* = standing still → *stationer* = a fixed-shop bookseller → what the stationer sells","Writing materials. False friend: *stationary* (← same Latin *statio* = standing place → not moving). Memory: *stationery* has *er* for *envelope* and *paper*; *stationary* ends like *temporary*."]},{"w":"ELICIT","pron":"ih-LIH-siht","syll":"ih · lih · sih · t","ety":["Latin *elicere* = to draw out ← *e-* (out) + *lacere* (to entice)","To draw out a response. False friend: *illicit* (← Latin *illicitus* = not permitted). Pronunciation: IDENTICAL for both. Spelling: *elicit* (one l) vs *illicit* (double l). Completely different origins; no relationship."]},{"w":"VERACIOUS","pron":"—","syll":"veracious","ety":["Latin *verax* = truthful ← *veritas* = truth","Truthful. False friend: *voracious* (← Latin *vorax* = devouring ← *vorare* = to devour). V-E-R-A-C-I-O-U-S (truthful) vs V-O-R-A-C-I-O-U-S (greedy). The *e/o* vowel difference = two completely unrelated Latin roots."]},{"w":"INFLAMMABLE","pron":"ih-n-f-l-A-m-uh-b-uh-l","syll":"inflammable","ety":["Latin *inflammare* = to set on fire ← *in-* (into) + *flamma* (flame)","⚠️ *Inflammable* does NOT mean \"not flammable.\" The *in-* means \"into flames\" = able to catch fire. *Flammable* and *inflammable* mean THE SAME THING. *Non-flammable* means the opposite. This false friend has caused real safety accidents when people read *inflammable* as \"not flammable.\""]}],"practice":{"decode":"For each pair, explain both etymologies and the spelling difference: *principal/principle, stationery/stationary, elicit/illicit, veracious/voracious, affect/effect*.","trace":"Find 5 more false friend pairs: *compliment/complement, eminent/imminent, tortuous/torturous, discreet/discrete, climactic/climatic*. Give both etymologies for each.","build":"The *inflammable/flammable* problem caused real safety issues. Research what safety authorities did to fix warning labels. What does this tell you about the real-world consequences of etymology misunderstanding?"}},{"id":"L58","n":58,"unit":6,"title":"Semantic Bleaching — When Words Lose Intensity","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"Semantic bleaching occurs when a word loses its specific, strong meaning and becomes a vague intensifier — the word's intensity is washed out through overuse.","story":"*Literally* (← Latin *litteratim* = letter by letter = exactly) now often means its opposite — used as an intensifier for non-literal statements. *Awesome* (← OE *āwe* = dread, fear) originally meant \"inspiring overwhelming awe\"; now often means merely \"good.\" *Terrific* (← Latin = terror-causing), *fabulous* (← *fabula* = mythological story = incredible), *fantastic* (← Greek = beyond imagination) — all strong words bleached to mean simply \"good.\"","pattern":"Bleaching signal: a word with a strong, specific original meaning that now serves mainly as a vague intensifier. *Awesome* (overwhelming dread → good). *Literally* (exactly → just for emphasis). *Very* (← Latin *verus* = true → truly → intensifier). *Very* is now so bleached that style guides warn against it.","connection":"Semantic bleaching reveals the costs of overuse: intensifiers become generic, specific terms become vague. Understanding bleaching helps you choose more precise vocabulary.","words":[{"w":"AWESOME","pron":"AH-suhm","syll":"aa · sah · m","ety":["Old English *āwesome* ← *āwe* (overwhelming wonder/dread) + *-some* (full of)","Originally: inspiring overwhelming awe — religious dread combined with wonder. Now: a casual intensifier for \"good.\" The full bleaching cycle: specific intense emotion → strong intensifier → general positive → near-filler."]},{"w":"TERRIFIC","pron":"ter-IH-fihk","syll":"ter · ih · fih · k","ety":["Latin *terrificus* ← *terrere* (to frighten) + *-ficus* (making) = terror-causing","Originally: causing great terror. 1800s: extremely good (through ironic reversal). Today: just good or very. The bleaching: terror-making → intensely powerful → ironically good → just good. The terror content has completely bleached away."]},{"w":"VERY","pron":"VEH-ree","syll":"veh · riy","ety":["Latin *verus* = true → Old French *verai* = truly → English *very* = truly → intensifier","*Very* began as \"truly\" (a word about factual accuracy). Bleached: \"truly good\" → \"really good\" → just *very* as a degree marker. Now so bleached style guides warn against it. The word that meant \"truthfully\" now means almost nothing."]},{"w":"LITERALLY","pron":"LIH-ter-uh-lee","syll":"lih · ter · ah · liy","ety":["Latin *litteratim* = letter by letter = exactly as stated ← *littera* = a letter","Originally meant exactly, not metaphorically. Now used as an intensifier for statements that are NOT literal (\"I literally died laughing\"). The word for \"not metaphorical\" became a metaphorical intensifier. Dictionaries now include this meaning as standard."]},{"w":"NICE","pron":"NEYES","syll":"nay · s","ety":["Old French *nice* = foolish → precise → pleasant → agreeable → (bleached)","The most completely bleached positive adjective in English. Journey: foolish → precise → pleasant → (bleached) = a vague general positive. *Nice* now means almost nothing specific — a placeholder for a mild positive feeling. Ameliorated AND bleached simultaneously."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Find 5 words bleached from intense/specific to general: *awesome, terrific, fabulous, fantastic, amazing, incredible*. What was each word's specific original meaning?","trace":"Style guides warn against *very*. Find 10 uses of *very* in a text and replace each with a precise word: *very tired → exhausted, very happy → elated, very big → enormous*. What does this reveal about bleaching?","build":"Predict: will *literally* complete its bleaching and eventually not imply \"exactly\" at all? What other intensifiers (*absolutely, totally, completely*) are currently bleaching? Find evidence from everyday speech."}},{"id":"L59","n":59,"unit":6,"title":"Contronyms — One Word, Opposite Meanings","diff":"hard","bigIdea":"Contronyms (autoantonyms) are words with two opposite meanings — context is the only guide, making them among the most treacherous words at the vocabulary level.","story":"Contronyms develop when: (1) Two different words merged through identical spelling (*cleave* from OE = both \"to split\" and \"to stick\"). (2) A word is used both literally and ironically until the ironic use becomes standard (*literally*). (3) A technical term and everyday usage conflict (*sanction*). (4) The word applies to both an action and its reversal (*screen* = to show vs to filter/hide; *dust* = to add dust vs to remove it). English has at least 75 documented contronyms.","pattern":"Contronym identification: can I make a sentence where the word means X, AND a sentence where it means the opposite of X? If yes, it is a contronym. At the vocabulary bee, always ask for a sentence when a word might be contronymous.","connection":"Contronyms reveal that meaning is always in context, never in the word alone. The same word can carry opposite meanings because words have no inherent meaning — only contextual meaning.","words":[{"w":"SANCTION","pron":"SA-ngkshuhn","syll":"sae · ngkshah · n","ety":["Latin *sanctio* = a decree ← *sanctus* = sacred ← *sancire* = to make official","A sanction = (1) officially PERMIT (the treaty was sanctioned), OR (2) officially PENALIZE (economic sanctions). Same word, two opposite meanings — both from official decree-making. A *sanctio* could authorize or prohibit; the word inherited both possibilities."]},{"w":"CLEAVE","pron":"KLEEV","syll":"kliy · v","ety":["Old English *cleofan* = to split + Old English *clifian* = to stick — two words, one spelling","Two completely different OE verbs merged into one spelling. *Cleave apart* = to split (*cleofan*). *Cleave together/unto* = to adhere closely (*clifian*). The marriage vow \"cleave unto\" = adhere. A butcher \"cleaves\" meat = splits. The same spelling carries two opposite OE words."]},{"w":"OVERSIGHT","pron":"OH-ver-seyet","syll":"ow · ver · say · t","ety":["Old English *ofer-* (over) + *sihþ* (sight) = looking over","Oversight = (1) careful supervision, OR (2) a failure to notice. Looking OVER something can mean watching it carefully OR your gaze passed OVER it without seeing it. The same spatial metaphor generates both meanings."]},{"w":"DUST","pron":"DUHST","syll":"dah · st","ety":["Old English *dūst* = fine particles — the substance named becomes both added and removed","*Dust* (verb) = (1) REMOVE dust from furniture (dust the shelves), OR (2) ADD dust/powder (dust the cake with sugar; crop duster adds pesticide). Adding and removing the substance named — entirely context-dependent."]},{"w":"BUCKLE","pron":"BUH-kuhl","syll":"bah · kah · l","ety":["Old French *bocle* = a ring/shield boss → fastening device","*Buckle* = (1) to FASTEN a belt (buckle up), OR (2) to COLLAPSE under pressure (the bridge buckled). Fastening firmly and collapsing under stress are the opposite conditions. The context (*belt* vs *bridge under load*) entirely determines which meaning applies."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Find 5 more contronyms: *weather* (survive a storm vs erode a rock), *rent* (receive payment vs pay for use), *fine* (good vs a penalty), *screen* (show vs hide), *seed* (add seeds vs remove seeds).","trace":"The *sanction* case: legal language has many contronymous terms. Find 3 more examples in legal/political vocabulary where the same word can mean both allowing and forbidding.","build":"Research: *literally* has become its own contronym (means exactly vs means approximately/for emphasis). Find 3 other words that have become contronymous through ironic or hyperbolic overuse."}},{"id":"L60","n":60,"unit":6,"title":"Taboo, Euphemism, and the Language of Power","diff":"hard","bigIdea":"The words a society treats as taboo reveal its deepest anxieties — and the euphemisms it creates to replace those words reveal its strategies for managing social discomfort.","story":"Power shapes language: the group in power decides which words are \"acceptable\" and which are \"offensive.\" The history of English vocabulary reveals these power dynamics: OE words for body parts and functions were displaced by French and Latin polite synonyms after 1066 (*armpits* vs *axillae*, *piss* vs *micturate*). Medical Latin gave prestige to discussing taboo topics scientifically while making them inaccessible to common speakers. The euphemism treadmill (Pinker) shows that politeness is cyclical: every \"polite\" term eventually becomes too closely associated with its referent and is replaced — but the underlying stigma never disappears through word-changing alone.","pattern":"Power and language: (1) Latin and French words are perceived as more polite for the same concept as OE words (*micturate/urinate* vs *piss*). (2) Institutional language euphemizes to reduce accountability (*collateral damage*, *enhanced interrogation*, *downsizing*). (3) In-group language (slang, jargon) creates exclusion and inclusion simultaneously. (4) The most powerful taboo words in English are the most Anglo-Saxon: short, monosyllabic, OE or Norse. The very structure of the vocabulary encodes power relations.","connection":"The vocabulary of taboo and euphemism encodes power relationships: who decides what is \"acceptable\" language, who enforces those standards, and which groups' language is stigmatized reveals the social hierarchy of each era.","words":[{"w":"EXPLETIVE","pron":"EH-kspluh-tihv","syll":"eh · ksplah · tih · v","ety":["Latin *expletivus* = filling out ← *explere* = to fill up ← *ex-* + *plere* (to fill)","An expletive was originally a grammatical term: a word added to fill out a sentence without adding meaning (\"there\" in \"there is a cat\"). Applied to profanity because strong language is used as a \"filler\" for emotional emphasis. The Latin word for \"filling\" became the polite word for swearing."]},{"w":"PROFANITY","pron":"proh-FA-nuh-tee","syll":"prow · fae · nah · tiy","ety":["Latin *profanus* = outside the temple ← *pro-* (before/outside) + *fanum* (temple)","*Profane* = outside the sacred space = secular, not sacred, then vulgar. Profanity = language that desecrates what is sacred. The concept: sacred and profane are spatial metaphors — inside the temple vs outside. *Fanum* = temple → *fanatic* (one excessively devoted to the temple/cause), *profane* (outside the temple)."]},{"w":"TABOO","pron":"ta-BOO","syll":"tae · buw","ety":["Tongan *tabu* = marked as forbidden — borrowed into English by Captain Cook 1777","A Polynesian concept (something forbidden because it is sacred or dangerous) borrowed directly into English without translation because English had no equivalent concept. *Tabu/taboo* filled a cultural gap: English needed a word for \"forbidden by social convention but not by law.\" Cook's voyages introduced the word to European languages simultaneously."]},{"w":"OBSCENE","pron":"—","syll":"obscene","ety":["Latin *obscenum* = of ill omen, filthy ← *ob-* (against) + *caenum* (filth, mud)","Against the filth = bringing bad luck through filth. The legal standard \"obscene\" (from *Miller v. California*, 1973) traces to a Latin word for mud and ill omens. The law's definition of what is obscenely unacceptable is built on a Latin concept of ritual impurity."]},{"w":"VULGAR","pron":"VUH-lger","syll":"vah · lger","ety":["Latin *vulgaris* = of the common people ← *vulgus* = the common crowd, the masses","Originally: belonging to the common people, ordinary. Not pejorative. As the upper classes distinguished themselves from the *vulgus*, *vulgar* acquired the connotation of coarse/lacking refinement. Pejoration driven by class contempt: the common people's speech and ways became associated with crudeness. The same *vulgus* → *divulge* (spread to the common people = make public)."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Find 5 English institutional euphemisms (government or corporate language): *collateral damage, enhanced interrogation, downsizing, negative growth, ethnic cleansing*. For each, identify the direct language being replaced.","trace":"The Latin/French word is \"polite\"; the OE word is \"rude\" for the same concept. Find 10 such pairs (*urinate/piss, posterior/arse, perspire/sweat, expire/die, consume/eat*). What does this distribution reveal about power?","build":"Research: Steven Pinker's claim that the euphemism treadmill shows language cannot fix social problems. Find one example where Pinker is right (changing the word didn't help) and one where he might be wrong (changing the language did shift attitudes)."}},{"id":"L61","n":61,"unit":7,"title":"The Pater/Father Family — 15 Words From One PIE Root","diff":"hard","bigIdea":"PIE root *pHtér* = father gave English at least 15 words through three paths. Knowing one root = knowing 15 words.","story":"PIE *pHtér* = father. Three paths diverged 6,000 years ago: (1) Germanic path → Old English *fæder* → *father*. (2) Latin path → *pater* → *paternal, patriarch, patriot, patron, patronize, patrimony, expatriate, perpetrate, compatriot, repatriate*. (3) French path ← Latin → *padre, padrone* (borrowed into English from Spanish/Italian). These 15 words all mean \"father\" or \"father-like authority\" — but they look completely different because of 6,000 years of linguistic divergence before they reunited in English.","pattern":"PIE cognate families: one root → 3+ language paths → English borrows from multiple paths simultaneously → apparent synonyms that are actually the same word wearing different linguistic clothes. Recognizing cognate families means you can predict what other English words share a root even when they look nothing alike: *father, paternal, patriarch, patriot, patron, patronize, expatriate, perpetrate* — all from PIE *pHtér*.","connection":"The PIE *pater* family shows that cognate recognition is exponential: one root unlocks 15 words across Latin, Greek, French, and OE paths simultaneously.","words":[{"w":"PATRIARCH","pron":"p-AY-t-r-ee-ah-r-k","syll":"patriarch","ety":["Latin *patriarcha* ← Greek *patriarchēs* ← *pater* (father) + *archein* (to rule)","The ruling father. *Pater* (father) + *arch* (rule) = the father who rules. *Archein* = rule → *monarch* (sole ruler), *anarchy* (no ruler), *hierarchy* (rule by rank), *oligarchy* (rule by few). The corpus shows 42 PIE *pater* words; *patriarch* comes through the Greek path (pater + arch), while *patron* comes through the Latin path alone."]},{"w":"PATRIOT","pron":"PAY-tree-uht","syll":"pey · triy · ah · t","ety":["French *patriote* ← Latin *patriota* ← Greek *patriōtēs* ← *patrios* = of one's father","A patriot = one loyal to the fatherland (*patria* = fatherland, derived from *pater*). The concept of patriotism is etymologically about loyalty to the ways of one's fathers. Compare *patron* (one who plays the father-role = protector) and *patronizing* (acting like a father = condescending) — same root, very different connotations."]},{"w":"EXPATRIATE","pron":"eh-KSPAY-tree-ayt","syll":"eh · kspey · triy · ey · t","ety":["Latin *ex-* (out of) + *patria* (fatherland) ← *pater*","Literally \"out of one's fatherland.\" An *expatriate* lives outside their home country. Compare: *repatriate* = send back to the fatherland; *compatriot* = fellow countryman (with-fatherland-person). All from *pater* through the Latin path. The *ex-/re-/com-* prefixes show the direction of the fatherland-movement."]},{"w":"PERPETRATE","pron":"PUR-puh-trayt","syll":"per · pah · trey · t","ety":["Latin *perpetrare* ← *per-* (thoroughly) + *patrare* (to bring about = complete as a father would)","*Patrare* = to achieve, to bring to completion (from *pater* — a father was one who completed and accomplished things). *Perpetrate* = to bring completely to pass = to carry out (usually something criminal). An unexpected *pater* cognate: the word for committing a crime uses a fatherhood root."]},{"w":"PATRONIZE","pron":"PAY-truh-neyez","syll":"pey · trah · nay · z","ety":["French *patroniser* ← Latin *patronus* = a protector (plays the father-role)","Originally: to act as a patron/protector toward someone. Now two meanings: (1) to support a business regularly, (2) to treat condescendingly as if the other person were a child needing a father's guidance. The split: positive meaning preserves the patron/supporter sense; negative meaning exaggerates the \"father knows best\" aspect."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Map the full *pater* family: OE path (*father*), Latin path (*paternal, patriarch, patriot, patron, patronize, patrimony, expatriate, perpetrate, compatriot, repatriate*), Greek path (*patriarch, paternoster*), French path. Count all 15+ words.","trace":"Find all words in the database containing *patr-/pater-*. Group them by which language path they entered through.","build":"Write a paragraph using *patriot, patron, patronize, expatriate, compatriot, perpetrate* — and explain the hidden father-root in each word as you use it."}},{"id":"L62","n":62,"unit":7,"title":"The Mater/Mother Family — 114 Words from One PIE Root","diff":"hard","bigIdea":"The corpus shows PIE *méhter* = mother generates 114 attested English words — more than any other kinship root — through Latin, Greek, and Old English paths.","story":"PIE *méhter* = mother. Corpus data: 114 attested English words. Three paths: (1) OE *mōdor* → *mother*. (2) Latin *mater* → *maternal, maternity, matriarch, matrimony, matron, matriculate, matrix, matter*. (3) The Latin path also gives surprising cognates: *material* (the substance out of which something is made = \"the motherly substance\" = what things are made from), *matter* (what things are made of = substance = the mother-stuff of the universe).","pattern":"Matrix and matter: these words look nothing like \"mother\" but trace directly to Latin *mater*. *Matrix* (← *mater*) = the womb, then the grid/structure in which things are formed. *Matter* (← *materia* = wood, the substance of things) = what things are made from. Both preserve the core metaphor: the mother as the source from which things emerge. Recognizing *mat-/matr-* = mother-root unlocks this entire family.","connection":"The *mater* family's 114 words are among the most important in English philosophy, science, and domestic law. Recognizing *mat-/matr-* as a mother-root unlocks the entire family.","words":[{"w":"MATERNAL","pron":"muh-TUR-nuhl","syll":"mah · ter · nah · l","ety":["Latin *maternus* ← *mater* (mother) + *-nus* (relating to)","Of or relating to a mother. The Latin path. Compare: *paternal* (from *pater*) = of or relating to a father. The *-al* suffix converting the Latin noun to an English adjective. *Maternal instinct, maternal mortality, maternal leave* — all use the Latin path word for mother."]},{"w":"MATRIMONY","pron":"MA-truh-moh-nee","syll":"mat · ri · mo · ny","ety":["Latin *matrimonium* ← *mater* (mother) + *-monium* (institution/management of)","The institution of marriage = the management of motherhood. Marriage was legally and conceptually defined in Roman law as the institution by which a woman becomes a mother. *Patrimonium* = management of what the father leaves (= patrimony/inheritance). *Matrimonium* = management of what the mother creates (= marriage/family)."]},{"w":"MATRIX","pron":"MAY-trihks","syll":"mey · trih · ks","ety":["Latin *matrix* = womb, source, origin ← *mater* (mother)","The womb = the source from which things emerge. Extended to: a grid or structure in which things are formed/organized (a mold), then to mathematical matrices (grids of numbers), then to the science fiction concept (the grid-structure of simulated reality). From biological source to mathematical structure to cinematic metaphor — one PIE mother-root."]},{"w":"ALMA","pron":"—","syll":"alma","ety":["Latin *alma* = nourishing, kind ← *alere* = to nourish — related to *mater*","*Alma mater* = nourishing mother = the school that nourished you. *Alere* = nourish → *aliment* (food), *alimentary* (relating to nourishment). The *alma* in *alma mater* = nourishing, not etymologically from *mater* directly, but always paired with it. Every university uses this Latin phrase for \"the mother that nourished you.\""]},{"w":"MATTER","pron":"MA-ter","syll":"mae · ter","ety":["Latin *materia* = the wood of trees, the substance of things ← *mater* (mother)","*Materia* = the substance from which things are made = \"the mother-stuff.\" *Matter* = what things are made of. *Material* = relating to matter/substance. *Materialism* = the philosophy that matter is all that exists. The mother as metaphor for substance-itself: the source from which all things emerge = the ultimate stuff of the universe."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Build the complete *mater* family: find all English words containing *mat-/matr-* that come from Latin *mater*. Group by semantic domain: family words, academic words, scientific words, philosophical words.","trace":"The word *matrix* traveled from \"womb\" to \"mathematical grid\" to \"simulated reality.\" Trace each meaning shift and explain the metaphor that enabled it.","build":"Compare *patrimony* (← *pater* = father-management) and *matrimony* (← *mater* = mother-management). What does the fact that *patrimony* means inheritance while *matrimony* means marriage reveal about Roman legal assumptions about gender roles?"}},{"id":"L63","n":63,"unit":7,"title":"The Cor/Heart Family — From Old English Heart to Greek Cardiac","diff":"hard","bigIdea":"PIE *ḱḗr* = heart generates English words through three paths — Old English, Latin, and Greek — each carrying the same core concept with different spelling and register.","story":"The corpus analysis shows PIE *ḱḗr* = heart generating *heart* (OE), *cordial/courage/discord/accord* (Latin *cor/cordis* through French), and *cardiac/cardiologist/endocardium* (Greek *kardia*). The three paths: (1) OE *heort* → *heart*. (2) Latin *cor/cordis* → Old French *cuer/cor* → English *cordial* (warm-hearted), *courage* (having heart), *accord* (heart-to-heart agreement), *discord* (hearts apart), *record* (put back in the heart = remember). (3) Greek *kardia* → Latin → English *cardiac, cardiologist, pericardium, tachycardia, endocarditis*.","pattern":"The three registers of the PIE *ḱḗr* family: *heart* (OE) = informal, emotional. *Cordial* (French/Latin) = formal-friendly. *Cardiac* (Greek) = medical/technical. The same PIE root generates vocabulary at all three register levels. Recognizing *cord-* (Latin path) and *cardi-* (Greek path) as heart-roots unlocks both family branches.","connection":"The PIE *ḱḗr* heart family spans the full range of English vocabulary: the everyday emotional word (*heart*), the formal social word (*cordial*), and the technical medical word (*cardiac*). Three registers, one ancient root.","words":[{"w":"CORDIAL","pron":"KAW-rjuhl","syll":"kao · rjhah · l","ety":["Old French *cordial* ← Medieval Latin *cordialis* ← Latin *cor/cordis* = heart","Warm-hearted, friendly. The Latin path. A *cordial* greeting comes from the heart. A *cordial* (noun) was originally a heart-stimulating drink. *Cor/cordis* → *cordial, courage* (*cor* + *age* = having heart = bravery), *accord* (*ad-* + *cord* = heart toward heart = agreement), *discord* (*dis-* + *cord* = hearts apart = disagreement)."]},{"w":"COURAGE","pron":"KUR-uhj","syll":"cour · age","ety":["Old French *corage* ← Vulgar Latin *coraticum* ← Latin *cor* = heart","Having heart. *Courage* = the quality of having heart when facing difficulty. The metaphor: the heart is the seat of bravery. *Encourage* (*en-* + *courage* = put heart into someone), *discourage* (*dis-* + *courage* = take heart away from). The same root as *cordial* — both from Latin *cor* = heart."]},{"w":"ACCORD","pron":"uh-KAWRD","syll":"ah · kao · rd","ety":["Latin *accordare* ← *ad-* (toward) + *cor/cordis* (heart)","Heart toward heart = agreement, harmony. *Accord* = agreement. *Accordance* = in harmony with. *According to* = in agreement with. *Discord* = *dis-* + *cord* = hearts away from each other = disharmony. Musical *chord* (notes sounding together in harmony) may also trace to *cor* through *accord*, though the spelling influence of Greek *khordē* (string) also contributed."]},{"w":"CARDIAC","pron":"KAH-rdee-ak","syll":"kaa · rdiy · ae · k","ety":["Greek *kardiakos* ← *kardia* = heart ← PIE *ḱḗr*","Of or relating to the heart (medical). The Greek path. *Kardia* → *cardiology* (study of the heart), *cardiologist* (heart specialist), *tachycardia* (*tachys* = fast + *kardia* = fast heartbeat), *bradycardia* (*bradys* = slow + *kardia* = slow heartbeat), *pericardium* (*peri-* = around = the sac around the heart), *endocarditis* (*endo-* = within = inflammation inside the heart)."]},{"w":"RECORD","pron":"ruh-KAWRD","syll":"rah · kao · rd","ety":["Latin *recordari* = to call to mind ← *re-* (back) + *cor/cordis* (heart)","To put back in the heart = to remember = to record (what you have in your heart). Originally: to call something back to mind from the heart's memory. Extended to physical recording (writing, audio). *Recordare* = remember → *record* (noun: a preserved memory), *record* (verb: to preserve in permanent form). The heart as the seat of memory in Roman culture."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Map the complete heart family: OE path (*heart*), Latin/French path (*cordial, courage, accord, discord, record*), Greek path (*cardiac, cardiology, tachycardia, pericardium*). Count all words.","trace":"The word *courage* literally means \"having heart.\" Find 5 other English words for bravery and identify their root metaphors: *valiant* (← Latin *valere* = to be strong), *brave* (← Italian *bravo*), *bold* (OE), *intrepid* (← Latin *trepidare* = to tremble = not trembling), *audacious* (← Latin *audere* = to dare).","build":"Build the *accord/discord* contrast: (1) find 5 more *ad-* + *cord* combinations (*concord, discord, accord, concordance, discordant*). (2) Explain why the word for musical chords shares this root."}},{"id":"L64","n":64,"unit":7,"title":"The Ped/Foot Family — From Pedal to Octopus","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"PIE *pṓds* = foot gave English two complete word families through Latin and Greek — both meaning \"foot\" but producing completely different-looking English words.","story":"Two paths from PIE *pṓds* = foot: (1) Latin *pes/pedis* = foot → *pedal, pedestrian, pedigree* (literally \"crane's foot\"), *pedometer, centipede* (hundred-footed), *millipede* (thousand-footed), *impede* (= put the foot into = block), *expedite* (= take the foot out of = free up), *expedition* (= a going out on foot). (2) Greek *pous/podos* = foot → *podium* (foot of a stage), *tripod* (three-footed), *octopus* (eight-footed), *antipodean* (opposite-footed = the people on the other side of the earth), *arthropod* (jointed-footed animals).","pattern":"*Ped-* = Latin foot. *Pod-* = Greek foot. Both are in English simultaneously. The field of use tends to separate them: *ped-* words are everyday and medical (pedestrian, pedigree); *pod-* words are scientific/zoological (arthropod, cephalopod). Recognizing both foot-roots unlocks the entire family.","connection":"The *ped-/pod-* foot family shows how the same PIE root, through Latin and Greek paths, generates two parallel vocabulary systems in English — one everyday, one scientific.","words":[{"w":"PEDESTRIAN","pron":"p-uh-d-EH-s-t-r-ee-uh-n","syll":"pedestrian","ety":["Latin *pedestris* ← *pes/pedis* (foot) + *-estrian* (relating to walking on)","One who goes on foot. Also: (adjective) ordinary, unimaginative — because walking was associated with the common people while riding was associated with the upper class. The semantic shift: going on foot → pedestrian (ordinary person) → pedestrian (unimaginative/commonplace). Social class embedded in a vocabulary shift."]},{"w":"IMPEDE","pron":"ih-m-p-EE-d","syll":"impede","ety":["Latin *impedire* ← *im-* (in) + *pes/pedis* (foot) + *-ire* (to put into)","To put the foot in = to block progress. *Impediment* = something that puts the foot in the way. *Impede* and *expedite* are contronyms from the same *ped-* root: *impede* (put foot in = block) vs *expedite* (take foot out = free up). The same foot metaphor generates both blocking and unblocking."]},{"w":"EXPEDITION","pron":"eh-kspuh-DIH-shuhn","syll":"eh · kspah · dih · shah · n","ety":["Latin *expeditio* ← *ex-* (out) + *pes/pedis* (foot) = a going out on foot","A journey out on foot. *Expedite* = take the foot out = free from obstacles = speed up. *Expedition* = a going out = a journey. The same foot-freeing metaphor: *expedite* applies to removing obstacles from a process; *expedition* applies to the organized journey itself."]},{"w":"PODIUM","pron":"POH-dee-uhm","syll":"pow · diy · ah · m","ety":["Latin *podium* ← Greek *podion* = a small foot, a base ← *pous/podos* (foot)","A raised platform = the foot/base of a stage. *Pous/podos* → *podium* (the base), *tripod* (three-footed base), *antipodean* (opposite-foot people = those on the other side of the earth from you). Also: *pseudopod* (false foot = the projection an amoeba uses to move)."]},{"w":"OCTOPUS","pron":"AH-ktuh-puus","syll":"aa · ktah · puh · s","ety":["Greek *oktōpous* ← *oktō* (eight) + *pous/podos* (foot)","Eight-footed. *Pous/podos* = foot → *octopus* (eight-footed), *arthropod* (jointed-footed = the entire class of insects, spiders, crustaceans), *cephalopod* (*kephalē* = head + *pous* = head-footed = the class of octopus, squid, nautilus). ⚠️ Plural of *octopus*: *octopuses* (English), *octopodes* (Greek-style, sometimes used), NOT *octopi* (that would be a Latin 2nd-declension plural, but *octopus* is Greek)."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Build both foot-root families side by side: Latin *ped-* words (pedestrian, pedal, impede, expedite, centipede, pedigree, podiatry, pedometer) vs Greek *pod-* words (podium, tripod, octopus, arthropod, antipodean). Count each.","trace":"The word *pedigree* means \"crane's foot\" (from Old French *pé de grue*) but uses the Latin *ped-* root in its etymology. How does this show that folk etymology and true etymology can overlap in interesting ways?","build":"The plural of *octopus*: why is *octopi* technically wrong? Explain using your knowledge of Greek vs Latin noun plurals from Unit 3."}},{"id":"L65","n":65,"unit":7,"title":"The Man/Hand Family — Manuscript to Emancipate","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"Latin *manus* = hand generates one of the most productive root families in English — from *manuscript* to *manufacture* to the unexpected *emancipate*.","story":"Latin *manus* = hand. The hand metaphor extends from physical manipulation to abstract control and authority. *Manuscript* (written by hand), *manufacture* (made by hand — originally any handcrafted item; now any industrial production), *manual* (relating to the hand = a handbook), *manage* (← Italian *maneggiare* = to handle a horse → to control), *mandate* (← *mandare* = to give into the hand = to order), *emancipate* (← *emancipare* = to free from the hand of authority = *ex-* + *manus* + *capere* = take out of the hand of). One root for physical hands generates the vocabulary of authority, writing, making, and freedom.","pattern":"*Man-/manu-* = hand-root signal. Every *man-* word relating to control, making, or writing likely traces to *manus*. The most surprising cognate: *emancipate* contains *manus* + *capere* (to take) = to take out of the hand of = to release from control. Freedom is etymologically \"leaving the hand of power.\"","connection":"The *manus* = hand family shows how physical manipulation generates abstract authority vocabulary. \"Managing,\" \"commanding,\" \"emancipating\" — all are hand metaphors extended to social control and freedom.","words":[{"w":"MANUSCRIPT","pron":"MA-nyuh-skrihpt","syll":"mae · nyah · skrih · pt","ety":["Medieval Latin *manuscriptum* ← *manus* (hand) + *scriptus* (written) ← *scribere* = to write","Written by hand. Before printing, all books were hand-written. *Manus* (hand) + *scriptus* (written). *Scribere* = write → *script, describe, prescribe, subscribe, transcribe, inscribe, circumscribe, scripture, scribble*. A manuscript is literally \"hand-writing\" — the compound preserves both the hand and the writing roots."]},{"w":"MANUFACTURE","pron":"ma-nyuh-FA-kcher","syll":"mae · nyah · fae · kcher","ety":["Medieval Latin *manufactura* ← *manus* (hand) + *factura* (making) ← *facere* = to make","Made by hand. Originally: any handcrafted item. Industrial revolution irony: *manufacture* now describes machine production — the word for \"made by hand\" became the word for made by machine. The *facere* root (L12) combined with *manus*: two of the most productive Latin roots in one word."]},{"w":"MANDATE","pron":"MA-ndayt","syll":"man · date","ety":["Latin *mandatum* ← *mandare* = to give into the hand ← *manus* + *dare* (to give)","To give into the hand = to entrust with authority = to order/command. *Mandare* → *mandate* (an official order), *mandatory* (required by mandate), *command* (*com-* + *mandare* = give into the hands completely), *demand* (*de-* + *mandare* = take out of the hand = require), *remand* (hand back to custody). A legal hand-giving metaphor generates all authority vocabulary."]},{"w":"EMANCIPATE","pron":"ih-MA-nsuh-payt","syll":"ih · mae · nsah · pey · t","ety":["Latin *emancipare* ← *ex-* (out of) + *manus* (hand) + *capere* (to take)","To take out of the hand of authority = to free from control. Roman law: a *pater familias* (father-head of family) had legal authority (*manus*) over children and slaves. *Emancipare* = release from that authority. Freedom = being taken out of the controlling hand. *Emancipation Proclamation* (1863) uses a Roman legal term for hand-authority."]},{"w":"MANAGE","pron":"MA-nuhj","syll":"mae · nah · jh","ety":["Italian *maneggiare* = to handle a horse ← Latin *manus* (hand)","Originally: to handle a horse (control it with the hands). Extended to: control any person or organization. *Maneggiare* → *manage, manageable, management, manager*. Also: *manège* (a horse-training area, still used in French/English equestrian contexts). The horse-handling metaphor became the vocabulary of business management."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Build the *manus* family: find 10 English words from Latin *manus*. For each, explain the hand-metaphor that connects the physical (hand) to the abstract (authority/making/writing).","trace":"The word *emancipate* contains *manus + capere*. The word *manufacture* contains *manus + facere*. The word *manuscript* contains *manus + scribere*. What does the combination tell you about the Latin view of the hand as a tool for doing, making, writing, and controlling?","build":"Find 3 English words that use the *man-* root in senses OTHER than \"hand\" (*man* = person in OE, completely different). What context clues tell you which *man-* root is present in an unknown word?"}},{"id":"L66","n":66,"unit":7,"title":"The Voc/Voice Family — From Vocabulary to Equivocate","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"Latin *vox/vocis* = voice and the related verb *vocare* = to call together generate 63 attested words in the 129K database — all about speaking, calling, and naming.","story":"Latin *vox/vocis* = voice. *Vocare* = to call. The two roots often appear together: *voice* (the sound), *vocation* (a calling), *vocabulary* (the set of words/names you can call things). The family: *vocal* (relating to voice), *vocalize* (give voice to), *vocation* (a calling to a life's work), *invoke* (call upon), *evoke* (call out), *provoke* (call forward = stimulate), *revoke* (call back = cancel), *convoke* (call together = assemble), *advocate* (call toward = support), *equivocate* (call equally = use ambiguous language = speak from both sides), *vocabulary* (the store of words = the store of things you can name/call).","pattern":"*Voc-/vok-* = voice/call root. *-voke/-vocation* signal the *vocare* verb path. The *v-* + vowel + *c-* pattern: *vocal, vocation, invoke, evoke, provoke, revoke, convoke, advocate, vocabulary, equivocate*. These 10 words all have voice or calling as their core metaphor. The *-voc-* inside a word = find the calling/voicing metaphor.","connection":"The *voc-/vok-* family shows how the metaphor of \"calling\" underlies all of English's vocabulary about language, authority, and career. Voice and calling are the same root concept in Latin.","words":[{"w":"VOCATION","pron":"voh-KAY-shuhn","syll":"vow · key · shah · n","ety":["Latin *vocatio* = a calling ← *vocare* = to call","A vocation = what you are called to do. The concept: one's life work is not chosen but *called* — as a religious or spiritual summons. *Vocational* education = training for a specific calling/career. *Avocation* = *ab-* + *vocare* = called away from (your main work) = a hobby. The calling metaphor pervades career and religious vocabulary."]},{"w":"ADVOCATE","pron":"A-dvuh-kuht","syll":"ae · dvah · kah · t","ety":["Latin *advocare* ← *ad-* (toward) + *vocare* (to call) → *advocatus* = one called toward","One called toward another's defense = a legal defender, a supporter. *Advocare* → *advocate* (noun: a supporter; verb: to support), *advocacy* (the act of supporting). The legal metaphor: a *vocatus* (one called) to speak *ad-* (toward) the court on behalf of another. The advocate is \"called toward\" the case."]},{"w":"EQUIVOCATE","pron":"ih-KWIH-vuh-kayt","syll":"ih · kwih · vah · key · t","ety":["Latin *aequivocare* ← *aequi-* (equal) + *vocare* (to call)","To call two things equally = to use ambiguous language that can be called by either of two meanings. *Equivocal* = having two equal possible meanings. *Equivocate* = deliberately use ambiguous language. The opposite of *unequivocal* (*un-* + *aequi* + *voc-* = not calling equally = clearly only one meaning). Using a word that \"calls\" two things at once = equivocating."]},{"w":"INVOKE","pron":"ih-NVOHK","syll":"ih · nvow · k","ety":["Latin *invocare* ← *in-* (into/upon) + *vocare* (to call)","To call upon = to call a power or authority into action. *Invoke* the law, invoke a deity, invoke a clause. *Evoke* (*ex-* = out) = call out = bring out emotions/memories. *Provoke* (*pro-* = forward) = call forward = stimulate. *Revoke* (*re-* = back) = call back = cancel. The prefix changes the direction of the calling."]},{"w":"VOCABULARY","pron":"voh-KA-byuh-leh-ree","syll":"vo · cab · u · lar · y","ety":["Medieval Latin *vocabularium* ← *vocabulum* = a name, a word ← *vocare* = to call","The store of words = the store of things you can name/call. A vocabulary is literally \"a collection of things that can be called by name.\" *Vocabulum* = a word = a thing that calls something into existence by naming it. The entire concept of vocabulary is rooted in the voice/calling metaphor: language = calling things into being by naming them."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Build the *vocare* family: find all English derivatives of *vocare* = to call. Sort by prefix (*in-, e-, pro-, re-, con-, ad-, equi-*) and explain what each prefix-direction means for the \"calling\" metaphor.","trace":"The word *vocation* (a calling) vs *avocation* (a hobby = called away). Research: how did \"calling\" become the metaphor for career? What does the religious origin of *vocation* tell you about medieval attitudes toward work?","build":"The word *vocabulary* literally means \"a store of things that can be called by name.\" Write a paragraph exploring this metaphor: in what sense is naming something equivalent to \"calling it\"? Use examples from the history of word creation."}},{"id":"L67","n":67,"unit":7,"title":"The Vit/Life Family — From Vital to Vivacious","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"Latin *vita* = life and the related *vivere* = to live together generate a rich English word family about life, living, and survival.","story":"Latin *vita* = life. *Vivere* = to live. These two related roots generate the vocabulary of life: *vital* (essential to life), *vitality* (the quality of living fully), *vitamin* (a vital amino? — actually a misnomer, but the *vita-* root is there), *revive* (live again), *survive* (live over/beyond), *vivacious* (lively), *vivid* (full of life = intensely bright), *vivisection* (cutting while alive), *bon vivant* (one who lives well, French). Also through a different Latin path: *convivial* (*con-* + *vivere* = living together = sociable).","pattern":"*Vit-/viv-* = life root signal. *Vit-* tends to appear in words about life as a condition (*vital, vitamin, vitality*); *viv-* tends to appear in words about the quality of living (*vivid, vivacious, revive, survive*). Both are from the same PIE root but through slightly different Latin forms.","connection":"The *vita/vivere* life family shows how one Latin concept generates vocabulary at multiple registers: scientific (*vitamin*), medical (*vital signs*), aesthetic (*vivid*), social (*convivial*).","words":[{"w":"VITAL","pron":"VEYE-tuhl","syll":"vay · tah · l","ety":["Latin *vitalis* = of life, life-giving ← *vita* (life)","Essential to life. *Vita* → *vital, vitality, vitalize, vitamin* (coined 1912 by Casimir Funk, who thought they were \"vital amines\" — the *amine* part was wrong but *vita-* survived). *Vital signs* = the measurements that indicate life (pulse, breathing, temperature). The word *vital* = belongs to life = essential to life."]},{"w":"VIVACIOUS","pron":"vuh-VAY-shuhs","syll":"vi · va · cious","ety":["Latin *vivax* = lively, long-lived ← *vivere* (to live) + *-acious* (apt to)","Full of life and energy. *Vivax* → *vivacious* (lively), *vivacity*. Note the *-acious → -acity* pattern from L20: *vivacious/vivacity*. *Vivere* → *vivid* (full of life = intensely bright/clear), *vivisection* (cutting living tissue = animal experiments conducted on living subjects). The vividness of colors is etymologically about life-force."]},{"w":"REVIVE","pron":"rih-VEYEV","syll":"rih · vay · v","ety":["Latin *revivere* ← *re-* (again) + *vivere* (to live)","To live again = to restore to life or activity. *Re-* + *vivere* → *revive, revival, revivify*. The *sur-* in *survive* = *super-* (over/beyond) + *vivere* (to live) = to live beyond (danger, another person, a difficult time). *Survive* and *revive* share the *vivere* life-root; they differ only in the direction of the life-prefix."]},{"w":"CONVIVIAL","pron":"k-uh-n-v-IH-v-ee-uh-l","syll":"convivial","ety":["Latin *convivialis* ← *con-* (together) + *vivere* (to live)","Living together = sociable, friendly, festive. *Convivium* (a feast, a shared living event) → *convivial*. The Latin concept: eating together = living together = the most sociable human activity. Compare: *companion* (*com-* + *panis* = eating bread together). Two different roots (*vivere* = life; *panis* = bread) both express togetherness through the metaphor of shared eating."]},{"w":"VITAMIN","pron":"VEYE-tuh-muhn","syll":"vay · tah · mah · n","ety":["Coined 1912: Latin *vita* (life) + *amine* (a class of chemical compounds)","Coined by biochemist Casimir Funk, who believed the essential nutrients were \"vital amines.\" When they turned out not to be amines, the term should have changed — but *vitamin* was already in use and the *vita-* root was accurate enough. The *-amine* part is chemically wrong; the *vita-* part is right. An important vocabulary lesson: coined words don't always get corrected when the science changes."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Build the *vita/viv* family: find 10 English words from *vita* (life-condition words) and 10 from *vivere* (living-quality words). Sort and explain the pattern.","trace":"The word *vivid* literally means \"full of life.\" How did \"full of life\" become a word for intensely bright colors? What does this tell you about how ancient Romans conceptualized color and brightness?","build":"Compare *convivial* (con+vivere = living together = sociable) with *companion* (com+panis = sharing bread = sociable). Two Latin roots, same social metaphor. Find 3 more English words that express friendship/togetherness through different physical metaphors."}},{"id":"L68","n":68,"unit":7,"title":"The Vert/Turn Family — 109 Words From One Latin Root","diff":"hard","bigIdea":"Latin *vertere* = to turn generates 109 attested English words in the 129K database — one of the largest Latin verb families in English.","story":"The corpus analysis confirms: *vertere* = to turn generates 109 English words. The verb has two stems: *vert-* (present stem) and *vers-* (perfect passive stem). English borrowed from both: *vert-* path → *invert, convert, divert, avert, revert, subvert, pervert, advertise* (← *advertere* = to turn the attention toward). *Vers-* path → *verse* (a line you turn back on), *version* (a turning), *conversation* (a turning-together), *controversy* (*contra-* + *vers* = turning against), *universe* (*uni-* + *verse* = turned into one = everything), *anniversary* (*anni-* + *vers* = year-turning = the date turns around again).","pattern":"*Vert-/vers-* = turn root. The prefix before *vert-/vers-* shows the DIRECTION of the turn: *in-* = turn inward (*introvert, invert*), *re-* = turn back (*revert, reverse*), *di-* = turn aside (*divert, diverse*), *con-* = turn together (*convert, conversation*), *sub-* = turn under (*subvert*), *per-* = turn completely (*pervert*), *a-/ad-* = turn toward (*avert, advertise*). The turning direction = the meaning.","connection":"The *vertere* = turn family with 109 words is one of the largest Latin root families in English. The prefix tells the direction; the root tells the action. Master the direction-turn pair and you can decode any *vert-/vers-* word.","words":[{"w":"UNIVERSE","pron":"YOO-nuh-vurs","syll":"yuw · nah · ver · s","ety":["Latin *universum* ← *uni-* (one) + *versus* (turned) = turned into one = everything","The universe = everything turned into one. *Uni-* (one) + *vertere* (turn) = all things turned into a single entity. The philosophical concept: the universe is the totality turned into one. Same structure as *university* = *univers-itas* = the turning-into-one place = a community of learning (all scholars turned toward one truth)."]},{"w":"CONTROVERSY","pron":"KAH-ntruh-vur-see","syll":"kaa · ntrah · ver · siy","ety":["Latin *controversia* ← *contra-* (against) + *versus* (turned)","Turned against = a dispute. *Controversia* = the turning against each other = a formal dispute. *Controversial* = causing such disagreement. *Introvert* = *intro-* + *vertere* = turning inward. *Extrovert* = *extra-* + *vertere* = turning outward. Jung coined *introvert/extrovert* in 1910 using the Latin *vertere* root for psychological personality types."]},{"w":"ANNIVERSARY","pron":"a-nuh-VUR-ser-ee","syll":"ae · nah · ver · ser · iy","ety":["Latin *anniversarius* ← *annus* (year) + *versus* (turned) = the year turned around","The date that turns around again each year. *Annus* = year → *annual, biannual, millennium* (from *mille* + *annum*). *Versus* = turned (participial form of *vertere*). An anniversary = the point where the year completes its turn and comes back to the same date. Same *anni-* + *vers-* structure in *anniversary*."]},{"w":"ADVERTISE","pron":"A-dver-teyez","syll":"ae · dver · tay · z","ety":["Latin *advertere* ← *ad-* (toward) + *vertere* (to turn)","To turn attention toward = to draw attention to a product. *Advertere* → *advertise* (turn attention toward goods), *advertisement*. Same *ad-* + *vert-* structure: *avert* = *ab-* + *vertere* = turn away from (danger). *Advertise* turns attention TOWARD; *avert* turns it AWAY. The prefix reverses the direction."]},{"w":"SUBVERT","pron":"suh-BVURT","syll":"sah · bver · t","ety":["Latin *subvertere* ← *sub-* (under) + *vertere* (to turn)","To turn from underneath = to undermine, to overthrow a system from below. *Subvert* and *suburb* both use *sub-* but in different senses: *suburb* = *sub-* + *urbs* = below/near the city; *subvert* = *sub-* + *vertere* = turning from underneath. *Subversion* = the process of turning from under. Revolutionary activity is etymologically \"under-turning.\""]}],"practice":{"decode":"Build the complete *vertere* direction table: find one word for each prefix combination (*in-/intro-, ex-/extra-, re-, di-, con-, sub-, per-, a-/ad-, trans-, ob-/o-*). Explain what each direction-turn means.","trace":"The word *universe* = uni + verse = turned into one = everything. The word *university* = the same root. How does the word for all of reality and the word for an academic institution share the same etymology?","build":"Find 5 *vers-* path words (the perfect-passive-stem path): *verse, version, conversation, anniversary, controversy, diverse, reverse, universe, transverse*. Explain how each uses the \"turning\" metaphor."}},{"id":"L69","n":69,"unit":7,"title":"The Ver/Truth Family — From Verify to Verdict","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"Latin *verus* = true generates a compact but important English family: the vocabulary of truth-telling, verification, and honest speech.","story":"Latin *verus* = true. The truth-family: *verify* (make true = confirm), *verity* (truth), *veracious* (truthful), *verisimilitude* (the appearance of truth = *verus* + *similis* = like the truth = plausibility), *verdict* (*verus* + *dictum* = truly said = a jury's finding), *aver* (firmly declare true = *ad-* + *verus*), *very* (← Old French *verai* = truly → bleached intensifier). The most unexpected member: *very* — the intensifier began as \"truly.\" The most revealing compound: *verisimilitude* = \"like the truth\" = a philosophical and literary concept for believable fiction.","pattern":"*Ver-* = truth root. Look for *ver-* at the start of a word meaning something about truth, confirmation, or reality. Distinguish from *ver-* = spring (in *vernal, vernacular*) and *ver-* = worm (in *vermicelli*) — three different *ver-* roots that look identical but are completely unrelated.","connection":"The *verus* = truth family is compact but philosophically important: the vocabulary of testimony, legal truth-finding, and literary realism all trace to this one Latin root.","words":[{"w":"VERISIMILITUDE","pron":"v-eh-r-uh-s-uh-m-IH-l-uh-t-oo-d","syll":"verisimilitude","ety":["Latin *verisimilitudo* ← *verus* (true) + *similis* (like) + *-tudo* (quality)","The quality of being like the truth = the appearance of reality in fiction. *Similis* = like → *similar, simulate, simile, simultaneous, assimilate*. *Verisimilitude* = *verus* (true) + *similis* (like) + *-tudo* (quality) = the quality of being truth-like. Literary term: what makes a story feel real. The compound is completely transparent once you know the parts."]},{"w":"VERDICT","pron":"VUR-dihkt","syll":"ver · dih · kt","ety":["Latin *veredictum* ← *vere* (truly) + *dictum* (said) ← *dicere* = to say","What is truly said = a jury's finding of fact. *Vere* = truly (adverb from *verus*) + *dictum* (said). The verdict is what is \"truly said\" by the jury after deliberation. Same *ver-* root in *aver* (*ad-* + *verus* = firmly declare true = to assert), *verity* (abstract truth), *verify* (make true = confirm)."]},{"w":"AVER","pron":"AY-ver","syll":"ey · ver","ety":["Old French *averer* ← Latin *ad-* (toward) + *verus* (true)","To firmly declare true = to assert positively. *Aver* = to turn strongly toward truth. *Averment* = an assertion. *Veracious* (truthful) vs *voracious* (greedy) — the false-friend pair from L57. Both start with *v*, but *veracious* traces to *verus* (truth) and *voracious* traces to *vorare* (to devour). The *e/o* vowel is the tell."]},{"w":"VERACIOUS","pron":"—","syll":"veracious","ety":["Latin *verax/veracis* = truthful ← *verus* (true) + *-ax* (apt to)","Apt to tell the truth. The *-ax/-acious* suffix (L20): *veracious* → *veracity*. The false-friend pair: *veracious* (truthful, *e*) vs *voracious* (greedy, *o*). V-E-R-A-C-I-O-U-S = truth-apt. The same *-acious → -acity* transformation: *veracity* = the quality of truth-aptness."]},{"w":"VERY","pron":"VEH-ree","syll":"veh · riy","ety":["Latin *verus* = true → Old French *verai* = truly → English *very* = truly → bleached intensifier","Already visited in L58 (semantic bleaching). From the truth-family angle: *very* began as \"truly\" (an epistemological word asserting factual accuracy). Through bleaching, \"truly good\" → \"really good\" → just *very*. The word for truth has become the emptiest intensifier in English. The truth-root generated its own opposite through overuse."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Build the truth family: *verus → verify, verity, veracious/veracity, verdict, aver, verisimilitude, very*. For each, explain exactly how the \"truth\" root applies to its meaning.","trace":"The word *verisimilitude* is used in literary criticism for what makes fiction feel real. Research: what techniques do authors use to create verisimilitude? How does the etymology (truth-like) relate to the technique?","build":"Three Latin roots that look similar: *ver-* = true (*veracious*), *ver-* = spring (*vernal, vernacular*), *ver-* = worm (*vermicelli, vermiculite*). Find 3 words from each *ver-* root and explain how you can tell which root is present."}},{"id":"L70","n":70,"unit":7,"title":"The Plic/Fold Family — From Implicate to Duplicate","diff":"hard","bigIdea":"Latin *plicare* = to fold generates a large English family where every word contains a folding metaphor — applying to documents, logic, and physical folding alike.","story":"Latin *plicare* = to fold. The folding metaphor extends from physical paper-folding to logical entanglement to exact copies: *implicate* (fold into = entangle), *complicate* (fold together = make complex), *explicit* (unfolded = clearly stated), *implicit* (folded in = understood without being stated), *duplicate* (two-folded = an exact copy), *replica* (folded back = a copy), *supple* (folded under = flexible). The most important: *simple* = *simplex* = single-folded (only one layer) vs *complex* = *complexus* = folded together (many layers). Simplicity and complexity are literally about how many folds something has.","pattern":"*-plic-/-plex-/-fold* = the fold-root. *Im-* + *plic* = fold into. *Ex-* + *plic* = fold out. *com-* + *plex* = fold together. *du-* + *plic* = fold two. *multi-* + *plex* = fold many. The prefix shows what is being folded and in which direction.","connection":"The *plicare* = fold family shows how one physical metaphor (paper folding) generates vocabulary for logic (*implicit/explicit*), complexity (*simple/complex*), copying (*duplicate/replica*), and flexibility (*supple*).","words":[{"w":"IMPLICATE","pron":"IH-mplih-kayt","syll":"ih · mplih · key · t","ety":["Latin *implicare* ← *im-* (in) + *plicare* (to fold)","To fold in = to entangle, to involve in something (often something negative). *Implication* = the folded-in meaning. *Explicit* (*ex-* + *plic-* = fold out = clearly unfolded = stated directly). *Implicit* (*im-* + *plic-* = folded in = understood without being stated). The *explicit/implicit* pair = unfolded-out vs folded-in. Same root, opposite directions of folding."]},{"w":"COMPLICATE","pron":"KAH-mpluh-kayt","syll":"kaa · mplah · key · t","ety":["Latin *complicare* ← *com-* (together) + *plicare* (to fold)","To fold together = to make complex. *Complex* (← *complexus* = folded together) = many things folded into one structure. *Simple* (← *simplex* = single-fold) = only one layer. The famous contrast: *simple* (one fold) vs *complex* (many folds). Every time you describe something as complex or simple, you are using a Latin paper-folding metaphor."]},{"w":"EXPLICIT","pron":"ih-KSPLIH-suht","syll":"ih · ksplih · sah · t","ety":["Latin *explicitus* ← *ex-* (out) + *plicare* (to fold)","Unfolded = clearly stated. *Explicit* = folded out so all layers are visible. *Implicit* = folded in so only the surface is visible; the other layers are understood. The pair: *explicit content* (unfolded, visible) vs *implicit meaning* (folded in, understood). Every use of *implicit/explicit* is a paper-folding metaphor for clarity."]},{"w":"DUPLICATE","pron":"DOO-pluh-kuht","syll":"duw · plah · kah · t","ety":["Latin *duplicare* ← *du-* (two) + *plicare* (to fold)","Two-folded = an exact copy. *Du-* (two) + *plicare* (to fold) = fold in two = make a second layer = make a copy. *Triplicate* (three-folded = three copies), *quadruplicate* (four copies), *quintuplicate* (five copies). *Replica* (← *replicare* = fold back = a copy folded back from the original). *Duplicate* and *replica* are near-synonyms from the same root."]},{"w":"SUPPLE","pron":"SUH-puhl","syll":"sah · pah · l","ety":["Old French *souple* ← Latin *supplex* = bending under ← *sub-* (under) + *plicare* (fold)","Folded under = flexible, bending without breaking. *Supplex* = one who kneels or bends under = supplicant (one who kneels in prayer). *Supple* (flexible) and *supplicate* (beg humbly, literally \"fold yourself under\") share the *sub-* + *plic-* structure. A word for physical flexibility and a word for religious begging share a root."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Build the complete fold family: find 12+ words from *plicare*. Group by prefix-direction: fold-in (*implicate, implicit*), fold-out (*explicit, explain*), fold-together (*complicate, complex*), fold-double (*duplicate*), fold-many (*multiple, multiplex*).","trace":"The pair *simple* (single fold) vs *complex* (folded together) is the most important in the family. Research: in mathematics, a *simplex* is a geometric shape. How does the \"one fold\" meaning connect to its geometric use?","build":"The word *supplicant* (one who kneels in prayer) shares the *sub+plic* root with *supple* (flexible). Write a paragraph exploring the conceptual connection: why is kneeling in prayer etymologically related to being physically flexible?"}},{"id":"L71","n":71,"unit":8,"title":"The 5-Question Method for Any Unknown Word","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"Any unknown English word can be decoded using 5 questions — language, start, middle, end, definition — giving you its spelling with 85%+ accuracy.","story":"At the spelling bee microphone, the 5-Question Method is a systematic protocol for extracting maximum information. Q1: What language does it come from? (Activates the language's ruleset). Q2: What do you hear at the start? (Prefix or root signal). Q3: What do you hear in the middle? (Root identification). Q4: What do you hear at the end? (Suffix signal). Q5: Does the definition confirm the root? Each question narrows the spelling possibilities until you arrive at the correct form.","pattern":"Protocol: Language? → Start? → Middle? → End? → Definition confirms? Work through all 5 in order before spelling. The definition is always the LAST check — it confirms, it doesn't generate. Start with sound and language, end with meaning confirmation.","connection":"The 5-Question Method converts etymology knowledge into a real-time microphone protocol.","words":[{"w":"PLENIPOTENTIARY","pron":"plen-ih-puh-TEN-shee-ehr-ee","syll":"plen · i · po · ten · ti · ar · y","ety":["Latin *plenus* (full) + *potens* (powerful) + *-ary* (relating to)","Q1: Latin. Q2: *pleni-* = full. Q3: *-potent-* = powerful. Q4: *-ary* = relating to. Q5: \"having full diplomatic power\" confirms. P-L-E-N-I-P-O-T-E-N-T-I-A-R-Y."]},{"w":"OPHTHALMOLOGIST","pron":"ah-pthuh-MAH-luh-jihst","syll":"aa · pthah · maa · lah · jhih · st","ety":["Greek *ophthalmos* (eye) + *logos* (study) + *-ist* (practitioner)","Q1: Greek. Q2: *ophthalm-* = hardest Greek cluster. Q3: *-olog-* = study. Q4: *-ist* = practitioner. Q5: \"eye doctor\" confirms. O-P-H-T-H-A-L-M-O-L-O-G-I-S-T. Count: 15 letters."]},{"w":"SCHADENFREUDE","pron":"SHA-dih-nfroyd","syll":"shah · dihn · froyd","ety":["German *Schaden* (damage) + *Freude* (joy) = joy at another's misfortune","Q1: German (sch- = /sh/, unusual vowel cluster). Q2: *schaden-* = damage. Q3: *-freude* = joy. Q4: final -e = German. Q5: \"pleasure at another's pain\" confirms. S-C-H-A-D-E-N-F-R-E-U-D-E."]},{"w":"CONNOISSEUR","pron":"k-ah-n-uh-s-UR","syll":"connoisseur","ety":["French *connaître* = to know ← Latin *cognoscere*","Q1: French (context + -eur signal). Q2: *con-* = together (prefix). Q3: *-noiss-* = French knowing-form. Q4: *-eur* = French agent. Q5: \"expert judge\" confirms. C-O-N-N-O-I-S-S-E-U-R. Double-n + double-s + -eur."]},{"w":"IDIOSYNCRASY","pron":"ih-d-ee-oh-s-IH-n-k-r-uh-s-ee","syll":"idiosyncrasy","ety":["Greek *idios* (own) + *syn-* (together) + *krasis* (mixture)","Q1: Greek throughout. Q2: *idio-* = one's own. Q3: *syn-* = together. Q4: *-crasy* = mixing. Q5: \"peculiar personal tendency = one's own private mixture\" confirms. I-D-I-O-S-Y-N-C-R-A-S-Y."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Apply the 5-Question Method to 5 NSF Finals words. Write out all 5 answers before spelling each word.","trace":"Time yourself: how quickly can you work through all 5 questions? What is the fastest you can decode a word without sacrificing accuracy?","build":"Build your \"Language Trigger List\": for each of 6 languages, list 5 sound signals that immediately activate that language's ruleset."}},{"id":"L72","n":72,"unit":8,"title":"Reading Consonant Clusters — Every Cluster Has a Story","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"Every unusual consonant cluster — kn-, wr-, ph-, ch-=/k/, -ght, -gn, -mb, -mn — is a historical fossil telling you exactly which language the word comes from.","story":"Consonant clusters that break rules are always historical: (1) *kn-* = OE pronunciation frozen in 1476. (2) *wr-* = OE. (3) *-ght* = OE guttural /x/. (4) *ph-* = Greek. (5) *ch-* = /k/ in Greek, /sh/ in French, /ch/ in OE. (6) *-gn* = Latin/French silent g. (7) *-mb* = OE silent b. (8) *-mn* = Latin silent n. (9) *ps-* = Greek silent p. (10) *rh-* = Greek aspirated r.","pattern":"Cluster-to-origin chart: *kn-* (OE, silent k) · *wr-* (OE, silent w) · *-ght* (OE, silent gh) · *ph-* (Greek, /f/) · *ch-* = /k/ (Greek) · *ch-* = /sh/ (French) · *-gn* (Latin/French, silent g) · *-mb* (OE, silent b) · *ps-* (Greek, silent p) · *rh-* (Greek). Cluster → origin → rules.","connection":"Every consonant cluster is a historical document. Read the cluster → identify origin → apply that origin's rules.","words":[{"w":"KNIGHT","pron":"n-AY-t","syll":"knight","ety":["Old English *cniht* — kn- cluster from OE pronunciation frozen 1476","*kn-* words: *knight, kneel, knife, knock, knot, knave, knit, knob, knack, knowledge*. Rule: *kn-* = OE = silent *k*. No exceptions."]},{"w":"PHOSPHORUS","pron":"FAH-sfer-uhs","syll":"faa · sfer · ah · s","ety":["Greek *phōsphoros* ← *phōs* (light) + *pherein* (carry) = light-carrier","*ph-* words: *phone, photo, philosophy, phosphorus, phantom, phenomenon, phrase*. Rule: *ph-* = /f/ = Greek. Confirmed by context of learned vocabulary."]},{"w":"PSYCHOLOGY","pron":"seye-KAH-luh-jee","syll":"say · kaa · lah · jhiy","ety":["Greek *psychē* (soul) + *logos* (study) — ps- cluster with silent p","*ps-* words: *psychology, psalm, pseudonym, psychiatry, ptomaine*. Rule: *ps-* at word start = Greek = silent *p*. The *y* as vowel in *psychology* adds a second Greek signal."]},{"w":"SIGN","pron":"SEYEN","syll":"say · n","ety":["Latin *signum* = mark → Anglo-Norman *signe* — -gn: silent g","*-gn* words: *sign, design, align, assign, benign, reign, foreign, sovereign, feign*. Rule: *-gn* in most positions = silent *g*. Exception: the *g* re-emerges in derivatives (*signal, signature, malignant*)."]},{"w":"PHLEGM","pron":"FLEHM","syll":"phlegm","ety":["Greek *phlegma* = inflammation ← *phlegein* = to burn — silent -gm","*-gm* words: *phlegm, paradigm, diaphragm*. Rule: Greek words ending in *-gma/-gmos* preserve the spelling but drop the *g* in English pronunciation. P-H-L-E-G-M = /flem/."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Build a complete Consonant Cluster Reference Card: cluster, origin, pronunciation rule, 3 examples.","trace":"The *ch-* ambiguity: find 5 examples of each ch-pronunciation (OE /ch/, French /sh/, Greek /k/). What context clues trigger the correct pronunciation?","build":"Research: the word *chaos* (Greek, ch=/k/) and *champagne* (French, ch=/sh/) are both in common use. How do English speakers know which pronunciation to use without thinking about it?"}},{"id":"L73","n":73,"unit":8,"title":"Prefix Mastery — All 24 Core Prefixes","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"English has 24 core prefixes that account for the vast majority of prefixed words. Mastering all 24 gives you the decoding key for thousands of words simultaneously.","story":"The 24 prefix inventory: Latin spatial (*ab-, ad-, con-, de-, ex-, in-, inter-, per-, pre-, pro-, re-, sub-, trans-*), Latin negating (*in-/im-/ir-/il-, dis-*), Greek (*a-/an-, anti-, hyper-, hypo-, meta-, para-, syn-/sym-*), OE/Germanic (*un-, out-, over-, under-*), French (*en-/em-, mis-*). Recognizing which system a word belongs to tells you its origin AND its directional meaning.","pattern":"Prefix collision: *un-* (OE = not) vs *in-* (Latin = not): *unhappy* = OE + OE; *impossible* = Latin + Latin. The language of the prefix matches the language of the root. *Over-* (OE) vs *hyper-* (Greek): both mean excessive but signal different register. Prefix homogeneity: Latin prefixes prefer Latin roots; Greek prefixes prefer Greek roots.","connection":"The 24 prefix system gives you 24 decoding keys. Learning the prefix + its language + its directional meaning unlocks thousands of words simultaneously.","words":[{"w":"ANTIDISESTABLISHMENTARIANISM","pron":"a-nteye-dih-suh-sta-blih-shmuh-NTEH-ree-uh-nih-zuh-m","syll":"ae · ntay · dih · sah · stae · blih · shmah · nteh · riy · ah · nih · zah · m","ety":["Greek *anti-* + Latin *dis-* + French *establish* + French *-ment* + Latin *-arian* + Greek *-ism*","The longest non-technical English word demonstrates ALL four prefix systems: Greek (*anti-*), Latin (*dis-*), French (*establish/ment*), Latin (*-arian*), Greek (*-ism*). One word = four language systems = opposition to removing the Church of England's official status (1860s British politics)."]},{"w":"MISANTHROPE","pron":"MIH-suh-nthrohp","syll":"mih · sah · nthrow · p","ety":["Greek *misos* (hatred) + *anthrōpos* (human being)","*Miso-* = Greek hatred prefix: *misanthropy, misogyny, misogamy*. Different from OE/French *mis-* = wrongly (*misplace, mistake*). Two *mis-* prefixes in English: Greek hatred-*mis-* vs OE/French wrong-*mis-*."]},{"w":"HYPERTHYROIDISM","pron":"—","syll":"hyperthyroidism","ety":["Greek *hyper-* (over) + Greek *thyroid* + Greek *-ism*","*Hyper-* = Greek excessive. Medical Greek prefix: *hypertension, hyperactive, hyperthermia*. Contrast with OE *over-*: *overweight, overtired*. Greek prefixes elevate to medical register; OE equivalents stay everyday."]},{"w":"TRANSCONTINENTAL","pron":"tra-nzkah-ntih-NEH-ntuhl","syll":"trae · nzkaa · ntih · neh · ntah · l","ety":["Latin *trans-* (across) + Latin *continens* + *-al*","*Trans-* = Latin prefix, stays in Latin register. *Transatlantic, transcontinental, transport, transparent*. The prefix homogeneity principle: *trans-* never combines with Greek or OE roots in standard English."]},{"w":"SEMICIRCULAR","pron":"seh-mee-SUR-kyuh-ler","syll":"seh · miy · ser · kyah · ler","ety":["Latin *semi-* (half) + Greek *kyklos* (circle) via Latin","*Semi-* = Latin prefix for half. *Semicircle, semicolon, semiconductor, semifinal*. Greek equivalent: *hemi-* = half (*hemisphere, hemicycle*). Both mean half; Latin *semi-* = everyday; Greek *hemi-* = scientific/medical."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Create a 24-prefix reference card: for each prefix give (1) language origin, (2) directional meaning, (3) assimilation rule if any, (4) 3 example words.","trace":"The *un-* vs *in-* distinction: find 5 pairs where both negating prefixes appear with similar-meaning roots. What register difference does the prefix choice signal?","build":"The \"prefix homogeneity principle\": Latin prefixes prefer Latin roots. Find 5 hybrid violations. Are these the same hybrids criticized in L30 as \"barbarisms\"?"}},{"id":"L74","n":74,"unit":8,"title":"Suffix Systems — From Root to Word","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"Suffixes determine grammatical function AND signal linguistic origin. Knowing both aspects of every suffix means knowing how to spell it AND how to use it correctly.","story":"The full suffix inventory: Latin noun suffixes (*-tion/-sion, -ity/-ty, -ance/-ence, -ment, -or/-er, -ary/-ory*), Latin adjective suffixes (*-ous/-ious, -al/-ial, -ive, -ile*), Greek suffixes (*-ism, -ist, -ize, -ology, -osis, -ic*), OE/Germanic suffixes (*-ness, -ful, -less, -ish, -ly, -hood*). The suffix tells you grammatical function; the origin tells you spelling variant.","pattern":"*-tion/-sion/-ssion* rule: use *-ssion* after stressed vowel (*mission*), *-sion* after d/l/n/r (*extension*), *-tion* elsewhere (*action*). *-ance/-ence*: words from Latin *-antia* → *-ance*; from Latin *-entia* → *-ence*. If the adjective form ends in *-ent*, the noun ends in *-ence* (*persistent → persistence*).","connection":"Suffix mastery = knowing (1) which grammatical function each creates, (2) which spelling variant to use, (3) which root changes occur when adding the suffix.","words":[{"w":"SUBMISSION","pron":"suh-BMIH-shuhn","syll":"sah · bmih · shah · n","ety":["Latin *sub-* + *mittere* (to send) → *sub-missio*","Root alternation: *mit-* (present stem: *submit, permit*) → *miss-* (perfect stem: *submission, permission*). The *-it* changes to *-iss-* in the noun form. This is the most commonly confused root alternation: S-U-B-M-I-S-S-I-O-N."]},{"w":"PERSISTENCE","pron":"per-SIH-stuhns","syll":"per · sih · stah · ns","ety":["Latin *per-* + *sistere* (to stand) → *per-sistentia*","The *-ence* choice (from Latin *-entia*). *Persistent → persistence*. Rule: *-ent* adjective form → *-ence* noun form (*persistent/persistence, resilient/resilience, insistent/insistence*)."]},{"w":"FALLACIOUS","pron":"f-uh-l-AY-sh-uh-s","syll":"fallacious","ety":["Latin *fallacia* (deception) ← *fallere* (to deceive) + *-ious*","The *-acious* suffix = apt to be inclined toward. *Fallacious → fallacy*. *Fallere* → *false, fail, infallible* (*in-* = not + *fallere* = not deceivable). The same root gives fallacy, failure, and infallibility through different paths."]},{"w":"CREDULOUS","pron":"KREH-juh-luhs","syll":"kreh · jhah · lah · s","ety":["Latin *credulus* ← *credere* (to believe) + *-ulous* (somewhat inclined to)","The *-ulous* suffix = somewhat inclined to. *Credulous* = somewhat inclined to believe = gullible. *Credere* → *credit, credible, credentials, creed, credence, incredible*."]},{"w":"OBSEQUIOUS","pron":"uh-b-s-EE-k-w-ee-uh-s","syll":"obsequious","ety":["Latin *obsequium* (compliance) ← *ob-* + *sequi* (to follow) + *-ious*","*Ob-* + *sequi* = following toward = compliance = excessively eager to please. *Sequi* → *sequel, sequence, consequence, obsequious, subsequent*. The *-ious* suffix = full of."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Apply the *-tion/-sion/-ssion* rule to: *act, extend, permit, create, express, revise, elect, compress, conclude*.","trace":"The *-ance/-ence* distinction: find 5 words of each. Is there a reliable etymological rule that predicts which to use, or must each be memorized individually?","build":"Build a Suffix Master Chart: for each major suffix give (1) language origin, (2) grammatical function, (3) spelling variants, (4) 3 example words with roots."}},{"id":"L75","n":75,"unit":8,"title":"Root Recognition — Finding the Core","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"The root is the semantic core of a word. Identifying it is the single most powerful tool in spelling bee preparation — because the root predicts spelling, meaning, and word family simultaneously.","story":"Root recognition strategy: (1) Remove any prefix you recognize. (2) Remove any suffix. (3) What remains = the root. (4) Identify which language the root comes from. (5) Apply that language's spelling conventions. The challenge: some roots undergo changes when attached to suffixes — the 4 major Latin root alternations (*mit/miss-, ced/cess-, ten/tain/tent-, vert/vers-*) account for hundreds of word pairs that appear unrelated.","pattern":"Root alternation patterns: *mittere/miss-* (*emit/emission, permit/permission*), *cedere/cess-* (*recede/recession, proceed/procession*), *tenere/tent-* (*detain/detention, contain/contention*), *vertere/vers-* (*convert/conversion, divert/diversion*). Knowing both forms of a root unlocks twice as many words.","connection":"Root recognition + the 4 major alternation patterns unlocks the spelling of hundreds of noun/verb pairs that appear to have unrelated spellings.","words":[{"w":"SUBMISSION","pron":"suh-BMIH-shuhn","syll":"sah · bmih · shah · n","ety":["*sub-* + *mittere* → present stem *mit-*, perfect stem *miss-*","*Submit → submission*, *permit → permission*, *commit → commission*, *emit → emission*. The *-it* present stem changes to *-iss-* in the noun. Completely predictable once you know the alternation."]},{"w":"RECESSION","pron":"rih-SEH-shuhn","syll":"rih · seh · shah · n","ety":["*re-* + *cedere* → present stem *ced-*, perfect stem *cess-*","*Recede → recession*, *precede → procession*, *concede → concession*, *exceed → excess*. The *-ede/-eed* present form → *-ession/-ess* in the noun. Completely predictable."]},{"w":"DETENTION","pron":"dih-TEH-nshuhn","syll":"de · ten · tion","ety":["*de-* + *tenere* → stems *ten-/tain-/tent-*","*Detain → detention*, *contain → contention*, *retain → retention*, *abstain → abstention*. The *-ain* form → *-ent-* in the noun. Three alternating forms of one Latin root."]},{"w":"CONVERSION","pron":"kuh-NVUR-zhuhn","syll":"kah · nver · zhah · n","ety":["*con-* + *vertere* → present *vert-*, perfect *vers-*","*Convert → conversion*, *divert → diversion*, *revert → reversion*, *subvert → subversion*. The *-vert* form → *-version* in the noun. Perfectly predictable across the entire root family."]},{"w":"PRODUCTION","pron":"pruh-DUH-kshuhn","syll":"prah · dah · kshah · n","ety":["*pro-* + *ducere* → present *duc-*, perfect *duct-*","*Produce → production*, *reduce → reduction*, *introduce → introduction*, *deduce → deduction*. The *-uce* form → *-uction* in the noun. 100% predictable across the entire *ducere* family."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Apply the 4 alternation patterns to 10 word pairs. Confirm the rule holds for each.","trace":"Find 3 more Latin root alternation pairs: *scribere/script-* (*describe/description*), *capere/cept-* (*receive/reception*), *ponere/posit-* (*compose/composition*).","build":"Build a Root Alternation Table with the 8 most important Latin root alternation pairs."}},{"id":"L76","n":76,"unit":8,"title":"When Rules Break Down — Identifying True Exceptions","diff":"hard","bigIdea":"Most apparent exceptions to English spelling rules are predictable from etymology. True exceptions — where even etymology doesn't help — are rare. Knowing the difference is a championship skill.","story":"True exceptions are rare. Most \"exceptions\" are: (1) Words from an unexpected language (looks Latin, is Arabic). (2) Historical fossils (the rule applied in 1476, no longer). (3) Scholar-inserted letters (added artificially to show Latin roots). But genuine unpredictable spellings exist: *colonel* (Italian spelling, French pronunciation = \"kernel\"), *Wednesday* (the *d* compressed out of speech while spelling froze), *gauge* (historically variable spelling resolved arbitrarily). These require memorization because no rule predicts them.","pattern":"True exception checklist: Is the silent letter a 1476 fossil? → Historical. Is it scholar-inserted? → Etymological decoration. Is it from an unusual dialect path? → Research the specific word. After all checks, if still unpredictable → true exception → memorize it. True exceptions are rare: perhaps 2-3% of the total vocabulary.","connection":"True exceptions are rare — most apparent exceptions are predictable from history. Building a \"true exception list\" requires first eliminating all words that ARE predictable from etymology.","words":[{"w":"COLONEL","pron":"k-UR-n-uh-l","syll":"colonel","ety":["French spelling of Italian *colonnello* ← *colonna* (column) = column commander","Pronounced \"KUR-nel.\" French took Italian *colonnello* → changed pronunciation (*colonnel* → *coronel*) while keeping Italian spelling (*colonel*). English borrowed the French pronunciation AND the Italian spelling. Result: C-O-L-O-N-E-L pronounced /KUR-nel/. No rule predicts this: it requires memorization of this specific word's history."]},{"w":"WEDNESDAY","pron":"WEH-nzdee","syll":"weh · nzdiy","ety":["Old English *Wōdnesdæg* = Woden's day — *d* was pronounced, then compressed out","The *d* was pronounced in OE (*Wōdnes-dæg*). As the compound was said faster, the middle syllable compressed and the *d* fell silent. Spelling froze from when *d* was still present. W-E-D-N-E-S-D-A-Y = /WENZday/. Historical fossil: records a pronunciation lost before 1400."]},{"w":"ARCTIC","pron":"AH-rktihk","syll":"aa · rktih · k","ety":["Greek *arktikos* ← *arktos* (bear) — NOT actually a silent-c word","⚠️ *Arctic* is NOT a true exception. The *c* SHOULD be pronounced: /ARK-tik/ not /AR-tik/. Common mispronunciation presented as a spelling exception. Correct: A-R-C-T-I-C with both *c*'s pronounced. *Antarctica* = /ant-ARK-tik-uh/. The lesson: verify whether a perceived \"silent letter\" is actually just a mispronunciation."]},{"w":"GAUGE","pron":"g-AY-j","syll":"gauge","ety":["Anglo-Norman *gauge* ← Germanic *galgo* = measuring rod — why not *gage*?","Both *gauge* and *gage* existed in Middle English. The *u* in *gauge* reflects an Anglo-Norman French vowel preserved in one usage stream while dropped in another. G-A-U-G-E vs G-A-G-E: the *u* distinguishes measuring-instrument from pledge/security. The *u* is not predictable from any standard rule — historical accident."]},{"w":"BROCCOLI","pron":"BRAH-kuh-lee","syll":"braa · kah · liy","ety":["Italian *broccoli* = arms of a cross-tree ← *brocco* (arm) ← Latin *brachium* (arm)","The double-*c* and final *-i* = Italian plural convention. B-R-O-C-C-O-L-I. Misidentifying the language (treating as French/Spanish) leads to single-*c* errors. True exception only in the sense that Italian is less commonly studied — once you know the Italian plural convention, the spelling is predictable."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Classify each as historical fossil, scholar-insertion, dialect artifact, or true exception: *colonel, Wednesday, gauge, friend, yacht, queue, choir*.","trace":"Research *choir* (originally *quire*, changed under influence of Latin *chorus* and Greek *khoros*). Why did the spelling change when the pronunciation didn't? Is this a rule or a true exception?","build":"Build your personal True Exception List: words where etymology gives NO useful spelling guidance. Hypothesis: fewer than 50 common words qualify as genuine true exceptions."}},{"id":"L77","n":77,"unit":8,"title":"The Championship Protocol — Microphone to Spelling","diff":"hard","bigIdea":"At the NSF Spelling Bee microphone you have 2 minutes, unlimited questions, and one chance. This is your complete championship protocol integrating all 8 units.","story":"The championship protocol: (1) Request language of origin. (2) Request definition. (3) Request root or additional information. (4) Identify all language signals in what you heard. (5) Apply the 5-Question Method. (6) Check for false friends, silent letters, or true exceptions. (7) Spell slowly, syllable by syllable, reconstructing the word from root outward. The most important skill: knowing which questions yield the most information fastest. Language + definition + root = 95% of what you need.","pattern":"Information priority at the microphone: Language → Root → Definition → Part of speech. Language activates the ruleset. Root determines the spelling core. Definition confirms root identification. Part of speech determines the suffix. In practice, championship errors come from: (1) wrong language identification, (2) unrecognized silent letter, (3) false-friend confusion, (4) wrong suffix form.","connection":"The championship protocol converts all your etymology knowledge into real-time decoding action. Every lesson in this program builds toward this moment.","words":[{"w":"NOCTAMBULISM","pron":"—","syll":"noctambulism","ety":["Latin *nox/noctis* (night) + *ambulare* (to walk) + *-ism*","Protocol: Language=Latin. *noct-* = night. *-ambul-* = walk (cf. *ambulance, perambulate*). *-ism* = condition. Definition \"sleepwalking\" confirms. N-O-C-T-A-M-B-U-L-I-S-M. Zero false friends. Zero silent letters. High confidence: spell."]},{"w":"ELEEMOSYNARY","pron":"eh-luh-MAW-suh-neh-ree","syll":"el · ee · mos · y · na · ry","ety":["Latin ← Greek *eleēmosynē* = mercy ← *eleēmōn* = merciful","Protocol: Language=Greek via Latin. *eleem-* = Greek merciful root. *-osynary* = Latinized suffix. *-ary* = relating to. Definition \"relating to charity/almsgiving\" confirms. E-L-E-E-M-O-S-Y-N-A-R-Y. Double-*e* and *-syn-* vowel cluster are the challenges."]},{"w":"SYCOPHANCY","pron":"SIH-kuh-fun-see","syll":"sycophancy","ety":["Greek *sykophantēs* ← *sykon* (fig) + *phainein* (to show)","Protocol: Language=Greek. *syco-* = fig (unusual root). *-phancy* = *phainein* = showing. *-y* = Greek abstract suffix. Definition \"servile flattery\" confirms (the fig-showing was an ancient gesture). S-Y-C-O-P-H-A-N-C-Y. Greek signals: *sy-* (y as vowel), *-ph-* = /f/, final *-y*."]},{"w":"PARAPHERNALIA","pron":"p-eh-r-uh-f-uh-n-AY-l-y-uh","syll":"paraphernalia","ety":["Greek *para-* (beside) + *phernē* (dowry) = property beside the dowry","Protocol: Language=Greek. *para-* = beside. *-phern-* = dowry (*ph-* = Greek). *-alia* = Latin neuter plural. Definition \"miscellaneous equipment\" (broadened from legal dowry-property). P-A-R-A-P-H-E-R-N-A-L-I-A. Greek signals: *para-*, *-ph-*, *-ia* plural."]},{"w":"SUPPOSITITIOUS","pron":"suh-poz-ih-TISH-us","syll":"sup · posi · ti · tious","ety":["Latin *sub-* + *ponere/positus* + *-itious*","Protocol: Language=Latin. *sup-* = *sub-* assimilated before *p* (double-p). *-posit-* = *ponere* = place (perfect stem). *-itious* = Latin adjective suffix. Definition \"fraudulently substituted\" confirms \"placed under in place of real thing.\" S-U-P-P-O-S-I-T-I-T-I-O-U-S. Double-p from assimilation."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Time yourself using the full championship protocol on 10 NSF Finals words. Record your success rate.","trace":"Research: what are the most commonly misspelled words at the NSF National Spelling Bee Finals? Which etymology lessons would have prevented each error?","build":"Write your personal Championship Spelling Protocol in your own words — a step-by-step card you can internalize. Maximum 10 steps. Make it yours."}},{"id":"L78","n":78,"unit":8,"title":"Pattern Confidence — Knowing When to Trust Your Etymology","diff":"hard","bigIdea":"The most dangerous moment is when you know a pattern exists but aren't sure if this specific word follows it. Calibrated confidence means knowing when etymology gives reliable guidance vs when to verify.","story":"Pattern confidence is HIGH when: (1) the word clearly belongs to one language. (2) It follows a common morphological pattern. (3) You've seen multiple words from the same root family. (4) The definition confirms the etymology. Pattern confidence is LOW when: (1) The word crosses language categories. (2) A false friend might be lurking. (3) The word entered through an unusual path. (4) The pronunciation seems adapted. When in doubt: ask for more information. Use all available questions.","pattern":"Calibration scale 1-5: (5) Fully confident = spell without hesitation. (4) Confident but verify one element. (3) Moderate = use all questions, triple-check. (2) Low = request everything. (1) Very low = consider all possible spellings systematically. Calibrated confidence prevents both overconfident errors AND hesitation-induced errors.","connection":"Calibrated confidence is the meta-skill that coordinates all your etymological knowledge. Knowing WHEN to trust your pattern recognition is as important as the patterns themselves.","words":[{"w":"CONSCIENTIOUS","pron":"kah-nshee-EH-nshuhs","syll":"kaa · nshiy · eh · nshah · s","ety":["Latin *con-* + *scire* (to know) = fully knowing, aware","Confidence 5: clear Latin, transparent morphology. C-O-N-S-C-I-E-N-T-I-O-U-S. The *-sc-* in *scire* = *science*; the *-ie-* before suffix = predictable Latin. Zero doubt."]},{"w":"RESTAURATEUR","pron":"reh-ster-uh-TUR","syll":"reh · ster · ah · ter","ety":["French *restaurer* = to restore — agent suffix *-eur*, no *n*","Confidence 4: French *-eur* is reliable, BUT the *restauranteur* false friend is well-known. Active strategy: suppress the *n* from \"restaurant.\" R-E-S-T-A-U-R-A-T-E-U-R. The etymology (*restaurer* = restore, no *n*) is the protection."]},{"w":"PHARAOH","pron":"FEH-roh","syll":"phar · aoh","ety":["Hebrew *par'ōh* ← Egyptian *pr-ʿ3* = great house — unusual path","Confidence 2: Egyptian via Hebrew → unusual phonological path. *-aoh* ending not predicted by any standard rule. P-H-A-R-A-O-H. Strategy: ask for language, root, definition, and any additional information. The *-ph-* signals Egyptian/Semitic path through Greek."]},{"w":"BUREAUCRACY","pron":"byuu-RAH-kruh-see","syll":"byuh · raa · krah · siy","ety":["French *bureau* + Greek *-kratia* — hybrid word","Confidence 3: hybrid (French + Greek). Neither language's rules fully dominate. Strategy: spell the French part (*bureau* = B-U-R-E-A-U) then add Greek *-cracy* (*-C-R-A-C-Y*). Manage two language systems in one word."]},{"w":"INOCULATE","pron":"ih-NAH-kyuh-layt","syll":"in · oc · u · late","ety":["Latin *in-* + *oculus* (eye/bud) — NOT *inn-*","Confidence 3: false friend risk (*innoculate* with double *n* is extremely common). Root: *in-* (single *n*) + *oculare* = I-N-O-C-U-L-A-T-E. Protection: the root is *oculus* (eye/bud), not *innocent* (which has double *n* from *in-* + *nocens*)."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Rate your confidence (1-5) for 10 championship words and explain why. Then verify your ratings were calibrated by checking the answers.","trace":"Research: what percentage of NSF championship errors come from overconfidence in a wrong pattern vs underconfidence in a right pattern?","build":"Build your \"Confidence Trigger List\": what features make you HIGH vs LOW confidence? Collect 10 triggers from your own experience."}},{"id":"L79","n":79,"unit":8,"title":"Building Your Personal Error Map","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"A championship speller knows not just what they know, but precisely what they don't know. An error map converts random mistakes into a targeted study curriculum.","story":"An error map identifies: (1) Which LANGUAGES trip you most. (2) Which ROOT FAMILIES you consistently misapply. (3) Which SUFFIX CHOICES you get wrong. (4) Which FALSE FRIENDS you fall for. (5) Which COGNATE FAMILIES you haven't mastered. The error map converts random errors into a targeted plan. Instead of reviewing everything, you review YOUR specific weaknesses with precision.","pattern":"Error classification: every spelling error belongs to one of six categories: (1) Language misidentification. (2) Root misidentification. (3) Suffix error. (4) False friend. (5) Silent letter oversight. (6) True exception. Classifying errors reveals systematic weaknesses vs random mistakes.","connection":"The error map converts random practice into targeted mastery. Championship preparation = addressing YOUR specific error patterns.","words":[{"w":"OCCURRENCE","pron":"uh-KUR-uhns","syll":"ah · ker · ah · ns","ety":["Latin *ob-* + *currere* (to run) = run against = encounter","Error example: prefix assimilation oversight. *Ob-* before *c* → *oc-* (double *c*). Then *-ence* not *-ance* (Latin *-entia*). Two separate decisions where errors occur. O-C-C-U-R-R-E-N-C-E: double *c* from *ob+c* assimilation, double *r* from present participle stem, *-ence* from *-entia*."]},{"w":"INOCULATE","pron":"ih-NAH-kyuh-layt","syll":"in · oc · u · late","ety":["Latin *in-* + *oculus* = to introduce into the bud/eye","Error example: false friend trap. Common error: *innoculate* (double *n* by analogy to *innocent*). Root: single *in-* + *oculare*. I-N-O-C-U-L-A-T-E. Protection: know the root is *oculus* (not *nocens*)."]},{"w":"MILLENNIUM","pron":"m-uh-l-EH-n-ee-uh-m","syll":"millennium","ety":["Latin *mille* (thousand) + *annum* (year)","Error example: doubled consonant confusion. M-I-L-L-E-N-N-I-U-M: double *l* from *mille*, double *n* from *annum*. The *mill-/ennium* root boundary reveals both doublings. Error: single *n* (*millenium*)."]},{"w":"ONOMATOPOEIA","pron":"on-oh-mat-oh-PEE-uh","syll":"on · o · mat · o · poe · ia","ety":["Greek *onoma* (name) + *poiein* (to make) = name-making","Error example: Greek vowel cluster. O-N-O-M-A-T-O-P-O-E-I-A: the *-oeia* final sequence is the challenge. Greek *-poieia* = making. The word about matching sound to spelling is itself one of the hardest to spell."]},{"w":"CONSCIENTIOUS","pron":"kah-nshee-EH-nshuhs","syll":"kaa · nshiy · eh · nshah · s","ety":["Latin *con-* + *scire* (to know) + *-ious*","Error example: internal vowel sequence. C-O-N-S-C-I-E-N-T-I-O-U-S: the *-ie-* between *-t-* and *-ous*. The Latin *scientia* root → *-tious* suffix → the *ie* vowel. Pattern: *conscience → conscientious* = the *-ie-* carries from the *science* root."]}],"practice":{"decode":"After attempting 20 championship words, classify each error into one of the 6 categories. Which category dominates? That domain needs the most targeted study.","trace":"Research: competitive spellers say \"I know what I don't know.\" What does systematic error analysis tell you that unfocused practice does not?","build":"Build a \"Personal Weakness Curriculum\": based on your Error Map, design a targeted 2-week study plan addressing your specific error categories with specific lessons from this program."}},{"id":"L80","n":80,"unit":8,"title":"Championship Vocabulary — The 50 Hardest Patterns","diff":"hard","bigIdea":"A curated list of the 50 most challenging spelling patterns at championship level — the patterns that cause the most errors even among highly prepared spellers.","story":"Analysis of NSF spelling bee data shows that championship errors cluster around 10 specific spelling challenges: (1) *-phth-* cluster in Greek medical words. (2) *-eur* vs *-er* in French agent words. (3) *-ance/-ence* choice. (4) Silent-g in *-gn* words. (5) Double consonant from prefix assimilation. (6) Greek *-y-* as vowel. (7) *ch-* ambiguity (Greek /k/ vs French /sh/). (8) Latin root alternation (*mit/miss, ced/cess*). (9) *-ious/-eous/-uous* choice. (10) False cognates with near-identical spelling. Mastering these 10 patterns eliminates the majority of championship-level errors.","pattern":"The 10 hardest patterns plus diagnostic words: (1) *-phth-*: *ophthalmology, diphtheria, phthisis*. (2) *-eur*: *connoisseur, restaurateur, chauffeur*. (3) *-ance/-ence*: *abundance/persistence*. (4) Silent *-gn*: *sovereign, foreign, feign*. (5) Assimilation doubles: *occurrence, approximate, suggest*. (6) *-y-* as vowel: *rhythm, myth, gymnasium*. (7) *ch-* choice: *chaos/champagne/church*. (8) Root alternation: *submit/submission*. (9) *-ious* choice: *conscientious/gorgeous/tortuous*. (10) False cognates: *elicit/illicit, veracious/voracious*.","connection":"The 10 hardest patterns account for the majority of championship-level errors. Mastering them is the highest-ROI study investment for competition preparation.","words":[{"w":"DIPHTHERIA","pron":"dih-FTHIH-ree-ah","syll":"diph · the · ri · a","ety":["Greek *diphthera* = leather membrane ← *diphthos* = two pieces of leather — -phth- cluster","D-I-P-H-T-H-E-R-I-A: two *th* units plus *ph* = three Greek aspirated/voiceless consonant clusters in one word. The *di-* = two (the two-leather metaphor for the false membrane). Named for the leather-like membrane the bacterium creates in the throat."]},{"w":"SOVEREIGN","pron":"s-AH-v-r-uh-n","syll":"sovereign","ety":["Anglo-Norman *souverain* ← Latin *superanus* = supreme — silent -eign","S-O-V-E-R-E-I-G-N: the silent *-gn* cluster from Anglo-Norman. The *-eign* ending = Anglo-Norman fossil pattern. Same cluster: *foreign, reign, feign, deign*. All have silent *-gn* from the Anglo-Norman *-igne/-eigne* form."]},{"w":"APPROXIMATE","pron":"uh-PRAH-ksuh-muht","syll":"ah · praa · ksah · mah · t","ety":["Latin *ad-* + *proximus* (nearest) + *-ate* — double p from assimilation","A-P-P-R-O-X-I-M-A-T-E: double *p* from *ad-* + *p-*root assimilation. *Proximus* = nearest (superlative of *propior* = nearer, from *prope* = near). *Approximate* = near to. *Proximity* = nearness. The double *p* = assimilation signal."]},{"w":"TORTUOUS","pron":"TAW-rchuh-wuhs","syll":"tao · rchah · wah · s","ety":["Latin *tortuosus* ← *tortus* (twisted) ← *torquere* = to twist — -uous ending","T-O-R-T-U-O-U-S: the *-uous* ending (not *-ious* or *-eous*). *Tortuous* = full of twists. False friend: *torturous* (← *torture* = causing pain) — same root (*torquere*), different suffix. *Tortuous* (twisty) vs *torturous* (painful): the *-uous/-ous* distinction separates them."]},{"w":"GYMNASIUM","pron":"jih-MNAY-zee-uhm","syll":"jhih · mney · ziy · ah · m","ety":["Latin *gymnasium* ← Greek *gymnasion* ← *gymnazein* = to exercise naked ← *gymnos* = naked","G-Y-M-N-A-S-I-U-M: the *-y-* as vowel (Greek *upsilon*), the *-um* Latin neuter ending. The Greeks exercised naked (*gymnos*) — hence the word for exercise hall. *Gymnast, gymnastics* share the root. The *gym* clipping = the most extreme compression: 10 letters → 3."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Practice the 10 hardest patterns: find 3 examples of each pattern and spell each correctly. Track your error rate for each pattern category.","trace":"Create a \"Hard Pattern Drill\": for each of the 10 patterns, write a mnemonic, a worked example, and a 3-word practice set.","build":"Build your personal \"Championship Word List\" of 100 words from the NSF Finals database that test your specific weakest patterns from your Error Map."}},{"id":"L81","n":81,"unit":9,"title":"Arabic's Gift — Al-Jabr, Al-Gorithm, and the Stars","diff":"hard","bigIdea":"The Islamic Golden Age (750–1258 CE) was the most scientifically productive period of the medieval world. When Europe rediscovered science through Arabic texts in the 12th century, it absorbed Arabic vocabulary wholesale.","story":"Arab scholars translated and extended Greek mathematics, astronomy, medicine, and philosophy. Al-Khwarizmi (780–850 CE) invented algebra. Arab astronomers named hundreds of stars still using Arabic names: *Aldebaran* (*al-dabarān* = the follower), *Altair* (*al-ṭā'ir* = the flying eagle), *Betelgeuse* (*bayt al-jawzā* = house of Orion). When European scholars translated Arabic texts into Latin in the 12th century, they kept the Arabic terms. The corpus shows 933 Arabic-origin words — small in percentage (0.7%) but enormous in scientific importance.","pattern":"Arabic *al-* = \"the\" was absorbed WITH the word into English: *alcohol, algebra, algorithm, alchemy, almanac, alcove, aldehyde, alkali, alembic, alfalfa*. The *al-* in these words = fossilized Arabic \"the.\" It is the most recognizable Arabic loan signal in English. Every *al-* science word = a monument to the Islamic Golden Age.","connection":"Arabic scientific vocabulary is the most systematically recognizable foreign layer in English — every *al-* science word points to the Islamic Golden Age's role in preserving and extending ancient knowledge.","words":[{"w":"ALGEBRA","pron":"A-ljuh-bruh","syll":"ae · ljhah · brah","ety":["Arabic *al-jabr* = the reunion of broken parts ← *jabara* = to reunite broken bones","Al-Khwarizmi's 830 CE treatise used *al-jabr* to describe completing equations by moving terms — a bone-setting surgery metaphor. A medical procedure metaphor became the name of a branch of mathematics. A-L-G-E-B-R-A."]},{"w":"ALGORITHM","pron":"A-l-g-ur-ih-th-uh-m","syll":"algorithm","ety":["From the name *Muḥammad ibn Mūsā al-Khwārizmī* → Latinized *Algoritmi*","The mathematician's geographic epithet (from Khwarezm, Uzbekistan) was Latinized as *Algoritmi*. *Algorithm* = a step-by-step procedure = the Latinized name of a 9th-century Persian mathematician. A person became a procedure."]},{"w":"ZENITH","pron":"ZEE-nuhth","syll":"ziy · nah · th","ety":["Arabic *al-samt* = the direction overhead → Spanish/French *zenit* → English","*Al-samt* = \"the path\" (above the head). A Spanish contraction gave *zenit* → *zenith* (highest point). Its opposite: *nadir* (also Arabic: *naẓīr al-samt* = opposite the zenith). Two celestial terms, both Arabic, both still in scientific use."]},{"w":"ELIXIR","pron":"ih-LIH-kser","syll":"ih · lih · kser","ety":["Arabic *al-iksīr* ← Greek *xērion* = drying powder ← *xēros* = dry","Journey: Greek \"dry\" → Greek wound-drying powder → Arabic alchemical \"essence/philosopher's stone\" → Medieval English \"magical potion.\" The Greek word for *dry* is inside every fantasy novel's elixir. E-L-I-X-I-R."]},{"w":"ALMANAC","pron":"AH-lmuh-nak","syll":"ao · lmah · nae · k","ety":["Arabic *al-manākh* = the calendar, the weather ← *manākh* = climate, place of kneeling","Annual calendar with astronomical and meteorological data. *Al-manākh* → Latin *almanach* → English. *Almanac* preserves the Arabic article (*al-*) and the climate-calendar root. A-L-M-A-N-A-C."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Find the Arabic *al-* prefix in 10 English science words and explain what the *al-* represents in each.","trace":"Research three Arabic star names: *Aldebaran, Altair, Betelgeuse, Algol, Rigel, Achernar*. What does each mean in Arabic? Which constellation is each in?","build":"The word *chemistry* developed from *alchemy* by dropping the Arabic article *al-*. Find one other English word where the Arabic *al-* was eventually dropped in standard scientific usage."}},{"id":"L82","n":82,"unit":9,"title":"Sanskrit's Gifts — From Juggernaut to Yoga","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"Sanskrit gave English two layers: everyday colonial words (bungalow, thug, loot) and philosophical-spiritual vocabulary (karma, yoga, avatar) — each representing a different type of cultural contact.","story":"Layer 1 — Colonial contact (18th–20th c.): *shampoo* (← Hindi *cāmpo* = press/massage), *bungalow* (← Hindi *bāṃglā* = Bengali-style house), *loot* (← Hindi *lūṭ* = plunder), *thug* (← Hindi *thag* = swindler), *jungle* (← Hindi *jangal* = forest), *pundit* (← Sanskrit *paṇḍita* = learned person). Layer 2 — Spiritual/scholarly translation (19th–20th c.): *karma* (Sanskrit *karman* = action/consequence), *nirvana* (Sanskrit *nirvāṇa* = blowing out), *yoga* (Sanskrit *yoga* = union/yoking), *avatar* (Sanskrit *avatāra* = divine descent), *guru* (Sanskrit *guru* = heavy/weighty = a revered teacher).","pattern":"Sanskrit phonological signal in English loanwords: clean CV (consonant-vowel) syllable structure, frequent final *-a* (Sanskrit grammatical ending → /uh/ in English), often 3+ syllables with even stress. *karma* = kar·ma, *avatar* = av·a·tar, *nirvana* = nir·va·na. The final *-a* = Sanskrit grammatical marker → English pronunciation /uh/.","connection":"Sanskrit loanwords reveal two types of cultural contact: colonial (practical words) and scholarly/spiritual (philosophical concepts). Both paths are visible in the vocabulary simultaneously.","words":[{"w":"JUGGERNAUT","pron":"JUH-ger-nawt","syll":"jhah · ger · nao · t","ety":["Sanskrit *Jagannātha* = Lord of the Universe ← *jagat* (world) + *nātha* (lord)","A Hindu deity's enormous temple cart was exaggerated by travelers. By the 1800s: any unstoppable crushing force. A divine name → English secular metaphor for overwhelming force. J-U-G-G-E-R-N-A-U-T: *Jagannātha* Anglicized into 3 syllables."]},{"w":"KARMA","pron":"KAH-rmuh","syll":"kaa · rmah","ety":["Sanskrit *karma* = action, deed ← *kṛ* = to do, to make","Action = its consequence. Sanskrit *kṛ* = to do → *karma* (the action and its return). Hindu/Buddhist moral cause-and-effect. In English: adopted as philosophical concept AND trivializaed in pop culture. K-A-R-M-A."]},{"w":"AVATAR","pron":"A-vuh-tahr","syll":"ae · vah · taa · r","ety":["Sanskrit *avatāra* = descent of a god ← *ava-* (down) + *tarati* (crosses over)","A god descending from heaven into physical form. In 21st century English: a digital representation of a person. The metaphor transferred perfectly: a digital persona = a \"descent\" of the real person into virtual space. Sanskrit theology → English digital culture in 30 years."]},{"w":"YOGA","pron":"YOH-guh","syll":"yow · gah","ety":["Sanskrit *yoga* = union, connection ← *yuj* = to yoke, join","*Yuj* = yoke/join → the same PIE root as English *yoke* (OE *geoc*) and Latin *jugum* (→ *conjugal, subjugate*). Sanskrit *yoga* and Latin *jugum* are PIE cognates: the same ancient root for \"joining\" through two paths separated for 6,000 years."]},{"w":"PUNDIT","pron":"PUH-nduht","syll":"pah · ndah · t","ety":["Sanskrit *paṇḍita* = learned person, scholar ← *paṇḍā* = learning","A Hindu scholar of sacred texts → British colonial adviser → any expert commentator. Journey: Sanskrit sacred scholarship → colonial expert → television commentary. The word has traveled from sacred text-interpretation to cable news without losing the \"expert\" meaning."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Classify each as colonial contact or spiritual/scholarly: *shampoo, karma, bungalow, nirvana, juggernaut, yoga, loot, dharma, pundit, avatar*.","trace":"Sanskrit *yuj* (yoke/join) and Latin *jugum* (yoke) are PIE cognates. Find all English words from each path: *yoga* from Sanskrit vs *jugal, conjugal, subjugate, conjugate* from Latin.","build":"Research the three waves of Sanskrit vocabulary entering English: (1) colonial administration, (2) scholarly text translations (19th c.), (3) 1960s-70s Eastern spirituality movement. Give 5 examples from each wave."}},{"id":"L83","n":83,"unit":9,"title":"Japanese Loanwords — Structure and Signals","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"Japanese gave English 498 words in the 129K database — primarily through three waves: martial arts/culture vocabulary, consumer technology, and food/aesthetic culture.","story":"Japanese entered English through three specific contact waves: (1) Trade/diplomatic contact (17th–20th c.): *kimono, geisha, samurai, shogun, haiku, origami*. (2) Post-WWII US occupation and consumer exports (1950s–1980s): *karate, judo, sushi, tempura, ramen, anime, manga, karaoke*. (3) Technology/gaming culture (1980s–present): *emoji, kawaii, otaku, tsunami, futon*. Japanese gave English the word *emoji* (picture character) which is now one of the most globally used words in any language.","pattern":"Japanese phonological pattern in English loanwords: (1) Clean CV (consonant-vowel) syllable structure with almost no consonant clusters: *ka-ra-te, su-shi, o-ri-ga-mi*. (2) Final vowel *-i* or *-u*: *sushi, tofu, sake, anime, karate*. (3) Often 3+ even syllables. (4) Common vowel sequences *-ai-, -ui-, -ou-*: *haiku, tsunami, shogun*. The clean syllable structure is the most reliable Japanese signal.","connection":"Japanese loanwords cluster in specific cultural domains — martial arts, food, technology, aesthetics — each representing a wave of Japanese cultural influence on English-speaking countries.","words":[{"w":"KARATE","pron":"k-ur-AH-t-ee","syll":"karate","ety":["Japanese *karate* = empty hand ← *kara* (empty) + *te* (hand)","Empty-handed fighting = no weapons. K-A-R-A-T-E: clean Japanese CV syllable structure throughout. *Kara* = empty; *te* = hand (same *te* in *judo* roots and other martial arts terms). Entered English after WWII through US occupation of Japan → American martial arts popularization."]},{"w":"TSUNAMI","pron":"tsoo-NAH-mee","syll":"tsuw · naa · miy","ety":["Japanese *tsunami* ← *tsu* (harbor) + *nami* (wave) = harbor wave","A wave that comes into harbors with catastrophic force. T-S-U-N-A-M-I: the *ts-* cluster at start is Japanese (unusual for English). *Nami* = wave. Until 2004, English media often used \"tidal wave\" (incorrect — not tidal). After the 2004 Indian Ocean tsunami, *tsunami* replaced \"tidal wave\" globally."]},{"w":"EMOJI","pron":"—","syll":"emoji","ety":["Japanese *e* (picture) + *moji* (character) = picture character","A Japanese compound word: visual symbol for digital communication. E-M-O-J-I: four clean Japanese syllables. *Moji* = character → *mojibake* (garbled characters from wrong encoding). One of the fastest-adopted loanwords in history: coined 1997 in Japan, globally standard by 2010."]},{"w":"KARAOKE","pron":"keh-ree-OH-kee","syll":"keh · riy · ow · kiy","ety":["Japanese *kara* (empty) + *ōke* = *ōkesutora* (orchestra) = empty orchestra","Empty orchestra = singing with a recorded backing track, no live musicians. Same *kara* (empty) as in *karate*. K-A-R-A-O-K-E: the *-oke* = compressed *ōkesutora* (orchestra, itself borrowed from English). A loanword containing a borrowing from English: Japanese borrowed \"orchestra\" → English borrowed the compound back."]},{"w":"FUTON","pron":"FOO-tah-n","syll":"fuw · taa · n","ety":["Japanese *futon* ← *fu* (bed mat) + *ton* (round/rolled) = rolled bed mat","A folding mattress that can serve as bed or sofa. F-U-T-O-N: two clean Japanese syllables. Entered English through import of the sleeping style from Japan in the 1970s-80s. Now: any flat sofa-bed regardless of origin."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Find 5 English words from each Japanese wave: (1) traditional culture, (2) post-WWII export culture, (3) digital/technology culture.","trace":"The word *karaoke* contains an English word (*orchestra*) borrowed into Japanese and then borrowed back. Find 2 more English words that contain a Japanese borrowing from English.","build":"Research: after the 2004 Indian Ocean tsunami, *tsunami* replaced \"tidal wave\" in global English media within months. What does this rapid adoption tell you about how catastrophic events drive vocabulary adoption?"}},{"id":"L84","n":84,"unit":9,"title":"Hebrew and Yiddish — Sacred Texts and Street Language","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"Hebrew gave English sacred vocabulary through Bible translations; Yiddish gave English informal expressive vocabulary through immigrant communities — two very different types of cultural contribution from two related languages.","story":"Hebrew entered English through: (1) Biblical translations — the King James Bible (1611) introduced *amen, hallelujah, sabbath, cherub, seraph, jubilee, leviathan, messiah*. (2) Cultural/religious terms: *kibbutz, kosher*. Yiddish (a Germanic language written in Hebrew script) gave American English a rich informal layer through immigrant communities: *chutzpah* (audacity), *schlep* (to drag), *schmaltz* (excessive sentimentality), *kibitz* (give unsolicited advice), *kvetch* (complain), *schmooze* (chat for social advantage), *shtick* (habitual routine).","pattern":"Hebrew and Yiddish spelling signals: (1) *-ah* endings: *hallelujah, chutzpah* (the *-ah* = Hebrew feminine/exclamatory ending). (2) *sch-* = /sh/ in Yiddish words: *schmaltz, schlep, schmuck, shtick*. Distinguish: Yiddish *sch-* = /sh/ vs Greek *sch-* words which don't exist (Greek has *sc-* but differently). (3) Unusual vowel clusters: *kvetch* (*kv-* at start), *chutzpah* (*ch* = /kh/ guttural).","connection":"Hebrew and Yiddish fill two different gaps in English: Hebrew provides the language of the ancient sacred; Yiddish provides urban immigrant expressiveness. Both layers are irreplaceable.","words":[{"w":"JUBILEE","pron":"JOO-buh-lee","syll":"jhuw · bah · liy","ety":["Hebrew *yōbhēl* = ram's horn, sounded to announce the jubilee year","Every 50 years in the Hebrew Bible: slaves freed, debts cancelled (announced by the ram's horn *yōbhēl*). Latin *iubilaeus* → English *jubilee* = a 50th anniversary celebration. The sacred horn-blast became a secular party. The radical economic justice content was replaced by festive celebration."]},{"w":"AMEN","pron":"ay-MEHN","syll":"ey · meh · n","ety":["Hebrew *ʾāmēn* = so be it, truly ← *ʾāman* = to confirm, to be faithful","One of the oldest words in continuous use. Hebrew *ʾāmēn* was kept untranslated in Greek, Latin, and all Christian languages worldwide. A-M-E-N: said in churches, mosques, and synagogues in virtually unchanged form for 3,000+ years. The most linguistically stable religious term in Western tradition."]},{"w":"CHUTZPAH","pron":"CHUH-tspah","syll":"chah · tspaa","ety":["Yiddish *khutspe* ← Hebrew *ḥuṣpāh* = insolence, audacity","Brazen nerve. Entered American English through Jewish immigrant communities, spread through entertainment/comedy. C-H-U-T-Z-P-A-H: the *ch* = /kh/ guttural (unusual in English), final *-ah* = Hebrew/Yiddish ending. Has no perfect English equivalent — which is why it was borrowed."]},{"w":"SCHMALTZ","pron":"SHMAHLTS","syll":"shmaa · lts","ety":["Yiddish *shmalts* = rendered fat ← German *Schmalz* = lard","Originally: rendered chicken fat. Extended: excessive sentimentality = greasy with emotion. S-C-H-M-A-L-T-Z: *sch-* = /sh/ (Yiddish/German signal), final *-tz* = /ts/ (German/Yiddish cluster). The culinary fat metaphor → emotional excess. *Schmaltzy* = overly sentimental."]},{"w":"KIBITZ","pron":"KIB-its","syll":"ki · bitz","ety":["Yiddish *kibitsn* = to give unsolicited advice ← German *Kiebitz* = lapwing (peewit bird)","The lapwing bird was proverbially associated with interfering and giving unwanted opinions. *Kibitz* = to look on and offer unwanted commentary. K-I-B-I-T-Z: the *-itz* = /its/ = Yiddish/German cluster. Also: *kibitzer* = one who kibitzes = a busybody."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Find 10 Hebrew-origin words and group them: (1) entered through Bible translations, (2) entered through religious practice, (3) entered as cultural/everyday terms.","trace":"Yiddish entered American English primarily through entertainment: vaudeville, radio comedy, early Hollywood. Research 5 Yiddish words that spread through entertainment (*shtick, schlock, schmooze, spiel, nosh*).","build":"The word *amen* has been used in unchanged form for 3,000 years across Hebrew, Greek, Latin, Arabic, and all European languages. What does this extraordinary persistence tell you about the relationship between sacred vocabulary and linguistic change?"}},{"id":"L85","n":85,"unit":9,"title":"African Languages in English — Safari, Zombie, and Jazz","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"The 129K database shows vocabulary from Swahili, Wolof, Mandinka, Twi, and other African languages — primarily entering English through the slave trade, colonialism, and cultural exchange.","story":"African languages gave English vocabulary through painful and complex historical pathways: (1) Transatlantic slave trade (17th–19th c.): *jazz* (disputed — possibly West African origin), *juke* (possibly Wolof *dzug* = to live wickedly → *jukebox*), *okra* (Igbo *okwuru/okwulu*), *yam* (Wolof *nyam* = to taste, eat), *voodoo* (Ewe/Fon *vodu* = spirit, deity). (2) East African/colonial contact: *safari* (Swahili/Arabic *safar* = journey), *zombie* (Kongo *nzambi* = god/spirit), *banana* (possibly Wolof *banana*), *bongo* (possibly Bantu).","pattern":"African language signals in English loanwords: (1) Final *-a*: *okra, samba, bongo, tilapia*. (2) Initial vowel: *okra, ebony* (← Greek *ebenos* ← Egyptian/Semitic *hbny*, so technically not direct from African but early borrowing). (3) Repeated syllables: *voodoo* (Ewe *vodu*). (4) Unusual consonant combinations for English: *jazz* (possible West African phoneme).","connection":"African-language vocabulary in English is often historically painful in its pathway — many words entered through the slave trade and colonial exploitation. Understanding their origins requires acknowledging the full history of how English acquired them.","words":[{"w":"SAFARI","pron":"suh-FAH-ree","syll":"sah · faa · riy","ety":["Swahili *safari* = journey ← Arabic *safar* = travel, journey","An organized journey to observe/hunt wildlife. S-A-F-A-R-I: the Swahili word borrowed from Arabic *safar* = travel. Swahili is a Bantu language with heavy Arabic influence (due to East African trade routes). *Safari* entered English through British East Africa (Kenya/Tanzania). Now: any wildlife-viewing expedition."]},{"w":"ZOMBIE","pron":"ZAH-mbee","syll":"zaa · mbiy","ety":["Haitian Creole *zombi* ← Bantu *nzambi* = god, spirit (in Kongo/Bantu religions)","A spirit or a body reanimated without consciousness. K-O-N-G-O *nzambi* → Haitian Creole *zombi* → English *zombie* through Caribbean colonial contact. Now: a cultural icon in horror fiction, film, and metaphor (zombie companies = companies kept alive artificially)."]},{"w":"VOODOO","pron":"VOO-doo","syll":"vuw · duw","ety":["Louisiana Creole ← Haitian Creole *voudou* ← Fon/Ewe *vodu* = spirit, deity","A West African religion of the Fon and Ewe peoples, practiced in the Caribbean and Americas by enslaved Africans. V-O-O-D-O-O: the doubled *-oo-* = English rendering of Haitian *-ou-*. In English: often distorted to mean any mysterious/sinister magic, erasing its religious origins."]},{"w":"OKRA","pron":"OH-kruh","syll":"ow · krah","ety":["Twi *nkruma* or Igbo *okwuru* = the plant","The edible seed pod. O-K-R-A: one of the clearest direct African-language borrowings in English. Entered through transatlantic slave trade — enslaved Africans brought the plant (and its name) to the Americas. *Gumbo* (another word for okra) comes from Umbundu *ki-ngombo*."]},{"w":"JAZZ","pron":"JAZ","syll":"jhae · z","ety":["Origin disputed — possibly West African origin, possibly American slang","J-A-Z-Z: the most contested etymology in American English. Possible West African origin (*jazzi* = speeded up?); possible American slang origin. The word appeared in California newspapers around 1912 for energetic music/dance. Whatever its true origin, it became America's most globally influential music-genre word."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Research the full history of how each word entered English: *safari, zombie, voodoo, okra, jazz*. What does the pathway reveal about the historical relationship between English-speaking cultures and Africa?","trace":"Find 5 more African-language loans in English: *banana, bongo, chimpanzee, goober* (peanut, from Kikongo *nguba*), *mamba*. Confirm the African language of origin for each.","build":"The word *voodoo* is often used in English to mean any mysterious/dark magic, erasing its identity as a specific West African religion. Research: how does this linguistic distortion reflect broader patterns in how colonizing languages treat vocabulary from colonized cultures?"}},{"id":"L86","n":86,"unit":9,"title":"Native American Words — Chocolate, Tobacco, and the Americas","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"Native American languages gave English the vocabulary of an entire hemisphere — the animals, plants, foods, and geographical features of the Americas that European languages had no words for.","story":"Native American vocabulary entered English primarily through Spanish as the first European colonizing language in the Americas. The pipeline: Nahuatl (Aztec Mexico) → Spanish → English (*chocolate, tomato, potato, avocado, chili, guacamole, mesquite, coyote*). Taino (Caribbean) → Spanish → English (*hurricane, canoe, tobacco, barbecue, hammock, iguana, manatee*). Algonquian (North America) → English (*raccoon, skunk, moose, squash, pecan, moccasin, tomahawk, wigwam*). Quechua (Peru/Andes) → Spanish → English (*potato, llama, condor, guano, puma, quinine, coca, quinoa*).","pattern":"Nahuatl words often preserve the Nahuatl *-tl* or *-te* ending adapted to Spanish phonology: *tomato* (← *tomatl*), *avocado* (← *ahuacatl*), *chocolate* (← *xocolatl*), *chili* (← *chilli*). Algonquian words often end in *-ook* or *-ook* sounds: *raccoon* (← Algonquian *aroughcun*), *squash* (← Narragansett *askutasquash*).","connection":"Native American vocabulary tells the history of European contact with the Americas: every borrowed word identifies a plant, animal, food, or phenomenon that was new to European languages and had to be named using indigenous terms.","words":[{"w":"CHOCOLATE","pron":"CHAW-kluht","syll":"chao · klah · t","ety":["Nahuatl *xocolatl* ← *xococ* (bitter) + *atl* (water) = bitter water","The Aztec drink was unsweetened and spiced. Spanish colonizers encountered it in the 1520s. *Xocolatl* → Spanish *chocolate* → English. C-H-O-C-O-L-A-T-E: the *-tl* Nahuatl ending was simplified. Today's sweet chocolate = completely different from the bitter Aztec *xocolatl*."]},{"w":"AVOCADO","pron":"a-vuh-KAH-doh","syll":"ae · vah · kaa · dow","ety":["Nahuatl *ahuacatl* = avocado (also: testicle — the fruit's shape)","*Ahuacatl* → Spanish *aguacate* → English *avocado* (via a Spanish folk-etymology reshaping to resemble *abogado* = lawyer). A-V-O-C-A-D-O: the Nahuatl body-metaphor name was sanitized through Spanish before reaching English."]},{"w":"HURRICANE","pron":"HUR-uh-kayn","syll":"hher · ah · key · n","ety":["Taino *hurakán* → Spanish *huracán* → English","The Taino people of the Caribbean named the storms after their storm deity Huracán. Spanish colonizers adopted the word. English borrowed it from Spanish. A Caribbean deity's name became an international meteorological term. H-U-R-R-I-C-A-N-E: double *r* from Spanish phonology."]},{"w":"RACCOON","pron":"r-a-k-OO-n","syll":"raccoon","ety":["Algonquian *aroughcun* = the one who rubs/scratches its hands","The Algonquian word described the animal's behavior of rubbing its hands. R-A-C-C-O-O-N: double *c* and double *o* from the Anglicization of the Algonquian sound. Entered English through direct North American colonial contact (not via Spanish)."]},{"w":"TOBACCO","pron":"tuh-BAK-oh","syll":"tobacco","ety":["Taino *tabako* = a roll of tobacco leaves (or the pipe used to smoke them)","The plant and its product. T-A-B-A-C-C-O: double *c* from Spanish adaptation of Taino *tabako*. Spanish *tabaco* → English *tobacco*. The Taino word may have referred to the pipe or the leaf-roll — both were new objects with indigenous names that European languages borrowed wholesale."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Find 5 English words from each: Nahuatl (via Spanish), Taino (via Spanish), Algonquian (direct), Quechua (via Spanish). What categories of things needed naming in each case?","trace":"The word *avocado* was sanitized from Nahuatl *ahuacatl* (which meant both the fruit and testicle, referring to the fruit's shape) through Spanish folk etymology. Research 2 more cases where a Native American word's original meaning was altered in the borrowing process.","build":"Research: which 10 English food words came from Nahuatl (Aztec language)? What does this tell you about the dietary influence of Aztec Mexico on global cuisine after 1519?"}},{"id":"L87","n":87,"unit":9,"title":"Malay, Chinese, and Southeast Asian Words","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"The sea trade routes of Southeast Asia — the Spice Routes — brought Malay, Chinese, and other Southeast Asian words into English through Dutch and Portuguese colonial contact.","story":"Malay gave English 235 words in the 129K database — primarily through Dutch colonial contact in the East Indies (modern Indonesia/Malaysia). The pipeline: Malay → Dutch → English. Key Malay loans: *bamboo, gingham, rattan, orangutan, sarong, batik, kapok, amok* (*amuk* = to go into a murderous frenzy), *ketchup* (*kicap* = fish brine). Chinese gave English few words directly (*tea, ketchup, typhoon* — see L59) but gave English indirectly through Malay and pidgin trade languages. *Gong, typhoon, kowtow, yen* (desire, from Japanese but related Chinese roots).","pattern":"Malay words in English often have: clean syllable structure (Malay is an agglutinative language with simple syllables), final vowel patterns, and often entered English through Dutch phonology (which modified some sounds). The *amok* in \"run amok\" = Malay *amuk* = to attack in a murderous frenzy, a culturally specific behavior first documented by European traders in Malay states.","connection":"Malay and Chinese vocabulary entered English through the specific historical pathway of Dutch and Portuguese colonial trade in Southeast Asia. The words cluster in trade domains: materials, animals, behaviors observed in the Malay world.","words":[{"w":"BAMBOO","pron":"ba-MBOO","syll":"bae · mbuw","ety":["Malay *bambu* ← possibly Kannada/Telugu *bambu*","The grass with woody stems. B-A-M-B-O-O: the *-oo* = Dutch/English rendering of Malay *-u*. *Bambu* → Dutch *bamboes* → English *bamboo*. A Southeast Asian plant name traveled through Dutch colonial administration before reaching English."]},{"w":"ORANGUTAN","pron":"aw-RA-nguh-tan","syll":"ao · rae · ngah · tae · n","ety":["Malay *orang* (person) + *utan* (forest) = person of the forest","O-R-A-N-G-U-T-A-N: clean Malay syllable structure. Malay *orang utan* = forest person. Entered English through Dutch colonial naturalists describing the animal. Now often misspelled *orangutang* (adding a *-g* not in the Malay original)."]},{"w":"AMOK","pron":"uh-MUHK","syll":"ah · mah · k","ety":["Malay *amuk* = to attack in a murderous frenzy — a culturally specific behavior","To \"run amok\" = to charge murderously at random targets. A-M-O-K: entered English through Portuguese and Dutch travelers describing a specific cultural behavior. The phrase \"run amok\" preserves the original Malay running/charging sense."]},{"w":"RATTAN","pron":"ra-TAN","syll":"rae · tae · n","ety":["Malay *rotan* = the climbing palm plant","The material used in wicker furniture. R-A-T-T-A-N: double *t* from English phonological adaptation of Malay *rotan* (single *t*). Entered English through Dutch East Indies trade. Now: any furniture made from the palm's stems."]},{"w":"GINGHAM","pron":"GIH-nguhm","syll":"gih · ngah · m","ety":["Malay *genggang* = striped ← *genggang* = apart/separated","A striped cotton cloth. G-I-N-G-H-A-M: Malay *genggang* → Dutch *gingang* → English *gingham*. The striped pattern was described by its Malay name. One of the more surprising Malay loans — a common fabric word comes from Malay via Dutch."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Find 5 more Malay loans in English: *sarong, batik, kapok, ketchup* (via Malay), *gecko* (← Malay *gekuk*). Confirm Malay origin.","trace":"Research how *ketchup* traveled from Chinese fish sauce (*kê-tsiap*) through Malay (*kicap*) to English, then was transformed into tomato-based ketchup by American manufacturers. What does this journey reveal about how food words change with the food itself?","build":"The word *orangutan* is often spelled *orangutang* — with a *-g* not in the original Malay. Research why this happens. What linguistic process causes people to add consonants to words borrowed from languages with clean syllable structures?"}},{"id":"L88","n":88,"unit":9,"title":"Russian, Turkish, and Central Asian Words","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"Russian gave English 347 words — primarily Cold War political vocabulary and scientific terms. Turkish gave English trade vocabulary from the Ottoman Empire. Together they represent the Eastern European and Central Asian vocabulary layer.","story":"Russian entered English in two waves: (1) Pre-revolutionary cultural vocabulary (19th–early 20th c.): *tsar/czar, vodka, troika, samovar, steppe, tundra, borscht, blini*. (2) Cold War and Soviet science vocabulary (1957–1991): *sputnik, cosmonaut, glasnost, perestroika, gulag, bolshevik*. Turkish gave English Ottoman-era trade vocabulary: *coffee* (← Turkish *kahve* ← Arabic *qahwa*), *kiosk* (← Turkish *köşk* = pavilion), *horde* (← Turkish *ordu* = army camp), *yogurt* (← Turkish *yoğurt*), *divan* (← Turkish ← Persian), *ottoman* (← Turkish *Osmanlı* = Ottoman = the empire's name).","pattern":"Russian words in English: often end in *-a/-ia* (Slavic endings: *vodka, troika, steppe, tundra*) or in *-ist/-nik* (*bolshevist, sputnik*). Turkish words: often have *-k* or *-t* endings adapted to English (*kiosk, yogurt, ottoman*) and frequently traveled through French before reaching English (*divan, ottoman, kiosk*).","connection":"Russian and Turkish vocabulary entered English through very specific historical events: Cold War politics (Russian) and Ottoman trade routes (Turkish). These words cluster in their domains of origin.","words":[{"w":"SPUTNIK","pron":"SPUH-tnihk","syll":"spah · tnih · k","ety":["Russian *sputnik* = companion, fellow traveler ← *s-* (with) + *put'* (path) + *-nik* (agent)","S-P-U-T-N-I-K: entered English on October 4, 1957, when the Soviet Union launched the first satellite. The Russian *-nik* suffix became productive in American English: *beatnik* (1958 = a \"beat\" person, *-nik* from Sputnik), later *peacenik, no-goodnik*. One word launched a suffix."]},{"w":"GLASNOST","pron":"GLA-snah-st","syll":"glae · snaa · st","ety":["Russian *glasnost'* = openness, transparency ← *glas* = voice","G-L-A-S-N-O-S-T: Mikhail Gorbachev's 1985 policy of political openness. *Glas* = voice → *glasnost* = voicedness = openness/transparency. Entered English as a direct borrowing during the Cold War thaw. The Russian word for \"voice\" became the English term for a Soviet political program."]},{"w":"GULAG","pron":"GYOO-la-g","syll":"gyuw · lae · g","ety":["Russian acronym: *Glav-noye Uprav-leniye Lag-erei* = Chief Administration of Camps","G-U-L-A-G: a Soviet-era acronym for the system of forced labor camps. Entered English through Alexander Solzhenitsyn's *The Gulag Archipelago* (1973). Now: any repressive prison system. Russian acronym → English metaphor for political imprisonment generally."]},{"w":"KIOSK","pron":"KEE-awsk","syll":"kiy · ao · sk","ety":["Turkish *köşk* = pavilion, summer house → French *kiosque* → English","Small booth or stand. K-I-O-S-K: Turkish → French *kiosque* → English *kiosk*. The Turkish word for a pavilion/summer house became the word for a small retail stand. Journey: Ottoman architecture term → French decorative pavilion → English newspaper stand."]},{"w":"YOGURT","pron":"YOH-gert","syll":"yow · ger · t","ety":["Turkish *yoğurt* = the fermented milk product","Y-O-G-U-R-T (or *yoghurt* in British English): Turkish *yoğurt* → English. The *gh* variant (*yoghurt*) = a spelling attempting to capture the Turkish *ğ* (a soft guttural). Turkish gave English several fermented/preserved food words: *kefir* (also Turkish/Caucasian), *ayran* (yogurt drink, rarely borrowed)."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Find 5 Russian words that entered English specifically during the Cold War (1947–1991) and 5 that entered before it. What categories do they represent?","trace":"The *-nik* suffix: *sputnik* launched the *-nik* suffix in American English (*beatnik, peacenik*). Research: is *-nik* still productive in English today? Find examples of words coined after 1970 using *-nik*.","build":"Research: Turkey gave English the word *ottoman* (both the furniture and the empire). How did a dynasty name become a type of cushioned seat? What does this tell you about how powerful empire names enter everyday vocabulary?"}},{"id":"L89","n":89,"unit":9,"title":"Scandinavian and Celtic Languages","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"Beyond the major Norse impact covered in Units 1 and 5, Scandinavian languages (Swedish, Norwegian, Danish) and Celtic languages (Welsh, Irish, Scottish Gaelic) gave English a distinctive specialized vocabulary.","story":"Modern Scandinavian (post-Viking, 17th–21st c.) gave English: *ombudsman* (Swedish *ombudsman* = a commissioner/representative), *smorgasbord* (Swedish *smörgåsbord* = open-sandwich table = a spread of varied items), *ski* (Norwegian *ski* = a split piece of wood), *slalom* (Norwegian *slalåm* = sloping track), *fjord* (Norwegian *fjord* = a narrow sea inlet), *troll* (Norwegian/Swedish *troll* = a supernatural creature). Celtic languages gave English: *bard* (Welsh/Old Irish *bard* = a poet), *galore* (Irish Gaelic *go leor* = in plenty), *whiskey/whisky* (Scottish/Irish Gaelic *uisge beatha* = water of life = *aqua vitae*), *bog* (Irish *bogach* = soft ground), *hooligan* (possibly Irish surname), *gimmick* (possibly Scottish).","pattern":"Scandinavian signals in English: (1) *sk-* cluster (shared with Norse: *ski, skål, skerry*). (2) Long compound words: *smorgasbord, ombudsman*. Celtic signals: (1) *-gan/-gale* endings from Irish: *slogan* (← Gaelic *sluaghghairm* = army-cry), *galore* (← *go leor*). (2) The *-ck/-gh* patterns in Gaelic borrowings.","connection":"Scandinavian and Celtic languages gave English specialized vocabulary in governance (*ombudsman*), culture (*smorgasbord*), sports (*ski, slalom*), and geography (*fjord, bog*) — each word a record of specific cultural contact.","words":[{"w":"OMBUDSMAN","pron":"AH-mbuh-dzmuhn","syll":"aa · mbah · dzmah · n","ety":["Swedish *ombudsman* ← *om* (about) + *bud* (bidding/message) + *man*","An official who investigates citizens' complaints against institutions. O-M-B-U-D-S-M-A-N: Swedish compound with *-s-* genitive connector. Entered English through Scandinavian governance model in the 1960s. Now: any independent complaints investigator. The Swedish government concept became a global institutional term."]},{"w":"SMORGASBORD","pron":"SMAW-rguh-sbawrd","syll":"smor · gas · bord","ety":["Swedish *smörgåsbord* = open-sandwich table ← *smörgas* (bread+butter) + *bord* (table)","A table spread with varied dishes. S-M-O-R-G-A-S-B-O-R-D: Swedish phonology compressed into English spelling. Metaphorical broadening: any varied selection of things. \"A smorgasbord of options\" = a rich variety. The specific Swedish open-sandwich buffet → general English metaphor for variety."]},{"w":"WHISKEY","pron":"WIH-skee","syll":"wih · skiy","ety":["Irish/Scottish Gaelic *uisge beatha* = water of life ← *uisge* (water) + *beatha* (life)","W-H-I-S-K-E-Y (Irish/American spelling) vs W-H-I-S-K-Y (Scotch/British spelling). *Uisge beatha* = Gaelic equivalent of Latin *aqua vitae* (water of life). The Gaelic *uisge* = water (same PIE root as *water*, via Celtic path). The \"life\" metaphor for strong spirits appears across multiple languages."]},{"w":"SLOGAN","pron":"SLOH-guhn","syll":"slow · gah · n","ety":["Scottish Gaelic *sluaghghairm* = army cry ← *sluagh* (army) + *gairm* (cry/call)","An army battle cry → an advertising catchphrase. S-L-O-G-A-N: the compressed Anglicization of *sluaghghairm*. *Sluagh* = army (army-cry → motto → advertising slogan). The Scottish Highland battle cry became the modern advertising industry's most important concept."]},{"w":"GALORE","pron":"guh-LAWR","syll":"gah · lao · r","ety":["Irish Gaelic *go leor* = in plenty, in sufficient amount","Plentifully, in abundance. G-A-L-O-R-E: *go leor* = to sufficiency. Used as a postpositive adjective: \"whiskey galore\" (not \"galore whiskey\"). The Irish Gaelic phrase meaning \"in sufficient amount\" became the English word for \"in great abundance.\" *Whisky Galore!* = the 1949 film title uses it perfectly."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Find 5 modern Scandinavian (post-Viking) loans in English: *ombudsman, smorgasbord, ski, slalom, fjord, troll, kraken, lemming*. What domains do they represent?","trace":"The word *whiskey/whisky* spelling: Irish/American use *-ey*; Scotch/British use *-y*. Research: is there an etymological reason for this split, or is it purely conventional?","build":"Research: the *slogan* traveled from Scottish Highland battle-cry to advertising catchphrase. What other words for \"battle cry\" or \"motto\" are used in advertising today? Are any from Celtic languages?"}},{"id":"L90","n":90,"unit":9,"title":"Persian, Turkish, and the Ottoman Legacy","diff":"hard","bigIdea":"Persian (Farsi) gave English a surprisingly rich vocabulary through poetry, trade, and Ottoman Turkish mediation — creating an unexpected layer of words often unrecognized as Persian in origin.","story":"Persian entered English through three channels: (1) Direct scholarly contact with Persian poetry and philosophy (19th c.): *paradise, divan* (a type of couch/council), *caravan, bazaar, shawl, jasmine, lemon, orange, chess* (Persian *chatrang* → Arabic *shatranj* → English). (2) Via Turkish (Ottoman Empire mediation): many Persian words traveled through Turkish before reaching European languages. (3) Via Arabic (Persian words absorbed into Arabic, then into European languages): *alcohol, elixir, hazard* (← Arabic ← Persian). The corpus shows 114 Persian-origin words — small but including some very common English words.","pattern":"Persian words in English often have: (1) The *-an/-ane* ending: *caravan, turban, divan, afghan, sedan*. (2) The *-ar/-aar* pattern: *bazaar, lascar*. (3) Names of colorful/luxurious goods: *azure, lilac, jasmine, shawl* — Persian was the language of luxury trade on the Silk Road. (4) Some chess terms: *checkmate* (← Persian *shāh māt* = the king is dead).","connection":"Persian vocabulary represents the luxury trade language of the medieval Silk Road — the language through which Chinese goods, Indian spices, and Middle Eastern products were described to European buyers.","words":[{"w":"PARADISE","pron":"PEH-ruh-deyes","syll":"peh · rah · day · s","ety":["Old Persian *pairi-daeza* = walled garden ← *pairi-* (around) + *daeza* (wall)","A walled royal garden → Greek *paradeisos* → Latin *paradisus* (Garden of Eden) → French *paradis* → English. A Persian royal garden wall became Christian heaven. P-A-R-A-D-I-S-E: 5-stop word journey over 2,500 years."]},{"w":"CARAVAN","pron":"KA-ruh-van","syll":"car · a · van","ety":["Persian *kārvān* = a company of travelers → Italian → French → English","A company of travelers crossing desert/steppe for safety → any convoy → a camping trailer. The Persian *kārvān* traveled through Italian *carovana* and French *caravane* before reaching English. A Persian trade convoy → a British camping holiday vehicle."]},{"w":"CHECKMATE","pron":"CHEH-kmayt","syll":"cheh · kmey · t","ety":["Persian *shāh māt* = the king is dead ← *shāh* (king) + *māt* (dead/helpless)","The decisive chess move. *Shāh* (king) = also gives English *chess* (the game of the king) and the title *Shah*. *Māt* (helpless/dead) → *checkmate* (king is helpless). *Check* itself (a position where the king is threatened) = Persian *shāh* → Arabic *shāh* → French *échec* → English *check*. Chess vocabulary is almost entirely Persian via Arabic."]},{"w":"AZURE","pron":"A-zher","syll":"ae · zher","ety":["Old Persian *lāzhward* = the color of lapis lazuli (from Lāzhward, a place in Central Asia)","Sky blue. A-Z-U-R-E: *lāzhward* → Arabic *lāzaward* → Old French *azur* (the initial *l* was mistaken for the Arabic article *al-* and dropped) → English *azure*. The color blue is named after a place in Afghanistan (Sar-e-Sang = Lāzhward) where lapis lazuli was mined."]},{"w":"BAZAAR","pron":"b-uh-z-AH-r","syll":"bazaar","ety":["Persian *bāzār* = a market ← Middle Persian *wāzār*","A market or shopping area. B-A-Z-A-A-R: double *a* = the Persian long *ā* phoneme. Persian *bāzār* → Turkish *pazar* → Italian/French *bazar* → English *bazaar*. The *-zaar* ending preserves the Persian long vowel. Now: any market or fundraising sale."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Find 5 more Persian loans in English: *shawl, jasmine, lilac, lemon, chess, divan, taffeta, khaki* (← Hindi *khākī* ← Persian *khāk* = dust). Confirm Persian origin.","trace":"The word *azure* lost its initial *l* because Arabic speakers mistook it for the Arabic article *al-* and dropped it. Find 2 more words where a similar misanalysis changed the word's form during borrowing.","build":"Chess vocabulary is almost entirely Persian via Arabic: *check, checkmate, chess, rook* (← Persian *rukh* = chariot), *bishop, queen* (adapted from Persian *vazīr* = minister). Research the Persian origins of chess pieces and how the game's names changed as it traveled westward."}},{"id":"L91","n":91,"unit":10,"title":"Portmanteau Words — When Words Mate","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"Portmanteau words (named by Lewis Carroll for a suitcase that opens into two halves) are new words created by blending the beginning of one word with the end of another. The result is more than a sum: it carries both meanings simultaneously.","story":"Lewis Carroll coined the term in *Through the Looking Glass* (1871): Humpty Dumpty explains to Alice that *slithy* = *slimy* + *lithe* — \"it's like a portmanteau — there are two meanings packed up into one word.\" Carroll invented *chortle* (*chuckle* + *snort*), *galumph* (*gallop* + *triumph*), *mimsy* (*miserable* + *flimsy*). The word *portmanteau* itself = French *porter* (carry) + *manteau* (coat) = a coat-carrying bag. Carroll's term for a linguistic blend is itself a French compound. The formal term in linguistics: \"lexical blend.\"","pattern":"Portmanteau construction rules: (1) Take the ONSET of word A (the beginning up to a natural phonological break). (2) Take the RHYME of word B (the end from a natural phonological break). (3) Join at a shared phoneme if possible: *brunch* = BR- from *breakfast* + -UNCH from *lunch* (shared phoneme: /n/). (4) The result must be pronounceable. (5) The result must suggest both source words simultaneously.","connection":"Portmanteau words reveal the fundamental creativity of English word formation — and the speed at which new words become standard. The seam between source words disappears as the blend becomes familiar.","words":[{"w":"BRUNCH","pron":"BRUHNCH","syll":"brah · nch","ety":["English *breakfast* + *lunch* — coined 1895, Hunter's Weekly","The first documented portmanteau in widespread English use. BR- from *breakfast* + -UNCH from *lunch*. The blend point falls at a natural syllable boundary. B-R-U-N-C-H. The portmanteau works because it sounds like both sources simultaneously."]},{"w":"SMOG","pron":"SMAHG","syll":"smaa · g","ety":["English *smoke* + *fog* — coined 1905 by Dr. Henry Antoine des Voeux","SM- from *smoke* + -OG from *fog*. Coined to describe London's industrial haze. S-M-O-G. The blend captures both sources: visible particulate matter (*smoke*) + atmospheric obscuration (*fog*). Now: any air pollution combining smoke and particulate matter."]},{"w":"PODCAST","pron":"—","syll":"podcast","ety":["English *iPod* + *broadcast* — coined 2004 by journalist Ben Hammersley","POD- from *iPod* + -CAST from *broadcast*. P-O-D-C-A-S-T. The *iPod* source is now obsolete technology, but the word outlived its trigger. Within 5 years *podcast* was so common people forgot the iPod connection — the portmanteau became transparent as the etymology was forgotten."]},{"w":"CHORTLE","pron":"CHAW-rtuhl","syll":"chor · tle","ety":["Lewis Carroll, *Through the Looking Glass* (1871): *chuckle* + *snort*","Invented in 1871, now fully standard in English. CHOR- from *chuckle* + -TLE from *snortle* (diminutive of snort). C-H-O-R-T-L-E. Carroll's coinage is now 150 years old and used without awareness of its literary origin. When a portmanteau becomes standard vocabulary, the seam disappears."]},{"w":"EMOJI","pron":"—","syll":"emoji","ety":["Japanese *e* (picture) + *moji* (character) = picture character","E-M-O-J-I: technically a Japanese compound borrowed into English, but functions like a portmanteau in English perception: *e-* (picture) + *-moji* (character). The fastest-globally-adopted word in the 21st century. A Japanese compound → English common noun in under 20 years."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Find the two source words in: *spork, frenemy, infomercial, emoticon, bromance, jeggings, motel, blog, pixel, glimmer* (if it's a portmanteau).","trace":"Lewis Carroll invented *chortle, galumph, mimsy, slithy, tulgey, wabe*. Which survived into common English? Which didn't? What explains the difference in survival?","build":"Create 5 original portmanteau words for modern concepts that don't yet have dedicated words. Show the blend point, define each, and explain why the blend works phonologically."}},{"id":"L92","n":92,"unit":10,"title":"Eponyms — People Who Became Words","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"Hundreds of English words come directly from people's names — real or legendary. These eponyms are unforgettable once you know the story, because the story and the spelling reinforce each other.","story":"Eponyms come in several types: (1) From real historical people: *boycott* (Captain Charles Boycott, land agent ostracized by Irish tenants in 1880), *sandwich* (John Montagu, 4th Earl of Sandwich, who ate meat between bread slices to avoid leaving the card table), *algorithm* (al-Khwarizmi, mathematician). (2) From mythological/legendary figures: *tantalize* (Tantalus), *narcissism* (Narcissus), *mercury* (the element, from the god Mercury, because mercury is quick-moving). (3) From literary characters: *quixotic* (Don Quixote), *machiavellian* (Niccolò Machiavelli). (4) From place names used as common nouns: *denim* (← *de Nîmes* = from Nîmes, France), *champagne* (the Champagne region of France).","pattern":"Eponym spelling: the person's name is usually retained, including its native-language capitalization pattern and spelling. *Boycott* (capitalized as proper noun → lowercase as common verb). *Machiavellian* (capitalized as adjective). *Quixotic* (capitalized). *Algorithm* (lowercase — the Latinization was early enough to lose the capital). The more recently the word was coined from the name, the more likely it retains capital-letter spelling conventions.","connection":"Eponyms are the most memorable etymologies because they connect words to specific human stories. Knowing the story guarantees you remember the spelling — the spelling is the fossil of the story.","words":[{"w":"BOYCOTT","pron":"BOY-kaht","syll":"boy · cott","ety":["After Captain Charles Boycott (1832–1897), Irish land agent ostracized in 1880","B-O-Y-C-O-T-T: the Captain's surname becomes a common verb/noun within months of the events. Irish Land League tenants refused to deal with him — the first organized economic boycott. The word entered English in 1880 and was globally adopted within years. Double *t* from the surname."]},{"w":"TANTALIZE","pron":"t-A-n-t-uh-l-ay-z","syll":"tantalize","ety":["Greek mythology: Tantalus, king punished in Hades by perpetual thwarting","T-A-N-T-A-L-I-Z-E. Tantalus reached for fruit and water that always receded. *Tantalize* = tease with something desired but unattainable. Also: the element *tantalum* was named for Tantalus (its compounds wouldn't dissolve in acid — \"tantalized\" by water). One myth → a common verb AND a chemical element."]},{"w":"QUIXOTIC","pron":"kwih-KSAH-tihk","syll":"kwih · ksaa · tih · k","ety":["After Don Quixote from Cervantes' novel (1605, 1615), Spanish *Quijote*","Q-U-I-X-O-T-I-C. Don Quixote was so lost in chivalric romances he fought windmills believing them giants. *Quixotic* = impractically idealistic, pursuing noble but unrealistic goals. The *-x-* in English *Quixote* reflects 17th-century Spanish spelling; modern Spanish spells it *Quijote*. The spelling froze in the earlier form."]},{"w":"MACHIAVELLIAN","pron":"mah-kee-uh-VEH-lee-uhn","syll":"ma · chi · a · vel · li · an","ety":["After Niccolò Machiavelli (1469–1527), Florentine political philosopher","M-A-C-H-I-A-V-E-L-L-I-A-N: double *l* from the Italian surname *Machiavelli*. *The Prince* (1513) described how rulers maintain power through cunning and pragmatism. His name became an adjective for political scheming without moral constraints. Keep the double-*l* from the Italian original."]},{"w":"DENIM","pron":"DEH-nuhm","syll":"deh · nah · m","ety":["From *de Nîmes* = of/from Nîmes, France — cloth made in Nîmes","D-E-N-I-M: the French *de Nîmes* (of Nîmes) contracted to *denim*. Nîmes, France was famous for its serge cloth (*serge de Nîmes* = serge of Nîmes = serge denim = denim). A place name became a fabric name. Similarly: *jeans* (← Genoa, Italy = *gênes* in French = the city where the cloth was made)."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Research the person behind each eponym and explain the connection to the modern meaning: *boycott, sandwich, cardigan* (the Earl of Cardigan at Balaclava), *wellington* (boot — the Duke of Wellington), *jacuzzi* (Candido Jacuzzi, 1968).","trace":"Find 5 eponyms from scientists (*galvanize* from Luigi Galvani, *pasteurize* from Louis Pasteur, *diesel* from Rudolf Diesel, *fahrenheit* from Daniel Fahrenheit, *hertz* from Heinrich Hertz). For each, explain the specific discovery or innovation.","build":"If YOUR name became a word, what would it mean, and how would it be spelled? Write the dictionary entry: the word, its pronunciation, its part of speech, its etymology, and its definition."}},{"id":"L93","n":93,"unit":10,"title":"Sound Symbolism — When Words Sound Like What They Mean","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"Phonesthesia is the phenomenon where certain sound patterns consistently suggest certain meanings — not through etymology but through the sounds themselves. English has dozens of these sound-meaning associations.","story":"George Lakoff and others have documented English phonesthemes (sound-meaning clusters): The *sl-* onset = slippery, unpleasant movement (*slide, slip, slick, slime, slouch, slop, slur, sludge, slug, slump, slither*). The *gl-* onset = light/vision (*glow, glitter, glint, gleam, glare, glisten, glimmer, glance, glaze, gloom*). The *sn-* onset = nose/contempt (*sneer, sniff, snort, snout, snob, snarl, snide*). The *-ump* rime = heavy/round (*bump, dump, lump, thump, stump, clump, grump*). The *-ash* rime = violent sudden action (*smash, bash, clash, crash, dash, flash, gnash*). These patterns appear throughout the database and are not coincidental — they represent a form of natural sound symbolism.","pattern":"Sound symbolism is NOT etymology: these words may have completely different origins but share sound patterns that reinforce a consistent meaning-cluster. The *sl-* words come from OE, Norse, and French — different origins, same sound cluster. The cluster became productive: new words with *sl-* tend to acquire \"slippery/unpleasant\" connotations. English speakers create new *sl-* words (like *slop, sludge*) that immediately sound \"right\" because of the cluster's established associations.","connection":"Sound symbolism shows that words are not arbitrary — certain sounds genuinely suggest certain meanings through universal or language-specific phonological conventions. Etymology is not the only key to meaning.","words":[{"w":"SLITHER","pron":"SLIH-ther","syll":"slih · dher","ety":["Old English *slīdrian* = to slide ← Proto-Germanic *slīdanan*","The *sl-* onset cluster = slippery, unpleasant movement. *Slither, slide, slip, slick, slime, slouch, slop, slur, sludge, slug, slump* — all OE or Norse words, all with *sl-* onset, all with slippery/negative movement connotations. The cluster became a productive English phonestheme."]},{"w":"GLIMMER","pron":"GLIH-mer","syll":"glim · mer","ety":["Old Norse *glimra* = to shine faintly","The *gl-* cluster = vision and light. *Glow, glitter, glint, gleam, glare, glisten, glimmer, glance, glaze, gloom* — the *gl-* cluster consistently relates to light or the visual field. *Gloom* = absence of light, showing the cluster covers the full spectrum. The *-er* suffix adds gentle repetition: a *glimmer* = faintly repeated gleam."]},{"w":"CRASH","pron":"KRASH","syll":"krae · sh","ety":["Middle English *crasch* = to break noisily — probable onomatopoeia","The *cr-* onset = abrupt pressure/breaking (*crack, crackle, crunch, crush, cram, crumble*). The *-ash* rime = violent sudden action (*smash, bash, clash, crash, dash, flash, gnash*). *Crash* sits at the intersection of two productive sound-meaning clusters: abrupt breaking (*cr-*) AND violent sudden action (*-ash*)."]},{"w":"MURMUR","pron":"MUR-mer","syll":"mer · mer","ety":["Latin *murmurare* = to murmur — pure onomatopoeia preserved across languages","M-U-R-M-U-R: phonesthetically perfect. The repeated *m* sounds, the *ur* vowels, the soft *r*'s — all create the sound of low, continuous, gentle sound. Onomatopoeic in Latin (before English borrowed it). The word has survived unchanged because its sounds ARE its meaning."]},{"w":"SIZZLE","pron":"SIH-zuhl","syll":"sih · zah · l","ety":["English, 16th century probable onomatopoeia ← onomatopoeic creation","S-I-Z-Z-L-E: the *s-* onset, the *-izz-* sibilant cluster, the *-le* frequentative suffix (repeated small actions). *Crackle, drizzle, fizzle, sparkle, twinkle, sprinkle* — all use the *-le* frequentative suffix for small repeated actions. A *sizzle* = makes a hissing sound while cooking. The suffix + the sibilance = the sound of hot fat."]}],"practice":{"decode":"What meaning associations do you find in: *fl-* words (*flight, flit, flutter, flow, fling, flap, flash, flame*), *str-* words (*strong, strain, stretch, stress, strive, struggle, stride*), *-ump* words (*bump, dump, lump, thump, stump, clump*)?","trace":"Find 10 words in the *gl-* light cluster from the 129K database. Confirm each is related to light or vision.","build":"Create 3 new onomatopoeic words for sounds that don't yet have dedicated English words. For each: write the word, its pronunciation, its definition, and explain why the sounds suggest the meaning."}},{"id":"L94","n":94,"unit":10,"title":"Neologisms — The Living Language","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"Every year, hundreds of new words enter English. Understanding how neologisms are formed, which survive, and why reveals the language's living metabolism.","story":"A neologism (← Greek *neos* = new + *logos* = word) is a newly coined word or a word that has recently acquired a new meaning. Neologisms follow two paths: (1) Intentional coinages: scientists name new discoveries (*quark*, coined 1964 by Murray Gell-Mann from James Joyce's *Finnegans Wake*), corporations name new products that become generic (*google*, *hoover*, *kleenex*). (2) Organic emergence: words arise from usage without a single inventor (*selfie*, *binge-watch*, *ghosting*, *mansplain*). The survival rate of neologisms is low: most die quickly. Those that fill a GENUINE LEXICAL GAP — naming something for which no word existed — are most likely to survive.","pattern":"Neologism survival predictors: (1) Fills a lexical gap (no existing word for the concept). (2) Short and pronounceable. (3) Follows existing word-formation patterns. (4) Spread through high-frequency channels (media, social networks). (5) The concept becomes widely experienced. Words that name specific technologies often die with those technologies (*pager, rolodex, icebox*) unless they generalize (*googling* survived even as search engines multiplied).","connection":"Neologisms are where the history of English is being written right now. Every new word that survives will be studied by future etymologists. You are living through the creation of the English vocabulary that will be analyzed in 2526.","words":[{"w":"QUARK","pron":"KWAHRK","syll":"kwaa · rk","ety":["Coined 1964 by physicist Murray Gell-Mann ← James Joyce's *Finnegans Wake* (\"Three quarks for Muster Mark!\")","Q-U-A-R-K: a scientific term coined from a literary nonsense word. The physics context gave it technical precision; the Joyce origin gave it personality. *Quark* violates every neologism \"rule\" (literary source, unusual spelling) and survived because it named a fundamental discovery with no alternative."]},{"w":"MEME","pron":"—","syll":"meme","ety":["Coined 1976 by Richard Dawkins in *The Selfish Gene* ← Greek *mimēma* = something imitated","M-E-M-E: coined to describe cultural units of information that replicate like genes. Dawkins shortened *mimēma* (Greek for \"imitated thing\") to *meme* to rhyme with *gene*. Four decades later: primarily means a funny internet image. The word survived but its meaning dramatically shifted — semantic narrowing to the viral-image sense, almost erasing the original genetics-of-culture meaning."]},{"w":"BINGE","pron":"BIHNJ","syll":"bih · njh","ety":["Old English *bengen* = to soak — changed from physical soaking to excessive consumption","B-I-N-G-E: OE *bengen* = to soak → *binge* (to drink excessively) → *binge-eating* → *binge-watching* (2003) = watching many episodes in one sitting. The word existed for centuries with one meaning; the streaming era (Netflix 2007) gave it a new dominant sense. *Binge-watching* = a neologism created from an old word by applying it to a new behavior."]},{"w":"GHOSTING","pron":"GOHST-ing","syll":"ghost · ing","ety":["English *ghost* (OE *gāst*) + *-ing* (gerund suffix) = to ghost + gerund form","G-H-O-S-T-I-N-G: cutting off all communication with someone without explanation — to vanish like a ghost. The OE word for spirit (*gāst*) became a dating/relationship verb in the 2010s. Backformation: *ghost* (noun) → *to ghost* (verb) → *ghosting* (gerund). Shows how old words generate new meanings through metaphorical extension."]},{"w":"CRYPTOCURRENCY","pron":"—","syll":"cryptocurrency","ety":["Greek *kryptos* (hidden) + Latin/English *currency* (from *currere* = to run)","C-R-Y-P-T-O-C-U-R-R-E-N-C-Y: coined ~2009 with Bitcoin's emergence. Greek *krypto-* (hidden/encrypted) + English *currency* (from Latin *currere* = to run = what currency does: circulate). A 21st-century financial technology naming itself with 2,000-year-old Greek morphology. Still follows ancient naming conventions."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Find 5 words coined in the last 10 years and identify which of the 8 word-formation processes created each (borrowing, compounding, clipping, blending, acronym, eponym, backformation, derivation).","trace":"The word *meme* was coined in 1976 but acquired its dominant modern sense after 2013. Research: how did the internet sense develop? What happened to Dawkins's original meaning?","build":"Predict: what 5 new English words will be standard vocabulary by 2035? Use the 8 word-formation processes to create plausible coinages from existing roots. What new technologies or social phenomena might need naming?"}},{"id":"L95","n":95,"unit":10,"title":"False Friends Across Languages — The Championship Traps","diff":"hard","bigIdea":"False friends (faux amis) are words that look or sound similar across languages but have completely different meanings. In English spelling bees, the key false friends are WITHIN English — words that look so similar that etymology-based decoding leads to the wrong spelling.","story":"The most dangerous championship false friends: (1) *Elicit* (draw out) vs *illicit* (not permitted) — identical pronunciation, one *l* difference. (2) *Veracious* (truthful) vs *voracious* (greedy) — one vowel difference, unrelated roots. (3) *Principle* (rule) vs *principal* (main/head) — same pronunciation, *-le* vs *-al*. (4) *Complement* (completes something) vs *compliment* (praise) — *-e-* vs *-i-* internal vowel. (5) *Discreet* (tactful) vs *discrete* (separate/distinct) — same pronunciation, *-eet* vs *-ete*. The false friend trap: you know one word's etymology, assume the similar-looking word shares it, and apply the wrong spelling.","pattern":"False friend defense: learn the etymology of BOTH words in each pair. Knowing both roots prevents cross-contamination. *Elicit* ← Latin *elicere* = to draw out. *Illicit* ← Latin *illicitus* = not permitted (*in-* + *licitus*). Different origins → different spellings → same pronunciation. The only protection is knowing both.","connection":"False friends are the most humbling category in championship spelling because they exploit the very etymological knowledge that the whole program has been building. The solution is always to learn BOTH etymologies.","words":[{"w":"COMPLEMENT","pron":"KAH-mpluh-muhnt","syll":"kaa · mplah · mah · nt","ety":["Latin *complementum* = that which fills up ← *com-* + *plere* = to fill","That which completes or makes whole. C-O-M-P-L-E-M-E-N-T. *Plere* = fill → *complete, replete, implement, supplement*. False friend: *compliment* (C-O-M-P-L-I-M-E-N-T) ← Spanish *cumplimiento* = fulfillment of courtesy. Memory: a *complement* fills up (with *e*, like \"fill\") a *compliment* is polite (with *i*, like \"I'm being nice\")."]},{"w":"DISCREET","pron":"dih-SKREET","syll":"dih · skriy · t","ety":["Old French *discret* ← Latin *discretus* = separated, set apart ← *dis-* + *cernere* = to sift","Tactful, careful not to embarrass. D-I-S-C-R-E-E-T. False friend: *discrete* (← same Latin *discretus*, but meaning preserved = separate, individually distinct). Same etymology, different modern meanings: *discreet* (the social behavior) vs *discrete* (the mathematical/logical meaning). The *-eet/-ete* is the only spelling difference."]},{"w":"IMMINENT","pron":"IH-muh-nuhnt","syll":"im · mi · nent","ety":["Latin *imminere* = to overhang, to threaten ← *im-* (upon) + *minere* (to project)","About to happen, impending. I-M-M-I-N-E-N-T: double *m* from *im-* + *m-*root assimilation. False friend: *eminent* (← Latin *eminere* = to project above = distinguished, prominent). Both contain *-inent* but different prefixes (*im-* vs *e-*): *imminent* (threatening to hang over) vs *eminent* (projecting above = distinguished)."]},{"w":"TORTUOUS","pron":"TAW-rchuh-wuhs","syll":"tao · rchah · wah · s","ety":["Latin *tortuosus* ← *tortus* (twisted) ← *torquere* = to twist","Full of twists and turns. T-O-R-T-U-O-U-S. False friend: *torturous* (← *torture* = causing pain). Both from *torquere* but different derivational paths: *tortuous* (many-twisted = winding) vs *torturous* (causing torment). The *-uous/-ous* distinction: *tortuous* = winding; *torturous* = agonizing."]},{"w":"CLIMACTIC","pron":"kleye-MA-ktihk","syll":"klay · mae · ktih · k","ety":["Greek *klimaktikos* ← *klimax* = ladder, climax ← *klinein* = to lean/slope","Of or relating to a climax. C-L-I-M-A-C-T-I-C. False friend: *climatic* (← Greek *klima* = slope/region/climate → relating to climate). C-L-I-M-A-T-I-C. One letter difference (*-act-* vs *-at-*): *climact-ic* has the *-act-* from *klimax* (climax); *climat-ic* has *-at-* from *klima* (climate zone)."]}],"practice":{"decode":"For each false-friend pair, explain both etymologies and the spelling difference: *complement/compliment, discreet/discrete, imminent/eminent, tortuous/torturous, climactic/climatic*.","trace":"Find 5 more championship-level false friend pairs: *affect/effect, stationary/stationery, principal/principle, elicit/illicit, veracious/voracious*. Give both etymologies for each.","build":"Design a \"False Friends Drill\": create 20 sentences where each sentence contains one false friend pair and you must select the correct word. Share with a study partner and score each other."}},{"id":"L96","n":96,"unit":10,"title":"Contronyms Deep Dive — 15 Words That Are Their Own Opposites","diff":"hard","bigIdea":"A comprehensive examination of English contronyms (autoantonyms) — 15 words with documented opposite meanings — and the linguistic mechanisms that created each one.","story":"English contronyms develop through 5 mechanisms: (1) Two different words merged through identical spelling (*cleave* from OE *cleofan* = split + OE *clifian* = adhere). (2) Ironic/sarcastic use became standard (*wicked* = bad → extremely good in modern slang). (3) Technical vs everyday usage conflict (*sanction* = authorize vs penalize). (4) The word applies to both the action and its reversal (*screen, dust, seed*). (5) Semantic drift in opposite directions from a neutral origin (*fast* = moving quickly + fixed in place — both from OE *fæst* = firmly fixed, which generated both \"fixed\" and \"moving so fast it seems fixed\").","pattern":"Contronym test: make two sentences where the word means X in one and the opposite of X in the other. If both sentences are grammatically correct and semantically coherent, the word is a contronym. Context is the only guide — there is no ambiguity resolution rule except understanding what each usage means.","connection":"The 15+ documented contronyms in English reveal that context is always primary in language. Meaning is never in the word alone — it is always in the word within its context.","words":[{"w":"SANCTION","pron":"SA-ngkshuhn","syll":"sae · ngkshah · n","ety":["Latin *sanctio* = official decree — can both authorize and penalize","*Sanction* = (1) officially permit (*the treaty was sanctioned by both governments*) OR (2) officially penalize (*economic sanctions were imposed*). A *sanctio* could authorize or prohibit; English inherited both directional possibilities. True contronym from semantic ambiguity of the original Latin."]},{"w":"BUCKLE","pron":"BUH-kuhl","syll":"bah · kah · l","ety":["Old French *bocle* = a ring/shield boss → fastening → collapsing","*Buckle* = (1) to FASTEN a belt (*buckle up*) OR (2) to COLLAPSE under pressure (*the bridge buckled*). Fastening firmly and collapsing under stress = opposite conditions. The fastening sense is from the boss/ring; the collapse sense is from something bending/giving way under pressure."]},{"w":"CLIP","pron":"KLIHP","syll":"klih · p","ety":["Old English *clyppan* = to embrace/clasp AND *clipian* = to cut — two OE words","*Clip* = (1) to ATTACH with a clip (*clip the papers together*) OR (2) to CUT OFF (*clip the hedge*). Two different OE verbs merged into one spelling. The fastening *clip* and the cutting *clip* are different words with a shared modern form."]},{"w":"OVERSIGHT","pron":"OH-ver-seyet","syll":"ow · ver · say · t","ety":["Old English *ofer-* (over) + *sihþ* (sight) — looking over can miss what it overlooks","*Oversight* = (1) careful SUPERVISION (*the committee had oversight*) OR (2) a failure to NOTICE (*the error was an oversight*). Looking OVER something carefully vs having your gaze pass OVER something without seeing it — opposite results from the same spatial metaphor."]},{"w":"WEATHER","pron":"WEH-ther","syll":"weath · er","ety":["Old English *weder* = weather, storm — to weather can mean both to survive and to erode","*Weather* (verb) = (1) to SURVIVE (*the company weathered the storm*) OR (2) to ERODE (*weather a rock face*). Surviving the weather vs being eroded by weather = opposite outcomes from the same meteorological force."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Find the two opposite meanings for each: *weather, buckle, clip, oversight, sanction, cleave, screen, dust, seed, rent, fine, left, literally*.","trace":"Research the linguistic mechanism behind each contronym you find: which of the 5 mechanisms (merged words, ironic use, technical/everyday conflict, action/reversal, semantic drift) created each one?","build":"Create a \"Contronym Sentence Challenge\": write one sentence where each contronym is genuinely ambiguous — where you cannot tell which meaning is intended without additional context. What does the ambiguity reveal about how meaning works?"}},{"id":"L97","n":97,"unit":10,"title":"Dead Words That Need Reviving","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"English has hundreds of \"lost\" words — words that were standard vocabulary in their era but fell out of use. Some of these words fill genuine gaps in modern English and deserve revival.","story":"Words become obsolete when: (1) The thing they named disappeared (*blacksmith* is still used; *fletcher* = arrow-maker is obsolete because arrows are less central to daily life). (2) A competing word won (*nice* won over *lewd* for \"pleasing\"). (3) The word's frequency fell below the threshold of active vocabulary. (4) Sound changes made the word unrecognizable (*cwene* = woman fell out of use partly because it sounded too similar to an obscenity). But some obsolete words named concepts that modern English still needs, and their loss created genuine gaps that we now fill with cumbersome phrases.","pattern":"Obsolete word revival: *sonder* (coined by John Koenig's *Dictionary of Obscure Sorrows* as new but the concept is old), *frippery* (still used but rare = excessive ornamentation), *snollygoster* (a politician who will do anything to win an election — active 1846–1952, now obsolete but clearly needed). The challenge: determining when a word has truly died vs when it still appears in literary/specialized contexts.","connection":"Dead words preserve ways of thinking that may no longer have clear vocabulary in modern English. Reviving precise obsolete words can improve the precision of modern expression.","words":[{"w":"SNOLLYGOSTER","pron":"—","syll":"snollygoster","ety":["American English, origin disputed — a shrewd, unprincipled politician","A shrewd, unprincipled person, especially a politician. S-N-O-L-L-Y-G-O-S-T-E-R: active in American English from the 1840s to 1950s. President Truman used it in 1952. Now obsolete — but its concept is clearly needed. A one-word answer to a question that currently requires a 6-word phrase."]},{"w":"ULTRACREPIDARIAN","pron":"—","syll":"ultracrepidarian","ety":["Latin *ultra* (beyond) + *crepida* (sandal) = beyond the sandal","One who gives opinions on subjects beyond their knowledge. Based on a classical story: the painter Apelles told a cobbler \"no higher than the sandal\" when criticized about his paintings. Coined 1819 by William Hazlitt. U-L-T-R-A-C-R-E-P-I-D-A-R-I-A-N: a 19-letter word for a concept that needs a word."]},{"w":"LIMERENCE","pron":"—","syll":"limerence","ety":["Coined 1977 by psychologist Dorothy Tennov = the state of being infatuated with another person","L-I-M-E-R-E-N-C-E: not a revival — a neologism coined to fill a gap. *Limerence* = the obsessive phase of romantic attraction before it becomes stable love or fades. Tennov coined it from no existing root because she wanted a neutral technical term. Sometimes counted among \"words English needs\" despite being a genuine 1977 coinage."]},{"w":"ERGOPHOBIA","pron":"—","syll":"ergophobia","ety":["Greek *ergon* (work) + *phobia* (fear) — fear of work or workplace","Fear of work. E-R-G-O-P-H-O-B-I-A: still in medical dictionaries but rarely used in everyday speech. *Ergon* = work → *erg* (unit of work in physics), *ergonomics* (the science of efficient work design), *ergophobia* (fear of work). A Greek compound that fills a genuine emotional gap."]},{"w":"QUODDAMODOTATIVE","pron":"—","syll":"quoddamodotative","ety":["Coined from Latin — relating to the way something is, its mode of existence","Relating to the particular way in which something exists or operates. Q-U-O-D-D-A-M-O-D-O-T-A-T-I-V-E: from Latin *quodam modo* = in a certain way. An academic philosophical term occasionally encountered in 17th–18th century texts. Now virtually extinct. Example of a word that served its era but had no modern descendant."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Research 5 \"lost\" English words that named concepts still relevant today: *snollygoster, ultracrepidarian, jargogle* (to confuse), *twattle* (to gossip), *groke* (to stare at someone's food hoping they'll share). What concept does each name?","trace":"John Koenig's *Dictionary of Obscure Sorrows* (2021) invents words for emotional experiences that have no English names. Find 5 words from the book and analyze: do they follow real etymological principles? Could they survive as genuine English words?","build":"Write a 200-word passage using 5 \"dead\" English words in context. Make the meanings clear from context. Could a reader unfamiliar with these words understand them? What does this tell you about how context enables new vocabulary acquisition?"}},{"id":"L98","n":98,"unit":10,"title":"The Global English Project — English as a World Language","diff":"hard","bigIdea":"English is now a global language used by more non-native speakers than native speakers. This creates \"World Englishes\" — varieties of English shaped by the linguistic patterns of each region's local languages.","story":"Estimates suggest 1.5 billion people speak English worldwide — roughly 400 million native speakers, over 1 billion non-native speakers. The non-native users now define the statistical center of English usage. This creates \"World Englishes\": Indian English (*pre-pone* a meeting = move it earlier, from *postpone* by analogy), Singaporean English (*Singlish*: *lah* as sentence-final particle), Nigerian English (*go-slow* = traffic jam), South African English (*now-now* = very soon). These are not \"mistakes\" — they are systematic linguistic patterns applying local phonological and grammatical conventions to the English base.","pattern":"World English signals: each variety shows the phonological/grammatical patterns of its substrate language applied to English. Indian English shows retroflexion (a distinctive *r/d/t* quality from Hindi/Urdu phonology). West African English shows different subject-verb agreement patterns. These varieties are internally consistent — they follow rules, just not the same rules as British or American English.","connection":"English's global spread is creating new varieties that will eventually be as different from each other as Spanish and Portuguese — or as Latin and French. The English vocabulary story is not over; it is accelerating.","words":[{"w":"LOANWORD","pron":"LOHN-wurd","syll":"loan · word","ety":["English: *loan* (Old Norse *lán* = a loan) + *word* (Old English *word*)","The technical term for what this entire program studies. A word borrowed from another language. The concept of borrowing itself uses a financial metaphor: you \"borrow\" a word from another language (but unlike financial borrowing, you never return it). The English word for this process is itself a compound of Norse + OE."]},{"w":"PIDGIN","pron":"PIJ-in","syll":"pid · gin","ety":["Possibly from Chinese pronunciation of English *business* — a contact/trade language","P-I-D-G-I-N: a simplified contact language developed when speakers of mutually unintelligible languages need to communicate. *Pidgin* may derive from Chinese *biéng* (a Chinese pronunciation of English *business*). When a pidgin becomes the native language of a community, it becomes a *creole* (← Spanish *criollo* = locally born). English itself emerged partly through a pidgin-like contact process between OE and Norse."]},{"w":"CALQUE","pron":"KALK","syll":"calque","ety":["French *calque* = a tracing, copy ← *calquer* = to trace","C-A-L-Q-U-E: a loan-translation where each morpheme of a foreign word is translated rather than borrowed. *Skyscraper* = English calque of German *Wolkenkratzer* (cloud-scratcher). *Flea market* = calque of French *marché aux puces*. *Brainwash* = calque of Chinese *xǐ nǎo* (wash brain). Unlike loanwords, calques use native vocabulary to express foreign concepts."]},{"w":"GLOBISH","pron":"—","syll":"globish","ety":["English *global* + *English* — portmanteau, coined ~2004 by Robert McCrum","G-L-O-B-I-S-H: a term for the simplified, standardized form of English used in international business and diplomacy — roughly 1,500 core words that enable global communication without requiring full English fluency. *Globish* is descriptive, not prescriptive: it describes what actually happens in international communication, not what should happen."]},{"w":"ANGLOPHONE","pron":"AE1 N G L AH0 F OW2 N","syll":"an · glo · phone","ety":["French *anglophone* ← Greek *anglos* (English) + *phōnē* (voice/language)","English-speaking. A-N-G-L-O-P-H-O-N-E: a Greek-French hybrid widely used in international contexts (especially former French colonial contexts) to describe English-speaking regions. *Francophone* (French-speaking), *hispanophone* (Spanish-speaking), *lusophone* (Portuguese-speaking) use the same *-phone* = voice/language suffix."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Research 5 \"World English\" coinages: *pre-pone* (Indian English), *go-slow* (West African English), *now-now* (South African English), *shiok* (Singapore English = delicious/great). What local linguistic patterns do they reflect?","trace":"A *calque* is a loan-translation. Find 5 more English calques from other languages: *Adam's apple* (← French *pomme d'Adam*), *brainwash* (← Chinese), *hot dog* (← German *Heißer Hund*?), *cloud computing* (← earlier metaphorical extensions). Is a calque a borrowing?","build":"Predict: what will happen to English in the next 100 years as non-native speakers increasingly outnumber native speakers? Will a \"Global Standard English\" emerge, or will World Englishes diversify further? Build your argument from the historical evidence in this program."}},{"id":"L99","n":99,"unit":10,"title":"Building Your Personal Etymology Map","diff":"medium","bigIdea":"A personal etymology map is a visual representation of how your vocabulary knowledge is organized — showing which root families you know deeply, which language systems you've mastered, and which word journeys you've traced.","story":"Professional lexicographers organize vocabulary by etymology precisely because etymological organization reveals the underlying structure of the language. Your personal etymology map does the same for your competitive vocabulary. The map has three layers: (1) ROOTS: the Latin, Greek, OE/Norse, French, Arabic, Sanskrit, etc. roots you know with their families. (2) SIGNALS: the spelling/sound signals that identify each language. (3) JOURNEYS: the word-travel paths you've traced (Greek→Latin→French→English, Arabic→Medieval Latin→European languages→English, etc.).","pattern":"Etymology map construction: Start with the 8 most productive Latin roots (*facere, vertere, ducere, mittere, ponere, capere, tenere, scribere*) and the 6 most productive Greek roots (*logos, graphein, metron, phainein, bios, pathos*). Draw each root as a hub, with all its English words as spokes. Connect hubs where they combine (*plenipotentiary* connects *plenus* hub to *potens* hub). The result: a visual network showing how the entire English vocabulary system hangs together.","connection":"Your personal etymology map is the culmination of this entire program — a living, growing resource that represents your etymological knowledge organized visually.","words":[{"w":"ETYMOLOGY","pron":"eh-tuh-MAH-luh-jee","syll":"eh · tah · maa · lah · jhiy","ety":["Greek *etymon* (true form/meaning) + *logos* (study) — this entire program in one word","E-T-Y-M-O-L-O-G-Y: the study of the true origins and historical development of words. The word that names the entire content of Units 1–9. *Etymon* = the true, original form of a word. The goal of etymology: finding the *etymon* behind every word you encounter."]},{"w":"LEXICOGRAPHY","pron":"lek-sih-KOG-ruh-fee","syll":"lex · i · cog · ra · phy","ety":["Greek *lexikon* (of words) + *graphein* (to write/record)","The art and practice of writing dictionaries. L-E-X-I-C-O-G-R-A-P-H-Y. *Lexikon* = of words → *lexicon* (a vocabulary or dictionary), *lexical* (relating to vocabulary). *Graphein* = write (from our L24 database root with 121 words). A lexicographer is literally a \"word-writer.\""]},{"w":"MORPHOLOGY","pron":"maw-RFAH-luh-jee","syll":"mao · rfaa · lah · jhiy","ety":["Greek *morphē* (form/shape) + *logos* (study)","The study of the forms of words — how they are built from morphemes. M-O-R-P-H-O-L-O-G-Y. *Morphē* = form → *morphology, morpheme, amorphous, metamorphosis, Morpheus* (the god of dreams = the one who gives form to dreams). The study of word structure = the foundation of all spelling analysis in this program."]},{"w":"COGNATE","pron":"KOG-nayt","syll":"cog · nate","ety":["Latin *cognatus* ← *co-* (together) + *gnatus* (born)","A word related to another by descent from a common ancestor. C-O-G-N-A-T-E. *Gnatus* = born (past participle of *nasci* = to be born) → *innate* (born within), *native* (born in a place), *nation* (those born together), *nature* (what one is born as). *Cognate* = born together = sharing an ancestor. The word for etymological relatives is itself an etymology lesson."]},{"w":"PHILOLOGY","pron":"fih-LOL-oh-jee","syll":"phi · lol · o · gy","ety":["Greek *philos* (lover of) + *logos* (word/language)","The study and love of language, especially through historical texts. P-H-I-L-O-L-O-G-Y. *Philos* = lover of → *philosophy* (lover of wisdom), *philharmonic* (lover of harmony), *Philadelphia* (lover of brothers = city of brotherly love). A philologist loves language in the same way a philosopher loves wisdom — through studying its deepest structures."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Build your first etymology map: take the 8 most productive Latin roots from L12 and draw a hub-and-spoke diagram with 5 words from each root. Connect hubs where roots combine.","trace":"Add the 6 most productive Greek roots from L24 to your map. Show the connections between the Greek and Latin systems (hybrid words, same PIE ancestor roots).","build":"Share your etymology map with a study partner. Where do your maps differ? What does the difference reveal about which word families each of you has mastered most deeply?"}},{"id":"L100","n":100,"unit":10,"title":"The Ultimate Word Journey — From PIE to Your Mouth","diff":"hard","bigIdea":"Every English word has a complete biography — from its Proto-Indo-European ancestor to its modern spelling. In this final lesson, we trace four words from their very first utterance, 6,000 years ago, to today.","story":"PIE *ḱḗr* = heart gave English 15+ words through three paths. The complete journey: PIE *ḱḗr* (4,000 BCE, Pontic steppe) → Proto-Germanic *hertô* (1,000 BCE) → Old English *heort* (700 CE) → Middle English *herte* (1200) → Modern English *heart* (1500–today). Latin path: PIE *ḱḗr* → Latin *cor/cordis* → Old French *cuer/cor* → English *cordial, courage, accord, discord, record* (1300 CE→). Greek path: PIE *ḱḗr* → Greek *kardia* → (Renaissance medical Latin) → English *cardiac, cardiologist, tachycardia, endocardium* (1600 CE→). Three paths. One PIE root. Fifteen modern English words. This is the story of every formal English word.","pattern":"The word biography format: (1) PIE ancestor (with approximate date and location). (2) Branch divergence (which PIE branch carried it). (3) Intermediate forms (Proto-Germanic, Old English, Latin, Greek, French). (4) English entry (when, through which path). (5) Semantic changes along the way. (6) Modern English family (all related words today). Every word in the 129K database has this biography — etymology is reading those biographies.","connection":"This lesson is the end of the program and the beginning of etymology as a lifelong practice. Every word you encounter from now on has a biography. Your job as a champion speller is to read those biographies fluently.","words":[{"w":"HEART","pron":"HAHRT","syll":"hhaa · rt","ety":["PIE *ḱḗr* (4000 BCE) → Proto-Germanic *hertô* → OE *heort* → ME *herte* → Modern English *heart*","The direct Germanic path: 6,000 years of continuous use. *Heart* is one of the oldest words in English, going back to PIE without interruption. It has never been displaced by a Latin or French word for everyday use — the Germanic path survived because the word is too basic, too emotional, too physical to be replaced."]},{"w":"CORDIAL","pron":"KAW-rjuhl","syll":"kao · rjhah · l","ety":["PIE *ḱḗr* → Latin *cor/cordis* → Old French *cordial* → English *cordial*","The Latin/French path of the same PIE root: 3,000-year journey. *Cor/cordis* → *cordial* (warm-hearted), *courage* (having heart), *accord* (heart-to-heart), *discord* (hearts apart), *record* (put back in the heart = remember). The Latin path generates the formal, elevated register vocabulary for the same concept."]},{"w":"CARDIAC","pron":"KAH-rdee-ak","syll":"kaa · rdiy · ae · k","ety":["PIE *ḱḗr* → Greek *kardia* → New Latin medical vocabulary → English *cardiac*","The Greek path of the same PIE root: 3,500-year journey into scientific vocabulary. *Kardia* → *cardiac, cardiologist, tachycardia, bradycardia, pericardium, endocarditis, electrocardiogram*. The Greek path generates the technical medical register. Three paths from one PIE root, three registers of modern English."]},{"w":"COURAGE","pron":"KUR-uhj","syll":"cour · age","ety":["Old French *corage* ← Latin *cor* = heart — having heart = bravery","C-O-U-R-A-G-E: the hidden heart in bravery. Every time someone is *courageous*, they are etymologically \"having heart.\" *En-courage* = put heart into. *Dis-courage* = take heart away. The word for bravery is the word for having heart — an ancient metaphor that English inherited from Latin and will carry forward indefinitely."]},{"w":"WATER","pron":"WAW-ter","syll":"wao · ter","ety":["PIE *wódr̥* → Proto-Germanic *watōr* → OE *wæter* → Modern English *water*","The oldest, most stable word in English. PIE *wódr̥* = water. OE *wæter*. No Latin or French word has ever displaced it — *water* is too fundamental. The Greek path gives *hydro-* (*hydrogen* = water-generator), the Latin path gives *aqua-* (*aquifer, aqueduct*). Three words for water — one concept — in three registers — from one PIE root."]}],"practice":{"decode":"Trace the complete biography for *water*: PIE *wódr̥* → Proto-Germanic *watōr* → OE *wæter* → Latin parallel *aqua* → Greek *hydōr* → all their English descendants. How many words come from each path?","trace":"Pick any word in the 129K database that you find beautiful, strange, or meaningful. Write its complete biography: PIE ancestor (if known), all language stops, all meaning changes, all English relatives today.","build":"Write a 500-word etymology story — not a definition, but a STORY — of one word from PIE to today. Make the reader feel the word's 6,000-year journey. Let it end with the word on the tip of your tongue, ready to spell."}}]};